VALUES
	(113934,1,'2019-11-18 10:30:22','2019-11-18 16:30:22','The high school season is here in the state of Illinois! With that, we look at one of the top conferences in the state and a couple of its prospects!\n\n<strong>Preseason Player of the Year Nominations: </strong>\n\nRashamani Webb (<em>Normal West</em>) - Webb blew up this summer and with the energy and effort she plays with, she will be a focal point this year on a loaded Normal West team that will look to make a deep postseason run. She will be a fun watch and put up some massive numbers in every stat category this year.\n\nJaida McCloud (<em>Richwoods</em>) - Richwoods should be favorite to win the conference again and McCloud will be the best player on that team. She had a stellar run this summer and committed to UIC. She\'s a super versatile player with an incredibly long wingspan. She combines an ability to finish around the rim and has developed a consistent shot from the outside. Also is a plus driver from the perimeter.\n\nKylee Schneringer (<em>Normal Community</em>) - Schneringer has a diverse skillset and with Maya Wong\'s early graduation, Schneringer will be counted on to do even more and lead the Lady Irons. Kylee can do everything offensively: she can play in the post and on the perimeter. She has a smooth game with a fluid jump shot and tight handle.\n\nChanice Willis (<em>Champaign Central</em>) - There\'s a lot of buzz about Champaign Central. They play a loaded schedule and are looking to finally make the leap<span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\"> to state. Willis will be a key contributor for this to happen, Willis is looking to add to her stellar career at Champaign Central and win them a Regional Championship.</span>\n\nErin Houpt (<em>Danville</em>) - Houpt is the only junior on this list and she will make a strong case to win it this year. Last year, as a sophmore, she was special and she will need to be special again this year for Danville to contend. She, like the rest of the players on this list, will be a box office must-see. Offensively, she is extremely skilled and can score in bunches.\n\n<strong>Preseason Conference Favorite:</strong>\n\nThis should be a very entertaining conference this year. Richwoods isn\'t as talented as they\'ve been in recent years, but there\'s still a ton of talent there and they have a culture that expects success. Normal West will compete with their depth, between Olivia Demosthenes and the Webb sisters. Champaign Central should make a push for the conference crown, returning all 5 starters from last year\'s team. Ultimately, McCloud and Nia Williams should be enough for Richwoods to win the conference.\n\n<strong>Ranked Prospects to Watch:</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Jaida McCloud (<em>Richwoods</em>)</li>\n 	<li>Chanice Willis (<em>Champaign Central</em>)</li>\n 	<li>Olivia Demosthenes (<em>Normal West</em>)</li>\n 	<li>Chian Scott (<em>Urbana</em>)</li>\n 	<li>Derria Edwards (<em>Peoria</em>)</li>\n 	<li>Erin Houpt (<em>Danville</em>)</li>\n 	<li>Aija Gwin (<em>Champaign Central</em>)</li>\n 	<li>Jayden Wilson (<em>Champaign Central</em>)</li>\n 	<li>Nia Williams (<em>Richwoods</em>)</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Top Contenders</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Richwoods</li>\n 	<li>Normal West</li>\n 	<li>Champaign Central</li>\n 	<li>Normal Community</li>\n 	<li>Peoria High</li>\n 	<li>Danville</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Big 12 Conference Preview:','','publish','open','open','','big-12-conference-preview','','','2019-11-18 10:30:22','2019-11-18 16:30:22','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=113934',0,'post','',0),
	(113941,1,'2019-11-17 10:57:53','2019-11-17 16:57:53','Over the next three weeks, we\'re going to take a look at each class in Nebraska, starting with Class D2 and ending up with Class A right around Thanksgiving weekend.  Today, we will take a look at Class C2, which returns a tremendous amount of top-shelf talent and a loaded returning state champion squad.\n\n<strong>RETURNING CHAMPION: </strong>Hastings St. Cecilia raised the Class C2 state champions trophy, defeating another traditional power, Crofton, in the final, 63-45.  St. Cecilia\'s just barely made it into the final after defeating Oakland-Craig 72-68 in overtime in the semi-final, but the Hawkettes got things going late against Crofton and pulled away for their first state title since 2011.\n\n<strong>TOP RETURNING PLAYER: </strong>Perhaps the best basketball player in Class C2, Kalynn Meyer of Superior will not even pursue the sport in college.  The University of Nebraska volleyball recruit also does a great job on the basketball court as well, averaging 20 points and 17 rebounds a game for a Superior program that was knocked out of the state tournament in the opening round last season.\n\n<strong>TEAM ON THE BRINK:</strong> Centennial (Utica) is set to make some noise in C2 this season after narrowly missing out on the state tournament last year.  With all five starters returning from an 18-7 team, the Broncos are primed to make a jump this winter.  Kierra Green, a transfer in from McCool Junction, is expected to help the Broncos after averaging 10.1 points a game last year.  Depth and balance will help the Broncos move into the elite this season.\n\n<strong>BEST CONFERENCE:</strong> The Centennial Conference is one of the elite conferences in all sports and activities in the state, and that is no different in girls basketball.  Hastings St. Cecilia, Grand Island Central Catholic and Wahoo Neumann, the returning Class C1 state champions who dropped down to C2 this season, are amongst the great programs in this conference.  If you want to see a preview of the state tournament, watch the results of the Centennial Conference tournament on an annual basis.\n\n<strong>REGULAR SEASON GAME(S) OF THE YEAR: </strong>Three of our top four teams in Class C2 meet in the regular season in a pair of match-ups.  Hastings St. Cecilia heads to Fillmore Central on January 2nd, while the Hawkettes also hit the road for another great match-up on February 13th when they go to meet conference foe Grand Island Central Catholic.  These two games should be two great measuring sticks to see where everyone lines up going into the postseason.\n\n<strong>\"SUPER SEVEN\" INDIVIDUAL PLAYERS IN CLASS C2:</strong> Kalynn Meyer, Superior (20 ppg, 17 rpg, Sr.)/ Lacey Sprakel, Crofton (15.6 ppg, 7.8 rpg, Jr.)/ Bailey Kissinger, Hastings St. Cecilia (12.8 ppg, 3.5 rpg, So.)/ Kennedy Benne, Oakland-Craig (14.5 ppg, 4.3 rpg, Sr.)/ Kaci Day, Ponca (14.5 ppg, 4.8 rpg, Jr.)/ Jackie Schelkopf, Fillmore Central (13.5 ppg, 3.8 rpg, Jr.)/ Lindsay Thiele, Wahoo Neumann (12.1 ppg, 4.3 rpg, Sr.)\n\n<strong>\"ELITE EIGHT\" IN LINCOLN THE FIRST WEEKEND IN MARCH: </strong>Hastings St. Cecilia, Crofton, Fillmore Central, Grand Island Central Catholic, Nebraska City Lourdes, Oakland-Craig, Centennial (Utica), Superior\n\n<strong>PRE-SEASON STATE CHAMPIONSHIP PICK: </strong>I believe that there is a pretty distinct split between the top five squads in Class C2 and everyone else in the class, with Hastings St. Cecilia, Crofton, Fillmore Central, Superior and Grand Island Central Catholic (dropping down from C2 from C1 last year) a notch above everyone else.  Watch out for Superior to be the squad to perhaps spoil the party for the two combatants in last year\'s title game, but I see a rematch in Class C2, with the depth of Hastings St. Cecilia once again wearing down Aaron Losing\'s Crofton squad and repeating as state champions.','Class C2 Season Preview','','publish','open','open','','class-c2-season-preview','','','2019-11-17 10:57:53','2019-11-17 16:57:53','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=113941',0,'post','',0),
	(113947,1,'2019-11-17 13:34:26','2019-11-17 19:34:26','As the 2023 watchlist is currently under construction and growing, one name that is surely going to be on there is <strong>Olivia</strong> <strong>Anderson</strong> out of Ellensburg, WA. There is a lot of excitment surrounding the top tier of the 2023 class in Washington and Olivia is at the forefront of a lot of the buzz. At a legitimate 6\'4 and a 77 inch plus wingspan with the ability to hang from the rim with ease, she is already a sought after recruit before ever playing in a single high school game.\n\nOlivia knew she wanted to play college basketball when she first started playing competitively in the 7th grade. With so many players specializing in competitive basketball at a younger age, that makes Olivia\'s potential that much higher as she is barely scratching the surface. In her first spring and summer on the travel circuit during her 8th grade year, Olivia was an automatic impact player for the NW Blazers against some of the best 15u teams in the country. With her ability to run the floor, defend multiple positions, block shots and hit the 17 footer with solid form, she quickly caught the eye of college coaches from all around the country. The long list of schools already in contact with her includes Penn State, Michigan State, Oregon State, Gonzaga University, Butler University, Arizona State University, Hampton University, Yale, Texas Tech, Western Kentucky, University of Kentucky, Lehigh University, University of Missouri, Eastern Washington, and BYU. These are not just letters of interest in most cases, these are phone calls being set up and invites to get on campus. \"Real interest\" as I like to say. Olivia told Prep Girls Hoops, \"It\'s been extremely gratifying to have my hard work acknowledged by those I respect in the game.\"\n\n<img class=\"wp-image-113981 alignleft\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/OliviaAnderson1-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"243\" height=\"243\" />Olivia helped her Blazers team to the Heart of Texas National Showcase title, hitting the game winning shot during the Spring. By the end of Summer she was a major piece to helping the Blazers to a second place finish at the 15u adidas Nationals in Atlanta, GA. She also participated in the esteemed Future Stars USA event, which is an invite only showcase for the top 8th and 9th graders in the country. Olivia mentioned, \"I enjoyed Future Stars USA as I learned how to play in high intensity situations, for large high-profile crowds, and with unfamiliar teammates.\"\n\nDespite all of her talent, potential and college following, Olivia is about as humble as they come and knows there is still a lot of work to be done. \"I\'d like to be stronger with the ball, improve my handling, and see an increase of confidence in my post moves.\" Ellensburg is an absolute sleeper in the 2a division and have a core of young talent that should make them competitors for years to come. When it is all said and done, Olivia Anderson is a name everyone will know and she has an opportunity to put Ellensburg on the map in the coming years.','Prospect Intro: 2023 Olivia Anderson (Ellensburg HS)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-intro-2023-olivia-anderson-ellensburg-hs','','','2019-11-17 13:34:26','2019-11-17 19:34:26','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=113947',0,'post','',0),
	(113954,1,'2019-11-17 19:04:05','2019-11-18 01:04:05','This will be the last year for the Prairie State Conference so everyone wants to go out a winner. Alton Marquette is coming off a 21 win season and the conference championship. Coach Green returns most of his rotation and would look like the odds on favorite to repeat. Father McGivney was a 1 loss team in conference and also returns most of their rotation. Coach Oller is certainly looking to improve on last season simply by keeping everyone healthy. Wood River and Metro East Lutheran will be fighting to work their way up to the top while Nokomis and Bunker Hill try to rebuild and return to better days.The following is a list of players that be fighting for All Conference spots and trying to lead their team to a championship.\n\nAlton Marquette returns three first team All Conference players. All three were freshman last year and made a huge impact for the Lady Explorers. <strong>Adrenna Snipes </strong>is a 5\'5 point guard that was named Alton Telegraph small school player of the year. Snipes is able to consistently get into the lane where she uses her moves to finish consistently. She is also an excellent defensive player that set a new school record for steals in a season. <strong>Kamryn Fandrey </strong>is a 5\'5 guard that was the second leading scorer for Marquette. Kamryn excels on the defensive end where she can really frustrate other players with her ability to always be pressuring them. She is like that gnat that will never go away, constantly in your face. She has range out to the 3 point line where she can get hot and is an excellent free throw shooter. <strong>Abby Williams </strong>is a 5\'9 forward that is another hard nosed player for Coach Green. Abby does a good job penetrating against zones and finding the open spots. She finds a way to get offensive rebounds in critical situations. Abby just has a nose for the ball. Abby will be looked upon to contribute more offense this year by keeping herself out of foul trouble.\n\nFather McGivney also returns their top three players that can all be expected to be in the running for All Conference spots too. <strong>Macy Hoppes </strong>is a 5\'4 2020 point guard that stuffs the stats sheet for the Lady Griffins. She averaged 7 points, 6 rebounds, 4 assists and 4 steals per game last year. Macy is a bundle of energy that really gets the team going with her play.<strong>Anna McKee </strong>is a 5\'7 2021 guard that is the leading scorer returning for Coach Oller. Anna has scored over 800 points in her two varsity seasons using her 3-point shot as her main weapon. Anna excels on defense with her long arms and ability to anticipate passes which leads to many fast break layups for her team. <strong>Madison Webb </strong>is a 5\'9 2020 forward that may be the key cog for the Lady Griffins this year. After a very successful sophomore season Madison was unlucky enough to break a finger in pre-season practice last year. She only played in 14 of 32 games. When she did play Madison scored 12.3 points per game and pulled down 6 rebounds. Madison has always been tough inside but has really worked hard to develop a consistent outside shot to compliment her inside game. I expect a big senior season from Madison.\n\nOther players that should be in the mix for All Conference:\n<ul>\n 	<li><strong>Destiny Williams </strong>is a senior point guard from Metro East Lutheran. Destiny is the leading scorer returning for Coach Stock. She is capable of beating most defenders off the dribble. When Destiny gets to the lane she does a good job of scoring or passing off if she sees an open teammate. Destiny also excels on the defensive end of the floor.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Macee Eisenbarth </strong>is a 5\'7 2020 forward from Nokomis. Macee does a great job of getting results on pure guts and effort. That is not to suggest that she does not have talent, she does, but, constantly fighting against taller players in the post is not a life for everyone. Macee does a very good job off their side screen and roll offense by exploiting teams that switch or slower post players that cannot stay with her. She finishes consistently in the lane or gets fouled.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Kayla Brantley </strong>is a 5\'7 2020 guard from Wood River. Kayla is the leading scorer returning for the Lady Oilers and is a 3 year letterman. Kayla battled knee injuries last year and will need to stay healthy for Wood River to make a run for a conference title. Kayla has a good outside shot and has a knack for hitting shots in the mid range too.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Aubrey Robinson </strong>is a 6\'0 2020 forward from Wood River. Aubrey was named the MVP of the team last year. Coach Parmentier feels she is the best all around player on the team as she can score inside and outside but also uses her length very well on defense. Aubrey gets her hands on many passes in their zone which leads to those live ball turnovers everybody wants. Aubrey can hit shots consistently out to the 3 point line.</li>\n</ul>\nDefense played a big part in last years conference race with Alton Marquette and Father McGivney each giving up less than 30 points per game in conference play. This year should be no different. Alton Marquette was able to score 54 points per game so the key will be to slow them down some. These games are usually tight and exciting, I look forward to the season.\n\n&nbsp;','Prairie State Conference Preview','','publish','open','open','','prairie-state-conference-preview-2','','','2019-11-17 19:04:05','2019-11-18 01:04:05','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=113954',0,'post','',0),
