s Wings</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">.  </span><b>PGHCalifornia</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400\"> staff was really impressed with what we saw on this trip to Texas.</span></span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><b>Top Performers for Village: </b></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>21\', 5\'8, SG, Aiken Semones</strong> - She was a solid guard player with defensive skills, gets it done and is not afraid to play hard. Showed a touch from outside in the corner of the key, really liked the intensity she brought to the games as a whole.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>21\' 5\'7, PG, Karlie Sampson</strong> - She ran the floor and could finish at the rim thru contact, which also led to her hitting some big shots in the game for her team.  </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>21\', 6\'4, PF, Jada Malone (#1 in TX 2021 Rankings)</strong> - She was the most dominant post presence this weekend that can finish with both hands, finished at the line as well with ease. Big physical body, soft hands and can score at will.  She ran the floor, post sealed her opponent and finished them off with either hand in on the drop step.  </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>21\', 5\'8, PG, Tymberlin Criswell</strong> - She was the floor general on the team, softball passes on the money from volleyball hash line. Excellent passer and feel for the game like no one else.  She was the most poised guard we saw all weekend at this event.\n</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>22\', 5\'10, SG, Sydney Ward</strong> - She was a long athletic wing type that owned the paint for rebounds, relentless on the boards. Knocked down a couple of threes in this game to help her team get going on the floor.\n</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><b>Top Performers for Frisco Liberty:</b></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>20\', 6\'2, C, Kyla Crawford</strong> - She was a post presence with some considerable size, she knew how to use her body well to gain position for herself in the paint, it was a good battle between her and Jada Malone.  </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>21\', 5\'10, SG, Lily Ziemkiewicz</strong> - She was a big guard/wing type with an athletic build that can handle and distribute for her team. This team must shoot all the time, because she knocked down about three three-pointer herself in this game.  Nice form on her jumper as well.\n</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>21\', 5\'9, SG, Maya Jain</strong> - She was a slender guard with a nice frame and a nice stroke on her three point shot, again, everyone on this team could fill it up from the three line.\n</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>22\' 5\'3, PG, Kamen Wong</strong> -She was a little guard with handles that can distribute and shoot the three pointer on the floor. Knocked down three of them in this game.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>22, 5\'8, SG, Jazzy Owens-Barnett</strong> - She was a solid body type guard, not afraid to mix it up, crafty and could get to the basket with ease off the dribble. Ability to create and get the charity stripe,  also showed us her nice stroke from the three line as well.  </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400\"> </span></span>\n\n&nbsp;','Dallas Mavericks Fall Classic - 3rd Place Game - Top Performers','','publish','open','open','','dallas-mavericks-fall-classic-3rd-place-game','','','2019-11-20 14:44:45','2019-11-20 20:44:45','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=113994',0,'post','',0),
	(114045,1,'2019-11-17 20:18:24','2019-11-18 02:18:24','October 27th was our first Prep Girls Hoops Top 250 Expo in Iowa. It was the last of four this fall and we had an insane amount of talented players in the gym. We will be finishing up our Expo reviews today with the last two teams. Up next is a look at Team 15 from the Expo.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong>Amanda Treptow - 5\'4 PG - 2022 - Jesup HS (IA)</strong>\nTreptow is a very smart point guard who really looks to push the ball up the floor. She is fluid with the ball in her hands and has the ability to find open teammates with ease. Treptow does need to gain strength but her length allows her to play defense sufficiently. Treptow had a good showing at the Top 250. (Featured Photo)\n\n<strong>Trinity Cheatom - 5\'5 PG - 2022 - Roosevelt HS (IA)</strong>\nCheatom is a very quick point guard who has consistently been getting better. She shot the ball really well at the Expo and she seems as if she has gotten quicker. Her fast hands allow her to poke the ball away from her man and she can turn steals into points fairly fast. Look for Cheatom to have a big year at Roosevelt.\n\n<strong>Bryar Duwe - 5\'7 G - 2023 - Decorah HS (IA)</strong>\nDuwe is a very physical combo guard who can play both on and off the ball. She\'s very tough and that was evident on Sunday at the Top 250. Duwe is always going to be on the floor going after loose balls for her team. She showed that she can both distribute and score the ball at the Expo. She\'s among the best 2023\'s in the class.\n\n<strong>Katie Keitges - 5\'8 SG - 2020 - Knoxville HS (IA)</strong>\nKeitges is one of the top shooters in the state and she showed that willingness to shoot on Sunday at the Expo. She is a very good shooter off-the-catch but she was also showing her ability to get into the lane and score as well at the event. I look for Keitges to continue scoring the ball at a high level this upcoming season.\n\n<strong>Grace Stephenson - 5\'8 SF - 2023 - Marion HS (IA)</strong>\nMarion has a host of very good freshmen coming into the fray this year and Stephenson is one of them. She\'s a mobile wing who can create for herself and others. Stephenson showed the willingness to play both inside and outside at the event and I think that\'s a product of her versatility. I think down the road she\'s going to be a stud at Marion.\n\n<strong>Jenna LaDage - 5\'9 SF - 2020 - Solon HS (IA)</strong>\nLaDage was one of the uncommitted 2020\'s at the event and she played really well. Coaches were continually asking about her and expressing that she played well. She\'s a bit of a Swiss Army knife because she does so much really well on the floor. LaDage played really well at the Expo and showed a lot of improvement from last season.\n\n<strong>Nicole Storck - 5\'10 F - 2023 - ADM HS (IA)</strong>\nStorck is a very interesting player because of her versatility and athleticism at the forward spot. She impressed during AAU and she played very well at the Expo against some very good upperclass competition. She can score on the block but also stretch it out and score. She was one of the most impressive 2023\'s at the event.\n\n<strong>Ella Bockenstedt - 5\'11 F - 2023 - Marion HS (IA)</strong>\nBockenstedt is a thin forward who has a high basketball IQ and can really get things going on the offensive end of the floor. She moves without the ball really well and puts herself in good spots to receive the ball to score. I look for her to have a big year for Marion this year and will likely see the floor rather quickly.\n\n<strong>Ava Meyer - 6\' PF - 2023 - Iowa City Liberty HS (IA)</strong>\nMeyer is a very thin forward who will need to gain strength going forward. However, she does play the game at a high level and generally knows what plays to make on the floor. With her height, she is going to be a sought after player at the next level. I really like her ability to rebound and crash the boards. Meyer also proved that she is a very good outlet passer.\n\n<strong>Lexi Boles - 6\'1 C - 2021 - Dowling Catholic HS (IA)</strong>\nBoles might have been the player who impressed me the most at the event. She played with a high motor the entire day and scored the ball well at all three levels. She rebounded well and played very solid defense. Her effort at the Expo is certainly going to move her up the new 2021 rankings as they come out this week.','PGH Top 250 Review: Team 15','','publish','open','open','','pgh-top-250-review-team-15','','','2019-11-17 20:18:24','2019-11-18 02:18:24','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114045',0,'post','',0),
	(114055,1,'2019-11-18 09:00:34','2019-11-18 15:00:34','I was treated to a thrilling matchup between the Amarillo Sandies and the Arlington Martin Warriors in the championship game of the Dallas Mavericks Fall Classic. Arlington Martin led by a score of 22-17 in what was a sloppy first half of basketball littered with turnovers on both sides. However, both teams cleaned things up in the second half. The Sandies came out hot after halftime and took a slight lead over the Warriors and were able to control the game from that point on. Amarillo ultimately defeated Arlington Martin 47-39 and took home the championship trophy.\n\nHere are five takeaways from the Dallas Mavericks Fall Classic championship game:\n<h5 style=\"color: #212529;font-family: Lato, \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif\"><strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/zayla-tanner/\">Zayla Tinner</a> is a beast </strong></h5>\nThis girl is the real deal. Tinner operates as a point forward for the Sandies. Her size allows her to see over the defense and pick it apart. Her offensive versatility really caught my attention. She can shoot, pass, dribble, and rebound, all at a high level. The senior forward had a bit of a rough start to this game, but she took over in the second half. Tinner relentlessly got to her spots deep in the paint and made some tough shots and layups. It\'s impossible for smaller guards to stop her from getting inside. I also loved how she can find open shooters whenever she senses a double team coming her way. She is a matchup nightmare for opposing teams.\n<h5><strong>Arlington Martin had a clear edge in speed and athleticism</strong></h5>\nThe Warriors were unable to come away with a victory in this game. However, they were clearly the quicker and more athletic team on the floor Saturday. Their speed is apparent at both ends and it led to a lot of fast break points. The guard trio of <strong>Autumn Smith</strong>, <strong>Mariah Roberts</strong>, and <strong>Imani Gatlin-Kilgore</strong> can really fly. Smith in particular was causing all sorts of havoc on defense and came away with a ton of steals vs. Amarillo. Had these three been able to convert on a few of their difficult shot attempts inside, Arlington Martin would have been in a position to win this game.\n<h5><strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/zeryah-lee-aokusa/\">Zeryhia-Lee Tuimoloau Aokuso</a> is a star in the making</strong></h5>\nThe freshman combo guard is the first player off the bench for Amarillo, but I wouldn\'t be shocked if she finds her way into the starting lineup by the end of the year. Tuimoloau Aokuso is a physical player who isn\'t afraid to bump around with the bigs inside. She doesn\'t settle for jumpers, but instead opts to put the ball on the floor and attack the basket. Furthermore, she is a tremendous on-ball defender. The 2023 prospect does an excellent job of moving her feet and staying in front of opposing ball handlers. I was really impressed with her game. She\'s going to be a stud for Amarillo for the next four years.\n<h5><strong>Tall ball handlers of Amarillo gave Arlington Martin trouble</strong></h5>\nAmarillo often had either Tinner or Tuimoloau Aokuso bring the ball up on offense. This duo of tall ball handlers caused a lot of problems for Arlington Martin defensively. The duo managed to pick the Warriors apart and exploit mismatches on numerous occasions. And when their shots weren\'t there, their height allowed them to fling passes to open shooters on the perimeter. Like I said, Arlington Martin was the more athletic team on the court Saturday night, but they still couldn\'t overcome Amarillo\'s size advantage, and I think that was the difference in this game.\n<h5><strong>Mariah Roberts is a sniper</strong></h5>\nRoberts was Arlington Martin\'s best scoring option in this contest. She drilled quite a few threes from the catch as well as off the dribble. I was surprised that the Warriors didn\'t go to her more in the fourth quarter when the game started to slip away from them because she was doing her thing on offense. She has a good handle and a quick first step that forces the defense to respect her drive. It\'s really tough to guard her in isolation. The junior shooting guard is a really nice foil to Smith in the back court who is more of a playmaking point guard. Roberts is poised for a big season.','5 Takeaways: Dallas Mavericks Fall Classic Championship Game','','publish','open','open','','5-takeaways-dallas-mavericks-fall-classic-championship-game','','','2019-11-18 09:00:34','2019-11-18 15:00:34','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114055',0,'post','',0),
	(114056,1,'2019-11-17 19:11:59','2019-11-18 01:11:59','<span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">Prep Girls Hoops takes a look at the upcoming season in Kansas City area’s Big Six Gold.</span>\n\n<b>Big Six Gold</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Blue Springs (13-12,6-4), Blue Springs South (15-12, 6-4), Lee’s Summit North (5-20, 2-8), Lee’s Summit West (20-7, 10-0), Park Hill (14-12, 6-4), Raymore-Peculiar (6-20, 0-10).</span>\n\n<b>Saneea Bevley, 5’6, SG, 2022, Blue Springs South</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Bevly has a great feel for the perimeter and is dangerous as a scorer and facilitator. She has a great rhythm to her game and has a good bounce and ability to shake off opponents and create opportunities. Bevley can also create with her dribble and is a strong defensive player in full-court situations.</span>\n\n<b>Ja’Cole Johnson, 5’4, G, 2022, Blue Springs</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Another young guard for Blue Springs who looks to contribute wherever she can. Johnson has good speed and can handle the ball and can connect from distance from the top of the key in the wing spot. She shows a lot of promise as a catch-and-shoot scorer and is highly active on the defensive end and has good footwork and athleticism needed to come away with the ball on the defensive side of the floor.</span>\n\n<b>Tasia Johnson, 5’5, 2022, Lee’s Summit West</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A nice young player for Lee\'s Summit West, Johnson emerged last season showing speed a well-rounded skill-set and the ability to score. She has good handles for her age and shows a lot of potential with the ball in her hands. Johnson averaged 6.7 points, 2 rebounds and nearly two steals a game last season. </span>\n\n<b>Preslee Noirfalie, 5’9, G, 2022, Raymore-Peculiar</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Noirfalie is a strong young guard who can come away with the ball and finish on the opposite end. She has an eye for openings, is a good passer and can create some with her dribble and operate as a slasher and off ball scorer. She shows good movement and has strong hands and can get a hand on the ball and create some problems on the defensive side. </span>\n\n<b>Kennedy Townsend, 5’9, G, 2022, Park Hill</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">An elite young guard for Park Hill who earned first-team all-conference and first-team all-district honors as a freshman. She has solid playmaking skills with the ball and shows a creative nature and a high ceiling and basketball IQ. She looks to compete on both ends of the floor and can rip the ball away from opponents and finish through contact on the opposite end. Also a strong shooter who can connect from several feet behind the 3-point line as well as the mid-range area. </span>','PREVIEW: Big Six Gold\'s Top Sophomores to Watch','','publish','open','open','','preview-big-six-golds-top-sophomores-to-watch','','','2019-11-17 19:11:59','2019-11-18 01:11:59','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114056',0,'post','',0),
	(114059,1,'2019-11-18 12:00:15','2019-11-18 18:00:15','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Prep Girls Hoops takes a look at the upcoming season in Kansas City area’s Big Six Gold.</span>\n\n<b>Big Six Gold\n</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Blue Springs (13-12,6-4), Blue Springs South (15-12, 6-4), Lee’s Summit North (5-20, 2-8), Lee’s Summit West (20-7, 10-0), Park Hill (14-12, 6-4), Raymore-Peculiar (6-20, 0-10).</span>\n\n<b>Lauren Draney, 5’9, G/F, 2021, Lee’s Summit North</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">An active player who can show up on both sides of the floor. She can operate on the perimeter and can go inside and score. Draney has the ability to play on the wing and can connect from a distance and also the mid-range area and can get to the free-throw line and score as well </span>\n\n<b>Jordan Austin, 5’9, G/F, 2021, Park Hill</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Austin really showcases her talent on the defensive side of the floor. She is active and keeps her hands up and looks to block shots and jump passing Lanes. She\'s also a good transition player and can finish through contact. She\'s physical and looks to play aggressive and make teams play carelessly with the ball.</span>\n\n<b>Lauren Gillig, 6’0, F, 2021, Blue Springs South</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A nice shot blocking forward who has good overall size and Link. She\'s listed at 6\'0 and can secure rebounds and force opponents to challenge. Gillig also has the ability to score from deep and can knock down shots with a hand in her face. We look for her tab a big season. </span>\n\n<b>Aliyah Green, 6’2, F/C, 2021, Raymore-Peculiar</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A nice post player for Raymore-Peculiar who can extend plays with her outside shooting and mid-range jumpers. Green is a strong defensive presence and looks to block shots and forced turnovers. She is creative as a scorer and is quick to shoot after the catch. She has some good post moves and can operate from the low and high post. A flexible player with good athleticism and overall size. </span>\n\n<b>Abby Massengill, 6’0, F, 2021, Lee’s Summit West</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A strong forward for Lee\'s Summit West who can handle herself on both sides of the ball as a score and shot-blocking option near the basket. Massengill has good awareness and looks to keep her eyes on the play and contest shots at all cost. She\'s also a good rebounder as a defender and can rebound on the offensive end and cleanup plays. </span>','PREVIEW: Big Six Gold Top Juniors to Watch','','publish','open','open','','preview-big-six-gold-top-juniors-to-watch','','','2019-11-18 12:00:15','2019-11-18 18:00:15','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114059',0,'post','',0),
	(114065,1,'2019-11-19 12:00:50','2019-11-19 18:00:50','<b>PREVIEW: Big Six Gold</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Prep Girls Hoops takes a look at the upcoming season in Kansas City area’s Big Six Gold.</span>\n\n<b>Big Six Gold</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Blue Springs (13-12,6-4), Blue Springs South (15-12, 6-4), Lee’s Summit North (5-20, 2-8), Lee’s Summit West (20-7, 10-0), Park Hill (14-12, 6-4), Raymore-Peculiar (6-20, 0-10).</span>\n\n<b>Aliyah Bello, 5’9, G/F, 2020, Blue Springs</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A first-team all-conference and all-district performer who shows up on both sides of the floor and makes an immediate impact. Bello has great depth to her game and looks to score quickly and forced turnovers. She has an ability to break down opponents and defensive schemes and always seems to find an opening and get the balance. She has good vision as well and is a strong facilitator and unselfish player to boot.</span>\n\n<b>Elizabeth Ernsting, 2020, Blue Springs South </b><b>@eernsting121</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A William Jewell commit, Ernsting put together a strong summer playing for the Kansas Elite 17U White team this past offseason after putting together a solid junior season for BSS. She has a smooth left handed shot with range out to the 3-point line but also is a terrific shot blocker, rebounder and able to post up and score in the paint.</span>\n\n<b>Lily Queen, 5’5, G, 2020, Blue Springs</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">An active player on both sides of the floor, Queen can find her stroke from behind the three-point line and shows strong awareness as a defender. She moves her feet and looks to stay in front of opponents and can contest shots and even come away with the ball. She can handle it some for herself and looks to shoot when she has an opening and makes good passes as well. </span>\n\n<b>Charli Ritchey, 5’9, G, 2020, Lee’s Summit West</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ritchey is a smart guard who does a little bit of everything on the floor. She can handle the ball and can operate as a slasher and playmaker when she drives to the basket. She can connect from a distance and shows activity in a variety of ways on the defensive side and on the boards. Also a good 3-point shooter from the corner and wing spot.</span>\n\n<b>Marissa Ritchey, 5’9, G, 2020, Lee’s Summit West</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A good guard for Lee\'s Summit West who can handle the ball some and operate as a scoring guard. She can connect from a distance and has good timing coming off screens and looking for shots. Ritchey is an all-around player who hustles to the ball and applies good defense on the perimeter while having the size 2 switch out on post players and defend on the block some. Ritchey averaged nearly seven points per game and two rebounds last season.</span>\n\n<b>Jayla Sample, 5’7, G, 2020, Blue Springs</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">An electric senior guard who has great handles and the ability to get inside and score over taller opponents. She has good athleticism and news off the ball well and can score from distance and also look sharp as a defender on the perimeter who switches off opponents quickly and looks to create problems for opponents dribbling.</span>\n\n<b>Teresa Thomas, 5’7, F, 2020, Park Hill</b>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Thomas is a bit of an undersized interior player who uses her speed, quickness and aggressiveness to her advantage. She runs the floor exceptionally well, works hard on the defensive end to get around bigger players and is a quick leaper, able to grab offensive rebounds and easy put backs. She has a soft touch around the basket and is able to score over and around bigger players.</span>','PREVIEW: Big Six Gold Top Seniors','','publish','open','open','','preview-big-six-gold-top-seniors','','','2019-11-19 12:00:50','2019-11-19 18:00:50','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114065',0,'post','',0),
	(114068,1,'2019-11-18 12:00:41','2019-11-18 18:00:41','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After a strong offseason, Tipton 2020 guard Abby Backes is gearing up for a big senior season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">At 5’5, Backes is capable of playing either guard spot and is an aggressive player at both ends of the floor. She enjoys controlling the game at the point and works hard at the defensive end of the court.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">She was a part of a Cardinal team that lost in the Elite Eight her sophomore year and helped lead the team to a 28-2 and an appearance at sectionals last season. Backes averaged 21.4 points and 3.8 assists per game as a junior. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">She spent the offseason competing for the Missouri Phenom 17U squad and says the experience helped her take her game to another level.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“It was my first year for them and I honestly learned a lot and felt more mature on the court,” she said. “It allowed me to play against some girls on a higher level and better prepared me for college.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Backes says her Tipton team has high expectations this season with four of five starters returning.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“After coming up short in playoffs the past two years, were looking to make a huge run this year,” Backes said. “Our work ethic and hunger is there so we’re just looking to take it day by day. We added Bolivar and Mid Buchanan to our schedules, which are both solid programs and it’ll be a good test for us this year.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Backes says her sister Rachel and dad have had the biggest influence on her basketball career to date. She says her high school coach</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Family wise, my sister and my dad have been the biggest influencers as far as teaching me the game and how to work hard in every moment on and off the court,” she says. “My high school basketball coach has also impacted me in more ways than I can count. He’s shaped my game and character the past 3 years and has made me love basketball even more! All three of these people have never stopped being my biggest fans and I couldn’t imagine it any other way.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Backes says she grew up watching her older sister Rachel Backes play at Westminster.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I literally always wanted to be like her,” she said. “Her court vision and toughness were the biggest things that stuck out to me, and I’m always working to be like her.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Backes recently committed to Columbia College and says the choice was an easy one for her.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Coach Possail runs a great program and I can’t wait to be a part of it,” she said. “The energy and aggressiveness that he implements into his team stuck out to me right away, as well as the family atmosphere. I’m excited to start this next chapter and hope to bring lots of success with my new teammates.”</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Abby Backes (2020)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-abby-backes-2020','','','2019-11-18 12:00:41','2019-11-18 18:00:41','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114068',0,'post','',0),
