	(114077,1,'2019-11-20 05:00:20','2019-11-20 11:00:20','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">One of the state’s premier  returning players in the 2020 class, Lincoln College Prep guard Amari Conn is hoping for a full return this season after suffering a season-ending injury in the state playoffs last season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">The TCU commit is a 5’7 guard who enjoys playing a fast paced game, brings intensity at the defensive end of the court and plays an unselfish game. She averaged 14.5 points per game last season and helped her team advanced to the state championship. She suffered an ACL in the team’s regional contest, but was on hand to root for her team.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Being on the bench cheering them on was something I learned from,” Conn said. “I knew we could do it if we just put our all in.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Conn didn’t play during the offseason as she focused on her rehab and said the experience has been tough at times and hopes she will be able to come back in time for the second half of her senior season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Preparation for this season through rehab has been tough,” she says. “Some nights I still cry because I wish it never happened but other times I push through because it happened for a reason. So let’s hope I play second half of my senior season.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Lincoln has high hopes for the upcoming season at Lincoln and says there are several games on the schedule in 2020 that she is looking forward to.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Most of our hard games are in the second half because I won’t be able to play the first half,” she said. “I am looking forward to Bishop Miege because they always test us on our skills. There one of the hardest teams out here. My expectations aren’t very high this season just because I’m coming off an injury so I know my brace and knee has to get use to it. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“But it’s all just a mind game for me. So I’ll do my best this season so I can be healthy for college ball.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Conn says the biggest influence on her basketball career has been her parents.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“They have sacrificed so much for me and I want to be the best for them and myself,” Conn said. “I want to be better than they were in college. Another person that pushes me is my cousin Anthony who passed away. I always do it for him.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A fan of NBA guards Jamal Crawford and Derrick Rose and says she tries to implemennt several of their most popular moves.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“They’re some of the most slept on players in the league and so am I,” Conn said. “There quick on their feet and nice with the ball. I always try to implement their jab and jab cross. Or step back (hesitation).”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Conn says she fell in love with TCU the first time she stepped on campus and says the staff has made her feel welcome at her future home.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“They connected with me and my family,” she said. “Their basketball program is my style. Fast paced, pass cut, dribble drive. I am hoping to bring energy, aggressiveness and just an all around player to their program.”</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Amari Conn (2020)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-amari-conn-2020','','','2019-11-20 05:00:20','2019-11-20 11:00:20','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114077',0,'post','',0),
	(114084,1,'2019-11-20 12:00:40','2019-11-20 18:00:40','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After a strong offseason with Team Blackout, Columbia College recruit Mallory Shetley is gearing up for a big senior season for Sullivan.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A versatile 6-footer, Shetley takes pride in being able to play any position and bring to her team whatever is needed in the moment. She can bring the ball up the floor, score in the paint and is a hard worker who takes pride in being an example on the floor and off.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I am very passionate and do whatever it takes to help my team succeed,” she says.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Shetley played with her older sister Clare Shetley and Bria Jones, who are both currently playing at Columbia College, and helped Sullivan go 17-8 last season. She averaged 17 points, six rebounds and just under three blocks per game as a junior.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Tell us about your high school season last year. How did things end, how do you feel you did, throw some numbers in there if you know them, PPG, etc.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I feel that I had a good season, but I could have done many things better,” she said. “We ended the season on a close district loss to Owensville 38-39. We didn’t show up ready to play and they did. It made us learn what we need to work on and fuel the team for this season.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After putting together a strong offseason running with Team Blackout, Shetley says the experience of playing with the grassroots program the past seven years has helped her expand her game.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“My experience from summer ball with Blackout has helped me tremendously,” she said. “My coach Andy Cheesman always focused on the fundamentals and getting better every practice. This past year my coaches for Blackout changed to my dad, Blaine, and Kevin Williams, but the expectations didn’t change. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“We always work on fundamentals and learning from every experience. We play tough competition that pushes me to be mentally tough and play hard all the time.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Expectations at Sullivan are high this upcoming season as the program returns four starters from last year’s squad.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I expect us to make a good run for a District Championship and to go even further,” Shetley said. “All games are big games but I am especially looking forward to our matchups against conference rivals St. Clair and Owensville. St. Clair is always a good team and very competitive and is a huge rival. Owensville was who ended our season last year and I am looking forward to another chance to play them.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Shetley says the biggest influence on her basketball career to date has been her dad.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“He pushed me from the beginning. We set goals together and hold each other accountable, setting new goals as each is achieved,” she said. “He tells me after games what I need to work on to take my game to the next level. He makes sure that I am never satisfied with where I am, always looking for ways to improve. He talks to me about the mental part of the game and how training your mind is very important. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Being mentally tough can give you the upper hand on an opponent. He takes time out of his busy work schedule to work with me to make me the best I can be. He makes sure to be at as many games as he can, no matter how busy he gets. He has been my coach for two summers for summer ball. He is picky about my game but always makes sure I know that he is proud of me.” </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A fan of Orgeon’s Sabrina Ionescu, Shetley says she appreciates her hard work and motor on the floor.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“She is an extremely hard worker who gives her all no matter what,” Shetley said. “Standing at just 5’11 she does it all. She has the all-time NCAA triple double record and still has her senior year left. She looks to score, looks to get her team involved, and hustles to get rebounds. I try to implement her work ethic into my game. Also I try to look for my teammates and hustle for every ball like she does.” </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Shetley recently signed to continue her basketball career at Columbia College.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Columbia stuck out to me immediately,” she says. “I had gone on some other visits but Columbia had everything I wanted. They have an outstanding coaching staff, great team atmosphere and chemistry. I felt like part of the family very quickly. I hope to bring my work ethic and passion for the game to the team. They are a high level basketball team looking to win a national title, I would like to help make that happen. I am excited to be there next season!”</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Mallory Sheltey (2020)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-mallory-sheltey-2020','','','2019-11-20 12:00:40','2019-11-20 18:00:40','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114084',0,'post','',0),
	(114091,1,'2019-11-18 12:00:59','2019-11-18 18:00:59','As high school games begin this week here in Illinois, I wanted to highlight a group of teams that contain ‘Dynamic Duos’ throughout the area. Now more specifically, I looked for teams that I know have talented Point Guards, and one other high-level player on the team. There are most definitely teams with two dynamic players who aren’t Point Guards, but for this particular article I wanted to include those Floor Generals!\n\nOne of the preseason favorites in the Chicagoland area, Evanston returns a great deal of talent. Among those are standout Point Guard <strong>Kayla Henning</strong> and Forward <strong>Jayla Turchin</strong>. Henning’s ability to handle the ball and lead an offense matched with Turchin’s capability to score efficiently at all levels makes this duo so effective.  The Seniors, along with a host of others, look bounce back from a Sectional Championship loss a year ago and get the Wildkits to the State Tournament.\n\nGeneva’s <strong>Kate Palmer</strong> and <strong>Lindsay Blackmore</strong> will be a huge part of the Vikings success this season. Palmer, a Junior Point Guard, can handle and shoot the ball very well from both mid-range and beyond the three-point line. Blackmore, a Senior Colgate commit, is a strong post player who is tough to match up against. She does thrive in the lane but can also knock down shots from deep.\n\nAs a young team that made it to the Sectional Championship last season, Montini’s eyes are on Redbird Arena this year. Third Team All-State Point Guard <strong>Sophie Sullivan</strong> (2022) is a sure ball handler that can catch fire from three any given night. Her Sophomore teammate, <strong>Taylor Charles</strong>, is an athletic Forward that can play and guard any position using her length and quickness. Charles drives it well in the lane and can also knock down mid-range jumpers.\n\nAnother team looking to get back to the State Tournament next Spring, Whitney Young has as much talent as anyone. Senior Point Guard and Texas A&amp;M commit <strong>Kayla Green</strong> is one of the top PG’s in the state. Her ability to win one-on-one against nearly any defender and make things happen in the lane is unparalleled. Green’s Senior teammate <strong>Cameron Williams</strong>, a Michigan commit, is a 6’2” athletic post who is a tough matchup due to her strength and dominant post-game.\n\nLast year’s State Champion Maine West lost some valuable pieces last season, but brings back the dominant duo of <strong>Dylan Van Fleet</strong> and <strong>Angela Dugalic</strong>. Van Fleet, a Senior Point Guard, thrives on the defensive end, disrupting passing lanes and leading the transition offense. Dugalic, an Oregon commit, is perhaps the most dominant player in the state and has added to her offensive skillset since last season. She can shoot it well from outside, but at 6’4”, her athletic post moves make her nearly unguardable.\n\nFremd’s <strong>Emily Klaczek</strong> is another top Point Guard in Illinois. The UAB commit is a strong PG that can get in the lane with ease and absorb contact well, in addition to being a plus shooter from outside.  Klaczek’s Senior teammate <strong>Olivia Hill, </strong>a Bowling Green commit, is a lengthy Forward that can score in a variety of ways. Both girls were named to All-State teams last season and will be key pieces to Fremd’s success once again.','Dynamic Duos: Part 1','','publish','open','open','','dynamic-duos-part-1','','','2019-11-18 12:00:59','2019-11-18 18:00:59','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114091',0,'post','',0),
	(114114,1,'2019-11-17 23:15:17','2019-11-18 05:15:17','October 27th was our first Prep Girls Hoops Top 250 Expo in Iowa. It was the last of four this fall and we had an insane amount of talented players in the gym. We will be finishing up our Expo reviews today with the last two teams. Now, we have a look at our last team as we look back at Team 16.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong>Mary Kate King - 5\'5 PG - 2021 - Wahlert Catholic HS (IA)</strong>\nKing was a guard who I hadn\'t seen prior to the event but came away very impressed. She is a very solid guard who isn\'t afraid to take the ball into traffic. Her handling ability is good and she can take her defender off the bounce to the rim. King had a very good day at the Top 250.\n\n<strong>Maddax DeVault - 5\'6 G - 2022 - Nodawway Valley HS (IA)</strong>\nDeVault is a very good guard who can play both on and off-the-ball really well. She moves well without the ball and cuts to the basket really well. A lot of the time guards seem to stagnate but DeVault does not. She has a high basketball IQ and just simply makes plays on both ends of the floor.\n\n<strong>MaKayla Boatman - 5\'7 SG - 2023 - North Polk HS (IA)</strong>\nBoatman is a physical defender who looks to be aggressive on that end of the floor. She was continually making plays on the defensive end and with her skill she can turn turnovers into offense rather quickly. Boatman showed a very good ability to shoot the ball from distance as well.\n\n<strong>Jenna Twedt - 5\'8 SF - 2023 - Benton HS (IA)</strong>\nTwedt is a player who I hadn\'t seen and I was very happy with how she played for a freshman. She has a good frame with the ability to gain strength which will make her even stronger on the floor. Twedt plays with a very good motor and should be able to see the floor this upcoming winter.\n\n<strong>Samantha Stewart - 5\'8 SG - 2020 - Mount Ayr HS (IA)</strong>\nStewart can score from anywhere on the floor and was among the best pure scorers in the event, regardless of class. Her shot from the outside looked solid and she was able to get into the mid-range and hit off of the bounce. She changes speed with the ball in her hands really well and she performed tremendously.\n\n<strong>Kamryn Grissel - 5\'9 SF - 2022 - Cedar Rapids Prairie HS (IA)</strong>\nGrissel has really improved all summer long and she showed her continued improvement especially off the catch. Grissel has a ton of length and she uses that length to play very good defense. She is very versatile with her length and skill allowing her to play multiple spots on the floor.\n\n<strong>Carlee Rochford - 5\'10 SF - 2023 - New Hampton HS (IA)</strong>\nRochford wasn\'t out on the AAU circuit this spring and I was excited she could make it to the showcase. I thought she played extremely well and she\'s going to end up being one of the top 2023\'s in the state. Rochford is a very athletic wing capable of getting to the basket and scoring. In the short time she was there I saw multiple good things from her.\n\n<strong>Annika Richardson - 5\'11 F - 2021 - Northfield HS (MN)</strong>\nRichardson was one of the two Minnesota kids at the event and she played tremendously well. I thought that she got to the basket and scored well and she also was able to rebound the ball as well as anyone at the event, despite being four inches shorter than a teammate. Richardson has a good nose for the ball and showed it all day long.\n\n<strong>Jorja Hanselman - 6\' PF - 2021 - Van Meter HS (IA)</strong>\nOut of everyone that I saw this summer in the 2021 class, Hanselman might be the most improved player from last year. Hanselman is loaded with all the intangibles that you can\'t teach. She is vocal on the floor and the bench, she plays with a high motor, and she rebounds at a high level. I wouldn\'t be surprised to see her grab a wealth of college interest going forward.\n\n<strong>Lucy Schonlau - 6\'3 C - 2023 - Duchesne Academy HS (NE)</strong>\nSchonlau was the most intriguing player at the Expo because of her size. Most of the time when you see a 6\'3 freshman, they are very awkward. Schonlau is not awkward at all and seems very comfortable in her frame. She rebounded well, showed good skill around the basket, and impressed me overall. I think she has the potential to turn into something very special depending on how hard she works the next few years.','PGH Top 250 Review: Team 16','','publish','open','open','','pgh-top-250-review-team-16','','','2019-11-17 23:15:17','2019-11-18 05:15:17','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114114',0,'post','',0),
	(114131,1,'2019-11-18 09:30:21','2019-11-18 15:30:21','The 2019-20 high school basketball regular season is set to get underway this month. For some teams, they tip-off this week while others will start next week. The Southern California area is full of talent and this season should be a good one.\n\nI’ll be looking at schools in the CIF Division 1 from the areas that I’ll be covering at various points this season and highlighting a few players to look out for. These players aren’t necessarily stars on the team. Some of them might be, but others are key cogs that will play an important role on the team’s success this year.\n\nHere’s a look at some of those players.\n\n<strong>1. Camryn Kiernan – Mater Dei 2020</strong>\n\nAn incoming senior, Kiernan recently committed to Concordia University. There is a lot of talent on this Mater Dei team, and Kiernan is a player who can fit in to any role that the team needs. She is a glue player who does a lot of little things that don’t always show up on a stat sheet. She plays solid defense, she dives on the floor for loose balls, she rebounds well, and she can get a bucket if needed. Solid outside shooter.\n\n<strong>2. Kalaya Buggs – Long Beach Poly 2021</strong>\n\nBuggs is an incoming junior and has drawn some interest from a few colleges with an offer from Long Beach State. She is a solid all-around player on both ends of the floor. Offensively, she can shoot from the perimeter and she can attack the rim and finish strong. Working on becoming a stronger playmaker. Defensively, she has the tools to be a solid wing defender.\n\n<strong>3. Alexis Mead – ML King 2021</strong>\n\nMead is a tenacious defensive player and as the team’s point guard, she really sets the tone for the defensive intensity and physicality that the entire team plays with. She is a strong on ball defender and she is capable of matching up with players bigger than her. Offensively, she probes the defense well and picks when to attack and when to facilitate. Good court awareness and vision. Strong outside shooter.\n\n<strong>4. Calli Stokes – Redondo Union 2021</strong>\n\nStokes size and foot speed allows for her to be a versatile defensive player. She is capable of matching up against bigs in the paint and she can stay with wings on the perimeter and contest all the way to the basket. Scoring-wise, she can put the ball on the floor and make plays off the dribble. She also moves very well without the ball and makes strong cuts to the rim to be the recipient of a teammate’s pass.\n\n<strong>5. Nicole Rodriguez – Rosary 2020</strong>\n\nRodriguez is an incoming senior and recently committed to Loyola Marymount. She is a strong player on both ends of the court. She is a solid perimeter defender and contests shots well. Offensively, she is a lights out shooter if left open. She spots up well and is always ready to catch a pass. She can put the ball on the floor too and she has a nice pull-up jumper. Can shoot also with defenders in her face.','CIF Southern Section Division 1 Players to Watch Pt. 2','','publish','open','open','','cif-southern-section-division-1-players-to-watch-pt-2','','','2019-11-18 09:30:21','2019-11-18 15:30:21','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114131',0,'post','',0),
	(114175,1,'2019-11-18 07:58:19','2019-11-18 13:58:19','<strong>Isabel Reemsnyder </strong>is determined to leave her mark in high school basketball this season, and she appears ready to do just that. She\'s a 5\'10\" small forward from Mason High School and plays grassroots basketball with Elite Nation Basketball (ENB). <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>has played in the post most of her career but is transitioning to the wing/perimeter this season.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-114187\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/840699724e4a96321c9c536588642b02-1-300x157.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"157\" />\n\n<strong>Reemsnyder </strong>is an impressive player. Her leadership is irreplaceable. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>tries to set an example for her teammates. She calls out the offensive plays and defensive adjustments, all while continuously encouraging other players. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>has a high basketball IQ. Many coaches around Michigan call her a student of the game. She wants to know everyone\'s responsibilities on both ends. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>is always aware of where her teammates are and where they\'re supposed to be. She relentlessly studies her opponents. This helps her put her team in position to be successful. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>has great footwork on the basketball court. She uses her footwork in the paint to gain an advantage on both ends. Her game has evolved, and her quick feet have allowed her to be versatile and guard multiple positions.\n\n<strong>Reemsnyder </strong>is focused on her continued growth as a player. She is working to improve her speed to help her guard perimeter players in open space. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>is also improving as a shooter and ball handler. She wants to be a threat to score from any level at any time.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114190\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-114190\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_20191118_072731-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" /> Isabel Reemsnyder C/O Elite Nation Basketball[/caption]\n\n<strong>Reemsnyder </strong>cherishes the memories that basketball creates, but stays focused on what\'s ahead. Her best basketball moment came in her freshman season against Battle Creek Lakeview. She was so nervous before the game that she was physically shaking. The game was tied with less than 5 seconds left in overtime when she secured a rebound and was fouled. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>went to the free throw line and buried both shots to seal the victory. She said she will always remember the feeling of her older teammates celebrating with her and hugging her after the win. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>isn\'t looking forward to the next big game though. She just wants to play \"the next game\". She sees an opportunity to her and her team to improve every time out on the court.\n\n<strong>Reemsnyder </strong>should get some serious looks from colleges this season. She has been invited to a lot of elite camps and has seen some interest from schools. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>will provide a college coach with a vocal prescense and leadership. She will provide a team at the next level with a versatile and well rounded player that can shoot, defend, and rebound.\n\n<strong>Reemsnyder </strong>is driven by her goals. She wants to change the way her high school program has been viewed in the past. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>has made it a point to continue to be versatile and do whatever it takes for her team to win. She wants to be remembered in her community by helping to lay down a foundation for a strong girls basketball program at Mason High School. <strong>Reemsnyder </strong>is eyeing a future as a college basketball player. She wants to become a special education teacher after college.\n\n<strong>Reemsnyder </strong>is motivated by her Mom and Dad to be great at whatever she does.\n\n\"Hands down my Mom and Dad. Without them, the passion and drive I have to succeed would be nonexistent. They push me past what I think I\'m capable of every day.\" - <strong>Isabel Reemsnyder</strong>','Prospect Spotlight:  Isabel Reemsnyder (2021)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-isabel-reemsnyder-2021','','','2019-11-18 07:58:19','2019-11-18 13:58:19','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114175',0,'post','',0),
	(114189,1,'2019-11-18 11:35:55','2019-11-18 17:35:55','Two weeks and four wins into the new season, undefeated UN-Kearney &amp; USD look strong, ahead of the pack, fueled by SD &amp; MN talents (aided by Iowa &amp; Nebraska sisterhoods).\n\nUN-Kearney took down UM-Crookston &amp; Wayne State from the NSIC a week ago, with strong defense and shooting from <strong>STM\'s  Klaire Kirsch &amp; Brandon Valley\'s Trinity Law.  Lopers have great depth, with ten players seeing 10+ minutes/game. </strong>\n\n<strong>Sophomore Kirsch scores 6.5 points/game. has 12 steals on the year, 5 rebounds per game, and 3 assists per game.  High intensity on the bench and the floor, her specialty involves racing around a dribbler, and taking the rock back for sudden-change offense.</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114326\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-114326\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Lopers-vs-UM-Crookston-110619-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Kirsch to the Rim - photo courtesy of UN-Kearney staff[/caption]\n\nFreshman Law lifts her team with faster-than-the-eye-can-see-defense, and 54% marksmanship, hitting 7 of 13 from the perimeter.  At 5-7, and only 12 minutes per game, her zig-zag bursts confuse, confound, and frustrate defenses.  Law\'s floor time is increasing, game-by-game, earned from hard nosed performances.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114329\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-114329\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Law-Slashing-to-Hoop-300x285.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"285\" /> Law Slashing To The Hoop - photo courtesy of UN-Kearney staff[/caption]\n\nUN-Kearney finished another two game sweep Saturday, whacking Rocky Mountain Athletic Conference opponents. All in preparation for the tough MIAA winter battles against fun nicknames: Griffons, Jennies, Ichabods, Hillcats, and Blue Tigers. <em><strong>L</strong><strong style=\"font-size: 1rem\">opers Rule !!</strong></em>\n\nUN-Kearney &amp; USD both have former Crofton, NE, &amp; STM players now as teammates. Crofton fans willingly brag about their winning record over STM at the Hanson Classic over recent years.  Kirsch &amp;<strong> Kelsey Sanger</strong> (Jr) start for the Lopers, while<strong> Ciara Duffy &amp; Monica Arens</strong> star for USD, the top-ranked mid-major, which won over Utah (Pac-12) in OT on Saturday.\n\nThe Coyotes face Missouri 11/21 in Vermillion, the second of four Power Five troupes scheduled for 2019 - Ohio State in Las Vegas and off to South Carolina Dec 22nd.  <strong>Chloe Lamb of Sully Buttes HS (SD) and Madison McKeever of Winn-E-Mac HS (MN)</strong> join Duffy &amp; Arens as 35+-minutes/game stalwarts. In the post is <strong>Hannah Sjerven of Rogers HS (MN), splitting time with Taylor Frederick of Harlan (IA) HS</strong>. Sjerven\'s growth in toughness and grit is remarkable. She runs circles around 6\'-5\" beanpoles, jumps out to stop screen-n-rolls, and has happy feet with/without the ball. Off the bench,<strong> Liv Korngable of Rochester Mayo HS (MN) and Jeniah Ugofsky, Harrisburg HS (SD)</strong> contribute valuable minutes.  T\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114282\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-114282 size-medium\" title=\" photo courtesy of U\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/USD-Bench-at-Utah-111619-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" /> USD Bench in win over Utah 111619[/caption]\n\nTeamwise, the 83-pt/game average comes from drilling 47% from the floor, 16 assists/game, and 30 total thefts. USD\'s Summit League crown can be defended, and another postseason NCAA bid won with the athleticism and experienced playmaking shown early.\n\nGreat starts on special stories for two tenacious teams. Stay tuned.','SD & MN WBB Collegians Sparkle','','publish','open','open','','sd-mn-wbb-collegians-sparkle','','','2019-11-18 11:35:55','2019-11-18 17:35:55','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114189',0,'post','',0),
	(114240,1,'2019-11-18 11:18:46','2019-11-18 17:18:46','An impressive morning of basketball on Saturday, as Tri Village and Delphos St. John headed to Anna to collide in a three-way scrimmage as all three teams prepare to open their season this week. Opening Day in Ohio girls basketball is this Friday evening so this was one of the final times these three teams will take the floor in preparation for the start of the season.\n\n<strong>Vastly improved- </strong>I was impressed with the hard work and effort from the girls at Delphos St. John, as they showed some improvement over previous years. They play in one of the top small school conferences in the state of Ohio, and they are looking to compete with the talented teams every night in that league. Paige Gaynier was a player I was interested in seeing, after having seen her in a couple of events this summer. Paige <span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><strong>(pictured above) </strong></span>was a kid who really got after it, was a solid on-ball defender, can shoot from deep range and was a good floor leader. She stood out in the scrimmage when I was there.\n\n<strong>Glad to have her back- </strong>Everyone saw what the talented team from Tri Village did last year, making a run at the regionals in Division Four. They return all of their key components except for the big loss of Emma Printz to graduation. They also bring in two talented freshmen who will make an immediate impact. One player who fans did not see last year and I feel could be the key to their success is the return of Trissa Porter. The senior guard missed last season due to a medical issue, but she is back and brings a lot of steadiness and control to the team on the floor. Handles the ball well under pressure and is a major threat from the perimeter. She is a huge piece to their puzzle.\n\n<strong>Anna wants a big tourney run- </strong>Division Three basketball in this area is open for the taking, and one of the teams looking to challenge deep into the tournament are the Rockets. They have a lot of weapons both inside and out, and will challenge for a solid tourney run. Ella Doseck is a junior guard who handles the ball well, can score from the perimeter, but isn\'t flashy. She just gets it done. Lauren Barhorst is a 6-foot-2 presence on the boards, can run the floor well and finish at the rim. Another one to watch is Kip Rowland, a multidimensional player who can score inside or out. Solid, balanced team.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Anna, Tri Village and Delphos St. John tri-scrimmage on Saturday','','publish','open','open','','anna-tri-village-and-delphos-st-john-tri-scrimmage-on-saturday','','','2019-11-18 11:18:46','2019-11-18 17:18:46','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114240',0,'post','',0),
	(114280,1,'2019-11-20 13:50:45','2019-11-20 19:50:45','<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">PGH Kansas Team Preview</span>\n\nAs we enter the 2019-20 high school basketball season in Kansas, we at Prep Girls Hoops will preview Kansas City Area schools.  Giving you details on key players, season expectations and more.\n\nIn this article, we look at <strong>Schlagle High School</strong> in Kansas City, Kansas. The Lady Stallions are coming off another KCAL Conference Championship, a 5A state appearance, and overall record of 19-6 in 2018-19.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Players to watch</strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Ishante Suttington, Guard, Senior, (2020)  </span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114281\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"150\"]<img class=\"wp-image-114281 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Ishante-1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /> <span style=\"font-size: 8pt\">Photo Cred: WYCO Daily </span>[/caption]\n\nA 5’9 combo guard and recent Hutchinson Community College Commit is coming off a great junior year campaign.  Her ability to penetrate the lane and finish through contact separates her from guards her size.  She possesses a deep shooting range that allows her another great option for scoring.  Ishante averaged 20pts, 4rbs, 3ast, and 2stls in 2018/2019 and will look to lead Schlagle back to state this season with her on court productivity.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Camille Evans, Guard, Senior, (2020)</span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114283\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"150\"]<img class=\"wp-image-114283 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Camille-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /> <span style=\"font-size: 8pt\">Photo Cred: WYCO Daily </span>[/caption]\n\nThe 5’8, unsigned senior point guard is one of the most underrated kids in the 2020 class.  Evans averaged 10pts, 7rbs, 6ast, and 4 steals in 2018/2019.  Camille is a quick guard with good handle and IQ.  She has great vision, which helps her read defenses and create for teammates.  A high level on ball defender, which allows her to disrupt opposing teams offenses.\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Tylieea Wallace, Power Forward/Center, Junior, (2021)</span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114284\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"150\"]<img class=\"wp-image-114284 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/T-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /> <span style=\"font-size: 8pt\">Photo Cred: WYCO Daily</span>[/caption]\n\nA six foot, physical post player will be another returning starter for the Lady Stallions.  Tylieea, a highly skilled big has some of the best footwork I’ve seen for a player of her size and age.  She finishes just as strong left as she does with her dominant right hand.  She has great hands, vision and high IQ for a interior player.  A great post defender and even better team defender.  Wallace is coming off of a summer playing high level AAU with KC Dream 2021, one of the top development programs in the Kansas City area.  She will look to increase her production this year as Schlagle looks make a run for another conference championship and Class 5A State appearance.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSchlagle is under 1st year head coach and former Kansas Jayhawk, Tyler Johnson.  With a strong returning core, and a good group of role players the Lady Stallions are picked to be one of the top teams in Kansas again this season.\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Upcoming Games</span></strong>\n\nSchlagle opens the season at home, on Tuesday December 10th, 2019 against Topeka High School.','Team Previews: Schlagle Lady Stallions','','publish','open','open','','team-previews-schlagle-lady-stallions','','','2019-11-20 13:50:45','2019-11-20 19:50:45','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114280',0,'post','',0),
	(114295,1,'2019-11-19 15:22:05','2019-11-19 21:22:05','Opening Week! Girls Hoops opens up for the season this week, and I know everyone is excited for the year to begin. I spent every night last week (after my full-time job) attending preseason games, and I wanted to share some things that I took away from all of this early action. Here are five of my takeaways from what I personally saw this week:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>Florida HAS Talent</strong></span>\n\nThere is so much talent in the state of Florida when it comes to girls hoops. This is something that should be known statewide and nationwide. Florida has about 50-55 Division 1 commitments each year on average. It is typically a similar number for NAIA and maybe half that number goes D2 with a few less going D3. However, the vast majority of our Florida girls will go to a JUCO. That is a lot of players and a lot of talent to keep track of. I am going to do my best to bring exposure to all of these incredible ladies.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>Tampa Bay Tech is the Team to Beat</strong></span>\n\nThis season, Florida has two teams in the top 25 (depending where you look) with Tampa Bay Tech and Miami Country Day. I got to witness Tech dominate during preseason with a solid squad who will by vying for national attention all year. Sophomore <strong>Janiah Barker</strong> is one of the best players in the country with her shot blocking, rebounding, and ability to score at all three levels. Junior <strong>Jasmine Peaks</strong> had a solid stroke and smooth handles. Sophomore <strong>Amiya Evans</strong> dominated the paint. Junior <strong>Jayla Murray</strong> played great defense and hit her free throws. Junior <strong>K\'Nisha Godfrey</strong> did a little bit of everything well. This team is loaded, and I only mentioned their starters (no seniors) as they have some nice bench players, too. But like I said, there is SO much talent in the state.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>I Saw Quality Teams</strong></span>\n\nI only saw each of these teams play one game, so I wouldn\'t read much into these rankings. I was impressed with the play I saw from these ten:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>1. Tampa Bay Tech (6A)</strong> - See above for my reasoning here. They are ranked Top 10 nationally anywhere you look (6th by MaxPreps and 10th by USA Today). They outscored their opponents 141-13 in their two preseason games. Tech is looking to repeat at State Champions again this year.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>2. Florida Prep (2A</strong>) - They started off slow in the game I saw, but they are going to have a tremendous season with the amount of length and height they have. Florida Prep beat two nice squads with Braden River taking it to OT and a new-look Santa Fe Catholic team. They have one of the best Freshman in the state with 6-footer <em>Emma Risch</em> who is known as a shooter, but she rebounds and passes awfully well, too. In preseason play, Ole Miss product <em>Aleah Sorrentino</em> (who is back from injury) looked really smooth for not playing in such a long time. Aleah was strong around the hoop, and she can shoot it from anywhere. So. <em>Shamya Joiner</em> showed some great energy, and is an incredible teammate on both ends of the floor. FL Prep added even more size/length with <em>Emani Burks</em> who should be on all college\'s radars with the athleticism she has at her size. The Falcons play a very tough schedule, and are favorites to repeat as 2A State Champs after winning last year\'s title by 32 points.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>3. Braden River (6A) - </strong><em>O\'Mariah Gordon</em> was the best player I saw this week. She put up an impressive 77 points between the two preseason games. They also have Julia Rodriguez who is a D1 commit (Kennesaw St) that doesn\'t get enough credit. The Pirates lost last year in the Regional Finals to Tampa Bay Tech who would go on to win it all.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>4. Southeast (Bradenton) (5A) - </strong>The Seminoles are going to make some noise this year. I saw them fight back from being down 12 points to an impressive Winter Haven team to get a 3-point win. <em>Perryouna Youmans</em> can flat out carry a team with her shooting and defense, and <em>Kayla McDuffie</em> has a beautiful shot. They aren\'t tall, but <em>Charmaine Murray</em> is a tough presence in the post who has nice touch around the rim. <em>Ce\'Mya Brooks</em> might the X-factor between this team being good or being great by leading them back to state with her court awareness and ability to take care of the rock. Southeast lost a tough game in the State Semifinals last year by 1 point to Bishop Kenny.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>5. Winter Haven (6A) </strong><em><strong>- </strong></em>The Lady Blue Devils were without <em>Trinity Hardy </em>in the game I saw, but they still looked very good with the addition of <em>Jaida Young</em>. The best player on the night I went was Sophomore <em>Kayla Smith</em> who can score at all three levels, and is looking to have a strong career. I expect Jr. <em>Jazmine Spencer</em>, Jr. <em>Shomari Phillips</em>, and Sr. <em>Shelby Ricks</em> to play big roles as leaders in this teams success. Winter Haven got knocked out in the  Regional Semi\'s last year, and I think they will be hungry to do more damage this season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>6. Brooks DeBartolo (3A) - </strong>The Phoenix are a tough squad that has a strong, complete lineup. They play fast, and they only have one senior on the team. Jr. <em>Amarie Godwin</em> is really who drove this offense with her playmaking ability, court vision, and basketball IQ.<em> Triniti Youngblood</em> is another Junior who can carry this team with her ability to score using her strong frame. Don\'t forget about another Junior in <em>Brionna McClinton</em> who was stroking from the deep corners during the game I witnessed. They didn\'t have Junior <em>Ayonna Simmons</em> in this one, but once she is back, they will be fully loaded. Two underclassmen really impressed me as well with <em>Jaela D</em>avis shooting the lights out, and using her quickness to create some turnovers. Freshman <em>Maia Lewers</em> is another name to keep an eye out for as she played like a veteran in this one. Brooks DeBartolo made it to the Regional Finals last year, and they are in a lower class this year. Expect some noise from them!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>7. West Orange (7A) - </strong>This Warriors team has a very balanced attack who was led by sharp shooting Senior <em>Camryn Siemer</em> in the game I watched. She had six threes as part of her game-high 26 total points. West Orange also features two of the best Sophomores in the state with 6\'3 <em>Paris Pickett</em> and <em>Ajalon Gillard</em>. Paris is a strong lefty who has nice touch and finish with her solid post moves. She is a beast on the boards, too. Ajalon is a crafty passer who sees the court, but can score with the best of them. Two Juniors in <em>Lakada Bryant</em> and <em>Kyla Cruz</em> make this team very well-rounded. Lakada is another strong post presence that plays hard, and Kyla did a little bit of everything which is exactly the type of teammate you want. West Orange will look to avenge a Regional Semifinals loss from last season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>8. Lakewood (4A) - </strong>This is my vote for the best team in Pinellas County. Lakewood lost a transfer in Olivia Delancy, but they are an athletic bunch that play hard. Senior <em>Macey Zeh-Ardnt</em> is one of the best posts in 4A ball, and they also have Junior <em>Nauvi Williams</em> that is an unreal athlete. Don\'t count out Sophomore <em>Reilly Webb</em> as she is one of the smartest players I\'ve seen on the court, and leaves everything out there too. The reclassification of Florida High School\'s helps Lakewood as they were bumped out in the Regional Semifinals to Southeast who is now a class higher than them.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>9. Santa Fe Catholic (3A) - </strong>The Lady Hawks can shoot the lights out. Zaria Lawrence might be their only true big (13 boards in the game I saw), but they also have some tall shooters, so their size in not in question. Their are four Juniors of this squad that will really dictate how this season goes. <em>Omega Payton</em> is a smooth, quick operator on the court. She can score at ease, dish the rock, and cause havoc on defense. <em>Kassidy Jones</em> is the most lethal scorer on this team who can score at all three levels, and she\'s got the height to create a lot of mismatches. A welcome addition of <em>Courtni Demorest</em> brings another tall shooter on this team who was on fire from behind the arc in her first preseason game. Last, but not least, is <em>Kirsten Grindel</em> who knows the game and is another sharp shooter. Did I mention that this team can shoot? I expect that Santa Fe Catholic will do a complete 180 from their 10-win season a year ago.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>10. Clearwater (5A) - </strong>I did not get to see <em>D\'Mya Ferguson</em> play this preseason, but they will be a strong team with the addition of some talented Freshman. That will help with the loss of two players, one to graduation and one transferred. Look for Freshmen <em>Liv Fuller</em> and <em>Ace Sturdivant</em> to step up for Clearwater and help D\'Mya out.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>Fundamentals/IQ are Key</strong></span>\n\nThese two things is what really separated the good teams from the others. The ten teams above didn\'t miss easy buckets (free throws, layups, etc.) or not know how to use their non-dominant hand when dribbling. The elite players I watch could hit a jump shot, feel where the defender was on their back before making a post move, and crashed the boards on both ends. As far as IQ, the teams above also knew when there should be a bounce pass versus a chest pass. The top players could anticipate what was going to happen next and snag a steal or hit their teammate for an assist. I think this is something that Florida players, coaches, and parents need to stress when they are first learning the game.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>Girls Can Ball (Sometimes Better Too)</strong></span>\n\nSpeaking of fundamentals, this is one reason that I enjoy girls basketball at this level more than boys. Their egos are a little more tamed or in-check as opposed to their counterparts who sometimes just want to make the flashy play (I was guilty a time or two). Girls can ball too, let\'s not forget that.','Girls Hoops Starting Line: Five Takeaways from Preseason','','publish','open','open','','girls-hoops-starting-line-five-takeaways-from-preseason','','','2019-11-19 15:22:05','2019-11-19 21:22:05','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114295',0,'post','',0),
	(114300,1,'2019-11-19 14:39:55','2019-11-19 20:39:55','Coming up short with a tough loss to eventual Missouri Class 5 State Champion North Kansas City in the State Quarterfinals, the lady Titans of Lee\'s Summit West will look to bounce back this season. Lead by head coach Jared Broughton, the Lady Titans have a ton of talent headed into the 2019 - 2020 season.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><em><strong>Returning Impact Players</strong></em></span>\n\n<strong>Charli Ritchey Sr. 5\'8 Guard</strong> - Signed to play at Johnson County Community College\n\nCharli is a tremendous athlete. She is a gifted shooter who can stretch the defense. She has grown her game during the off-season to become more of an all-around player. Charli is an exceptional leader and is expected to have a big season on both Offense and Defense.\n\n<strong>Marissa Ritchey Sr. 5\'8 Guard</strong> - Signed to play at Johnson County Community College\n\nMarissa is an excellent shooter. A tremendous athlete, she is sneaky quick and uses this to attack and finish at the rim. She is a lefty who is very crafty in her ability to breakdown defenses. Marissa will be a big part of both the Offense and Defense this season.\n\n<strong>Tasia Johnson So. 5\'7 Guard </strong>- Offers from Wichita St. and Furman. Along with D1 interest from various schools. Plays AAU ball with KC Lady Run GMC\n\nTasia is a smart and skilled basketball player. She is an all-around player with elite level scoring ability. Tasia has tremendous court vision on the offensive end. She will be relied on to contribute on the boards and guard tough the opposing teams\' best player.\n\n<strong>Morgan Pietig Jr. 5\'9 Guard </strong>\n\nMorgan is a highly skilled passer with excellent vision and can shoot it well. She has a great basketball IQ. Morgan will be looked upon to compete on the glass for the team and guard the opponents better players each game.\n\n<strong>Aubrey Parson Sr. 5\'6 Guard </strong>- Signed to run Track and Cross-Country at Wichita St.\n\nAubrey is another tremendous athlete who can wear opponents down with her tenacity. She has improved her overall skill level offensively and will be a solid contributor for the team this season.\n\n<strong>\"This group are hard workers who do a great job of supporting each other. They have really bought into the system and style we want to play this year. I think we\'re going to be fun to watch and play with pace. We are going to play a positionless style of basketball that the girls have taken to. We have a great group of seniors and upperclassmen and they have provided tremendous leadership for our program.\" </strong>Coach Jared Broughton - Lee\'s Summit West Head Girls Basketball Coach\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><em><strong>Up and Coming Players to Watch</strong></em></span>\n\n<strong>Brooke Ellis Jr. 5\'8 Guard/Forward</strong> - Plays AAU ball with Precision Athletics\n\nBrooke is a hard worker who continues to improve and grow her game. She offers us a threat in the post and she is ready to have a breakout season.\n\n<strong>Jaiden Wilmes Jr. 5\'7 Guard</strong>\n\nJaiden is another hard worker and an all-around solid player. She will be a contributor to the teams\' success. Jaiden will have to be a jack of all trades for the team.\n\n<strong>Brooke Starr Fr. 5\'4 Guard </strong>- Plays AAU ball with Missouri Phenom\n\nBrooke is a smart guard who can really shoot it. She will be a contributor on Varsity throughout the season, as she continues to grow her game.\n\n<strong>Bailey Burns Fr. 5\'9 Guard </strong>- Plays AAU ball with Missouri Phenom\n\nBailey is a tremendous athlete. She continues to get better every day in practice and will likely be a solid contributor to the team.\n\n<strong>Aaliyah Chamber Sr. 5\'7 Guard </strong>- Signed to play at State Fair Community College\n\nAaliyah is a solid player. She is a slasher that can break down the defense and make plays for herself and the team.\n\n<strong>\"I have high expectations for our program every year and this year is no different. I expect us to play a fast and attacking style of basketball. We want to push the tempo and make our opponents play at an uncomfortable pace. I expect our girls to show up and bring great effort every night. It will be important for us to trust the process as we continue to implement a new system throughout the season. I think we have a special group of kids who are focused on being the best they can be together every day.\" </strong>Coach Jared Broughton - Lee\'s Summit West Head Girls Basketball Coach\n\nThe Lady Titans will be a team to keep an eye on when the regular season kicks off next week. Every time has championship aspirations but not every time has the players to get it done. we can expect to hear from the Lady Titans this season. As they prepare to make a run at the Missouri Class 5 State Championship.','Pre-Season Team Preview: Lee\'s Summit West lady Titans','','publish','open','open','','pre-season-team-preview-lees-summit-west-lady-titans','','','2019-11-19 14:39:55','2019-11-19 20:39:55','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114300',0,'post','',0),
	(114305,1,'2019-11-18 11:22:35','2019-11-18 17:22:35','The high school season now has two weeks in the books, as most teams from around the state have played their first official games. With that in mind, I wanted to finish our thorough preview of the 2019-2020 season. In this article, I will take a look at the second Class 4A South Regional, which incorporates the winners of Sectionals #13 through #16. Below is a look at the teams in each of those Sectionals, along with some general comments and analysis. That now concludes each of the Sectional previews for the 2019-2020 season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>(SAG = Final 2018-2019 Multiclass Sagarin Rating (403 teams); SOS = Final 2018-2019 Strength of Schedule)</em>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Sectional #13</strong></span>\n\nCenter Grove (22-4) SAG 12; SOS 10\nWhiteland Community (15-9) SAG 53; SOS 33\nFranklin Community (12-13) SAG 84; SOS 47\nFranklin Central (2-20) SAG 141; SOS 6\nGreenwood Community (4-19) SAG 187; SOS 38\nShelbyville (4-20) SAG 232; SOS 53\n\nSectional #13 has been entertaining in years past, and could be again this year. Center Grove has won the past two Sectional titles, but turnover each of the last couple of seasons will allow several players to step into new roles this year. 2019’s graduation took guards <strong>Ella Thompson</strong> (<em>13.3 ppg, 3.7 rpg</em>) and <strong>Emma Utterback</strong> (<em>12.4 ppg, 2.4 rpg, 2.6 apg</em>) from the Trojans, as well as forward <strong>Kylie Storm</strong> (<em>3.0 rpg</em>). Additionally, talented Sophomore forward <strong>Katie Egenolf</strong> (<em>2.6 rpg</em>) has chosen to focus on another sport and is not playing this year. Center Grove does return three starters, though, in Junior wing <strong>Mary Wilson</strong> (<em>9.6 ppg, 2.5 rpg</em>), a tough-nosed, high-motor kid who can really shoot it, Senior guard <strong>Claire Rake</strong> (<em>5.0 ppg</em>), a Truman State University commit who also shoots it well, and Senior wing <strong>Ashley Eck</strong> (<em>3.6 ppg, 3.9 ppg</em>), who has committed to play volleyball at Indiana State University. Senior forward <strong>Emily Rake</strong> and Senior wing <strong>Alaina Frankel</strong> are two more hard-working role players who have Varsity experience. Junior forwards <strong>Alli Lothamer</strong> and <strong>Emily McWilliams</strong> should be regulars this season, plus Freshmen guards <strong>Ella Hobson</strong> and <strong>Emily Karr</strong> have a bright future ahead of them.\n\nWhiteland put together a solid campaign in 2018-2019, but now they must overcome the loss of six graduates, including five of their top seven scorers. Gone are <strong>Megan Harlow</strong> (<em>12.5 ppg, 6.5 rpg, 2.6 apg, 2.0 spg</em>), <strong>Natalie Stuck</strong> (<em>9.1 ppg, 3.7 rpg, 4.3 apg, 2.9 spg</em>), <strong>Taylor Klenner</strong> (<em>5.3 ppg, 4.0 rpg</em>), <strong>Taylor Mirowski</strong> (<em>4.2 ppg, 3.2 rpg</em>), <strong>Madelyn Napier</strong> (<em>3.5 ppg</em>), and <strong>Libby Baker</strong>. Senior front-liner <strong>Toni Joyner</strong> (<em>9.4 ppg, 6.7 rpg, 2.3 apg, 3.4 bpg</em>) is a really nice option on the interior for the Warriors, so look for her to be the focal point this year. Junior guard <strong>Gracie McCullars</strong> (<em>5.8 ppg</em>) continues to improve and should be their top guard. Beyond those two, there really isn’t anyone left with more than a handful of minutes of Varsity experience. A deep Sophomore class could be key, with guard <strong>Kylee Marlin</strong>, wing <strong>Muskaan Ghuman</strong>, guard <strong>Bri Terkhorn</strong>, and guard <strong>Braylyn Clendenen</strong> standing out. 6’4 Senior post <strong>Wilnie Joseph</strong> could also have an impact. Franklin Community looks to get over .500, and the return of Sophomore wing <strong>Kuryn Brunson</strong> should certainly help with that once she returns. Brunson missed the entire grassroots season after suffering a knee injury. Unfortunately, Seniors <strong>Hailee Robbins</strong> and <strong>Peyton Wilson</strong> are no longer playing, but forwards <strong>Abby DeArmitt</strong>, a Senior, and <strong>Lauren Sandrock</strong>, a talented Junior, help solidify the frontline. Junior guard <strong>Kyra Baker</strong> is healthy now and is a steady point guard, while Senior guard <strong>Kiki Crabtree</strong>, plus Junior guard <strong>Megan Thompson</strong>, add depth to the backcourt. Look for Junior guards <strong>Liv Parramore</strong> &amp; <strong>Izzy Harrison</strong>, and Junior forward <strong>Natosha Root</strong>, to be in the mix as well.\n\nFranklin Central will surely post a better record this season, especially with the return of Senior forward <strong>Rachel Loobie</strong> (<em>20.0 ppg, 10.8 rpg, 2.6 apg, 2.6 spg, 2.5 bpg</em>). Loobie was a 2019 Indiana Junior All-Star and has committed to Central Michigan University. Sophomore wing <strong>Rayah Kincer</strong> (<em>8.4 ppg, 3.7 rpg, 2.0 apg</em>) had a solid Freshman year, but she should provide a lot more production this season. Junior forward <strong>Madison Weaver</strong> (<em>4.2 ppg, 6.7 rpg</em>), Sophomore forward <strong>Olivia Faust</strong> (<em>2.6 ppg</em>), Senior guard <strong>Ella Brewer</strong>, and Senior post <strong>Mya Perry</strong> return after being a part of the rotation last year. The most notable graduates were <strong>Erica Crawford</strong> (<em>4.1 ppg, 2.0 rpg</em>) and <strong>Amelia Magyar</strong> (<em>2.1 ppg, 2.6 rpg</em>), so the Flashes should easily be able to replace their contributions. One newcomer is actually a familiar face, as Senior wing <strong>Alexus Mobley</strong> (<em>2.9 ppg</em>) returns after spending her Junior year at Warren Central. Greenwood Community looks to improve as well, and they will do so behind Junior point guard <strong>Brooklyn Stubblefield</strong> (<em>7.3 ppg</em>). Unfortunately, though, <strong>Bailee Taft</strong> (<em>9.5 ppg</em>) and <strong>Sarah DeCastro</strong> (<em>7.3 ppg</em>) both graduated. Sophomore guard <strong>Anna Pritchett</strong> (<em>5.7 ppg</em>), Senior guard <strong>Ashley Buster</strong> (<em>5.7 ppg</em>), Junior forward <strong>Jenna Sawyer</strong> (<em>4.6 ppg</em>), and Sophomore forward <strong>Quinn Kelly</strong> (<em>4.6 ppg</em>) all return. Pritchett and Kelly could really step up in their second seasons. Freshman forward <strong>Ella Stivers</strong> is a possibility to contribute early on. Shelbyville aims to get better also, but the graduation loss of <strong>Olivia Knarr</strong> (<em>9.4 ppg, 5.6 rpg</em>) will certainly hurt. Also gone are <strong>Ryan Massey</strong> (<em>6.3 ppg, 3.7 rpg</em>) and <strong>Carris Decatur</strong> (<em>5.1 ppg, 4.7 rpg</em>). Also, Senior guard <strong>Olivia Byrd</strong> (<em>8.0 ppg, 3.7 rpg, 3.5 apg</em>) has opted not to play. Top returnees include Sophomore guard <strong>Jaidyn Tackett</strong> (<em>5.3 ppg, 2.8 rpg</em>), Junior guard <strong>Megan Eads</strong> (<em>4.8 ppg</em>), Senior wing <strong>Makayla Terrell</strong> (<em>3.2 ppg, 2.3 rpg</em>), and Junior forward <strong>Holly Hickman</strong> (<em>2.6 ppg, 3.0 rpg</em>). Freshman guard <strong>Kylee Edwards</strong> could be impactful from the outset.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Sectional #14</strong></span>\n\nBloomington South (21-4) SAG 20; SOS 32\nMartinsville (17-7) SAG 35; SOS 26\nEast Central (18-7) SAG 44; SOS 55\nColumbus North (18-8) SAG 52; SOS 39\nColumbus East (10-13) SAG 97; SOS 43\nBloomington North (6-17) SAG 195; SOS 78\n\nSectional #14 doesn’t get much publicity, but there really isn’t a weak program in the bunch, as they typically always have solid seasons, and when one school has a down year, they tend to bounce back pretty quickly. Bloomington South has had a nice run behind the play of graduated guard <strong>Addy Blackwell</strong>. With her at the University of Southern Indiana now, there will be a changing of the guard, both literally and figuratively. The backcourt remains strong, as Sophomore <strong>Kendall Harmon</strong> likely assumes point guard duties moving forward. She is highly skilled and can really shoot the basketball. Seniors <strong>Kristen Ridner</strong>, <strong>Cameron Gillard</strong>, and <strong>Clara Voskuil</strong> all have good skill and bring significant Varsity experience to the backcourt, plus Junior guard <strong>Brooke Grinstead</strong> has improved a great deal. Senior forward <strong>Anneke Furr</strong> is more of a wing but will likely play inside some due to the team’s overall lack of size. Junior forward <strong>Anya Friend</strong> is a tough-nosed, strong kid who can play inside-out as well. Martinsville remains very competitive behind the trio of Walker/Traylor sisters, who happen to also be the younger siblings of Purdue University Sophomore <strong>Kayana Traylor</strong>. Junior guard <strong>Pa’Shence Walker</strong> (<em>12.3 ppg, 2.9 rpg, 2.0 apg, 2.4 spg</em>) continues to develop her game, as she led the Artesians in scoring last year. Sophomore wing <strong>Ashlyn Traylor</strong> (<em>4.3 ppg, 2.8 rpg</em>) looks to increase her output in her second season, while Freshman wing <strong>Adelyn Walker</strong> is a strong and tough-nosed kid who should add production to the lineup. Martinsville did graduate <strong>Bethany Mackin</strong> (<em>9.9 ppg, 5.5 rpg, 2.2 apg</em>) and <strong>Gracie Johnson</strong> (<em>6.2 ppg, 3.1 rpg, 3.1 apg, 2.6 spg</em>), and both had been regulars on Varsity for some time. But the Artesians do return 6’2 Senior post <strong>Marlayna Kemp</strong> (<em>6.1 ppg, 4.4 rpg</em>) and Senior forward <strong>Paige Dorsett</strong> (<em>5.4 ppg, 4.6 rpg</em>), who together form a solid frontline. Sophomore <strong>Delaney Wolfe</strong> (<em>2.9 ppg</em>) is a nice youngster who should up her production, plus Junior guard <strong>Kenner Nunn</strong> and Senior post <strong>Jersey Tannehill</strong> look to contribute this season.\n\nEast Central has a history of tall rosters, but this year they might be as “short” as I can remember. The graduations of 6’4 post <strong>Alyssa Robben</strong> (<em>10.0 ppg, 7.1 rpg</em>) and 6’2 post <strong>Logan Cox</strong> (<em>9.8 ppg, 7.0 rpg, 1.7 bpg</em>) are part of the reason. The Trojans also graduated <strong>Abby Koch</strong> (<em>6.4 ppg, 3.6 rpg, 2.2 apg</em>), <strong>Ashley McCool</strong> (<em>3.4 ppg, 3.3 rpg</em>), <strong>Lauren Weiler</strong>, and <strong>Carley Knosp</strong>. East Central does return their leading scorer, Senior wing <strong>Brilan McCory</strong> (<em>10.1 ppg, 2.6 rpg, 4.3 apg, 2.8 spg</em>). Junior forward <strong>Kyla Maxwell</strong> (<em>6.8 ppg, 4.1 rpg, 2.6 apg</em>), Junior post <strong>Charsan McCory</strong> (<em>3.3 ppg, 3.0 rpg</em>), and Senior guard <strong>Megan Caudy</strong> (<em>2.0 ppg</em>) also return after playing a lot last season. Sophomore <strong>Hope Fox</strong> is a guard prospect who saw limited action in 13 games last year, but she can help this season. Freshman forward <strong>Josie Trabel</strong> is a talented youngster who can also help immediately with her diverse skillset. I’d also anticipate Junior forward <strong>Emma Ertel</strong>, plus Junior guards <strong>Molly Robison</strong> &amp; <strong>Natalie Schnell</strong>, and Freshman guard <strong>Julia Tiemann</strong> playing some sort of role this year. Columbus North has a history of success, and this year they look to top 20 wins once again. With just one 2019 graduate, <strong>Nadia Lomax</strong> (<em>9.6 ppg, 4.1 rpg</em>), that looks to be very possible. Junior guard <strong>Alexa McKinley</strong> (<em>10.9 ppg, 3.7 rpg, 3.6 apg, 2.0 spg</em>) returns to run the team. She can make shots or create for others. Senior guard <strong>Annie Anderson</strong> (<em>5.7 ppg, 3.5 rpg, 2.2 apg</em>) is another versatile guard who has a good feel for the game. Senior wing <strong>Sierra Norman</strong> (<em>7.6 ppg, 2.7 rpg</em>), Senior post <strong>Tessa Lomax</strong> (<em>5.6 ppg, 6.2 rpg, 1.7 bpg</em>), Sophomore forward <strong>Kylah Lawson</strong> (<em>4.2 ppg, 5.1 rpg</em>), and Junior wing <strong>Madison White</strong> (<em>3.6 ppg</em>) return a great deal of Varsity experience and production. Freshmen guards <strong>Lauren Barker</strong> and <strong>Emma Long</strong> might see some action sooner rather than later this year.\n\nColumbus East will attempt to get above the .500 mark this season, and with a player like Sophomore guard <strong>Koryn Greiwe</strong> (<em>19.0 ppg, 3.3 rpg, 2.7 apg, 2.2 spg</em>) in the lineup, that is certainly possible. She had an outstanding rookie year and should only continue to climb. The Olympians only graduated <strong>Claire Cunningham</strong> (<em>8.9 ppg, 7.5 rpg, 1.7 bpg</em>), <strong>Sarah Park</strong> (<em>4.8 ppg, 3.9 rpg</em>), and <strong>Beyoncey Coleman-Turner</strong>, so there is a lot of production back. Senior wing <strong>Katie Dougherty</strong> (<em>7.5 ppg, 2.5 rpg</em>), Senior guard <strong>Whitley Rankin</strong> (<em>7.4 ppg</em>), and Sophomore wing <strong>Albany Speer</strong> (<em>2.5 ppg</em>) are all back in perimeter positions. To have any chance at 15 or more wins, they’ll need someone to step up and strengthen the frontcourt. 6’3 Freshman post <strong>Gabby Dean</strong> is a real talent who continues to grow and develop. She could cause problems for opponents this year. Freshmen forwards <strong>Leah Bachmann</strong> &amp; <strong>Emma Jenkins</strong>, plus Freshmen wings <strong>Brielle Stevens</strong> &amp; <strong>Heidi Murphy</strong>, could all answer the call from the jump. Bloomington North is looking to get back to double-figure wins this time around, and they very well could behind an experienced group of Seniors. Senior guard <strong>Ainsley Urbanski</strong> (<em>18.9 ppg, 5.2 rpg</em>) is clearly the best of the bunch. Senior guard <strong>Erin Lillis</strong> (<em>7.2 ppg, 3.9 rpg, 2.5 apg</em>) had a nice Summer and should add more this year. Senior guard <strong>Bentlei Grooms</strong> (<em>4.7 ppg, 2.2 rpg</em>) and Senior forward <strong>Nadia Trent</strong> (<em>3.4 ppg, 4.9 rpg</em>) return as starters from a year ago. Junior wing <strong>Stephanie Nicola</strong> (<em>2.4 ppg, 4.6 rpg</em>) and Junior forward <strong>Elyse Goad</strong> (<em>4.8 rpg</em>) fight for bigger roles. Junior forward <strong>Casey Thomas</strong> returns after missing last season, and she should add athleticism and rebounding to the lineup. Freshman point guard <strong>Jamie Lian</strong> could carve out a role for herself as well. The Cougars only graduation losses were <strong>Allison Hopkins</strong> (<em>3.2 ppg, 2.4 rpg</em>) and <strong>Lexona Herendeen</strong>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Sectional #15</strong></span>\n\nBedford North Lawrence (23-6) SAG 13; SOS 18\nJeffersonville (14-10) SAG 18; SOS 19\nSeymour (13-10) SAG 90; SOS 30\nJennings County (16-9) SAG 98; SOS 59\nNew Albany (6-18) SAG 125; SOS 41\nFloyd Central (8-14) SAG 134; SOS 40\n\nThe Stars of Bedford North Lawrence will be transitioning these next couple of seasons from a team who relied on their size, to a team with outstanding guard play. 2019 Indiana Miss Basketball <strong>Jorie Allen</strong> (<em>19.1 ppg, 8.0 rpg, 3.3 apg</em>) has left, and classmates <strong>Jacy Hughes</strong> (<em>7.0 ppg, 3.8 apg</em>), <strong>Allie Fugate</strong> (<em>3.0 ppg</em>), <strong>Katie Fisher</strong>, <strong>Sylvia Woods</strong>, and <strong>Abby Riley</strong> are gone as well. That leaves a few voids to fill this season. 6’2 Senior post <strong>Madison Webb</strong> (<em>9.3 ppg, 7.0 rpg</em>) returns with a wealth of experience, and 6’4 Senior post <strong>Peyton Sweet</strong> should be ready to back her up and contribute as well. After those two, the team gets much smaller. Junior wing <strong>Chloe McKnight</strong> (<em>9.0 ppg, 3.3 rpg, 2.0 apg</em>) is a deft shooter who has played Varsity since her Freshman year. Junior wing <strong>Irye Gomez</strong> (<em>3.6 ppg</em>) is an athlete who has really worked on her skillset and should be much-improved this year. Senior guard <strong>Gracie Crulo-Rood</strong> and Junior guard <strong>Jenna Louden</strong> return at least some experience to the backcourt. Up front, Junior <strong>Makena Moore</strong> and Junior <strong>Haley Deckard</strong> look to contribute more this season. The arrival of pass-first Freshman point guard <strong>Karsyn Norman</strong> should really help, though, as the Stars finally have someone who can make this offense click. For as much as I like Bedford and what they have brewing, I think Jeffersonville very well could be the team to beat in Sectional #15. They have a mixture of everything, but they also return one of the state’s best players in Senior forward <strong>Nan Garcia</strong> (<em>19.9 ppg, 9.0 rpg</em>), a Penn State University commit. Nan doesn’t get the attention she deserves, probably because of location, because if she were at a MIC school in Indy, you’d hear about her all the time. The Red Devils have more weapons, though, starting with Senior wing <strong>Kiersten Poor</strong> (<em>8.7 ppg, 4.1 rpg, 2.3 apg</em>), who had a fantastic Summer. Poor is committed to Grace College. Junior wing <strong>Alexis Gibson</strong> (<em>6.0 ppg, 4.0 rpg</em>) could really improve her numbers this year, as could dynamic Senior point guard <strong>Kelsie James</strong> (<em>4.4 ppg, 4.2 rpg, 2.8 apg, 2.1 spg</em>), an Indiana University-Kokomo commit. Those four will need several less-experienced players to step up and help them this year to make a deep tournament run. Freshmen <strong>Cadence Singleton</strong>, <strong>Sophia Reese</strong>, and <strong>Tatum McFarland</strong> look to contribute immediately. Junior post <strong>Aija Estes</strong> and Junior guard <strong>Lauren Gillenwater</strong> should round out the core rotation. Jeffersonville graduated <strong>Tori Handley</strong> (<em>8.6 ppg, 3.7 rpg, 2.0 apg</em>), plus twins <strong>Jasmine</strong> &amp; <strong>Jade Lilly</strong>.\n\nWith their top two scorers graduating, Seymour will need to find some newcomers to help keep them above the .500 mark this season. Gone are <strong>Makenna Fee</strong> (<em>11.7 ppg, 7.7 rpg, 3.0 apg</em>), <strong>Ashton Chase</strong> (<em>12.6 ppg, 4.1 rpg, 2.1 apg</em>), and <strong>Megan Ritz</strong> (<em>3.1 ppg, 2.8 rpg</em>). The Owls will now turn to Junior forward <strong>Grace Meyer</strong> (<em>11.4 ppg, 6.5 rpg</em>) to lead the way. Senior guard <strong>Aidan Hiester</strong> (<em>5.7 ppg, 2.3 rpg, 2.0 apg</em>), Sophomore forward <strong>Grace Schrader</strong> (<em>3.8 ppg, 2.5 rpg</em>), and Junior guard <strong>Alyssa Perry</strong> all saw rotation minutes last season. Stepping up this season could be Sophomore guard <strong>Eliza Cash</strong>, or Freshmen <strong>Brooke Trinkle</strong> &amp; <strong>Cali Cummings</strong> might get an opportunity as well. Either way, there will be some new pieces learning the Varsity game on the fly. Jennings County would like to continue winning like last season, but with four of their top six scorers graduating, it could prove to be difficult. Gone via the diploma are <strong>Callie Wilder</strong> (<em>12.0 ppg, 7.4 rpg, 2.8 apg</em>), <strong>Kylee Matern</strong> (<em>11.1 ppg, 2.0 rpg</em>), <strong>Madi Skinner</strong> (<em>5.1 ppg, 2.8 rpg, 2.1 apg</em>), <strong>Alana Daeger</strong> (<em>4.4 ppg in 11 games</em>), and <strong>Tyla Roberts</strong>. What is good for the Panthers is they return their leading scorer, Junior guard <strong>Addyson Kent</strong> (<em>12.8 ppg, 3.7 rpg, 3.7 apg</em>). Kent is a sharpshooter whose numbers should continue to improve.   Sophomore forward <strong>Lily Ernstes</strong> (<em>7.7 ppg, 5.7 rpg</em>) saw quality minutes last season and should become the #2 to Kent. Junior forward <strong>Kenna Maschino</strong> (<em>2.1 rpg</em>) was a part of the rotation as well. I’d anticipate Freshmen <strong>Lindsey Millspaugh</strong> and <strong>Megan Vogel</strong> seeing the floor early this season as well.\n\nNew Albany seems to be transitioning into a youth movement, with several younger players having seen the floor last season, plus more entering the fold this year. Sophomore guards <strong>Maleea Roland</strong> and <strong>Taylor Treat</strong> are talented youngsters who continue to learn and grow. There are also any number of Freshmen on hand who will likely get their chance to step up and contribute. The lone Senior in the backcourt is <strong>Mya Jackson</strong>, and she is in her third year of Varsity action. Up front, Junior forward <strong>Layne Burke</strong> is a hard-working, athletic forward who can play inside-out. The Bulldogs also got a big transfer in 6’2 Senior post <strong>Naria Reed</strong>. Reed is originally a Jeffersonville native, but she had attended school at Louisville Ballard the last three years. Floyd Central will attempt to reach ten wins for the first time since the 2016-2017 season, but they must do so without graduates <strong>Grace Hale</strong>, a 6’2 post, plus <strong>Sophia Gianfagna</strong> and <strong>Kara Jermont</strong>. Also, wing <strong>Lindsey Dorsch</strong>, who led them in scoring last year, decided not to return for her Senior year. The Highlanders do return Senior point guard <strong>Kalissa Fosskuhl</strong>, and she has been a fixture in the lineup since her Freshman year. Sophomore guard <strong>Keegan Kaiser</strong> also returns, so their backcourt remains intact. Junior wing <strong>Grace Suer</strong> started some last year as well. Junior guard <strong>Sophie Gasaway</strong> and Sophomore wing <strong>Kendall Brown</strong> look for more of an opportunity this season. Additionally, Freshmen <strong>Callie Jo Celichowski</strong> and <strong>Mandy Hess</strong> could earn immediate playing time. Celichowski is the daughter of 1992 Indiana All-Star <strong>Missy Taylor</strong>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Sectional #16</strong></span>\n\nCastle (23-5) SAG 15; SOS 69\nEvansville North (13-12) SAG 99; SOS 82\nJasper (15-8) SAG 105; SOS 106\nEvansville F.J. Reitz (3-19) SAG 289; SOS 163\nEvansville Harrison (3-16) SAG 291; SOS 134\nEvansville Central (3-18) SAG 314; SOS 117\n\nWith a 46-6 record the last two seasons, Castle has been a dominant force in Southwestern Indiana. This year, however, Evansville North and Jasper could push the Knights for the Sectional #16 title. Castle is likely still a slight favorite, especially with Sophomore wing <strong>Natalie Niehaus</strong> (<em>12.4 ppg, 6.7 rpg, 2.6 apg, 2.3 spg</em>) leading the way. But the Knights did graduate <strong>Jessica Nunge</strong> (<em>16.3 ppg, 5.9 rpg, 2.3 apg, 2.1 spg</em>), <strong>Hannah Hood</strong> (<em>11.6 ppg, 3.6 rpg</em>), <strong>McKenna Tutt</strong> (<em>3.9 ppg</em>), <strong>Kial Mitchell</strong> (<em>3.0 ppg</em>), <strong>Paige Hopkins</strong> (<em>2.1 ppg</em>), and <strong>Mikele Niehaus</strong> (<em>2.1 rpg</em>). There are still a couple of girls on hand with quality Varsity experience. Senior guard <strong>Josie Freeman</strong> (<em>7.6 ppg, 2.1 rpg, 2.9 apg</em>) is a nice athlete. Senior wing <strong>Carly Harpenau</strong> (<em>4.3 ppg, 2.9 rpg, 3.7 apg, 2.3 spg</em>) is incredibly active and versatile. And Senior forward <strong>Allison Willis</strong> (<em>2.8 ppg</em>) helps up front. From there, the Knights will rely on newcomers to fill out the rest of the roster, and there is little to no experience provided by each of them. Guard <strong>Keira Moore</strong>, wing <strong>Megan Kain</strong>, point guard <strong>Kyrisha Hay-Swope</strong>, and forward <strong>Mariah Martinez</strong> form a nice Sophomore group that should help immediately. Freshman point guard <strong>Devyn Barton</strong> could also be in line for a role early this season.\n\nI would think Evansville North would be a primary challenger to Castle’s reign. The Huskies return all but graduate <strong>Arieonna Garrett</strong> (<em>7.2 ppg, 5.9 rpg</em>) and Junior guard <strong>Lindsay Johnson</strong> (<em>5.2 ppg</em>). Senior wing <strong>Kenna Hisle</strong> (<em>14.6 ppg, 4.6 rpg, 2.2 apg</em>) is the primary catalyst for North. Senior wing <strong>Gabby Joyner</strong> (<em>7.6 ppg, 3.8 rpg, 2.8 apg, 2.7 spg</em>) should make a much bigger impact this year, after looking strong all offseason. Senior guard <strong>Maddie Haynes</strong> (<em>4.6 ppg, 2.0 apg</em>), Sophomore wing <strong>Kaylee Martin</strong> (<em>4.5 ppg</em>), and Sophomore front-liner <strong>Kaliah Neighbors</strong> (<em>3.3 ppg, 3.6 rpg</em>) all saw significant minutes last time around. Martin and Neighbors should play much bigger roles in the Huskies’ success this season. Also look for Freshman post <strong>Jalyn Shelby</strong>, Sophomore athlete <strong>Malaya Mattingly</strong>, and Sophomore guard <strong>Caelynn Christian</strong> to see time in the rotation this year. Jasper is the other team I think could legitimately stake claim to the Sectional #16 crown. While leading scorer <strong>Kortney Ruhe</strong> (<em>12.8 ppg, 4.7 rpg, 2.3 apg</em>) and <strong>Rachel Gress</strong> (<em>3.0 ppg, 2.3 rpg</em>) did graduate, the Wildcats return everyone else. Senior wing <strong>Claire Knies</strong> (<em>9.6 ppg, 5.5 rpg, 2.4 apg</em>) is a nice, do-everything talent who has committed to Division-I Bellarmine University. Senior point guard <strong>Brooke Nottingham</strong> (<em>10.6 ppg, 2.2 rpg, 2.3 apg</em>) is rather under-appreciated, and she at times can be the pulse of this team with her extreme hustle. Senior forward <strong>Reagan Egbert</strong> (<em>8.3 ppg, 6.3 rpg</em>) and Senior wing <strong>Meredith Hilgefort</strong> (<em>5.4 ppg, 4.1 rpg, 2.4 spg</em>) rounded out the starting lineup last year, until Hilgefort missed all of January. Junior forward <strong>Emma Shelton</strong> (<em>3.7 ppg</em>) is primed for a much bigger year, plus Senior post <strong>Riley Merder</strong> (<em>2.3 ppg, 2.1 rpg</em>), Senior point guard <strong>Lexie Jerger</strong>, and Senior guard <strong>Isabelle Blazey</strong> all saw the court regularly last season.\n\nEvansville Reitz should be somewhat improved, as they return their top three scorers from a season ago. Back are Junior post <strong>Catie Shane</strong> (<em>9.5 ppg, 5.9 rpg, 1.5 bpg</em>), Sophomore gaurd <strong>Alyssa Haynes</strong> (<em>4.6 ppg, 2.7 rpg</em>), and Senior guard <strong>Mackenzie Groben</strong> (<em>4.4 ppg</em>). If Sophomore wing <strong>Carlee Effinger</strong> (<em>3.9 ppg, 2.7 rpg</em>), Senior post <strong>Jada Compton</strong> (<em>2.8 ppg, 4.0 rpg</em>), and Junior forward <strong>Lily Beyers</strong> (<em>2.7 ppg, 2.6 rpg</em>) can give them just a little more output this year, they could double their wins. Evansville Harrison is in a similar position as Reitz, but Harrison graduated six of their eight rotation players, including leading scorers <strong>Jaya Hedgepeth</strong> (<em>12.9 ppg, 7.9 rpg</em>) and <strong>Madison Beck</strong> (<em>9.5 ppg, 4.2 rpg, 3.7 apg, 2.1 spg</em>). If the Warriors are to be more successful, Senior guard <strong>Jada Morgan</strong> (<em>8.3 ppg, 3.5 rpg, 2.1 spg</em>) and Sophomore guard <strong>Naijana Collins</strong> (<em>3.1 ppg, 3.3 rpg</em>) must each step up their game significantly. Evansville Central had a rough year, but they’ve typically had talent and been successful. I can certainly see them approaching double-digit wins once again, and it all starts with Junior post <strong>Amaya Thomas</strong> (<em>11.9 ppg, 7.4 rpg</em>). She is tough-nosed and a tremendously hard worker, but her teammates must feed her and feed her often for the Bears to win games this season. It would also help if Senior guard <strong>Leslie Morton</strong> (<em>4.3 ppg</em>), Sophomore forward <strong>Mya Johnson</strong> (<em>2.8 ppg, 3.0 rpg</em>), and Senior guard <strong>Josie Jones</strong> (<em>2.6 ppg</em>) could give them just a little bit more this year. Seniors <strong>Alison Willman</strong> &amp; <strong>Faith Frank</strong>, and Sophomore <strong>Lauren Nalley</strong>, all guards, look to be more involved as well this season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Feature image is of Nan Garcia of Jeffersonville High School.  Image is courtesy of her own Twitter account.</em>','Class 4A Season Preview: Sectionals #13-#16','','publish','open','open','','class-4a-season-preview-sectionals-13-16','','','2019-11-18 11:22:35','2019-11-18 17:22:35','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114305',0,'post','',0),
	(114325,1,'2019-11-18 11:39:52','2019-11-18 17:39:52','It’s finally basketball season!\n\nOn Monday, Nov. 18, the first day girls and boys basketball teams in Colorado are officially begin practicing arrived as dictated by the Colorado High School Activities Association. Teams are allowed to begin official competition in two weeks, on Dec. 2.\n\nTeams will be restricted from competition and practice during the annual winter break, which runs from Dec. 27-Jan. 1, with voluntary practices allowed on Dec. 28, Dec. 30 and Dec. 31.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112111\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"218\"]<img class=\" wp-image-112111\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Lakewood9-270x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"218\" height=\"242\" /> Briana Robles - Lakewood[/caption]\n\nThe regular season for all classifications (1A-5A) will be completed by Feb. 22 and the postseason will begin the following week. The first round of the <strong>4A</strong> and <strong>5A</strong> state tournaments will begin on Feb. 25.District tournaments from Classes <strong>1A</strong>, <strong>2A</strong> and <strong>3A</strong> must be completed by Feb. 29.\n\nThe Final Four and championship games for all classes will be played Thursday through Saturday, March 12-14, at the Denver Coliseum.\n\nColorado’s basketball playoff fields will be determined by league champions and RPI (Ratings Percentage Index) scores. Here is the <strong>RPI formula</strong>:\n\n30% your team’s winning percentage + 40% your opponents’ winning percentage + 30% your opponents’ opponents’ winning percentage\n\nFollowing the <strong>1A</strong> and <strong>2A</strong> district and regional rounds, the eight regional winners will qualify for their respective state tournaments. In <strong>3A</strong>, seven districts each qualify two teams for the state bracket and the remaining 18 teams are determined by RPI.\n\nClasses <strong>4A</strong> and <strong>5A</strong> do not play district or regional tournaments. The nine league champions in 4A and the eight league champions in 5A automatically qualify for the respective 48-team state brackets in each classification. The remaining teams will be determined based on RPI.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_97390\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-97390\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Imani-Perez-1-300x223.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"223\" /> Imani Perez - Mullen[/caption]\n\nHere are the defending champions in each classification:\n\n<strong>5A:</strong> Cherry Creek\n\n<strong>4A:</strong> Mullen\n\n<strong>3A:</strong> St. Mary’s (two straight)\n\n<strong>2A:</strong> Yuma (two straight)\n\n<strong>1A:</strong> Kit Carson (three straight)\n\nGood luck to all our Colorado basketball teams. The 2019-20 season should be yet another great one in the Centennial State.','The \'19-20 hoops season begins today with first official practice','','publish','open','open','','the-19-20-basketball-season-begins-today-with-first-official-practice','','','2019-11-18 11:39:52','2019-11-18 17:39:52','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114325',0,'post','',0),
	(114410,1,'2019-11-19 15:24:20','2019-11-19 21:24:20','<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #000080;\"><strong>Super Scrimmage Review (From the I.H.)</strong></span></span>\n\n<em>James Nichols aka The Intelligent Hoodlum or The I.H., brings his \"unique\" twist to the events at this Saturday\'s Super Showcase Scrimmage.</em>\n\nThis past Saturday\'s scrimmage festival at Good Counsel, hosted by Good Counsel head coach, and Germantown Lady Panthers GM/Director/coach Milton Kimbrough.  It was a stellar event attended by you all\'s main man the IH, 40/50 college coaches, and at least 10 scouts and evaluators.  With entertainment provided by <strong>Bishop McNamara</strong> (Forestville, MD), <strong>The Bullis School</strong> (Potomac, MD), <strong>Elizabeth Seton</strong> (Bladensburg, MD), <strong>Georgetown Visitation</strong> (Washington, DC), <strong>Good Counsel</strong> (Olney, MD), <strong>The McDonogh School</strong> (Owings Mills, MD), <strong>National Christian Academy</strong> (Fort Washington, MD), <strong>Pallotti</strong> (Laurel, MD), <strong>Putnam Science Academy</strong> (Putnam, CT), <strong>Riverdale Baptist</strong> (Upper Marlboro, MD), <strong>Saint James School</strong> (Hagerstown, MD), <strong>St. John\'s Catholic</strong> (Frederick, MD), and <strong>St. John\'s College</strong> (Washington, DC).\n\nInteresting fun and games, and concerned parents.  Last thing first: the food spread.  The usual stadium food and snacks, but cheap.  The pizza was under-average but warm, Chick-fil-A (no long lines), and the service was steady and quick.  The IH was escorted (like at a casino) to the free-of-charge hospitality room, where the college coaches and other distinguished guests were commiserating.  A much more advanced menu than the concessions kiosk for the public.  Bottled water, about 10 varieties of chips in takeaway size, some large, funky-dope cookies, and the piece-de-resistance six different kinds of finger sandwiches and wraps with the appropriate condiments.  All in all, not bad.  The IH feels that, SJC will win the WCAC and end up in the top ten of the DMV and top five in the Washington Post.  Scribner is one of the better coaches in the DMV, and he has seven girls who can score.  He\'s going to need <strong>Taylor Napper</strong> and <strong>Isabella Tanedo</strong> to step up in real games, if so Scribner MIGHT be able to pull it off.  As an added bonus, he has a 5-10 freshman the IH really likes named <strong>Jade Tillman</strong>, a born shot-jacker who REALLY WANTS to score (every team needs one of those...).\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>The five most interesting players the IH saw:</strong> </span></span>\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #800000;\"><strong> Nekhu Mitchell - The McDonogh School</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_62709\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-62709\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/DSC_1011-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Nekhu Mitchell[/caption]\n\nAn extremely capable SG/SF for high school.  The IH has seen her play several times in the past school and club seasons, a potential beast and a gifted youngin.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #800000;\"><strong>Sahnya Jah - Bishop McNamara</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_22038\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-22038\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Saynya-Jah-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /> Sahnya Jah[/caption]\n\nA classic 6-3 athletic small forward who has 1st-Team All-Met potential but who also did nothing on Saturday.  Wait a minute, she two things: she rebounded outside of her area, and had the move of the day, going to the basket and finishing in traffic low long hard and athletic, contorting her body and laying the ball up at rim level BUCKET! Unlimited potential.\n\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #800000; text-decoration: underline;\">6-3 Daria Douglas from NCA, 6-3 Delaney Thomas from SJC, and 6-4 Brielle Wheeler from Seton</span></span>.</strong>\n\nAll high-level shot blockers for high school (especially Douglas who\'s gifted at it), each runs the court like a deer, each has that quiet thug in her, each is an excellent at the screen-and-roll game, Thomas can shoot it a little bit, and each one rebounds well outside of her area. Each of the three has a great college body right now, long, rangy, and solid.  The IH feels that each girl is a high mid-major prospect RIGHT NOW!\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff; text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>The Events Top Five Teams:</strong> </span></span>\n\nIf it matters at this point: <strong><em>#1 Riverdale Baptist</em></strong> (national-level loaded), <strong><em>#2 Bishop McNamara</em></strong> (national-level loaded), <em><strong>#3 St. John\'s College</strong></em> (DMV-level loaded, even without my youngin <strong>Azzi Fudd</strong>), <strong>#4 Saint James</strong> (DMV top twenty-level loaded), <strong><em>#5 Georgetown Visitation</em></strong> (ISL Championship-level loaded, and <strong>Taylor Webster</strong>, who should end up as ISL Player of the Year).\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>Top Overall Player:</strong></span></span>\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #800000;\"><strong>Madison Scott - Bishop McNamara</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_22316\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-22316\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/DSC_0396-1-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Madison Scott[/caption]\n\nThe IH felt that she was the best player in the gym and possibly the DMV.  She can defend all five positions on defense, can score at all five positions on offense, has the highest IQ of any small-forward in the DMV, she is the best passing small-forward in the DMV, and the best rebounding small forwards along with <em>St. Mary\'s Ryken\'s SF Chinwe Irondi and St. Frances Academy\'s SF Angel Reese.</em>\n\nThe physicality and athleticism required to play at a high-level in the SEC will not be a problem for her. If the Freeze at Maryland hasn\'t already put the fix in for Angel, Madison has Burger Girl potential...\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff;\"><strong>Observations on the other six teams at the event:</strong> </span></span>\n\n<strong>The Bullis School:</strong> A capable coaching staff, three meaningful-enough players, top four ISL potential, Monique Currie and Dwayne Haskins went there.\n\n<strong>Elizabeth Seton:</strong> The IH likes the starting PG, and the post, capable coaching, but will struggle to finish in the WCAC Final-Four.\n\n<strong>The McDonogh School:</strong> Great coaching, about eight players, will finish in the top four of the IAAM. NCA: the IH loves the post and a likes their entire roster (at times), consistency will be an issue until they become seasoned, don\'t know if they have the personnel to run that motion offense right now.\n\n<strong>Pallotti:</strong> Three players who the IH really likes a 1,2,and 3, they play hard, and no other school in, or near Laurel can beat them.\n\n<strong>Putnam Science Academy:</strong> The IH has no idea what\'s going on in Connecticut, they have a capable mob, and the had one of the event\'s best point-guard in Damoni Tucker-quick, fast, smart, can defend, can pass, and can score, she don\'t be faking.','Super Scrimmage Standouts from the I.H.','','publish','open','open','','super-scrimmage-standouts-from-the-i-h','','','2019-11-19 15:24:20'