	(114825,1,'2019-11-20 19:02:23','2019-11-21 01:02:23','The Grandview Lady Bulldogs head into the 2019 - 2020 season full of optimism and confidence that they will improve on their 17-10 overall record a season ago. Playing in the tough Suburban Small Six (Blue) Conference, the Lady Bulldogs will rely heavily on standout guard Cierra Smith, as well as 3 returning starters.\n\nLeading the Lady Bulldogs from the sideline is third-year Coach Heath Cooper. He will use his 8 years of coaching experience which included time coaching the boys\' teams at both Harmon high school and Baldwin High school on the Kansas side.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><strong>TOP RETURNERS</strong></span>\n\n<strong>Cierra Smith (So.) 5\'7 Guard</strong> - The class 4 1st team All-Conference, All-District selection\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_108635\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"170\"]<img class=\" wp-image-108635\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Cierra-Smith-1-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"170\" height=\"255\" /> Photo courtesy Nyree D Smith[/caption]\n\nlast returns for the Lady Bulldogs, ready to lead her team this season. The 18.6 ppg, 4 Reb, and 4 Stl perform will look to improve upon those numbers. Cierra excels on both ends of the floor. Her elite level on-ball defense along with her above-average defensive IQ, allows her to give the player she is guarding problems. Cierra can handle it well enough to create for herself or her teammates. She plays with high energy and can take over a game if needed.\n\n<strong>Oriyanna Barnes (Jr.) 5\'4 Guard</strong> - Playing the lead guard, Oriyanna has great court vision off the bounce. She plays strong with the ball and attacks the basket well. Oriyanna uses her quickness and size to advantage when getting to the basket. Her ability to finish through contact is solid.\n\n<strong>Chante\' Crusoe (Sr.) 5\'10 Guard</strong> - A diamond in the rough, Chante\' is a big guard that has deceptive quickness. At 5\'10 she can beat post players off the dribble. Chante\' rebounds well and finishes just about everything in the paint. She has a solid jump shot from the mid-range on catch and shoot situations or from three. Chante\' has above-average handles which give her the advantage against slower post players trying to guard her.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_115020\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"225\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-115020\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Arrianna-Smith.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"225\" /> Photo courtesy of HUDL[/caption]\n\n<strong>Arrianna Smith (Sr.) 6\'1 Forward</strong> - A solid defender with excellent timing when blocking shots. Arrianna finishes well at the rim both on the break and in the half-court. She is both quick off her feet and has excellent hands especially in the paint with defenders around her. Arrianna can handle it very well which allows her to play fast and beat her defender off the dribble.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt\"><strong>De’Ja Outley (Sr.) 5’5 Guard</strong></span> - The senior transfer will be a welcome addition for the Lady Bulldogs. De’Ja is a solid defender, both on the ball and as a help defender. She gets after it on the boards even at being undersized, using her quickness and strength. De’Ja is one of those ‘glue’ players that does all of the small things to help her team win.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>\"We return 4 starters from our 2018 - 2019 squad that went 17-10 overall and 7-5 (3rd in conference) in the Suburban Small Six (Blue) Conference, we also will ad De\'Ja Outley to our line-up after she transferred in. This will give us three senior starters set to return and we will need them to lead a young and talented core of young Lady Bulldogs. We have a very skilled group of freshmen who have definitely impressed in our preseason workouts. I believe with our veteran players returning, we should click earlier than usual.\" </strong>Coach Heath Cooper - Grandview Lady Bulldogs','Team Preview: Grandview Lady Bulldogs','','publish','open','open','','team-preview-grandview-lady-bulldogs','','','2019-11-20 19:02:23','2019-11-21 01:02:23','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114825',0,'post','',0),
	(114845,1,'2019-11-20 10:01:29','2019-11-20 16:01:29','If you want to a selfless and tough basketball prospect, you should go see <strong>Jacqueline Semerly</strong>. She\'s a 5\'7\" shooting guard in the class of 2021. She attends Okemos High School and plays grassroots basketball with Elite Nation Basketball (ENB). <strong>Semerly </strong>is a multi sport star that also carries a 4.0 GPA.\n\n<strong>Semerly </strong>is the definition of a well rounded player. She takes pride in emphasizing all aspects of her game. It all starts on the defensive end for <strong>Semerly</strong>. She uses her quick hands to create chaos and force turnovers, making her an old fashioned defensive stopper. <strong>Semerly </strong>plays with her head up and sees the floor, allowing her to get the ball to teammates in scoring positions. She\'s also a solid shooter from mid range and behind the arc.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-114891\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_20191120_090721-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />\n\n<strong>Semerly </strong>is always trying to improve as a player and gain meaningful experience. She is constantly working on her shooting, getting in the gym and tracking her shots and shooting percentage. <strong>Semerly </strong>sees improved shooting as an opportunity to help her team extend the defense and take pressure off other teammates. Her top experience in basketball came in her freshman season when her Okemos team won a District championship. <strong>Semerly </strong>started the title game and was in a battle, matched up with the opponents top offensive threat. She is looking forward to any game that she gets to guard a really good offensive player next season. <strong>Semerly </strong>also cherishes the opportunity to play against her grassroots teammates.\n\nCollege coaches will want to take a serious look at <strong>Jacqueline Semerly</strong>. She has played in, and been impressive at, Division 1 and 2 prospect camps. She doesn\'t worry much about recruiting and rankings. \"I just work hard, keep my mouth shut and trust that good things will happen,\" she said. <strong>Semerly </strong>certainly has things to offer to a college program. She\'s incredibly coachable and loves to learn about the game. <strong>Semerly </strong>will provide a college program with a team player that is willing to play any role that her coach needs.\n\n<strong>Semerly </strong>is focused on her goals. Above all else, she wants to \"play hard and be a great teammate\". Long term, <strong>Semerly </strong>wants to study business or engineering and play college basketball.\n\n\"I have always been internally driven, so I would say that my biggest motivation is me. My Dad also inspires me to be the best that I can be and I\'ve had some great coaches along the way that have been very inspirational.\" - <strong>Jacqueline Semerly</strong>','Prospect Spotlight:  Jacqueline Semerly (2021)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-jacqueline-semerly-2021','','','2019-11-20 10:01:29','2019-11-20 16:01:29','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114845',0,'post','',0),
	(114853,1,'2019-11-20 09:51:07','2019-11-20 15:51:07','Class of 2020 may be one of the most loaded classes in Kentucky basketball history, this class features several BCS top 25 commits and runs deep with collegiate talent of all levels. This class being so talented makes an interesting race for Miss Kentucky basketball, any other year the tenth or eleventh ranked player in this class would be a shoe in for the award. Miss Kentucky basketball is the most prestigious award that can be awarded to an individual, won by many great’s in the past and this year will be no different. The state has been blessed with three outstanding young ladies who have a legit shot at bringing the award home to their town, Taziah Jenks of Mercy High School, Maddie Scherr of Ryle High School and Ally Collet of South Laurel High School. This race for Miss Kentucky basketball is completely different than most as we have three ladies who are from all different parts of the state, Jenks from the Louisville area, Scherr from Western Kentucky and Collet from the mountains of eastern Kentucky. Let’s take a look at each player based on last year statistics and see who you would pick to win the award…\n\n<strong>Taziah Jenks</strong>, the West Virginia signee with a long and athletic reach had a impressive season last year for Mercy high school. Jenks lead her team in scoring with 18ppg on 43% shooting from the field and also was able to grab 9rpg, showering her ability to affect the game in more than one way. Jenks may have the most athletic upside between all three candidates and will transition into the college game well after her senior season.\n\n<strong>Maddie Scherr</strong>, the Oregon signee with great size and basketball IQ finished on top last season with a KHSAA state championship with the now Rice standout Lauren Schwartz, Ryle leading scorer last season. Scherr who averaged 15ppg along with 7rpg last season looks to make another run at a state championship title again this season.\n\n<strong>Ally Collett</strong>, the Western Kentucky signee maybe the mountains best kept secret since Jordan Brock and Standout UK player Blair Green. Collett maybe the most dangerous offensive player in the state with her 21ppg 48% shooting from the field and 7.1apg which lead the state last season, Collett was a large part of South Laurel being the 2nd highest scoring offensive in the state of Kentucky last year. Collett looks to guide her team to Rupp arena this season and make a run at a state championship.\n\nNo doubt all three of these young ladies would represent this award very well but I would have to give the edge to the mountain girl Ally Collett, I feel as if the mountains have been overlooked the past couple years for example Blair Green is no doubt a large part of the success for the Kentucky Wildcats this season. Collett is a juggernaut offensively and she also has a advantage with her coach, two time state champion Chris Souder who has had a player in Seygan Robins at Mercer County that won this award not too long ago. Who would you put as a early favorite as Miss Kentucky Basketball?','Early Miss Kentucky Basketball Preview','','publish','open','open','','early-miss-kentucky-basketball-preview','','','2019-11-20 09:51:07','2019-11-20 15:51:07','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114853',0,'post','',0),
	(114881,1,'2019-11-20 10:12:56','2019-11-20 16:12:56','The 4<sup>th</sup> Annual High School Preseason Tournament, hosted by <a href=\"http://www.coloradohustle.com/\">Colorado Hustle Basketball</a>, went off without a hitch and continues to draw plenty of the top teams in the state for an annual tune up to get ready for the upcoming season.\n\nThe lineup this year was quite competitive, including the reigning 3A and 5A state champions as well as a good chunk of the teams expecting to be in the mix this fall. Here’s the list:\n\n<em>Highlands Ranch, Arapahoe, Cherokee Trail, Pueblo West, Broomfield, George Washington, Windsor, Grandview, Lakewood, Berthoud, Erie, Horizon, St. Mary’s, Ralston Valley, Cherry Creek, Brighton, Centaurus, Mountain View, CBC 14U (club), Lightning (club) and Falcon.</em>\n\nIf you missed Part 1 of this season, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/colorado-hs-preseason-tournament-standouts-part-1/\">check it out here</a>. Now, let\'s highlight some more players who stood out the most for their respective teams.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112091\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112091\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Arapahoe2-300x249.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"249\" /> Kali March[/caption]\n\n<strong>Kali March, 2020, 5-5, PG, Arapahoe</strong>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kali-march/\">March</a> averaged 9.6 points and led the Warriors with 2.7 assists while shooting 31 percent from 3-point range last season. Still, she has flown relatively under the radar to this point. Also a talented softball player, March showed her ability as a playmaker at the Preseason Tournament and regularly got past her defender to set up her teammates. The senior point guard also scored regularly when she decided to take the ball to the basket and shot a high percentage from the perimeter.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Seneca Hackley, 2020, 5-9, SG/W, St. Mary’s</strong>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/seneca-hackley/\">Hackley</a> signed with Florida Gulf Coast the other day and one of the highlights of the Preseason Tournament was watching her and Colorado School of Mines-bound teammate <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/josephine-howery/\">Josephine Howery</a> lead the two-time defending 3A state champs and teammates like Ellie Hartman (2022), Elizabeth Rysavy (2022), Brooklyn Valdez (2020) and Catherine Cummings (2020) to a tournament title against a mostly 5A and 4A field. Her Division-I talent was on display as Hackley both scored and showed her coveted ability to defend multiple positions, and did so against excellent big-school competition.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_99167\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-99167\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/0BF5FC3C-76A9-4A6E-BADC-D8D9ABD4EFA1-300x295.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"295\" /> Brooklyn Seymour[/caption]\n\n<strong>Brooklyn Seymour, 2021, 5-11, F, Ralston Valley</strong>\n\nRalston Valley junior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sydney-bevington/\">Sydney Bevington</a> (PGH Colorado\'s No. 5 2021) certainly is an impressive player but the Mustangs weren’t a Sweet 16 team in 2019 because they rode one outstanding player. Sophomore Saya Sabus (2022) and Seymour looked great at the Preseason Tournament. Seymour stood out, particularly against Grandview, with her dynamic abilities, including a feathery touch around the rim on offense and the strength to guard opposing bigs in the post. She averaged 7.5 points and 6.5 rebounds as a sophomore, and Seymour looks like she could have double-double potential when it’s all said and done.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Kylie Sanger, 2021, 5-8, G, Windsor</strong>\n\nSanger had a handful of breakout scoring performances as a sophomore last season, including a 25-point game against Roosevelt in which she shot 11 for 12 from the field. With the Wizards graduating several top scorers, Sanger might be the next scoring leader for Windsor in ’19-20 as the Wizards look to keep their streak of 20-win seasons alive. She averaged 7.4 points last season and at the Preseason tournament, Sanger impressed several rival coaches with her ability to shoot with good range, both off the dribble and off the pass.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112149\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112149\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Highlands-Ranch4-1-300x219.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"219\" /> Kacy Horton[/caption]\n\n<strong>Kacy Horton, 2020, 5-8, SF/SG, Highlands Ranch</strong>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kacy-horton/\">Horton</a> was one of many talented young players who was buried deep on the Falcons’ lengthy roster last winter. At the Preseason Tournament, however, she got plenty of playing time and looked quite good when she was on the floor. While running the offense effectively, Horton handled the ball well and knocked down 3-pointers with regularity when given any space at all to shoot. The junior who shot 50 percent (25 for 50) from 3-point range last season looks like a breakout candidate this winter. Horton is a Rocky Mountain College commit.','CO HS Preseason Tournament: Standouts Part 2','','publish','open','open','','co-hs-preseason-tournament-standouts-part-2','','','2019-11-20 10:12:56','2019-11-20 16:12:56','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114881',0,'post','',0),
	(114906,1,'2019-11-21 10:08:00','2019-11-21 16:08:00','<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">PGH Kansas Team Preview</span>\n\nAs we enter the 2019/2020 high school basketball season in Kansas.  Prep Hoops will preview some of the Kansas City Area high schools.  These preview articles will give you details on key players, season expectations and more.\n\nIn this article, we look at <strong>St. James Academy Lady Thunder, </strong>a member of the EKL conference.  Coming off a below .500 season in 2018-2019 they will look to improve in 2019-20.  Coach O’Malley will be in her 3<sup>rd</sup> year as head coach and looking to get her girls back to competing at a high level.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Players to watch</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Claire Worthington, Guard, Junior, (2021)</span>\n\nClaire is a returning starter and led the Lady Thunder in scoring a year ago.  A very high IQ player with great vision <img class=\"alignleft wp-image-114929 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Claire1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />and good ball handling skills.  An elite level shooter, with a quick release.  In 2018-19 Worthington shot an amazing 50% from the beyond the arc.  In a hand full of games she dropped 6 or more 3 pointers last season, which shows her consistency and ability to be an elite level shooter.  The 5\'7 guard is a member of KC Dream Basketball grassroots program, where she spent the summer competing against high level competition around the country.  These year she will look to help lead St. James as they look to increase their win total from last year.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Faith Hawthrone, Forward, Junior, (2021) #2 Ranked in our PGH Kansas Class of 2021</span>\n\nThe prefect definition of a stretch four.  Faith is a high IQ athlete that has the size, strength and ability to battle down low on the block.  Her versatility allows her to <img class=\"wp-image-114926 size-thumbnail alignright\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_1196-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /><span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">put it on the floor and knock down the jump shot with consistency.  The 6’1 transfer is coming off a state championship at Bishop Miege a year ago and looks to be a key piece for the Thunder this year.  After a busy summer with KC Lady Run GMC </span>grassroots program<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">, Hawthorne will </span>definitely<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\"> help St. James in 2019-20. </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe Lady Thunder has a great group of returning players and some new freshmen that should help Coach O’Malley’s program be able to compete in a loaded EKL.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Upcoming Games</span></strong>\n\nSt. James opens the season against December 5<sup>th</sup> at Wyandotte High School against the Bulldogs.','Team Previews: St. James Lady Thunder','','publish','open','open','','team-previews-st-james-lady-thunder','','','2019-11-21 10:08:00','2019-11-21 16:08:00','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114906',0,'post','',0),
	(114913,1,'2019-11-20 13:20:03','2019-11-20 19:20:03','The girls high school basketball season is in full swing and just as I did for class 3A, I will be listing the top backcourts for class 4A. The list can be seen down below.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nCrown Point- <strong>Jessica Carrothers</strong>, 2022, <strong>Dash Shaw</strong>, 2020, &amp; <strong>Alyna Santiago, </strong>2021\n\nCrown Point has a star studded backcourt led by sophomore Jessica Carrothers (<em>21.6 ppg, 5.5 rpg, 3.1 apg, 4.7 spg</em>). She had a great freshman season and is already one of the best players in the class of 4A. Her ability to score the basketball and find teammates in transition is a beautiful thing to watch. Crown Point gets another elite scorer this season in Dash Shaw (<em>24.3 ppg, 2.7 rpg, 2.4 spg</em>). These two will give head coaches nightmares game in and game out. Adding to the already impressive backcourt, Santiago (<em>6.7 ppg, 3.6 rpg, 2.2 apg, 4.2 spg</em>) is one of the state\'s best on-ball defenders, which is a nice complement to the other two guards.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_35914\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-35914\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Jessica-Carrothers-1-300x218.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"218\" /> Photo Credit: Prep Girls Hoops[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nHamilton Southeastern- <strong>Sydney Parrish, </strong>2020, <strong>Jackie Maulucci </strong>2020, &amp; <strong>Lydia Self </strong>20201\n\nHSE returns all-world guard Sydney Parrish (<em>21.0 ppg, 6.9 rpg, 2.5 apg</em>), who is fresh off winning a state title last season. Parrish is not only one of the best players in the class of 4A, but is also one of the best players in the state of Indiana. HSE loses a lot of quality players from last season, however they are still not lacking in the talent department. Starter Jackie Maulucci (<em>7.2 ppg, 2.4 rpg</em>) returns for her senior season and is poised for a breakout year. Lydia Self (<em>3.8 rpg</em>) has stayed ready for her opportunity, and is a great shooter from behind the three-point line.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_11574\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"230\"]<img class=\" wp-image-11574\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Sydney-Parrish-e1536210121202-244x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"230\" height=\"283\" /> Photo Credit: Prep Girls Hoops[/caption]\n\nLawrence North- <strong>Jayla Smith, </strong>2021, <strong>Katie Davidson, </strong>2020, &amp;  <strong>Kristian Young </strong>2020\n\nJayla Smith (<em>14.1 ppg, 2.2 rpg</em>) is a lethal scorer, who is excellent at getting to her spot and knocking down shots at a high percentage. Smith is one of the top girls in the class of 2021, and she will look towards putting another strong season together this year. Katie Davidson (<em>10.4 ppg, 3.9 rpg</em>) displays a great deal of toughness, coming up with rebounds and fighting for loose balls and steals. Kristian Young\'s (<em>9.2 ppg, 4.2 rpg, 2.8 apg</em>) play was fantastic during the tournament run from last season and hoping to carry that into this season.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_36423\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-36423\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Jayla-Smith-e1554381307604-300x194.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"194\" /> Photo Credit: Prep Girls Hoops[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nBrownsburg- <strong>Ally Becki, </strong>2021, <strong>Allison Bosse, </strong>2020, &amp; <strong>Mackenzie Stien </strong>2020\n\nBecki (<em>13.4 ppg, 5.5 rpg, 4.4 apg, 3.5 spg</em>) is coming off a knee injury that really hurt Brownsburg\'s chances in the tournament last season, and is all ready to go for this season. She is really well-rounded and can do a little bit of everything on the court. Bosse (<em>15.7 ppg, 2.6 rpg, 2.9 spg</em>) was the leading scorer for the bulldogs last season, forming a dynamic duo with backcourt mate Becki. Mackenzie Stien (<em>8.5 ppg, 3.1 rpg, 2.0 apg</em>) is a versatile wing that can play multiple positions, which is a great asset for any team.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114991\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"320\"]<img class=\"wp-image-114991\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/bosse-300x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"320\" height=\"160\" /> Photo Credit: indystar.com[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nNorthwestern- <strong>Madison Layden, </strong>2020, <strong>Klair Merrell, </strong>2020, <strong>Jena Loer, </strong>2021\n\nNorthwestern must overcome a few players departing due to graduation, but it\'s hard not to include them as one of the best backcourts when you have a player like Madison Layden (<em>21.9 ppg, 4.8 rpg, 6.7 apg, 5.1 spg</em>). Her numbers speak for themselves, although it is impact to her team that really stands out for me. Layden\'s sister, McKenna Layden will also be playing this season as a freshman. I like that senior guard Klair Merrell (<em>7.2 ppg, 2.9 rpg, 3.4 apg</em>) is returning as well, since it provides more veteran leadership. Junior guard Jena Loer will be expected to take on more of an expanded role this year for Northwestern.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_115015\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"261\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-115015\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/layden-261x300.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"261\" height=\"300\" /> Photo Credit: usatodayhss.com[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;','Class 4A: Top Backcourts','','publish','open','open','','class-4a-top-backcourts','','','2019-11-20 13:20:03','2019-11-20 19:20:03','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114913',0,'post','',0),
	(114928,1,'2019-11-21 12:07:49','2019-11-21 18:07:49','Sunday was the last open run, organized by Denver-based coach and trainer <a href=\"https://www.mychalmartinezbasketball.com/\">Mychal Martinez</a>, for the year as players will be heading off to their high school team for the season. The open runs are elite girls basketball pick-up games, and provide a way for players to come and compete against one another without any coaches and parents.\n\nMartinez put together a mixtape of the action from the most recent open run. <a href=\"https://www.mychalmartinezbasketball.com/post/high-school-girls-invite-only-open-gym-sessions-november-17-2019-official-mixtape\">Check it out here</a>.\n\nPart of the development process is players applying moves that they have learned or have been experimenting with. There is no better way to develop specific skills than just going out and playing pick up games. Theses open runs are pick-up games where the players have the control of the score, are responsible for calling their own fouls and pick their own teams.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_115427\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-115427\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/f8MMr0gq_400x400-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /> Elaina Martinez[/caption]\n\nThe goal is to create a free play environment for the girls at the middle school, high school, and college/pro (during the summer for that group) levels, and parents are not allowed to spectate and no coaching and/or solicitation of programs of any kind is permitted, which the players have been enjoying a great deal. Players will also be free from any recruitment by any program/organization at these pick ups. T<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">here will never be a flyer handed out or marketing email list created from these sessions. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">Play, have fun, no pressure of any kind.</span>\n\n\"The improvement I\'ve seen from these girls is incredible,\" Martinez said. \"They\'re learning organically and figuring things out for themselves by playing with their peers and managing themselves. Just like us adults did as kids. Players are over-coached and under-taught these days.\"\n\nCreating an invite-only list with the top players in Colorado has been creating a buzz with other elite players. There will be more organized open runs coming this spring after players are done with their season. By summertime, you can expect to see college/high school invite only runs.\n\n“I honestly love the open gyms. Now and days you never get the chance to run with just girls. It’s a great way to just play with no worries. It’s all fun and you’re honestly just competing and getting better. The open gyms have helped me with my decision making. Playing with people you’ve never played before makes it a nice challenge to learn their ways and what they like to do. It’s a great way to increase your IQ. Also, it’s a great way to get even in more shape for season. When I came to my first one, I was coming back from being in a boot and these helped me get back in shape. The runs &amp; competitiveness was amazing.” Said Jada Moore who recently signed her National Letter of Intent to Kansas State\n\n<em>Here is a list of players that were in attendance:</em>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_96446\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-96446\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Jada-Moore-1-300x227.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"227\" /> Jada Moore[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jada-moore/\">Jada Moore</a>-  Regis Jesuit, 2020, committed to Kansas State</strong>\n\n<b><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tomia-johnson/\">Tomia Johnson</a>-  Grandview, 2020, committed to FGCU</b>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/payton-sterk/\">Payton Sterk</a>- Doherty, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/abby-wrede/\">Abby Wrede</a>- Cherry Creek, 2021</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/grace-talbot/\">Grace Talbot</a>- Chatfield, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong>Jessica Bollwahn- Columbine, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong>Lily Najmulski- Denver East, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong>Marya Hudgins- Grandview, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/seneca-hackley/\">Seneca Hackley</a>- St. Mary\'s, 2020,  committed to FGCU</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112160\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112160\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Cherry-Creek3-300x275.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"275\" /> Charley Gordon[/caption]\n\n<strong>Charley Gordon- Cherry Creek, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong>Rylie McMullen- Pine Creek, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong>Kaylie Whidden- Class of 2024</strong>\n\n<strong>Hannah Somorin- Class of 2024</strong>\n\n<strong>Elaina Martinez- Mullen, 2021</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brooke-murrell/\">Brooke Murrell</a>- Thomas Jefferson, 2023</strong>\n\n<strong>Shelby Foster- Grandview, 2021</strong>\n\n<strong>Dasiya Jones- Grandview, 2021</strong>\n\n<strong>Mia Collins- Cherokee Trail, 2021</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/olivia-waufle/\">Olivia Waufle</a>- Horizon, 2020</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_99170\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"279\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-99170\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/D9DDED4F-67F5-45B9-9335-A755F3BCA054-279x300.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"279\" height=\"300\" /> D\'Nae Wilson[/caption]\n\n<strong>Breelyn Robinson- Grandview, 2021</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mattie-stevens/\">Mattie Stevens</a>- Peak to Peak, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong>Brooklyn Seymour- Ralston Valley, 2021</strong>\n\n<strong style=\"font-size: 1rem\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dnae-wilson/\">D\'nae Wilson</a>- Sierra, 2020</strong>\n\n<strong>Brianna Linnear- Rangeview, 2021</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/briasia-johnson/\">Briasia Johnson</a>- Denver South, 2023 </strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/juliette-fillion/\">Juliette Fillion</a>- Lakewood, 2022</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/gianna-principato/\">Gianna Principato</a>- Highlands Ranch, 2021</strong>','Elite HS Invitational Open Runs Update','','publish','open','open','','elite-hs-invitational-open-runs-update','','','2019-11-21 12:07:49','2019-11-21 18:07:49','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114928',0,'post','',0),
	(114936,1,'2019-11-20 11:57:30','2019-11-20 17:57:30','I used flashback in the title because tomorrow will be a week since I opened up my trifecta of tournaments starting with the Lady Tiger Classic on Thursday, the Peggy Whitley Classic on Friday and closing with the Spring Branch ISD Invitational on Saturday. I already touched on <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/conroe-lady-tiger-classic-opens-with-offesnsive-firepower/\">some of the stars</a> from opening day, there was plenty of firepower as well as players hitting big shots at crucial times and after viewing everyone, I figured Waller was in the driver\'s seat and low and behold,  I was correct so let me playback some of the highlights in my head\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114959\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"135\"]<img class=\" wp-image-114959\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Maria-Byone-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"135\" height=\"203\" /> Maria Byone[/caption]\n\nAlvin\n\nWhen a 4 knocks a 1 off in the playoffs, in the opening round, you have my full attention and although that was a couple of seasons ago, this is a must-see squad for me for numerous reasons. Emma Robles made the offensive firepower list simply because she was scoring from just about everywhere and I made a special GIF for Maria Byone because she brought \"it\" but she always does, no matter what the situation is. The kicker is Mercedes Mancha, one of the best long ball shooters in the area was out but she\'ll be back for the FBISD Invitational I\'m covering\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114961\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"157\"]<img class=\" wp-image-114961\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Abby-Lynch-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"157\" height=\"236\" /> Abby Lynch[/caption]\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114962\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"151\"]<img class=\" wp-image-114962\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Jakayla-Bradford-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"151\" height=\"227\" /> Jakayla Bradford[/caption]\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">New Caney vs Conroe</span>\n\nI mentioned the offensive shootout between New Caney\'s Tori Garza and Conroe\'s Isabella Stafford but New Caney also has some nice pieces in Abby Lynch and Micah Mize. Lynch is rugged and can punish attacking the rim while Mize\'s range keeps the defense honest and allows the Lady Eagles some offensive options. Conroe pulled out the win, I don\'t know if it was considered an upset but they were scrappy. Jakyla Bradford got them going early and after that, Stafford just went completely off. I\'m thinking ahead to when Kennedy Powell returns because the talented sophomore PG just makes things happen\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114963\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"146\"]<img class=\" wp-image-114963\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Crishelle-Washington-Blessing-Okoh-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"146\" height=\"219\" /> Crishelle Washington &amp; Blessing Okoh[/caption]\n\nNorth Shore vs Cy Lakes\n\nThe Mustangs opened up the season with a huge road win against defending R-3 5A champ Hightower so on paper, they were considered one of the favorites but the game is played on the court and a scrappy Cy Lakes pulled off the upset or was it? North Shore\'s Makayla Patterson was on down the stretch as she hit big shot after big shot however the continuous improvement from sophomores Crishelle Washington and Ja\'Nyla Kennedy are going to pay dividends come district and beyond. Unsigned Cy\'Maya Colquitt continues to fill voids, on both ends and this team should not be taken lightly. Cy Lakes Destiny Maddox hit some huge threes while Timaya Burks uses her body well and that along with diving for loose balls are things that don\'t show up in the box score but play a pivotal role. While Tia Mitchell was attacking from everywhere, Blessing Okoh was showing she could drop the 3 and play around the rim, both are extremely athletic\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_114966\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"143\"]<img class=\"wp-image-114966 \" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/DSC_0293-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"143\" height=\"215\" /> Kailyn Peters[/caption]\n\nWaller\n\nThe first time I saw Laila Blair, I actually went and asked what her name was and I don\'t usually do that because I request rosters way ahead of time and no one\'s time is more important than mine, but there are always exceptions to my rules. The Houston signee gave me a triple a double, starting with 32 including 5 or 6 from bta, in fact she almost had a quadruple-double but Waller has at least 3 D1 players. Kailyn Peters is on the verge of exploding and the sophomore\'s offensive package is loaded from inside to outside. D\'Asia Thomas elevated into my PGH Top 10 for 2023 and with her desire, there is no telling how high she will fly','Conroe\'s Lady Tiger Classic opening day flashback','','publish','open','open','','conroes-lady-tiger-classic-opening-day-flashback','','','2019-11-20 11:57:30','2019-11-20 17:57:30','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114936',0,'post','',0),
	(114948,1,'2019-11-21 01:30:57','2019-11-21 07:30:57','<strong><span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Prep Girls Hoops Team Preview</span></strong>\n\nAs we enter the 2019/2020 high school basketball season in Kansas.  Prep Hoops will preview some of the Kansas City Area high schools.  These preview articles will give you details on key players, season expectations and more.\n\nIn this article, we preview the <strong>Blue Valley North Lady Mustangs</strong>.  North is coming off a 19-3 record, and finished 2nd in the EKL in 2018-19.  Coach Fritz is entering her 24th season at North.  She will look to continue her winning ways this upcoming season.\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n<strong>Players to watch</strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Paige Craft, Guard, Junior, (2021)</span>\n\nPaige, a key returner for the Lady Mustangs this year.  On a team full of upperclassman, she played <img class=\"alignleft wp-image-114968 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/athlete_2163914_profile-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />a valuable role off the bench a season ago.  This year Paige will step into a starting role, where she’ll be expected to be one of the leaders for BVN.  The silky smooth guard has the ability, skill and IQ to play both guard positions.  Has great court vision, handle and deceptive speed.  Shooting ranges, from midrange to beyond the arc.  Craft, a member of KC Dream Basketball continues to develop into one the area’s top guards. She\'s currently ranked #16 in our PGH Kansas Rankings for the class of 2021 and looks to climb this season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Lauren Cassaday, Forward, Senior, (2020)</span>\n\nThe Washburn University Women’s Basketball commit, is a returning starter for North.  Lauren, the multi-sport <img class=\"alignright wp-image-114980 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Lauren-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />athlete has been the “do it all” player for Lady Mustangs over the last couple of years.  Her non-stop motor allows her to be an effective post and perimeter defender as well as a relentless rebounder on both sides of the ball.  Can put it on the floor and finish strong at the basket, as well as shoot it from the perimeter.  Lauren is currently ranked #26 in our PGH Class of 2020.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">McKenna Simons, Guard, Junior, (2021)</span>\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115016 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Kenna-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Simons is another returner from last years team. After gaining more experience this summer playing with MO Phenom, she’ll be looked to play more of a role for the BVN.  The 5’9 guard, is great in transition and finishes strong around the basket using floaters and a variety of other moves.  A streaky perimeter shooter who has the ability to fill it up on any given night.  Look for Simons to have  break out season for the Lady Mustangs.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nLady Mustangs have some key returning girls off the bench from a year ago.  Kayte Delong &amp; Lexy Farrington should get valuable minutes for North this season.\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Upcoming Games</span></strong>\n\nDecember 6th, 2019, 6:00pm at home against Shawnee Mission South\n\n&nbsp;','Team Preview: Blue Valley North Lady Mustangs','','publish','open','open','','team-preview-blue-valley-north-lady-mustangs','','','2019-11-21 01:30:57','2019-11-21 07:30:57','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114948',0,'post','',0),
	(114958,1,'2019-11-20 14:30:32','2019-11-20 20:30:32','The 4<sup>th</sup> Annual High School Preseason Tournament, hosted by <a href=\"http://www.coloradohustle.com/\">Colorado Hustle Basketball</a>, went off without a hitch and continues to draw plenty of the top teams in the state for an annual tune up to get ready for the upcoming season.\n\nThe lineup this year was quite competitive, including the reigning 3A and 5A state champions as well as a good chunk of the teams expecting to be in the mix this fall. Here’s the list:\n\n<em>Highlands Ranch, Arapahoe, Cherokee Trail, Pueblo West, Broomfield, George Washington, Windsor, Grandview, Lakewood, Berthoud, Erie, Horizon, St. Mary’s, Ralston Valley, Cherry Creek, Brighton, Centaurus, Mountain View, CBC 14U (club), Lightning (club) and Falcon. </em>\n\nIf you missed Part 1 of this series, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/co-hs-preseason-tournament-sleepers-part-1/\">check it out here</a>. Here are some more sleeper players who stood out the most for their respective teams.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112135\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112135\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/George-Washington1-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /> Jaida Redwine[/caption]\n\n<strong>Jaida Redwine, 2023, 5-7, G, George Washington</strong>\n\nAn incoming freshman who will add to a young core at George Washington, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jaida-redwine/\">Redwine</a> didn’t shy away from the action against older players at the Preseason Tournament. The quick and long guard showed she is advanced for her age and that her abilities should translate to the high school level immediately. Redwine hit several big shots in games against tough teams in Brighton, Grandview, Highlands Ranch and two-time defending 3A champion St. Mary’s.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Ayanna Schroeder, 2020, 6-0, F, Mountain View</strong>\n\nA hip injury cost Schroeder her sophomore season but she is healthy again and looked good in the post for the Mountain Lions last Saturday. The six-foot forward showed good timing and anticipation while blocking shots and decent post moves at the offensive end.\n\n“I really enjoy playing basketball and it’s definitely my motivator,” Schroeder said. “I didn’t get to play my sophomore year so I’m really excited about this season. Maddie Medina didn’t play last year and she’s back too. I just think we have a lot of young talent and if we all get comfortable working with each other and get back into shape, we can have a great season.”\n\nhttps://twitter.com/PGHColorado/status/1193234794362155008\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112080\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112080\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Erie5-300x270.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"270\" /> Edie Morrow[/caption]\n\n<strong>Edie Morrow, 2022, 5-10, G/F, Erie</strong>\n\nThe Erie Tigers have a promising young core of players that has them very optimistic entering the ’19-20 season and Morrow might be the most athletic among them. At 5-foot-10, she moves and runs like a guard but has the length and leaping ability to block shots. Morrow averaged 4.0 rebounds and 1.8 steals per game as a freshman last year and while there’s still some rawness to her game, she has a very high ceiling.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Juliette Fillion, 2022, 6-0, F, Lakewood</strong>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/juliette-fillion/\">Fillion</a> is one of several young post players the Tigers are counting on to give them more balance and support their already-talented guards. At six feet tall, Fillion is athletic and moves fluidly. She averaged 3.6 points, 3.5 rebounds and 1.5 blocks as a freshman, and figures to play prominently into Lakewood’s plans this winter.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112116\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112116\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/St.-Marys4-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Ellie Hartman[/caption]\n\n<strong>Ellie Hartman, 2022, 5-6, PG/SG, St. Mary’s</strong>\n\nHartman nearly shed herself of sleeper status when she scored 16 points on 6-for-7 shooting from the field and hitting a pair of 3-pointers in the 3A state championship game last season. Now a sophomore, Hartman played like that title-game performance was no fluke and she’s ready to step into a bigger role for the two-time defending champs. Hartman was aggressive with the ball in her hands and got to the basket, either finishing with contact or collecting points for her team at the free-throw line. She also help her own defensively throughout a gauntlet of teams with talented guards in Arapahoe, Erie, Cherry Creek and George Washington.','CO HS Preseason Tournament: Sleepers Part 2','','publish','open','open','','co-hs-preseason-tournament-sleepers-part-2','','','2019-11-20 14:30:32','2019-11-20 20:30:32','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114958',0,'post','',0),
	(114973,1,'2019-11-20 20:07:35','2019-11-21 02:07:35','This year\'s Division-I signing day was a big day for some of Colorado\'s top players int he 2020 graduating class.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112115\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112115\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/St.-Marys3-300x280.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"280\" /> Josephine Howery[/caption]\n\nAs Colorado seniors signed their letters of intent on Wednesday, some of that state\'s top players left their official decision on where they wanted to continue their basketball careers until several days later. St. Mary\'s, which has won two state championships back-to-back in Class 3A, had two players with tremendous talent - Seneca Hackley and Josephine Howery - sign NLI\'s on Monday morning.\n\nHackley, who also is a product of the Rockies Basketball Club, signed to play at Florida Gulf Coast University. Though she will be playing across the country, Hackley will join several other Colorado products at FGCU. A guard who flew under the radar for several years, Hackley is extremely humble, completely coachable, and a fierce competitor who will fit in perfectly at FGCU.\n\nAlongside with Hackley, teammate Josephine Howery also signed her letter of intent. Howery will be taking her talents to Colorado School of Mines, joining Columbine 2020 Quincey Baum.\n\nAs teammates at Colorado Schools of Mines, Baum and Howery will from a tandem of an unselfish guard and a skilled forward who moves extremely well in the post.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_97360\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-97360\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Quincey-Baum-300x235.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"235\" /> Quincey Baum[/caption]','St. Mary\'s duo of Hackley, Howery signs national letters of intent','','publish','open','open','','st-marys-duo-of-hackley-howery-signs-national-letters-of-intent','','','2019-11-20 20:07:35','2019-11-21 02:07:35','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=114973',0,'post','',0),
	(115000,1,'2019-11-23 16:26:45','2019-11-23 22:26:45','A Player that is coming from Colorado springs will make her mark as she continues to develop\n\nKaylie Whidden is a very young player being only in the 8th grade.  She is a great kid, and simply loves the game of basketball.  Whidden loves to compete, and does not back down from a challenge when it comes to playing.  She works really hard on her game, and it shows on the court.  She has a great attitude, and gives you 110 percent effort.  Whidden talent level is beyond her years, what she can do on the court is jaw dropping.\n\nWhidden is one of many elite players that is on the elite open runs list, competing against top Colorado girls basketball players.  She holds her own each time she plays against that talented group.  Whidden shows the ability to handle the ball, finish around the rim, and she has great court vision.  The best part is that she is only getting started.  As she continue to learn and grow as a player there will be playing at a collegiate program in her future.  She is savy player who can play on both ends of floor.  Whidden has a high basketball IQ for her age as she will be a leader on the court\n\nIt will be exciting to watch her play where ever she ends up as a high school player in 2020-2021 season.  Whidden will add so many skills set to any team that she plays for.  Keep your eye open for Kaylie Whidden as she will be pojected as one of the top players in Class 2024\n\n\"I love to play basketball because as soon as i step on the court, its just the game and I.  Its almost like a safe place for me, where i just get to focus on basketball and that\'s why I love the game.\"\n\n<strong>Who is your favorite basketball player?</strong>\n\n\"My favorite player would have to be probably Diana Taurasi\"','Young Rising Player: Kaylie Whidden, Mountain Ridge Middle, 2024','','publish','open','open','','young-rising-player-kaylie-whidden-mountain-ridge-middle-2024','','','2019-11-23 16:26:45','2019-11-23 22:26:45','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115000',0,'post','',0),
	(115014,1,'2019-11-20 13:42:39','2019-11-20 19:42:39','The girls’ division of the Mavs Fall Classic with a high octane show. In the 6 pm slot Rick Reedy High School in Frisco hosts Richardson and The Village. The latter of the two would win in a landslide 68-36 victory. Though a rough outing for the purple and gold eagles both teams had some young talent.\n<div>From tip-off the game’s tempo was dictated by the defenses. The Village finishes the game with 14 blocks 12 of which came from three players; Junior Jada Malone, Sophomore Sydney Ward, and Freshman Rylee Gray. The trio formed a near-impenetrable wall to the basket.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115037 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-9-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Sydney Ward\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Ward anchored the teams press collecting several steals on the day and stifling ball handlers with her length. On offense, she shot the lights out from three making 3 of 5. Her playmaking ability on both ends really popped tonight.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignright wp-image-115038 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-8-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Rylee Gray\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Gray is a work in progress but there’s so much there to mold. She’s 6-3 with a strong frame with a high motor. She plays hard and understands verticality which leads to easy blocks thanks to her size.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115041 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-5-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Jada Malone\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Malone is creating a total package that coaches drool over. She’s tall, strong and capable of putting the ball on the ground to create plays without forcing them. When she’s near the rim on either end she’s bound to make a play that gives her team the edge.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignright wp-image-115039 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-7-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Aiken Semones\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Aiken Semones spent her time on the floor as a floor spaced and it’s obvious why. When her number was called she drilled her shots. As another player with an impressive frame Semones just may be scratching the surface of her play.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115042 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-4-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Tymberlin Criswell\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Tymberlin Criswell played her role with the best of them. The lead guard used her quicks to slip into the paint and finish at the rim. She’s long and puts up a fight on the defensive end. A little known bright spot in her game may be the ability to run the pick and roll it opens up her ability to drive with little resistance.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignright wp-image-115040 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-6-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Emily Dogbatse\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />The Village’s lone senior Emily Dogbatse is coming off an injury and is playing with a minute restriction but she’s talented. She plays hard and combines the size and skill to be a team’s swiss army knife.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>For Richardson, a trio of Juniors was the face of their game. Guards Callie Cooper, Zariah Tillman, Kaia Ponder filled the stat sheet, especially in the scoring column. When they’re on the court together they stretch the floor and make defenders squirm.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115045 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Callie Cooper\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Cooper’s quickness makes her a tough cover and when you mix that with her range well beyond the college three she’s a bucket. She has a tight handle, finishes well in the paint, and has the edge you want in a leader. In tight games, when you need someone to make a play she elevates her game in a flash.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignright wp-image-115044 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-2-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Zariah Tillman\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Tillman played as an off guard for most of the night but when Cooper needed a breath her game broke out. She’s another quick guard who knows how to get to paint and finish around size. Her quick handle allows her to stay shifty and opens her up for her smooth pull up jump shot.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115043 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-3-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Kaia Ponder\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Ponder’s size and skill make her a versatile tool for Richardson. Thanks to that she was forced to guard The Village’s giants and for nearly 32 minutes she fought for position on the block showing off her natural strength. She’s a willing passer and shows strong leadership instincts, rallying her teammates in needed situations.</div>','Mavs Classic: The Village vs. Richardson','','publish','open','open','','mavs-classic-the-village-vs-richardson','','','2019-11-20 13:42:39','2019-11-20 19:42:39','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115014',0,'post','',0),
	(115086,1,'2019-11-20 15:59:35','2019-11-20 21:59:35','If you miss the games on Saturday, there will be plenty of outstanding players and teams to see Sunday at Lakota West High School on the second day of the Journey to the Tourney, an event hosted by OGBR.\n\n9:00am- Franklin vs Sycamore: Jordan Rogers is back to lead Franklin this season, as the junior looks to take over the primary scoring role this year. Kristin Earles also back, as is Brooke Stover. Sycamore has 6-1 senior Aliah McWhorter back as their leading scorer, and 6-0 junior Briana Counts is also a huge factor. Watch for sophomore Leah Riley.\n\n10:30am- Springfield vs Reynoldsburg: High scoring junior Mickayla Perdue, who has narrowed down her choices to five, leads the way for Springfield. Perdue will be leading a young squad this season. Reynoldsburg brings in senior Kyria Walker and is generally one of the most consistent programs in Ohio.\n\n12:00pm- Kettering Fairmont vs Hamilton Heights (TN): both teams also plays Saturday.\n\n1:30pm- Pickerington Central vs New Hope Academy (MD): Nicole Stephens is ranked #15 in Ohio in the 2020 class for Pickerington Central, and junior Skye Williams returns as the #5 junior per PGH Ohio. Jocelyn Tate also landed in the top ten, ranked #9 in the 2021 class. They will need to be on their game to battle with New Hope Academy, who also plays Saturday.\n\n3:00pm- Huber Heights Wayne vs Toledo Notre Dame: While Wayne was previewed on Saturdays games, TND brings in the #2 2022 in Ohio Grace VanSlooten <strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">(pictured above/photo by Toledo Blade)</span></strong>, being recruited by everyone. Also Olivia Sims is a 5-8 2021 who will be a factor.\n\n4:30pm- Mercy McAuley vs Newark: both teams were previewed for their games on Saturday.\n\n6:00pm- Mount Notre Dame vs Gahanna Lincoln: Players to watch for Gahanna Lincoln include seniors Kennedy Lewis, Morgan Darnell and #19 ranked Edyn Battle, along with juniors Neomi Glover and Naomi Johnson. MND was also previewed for their Saturday game.\n\n7:30pm- Lakota West vs Springboro: Springboro has a lot of weapons, including seniors Olivia Majors, Jordan Crace and McKel Nation (Gannon U), juniors Jordan Hobbs (Rice) and Peyton Nation, along with sophomore Haley Crozier. Lakota West was previewed for their first game.','Journey to the Tourney- Day 2 games','','publish','open','open','','journey-to-the-tourney-day-2-games','','','2019-11-20 15:59:35','2019-11-20 21:59:35','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115086',0,'post','',0),
	(115087,1,'2019-11-21 11:06:08','2019-11-21 17:06:08','Over the next three weeks, we\'re going to take a look at each class in Nebraska, starting with Class D2 and ending up with Class A right around Thanksgiving weekend.  Today, we will take a look at Class C1, which, more than any class in the state, might be the most wide open to crown a champion and may have the most turnover of any class at the state tournament this season.\n\n<strong>RETURNING CHAMPION: </strong>Bishop Neumann out of Wahoo took home their third state championship in school history by upending conference rival Lincoln Christian in the title game, 45-29.  Neumann won two nail biters in the first two rounds, winning by a total of six points in those two tilts.  However, Neumann will not have a chance to defend its C1 crown, as it has moved down to Class C2 for the 2019-20 season.\n\n<strong>TOP RETURNING PLAYER: </strong>Olivia Hollenbeck of Lincoln Christian is the cream of the crop this year in Class C1 on an individual basis.  The Fort Hays State commit hopes to crown her career with a state championship after averaging 16 points and eight rebounds a game, and the 6\'4\" center is also a terrific rim defender.\n\n<strong>TEAM ON THE BRINK:</strong> Milford just narrowly missed out on the state tournament last year, finishing 19-6 after losing a heartbreaking district final to Hastings Adams Central 35-33 last year.  Returning their top three scorers, including Jayla Policky (13.3 ppg), Hannah Kepler (12.0 ppg) and Nevaeh Stauffer (10.3 ppg).  These three sharp shooters combined combined for 140 made three pointers last season, and that figure is sure to be higher this year.  Look for the Eagles to be at the top of the C1 rankings this season\n\n<strong>BEST CONFERENCE:</strong> As we talked about in our C2 preview, the Centennial Conference is one of the elite conferences in all sports and activities in the state, and that is no different in girls basketball.  Hastings St. Cecilia, Grand Island Central Catholic and Wahoo Neumann, all C2 teams, will give C1 schools Lincoln Christian, Omaha Concordia and Columbus Scotus more than a run for their money.\n\n<strong>REGULAR SEASON GAME(S) OF THE YEAR: </strong>Alot of our top teams do not meet in Class C1 during the regular season, but there is one high powered match up in this class in early January that we should all be looking at.  On January 3rd, North Bend-Central will make a trip to take on state tournament contender Milford.  It should be a great match-up between two teams that have a chance to make some noise in March\n\n<strong>\"SUPER SEVEN\" INDIVIDUAL PLAYERS IN CLASS C1:</strong> Olivia Hollenbeck, Lincoln Christian, 6\'4\" C (16 ppg, 7.8 rpg, Sr.)/ Kendal Bingham, Wahoo, 5\'5\" PG (10.2 ppg, 2.5 apg, Sr.)/ Ellie Glock, Wahoo, 6\'1\" G (8.4 ppg, 3.3 rpg, Jr.)/ Sidney Swanson, West Point-Beemer, 5\'7\" PG (14.5 ppg, 4.5 apg, Jr.)/ Jayla Policky, Milford, 5\'6\" SG (13.3 ppg, 5.6 rpg, 4.0 apg, Sr.)/ Megan Ortmeier, North Bend-Central, 5\'8\" G (11.3 ppg, 4.5 rpg, Sr.)/ Makylee Ailes, Lincoln Christian, 5\'8\" G (9.9 ppg, 2.7 rpg, Jr.)\n\n<strong>\"ELITE EIGHT\" IN LINCOLN THE FIRST WEEKEND IN MARCH: </strong>Broken Bow, North Bend-Central, Lincoln Chrisitan, Milford, Ogallala, Wahoo, O\'Neill, Omaha Roncalli\n\n<strong>PRE-SEASON STATE CHAMPIONSHIP PICK: </strong>Out of any class in Nebraska, this is the most wide open class.  There figures to be a large turnover in state tournament teams, and there is no clear cut favorite that is head and shoulders above everyone else.  That being said, I like teams that are coming back with some state tournament experience but also have a bit of a chip on their shoulder, and the one team that fits that formula is Lincoln Christian.  The duo of Hollenbeck in the frontcourt and Ailes in the backcourt, plus a challenging regualr season schedule that will have them battle-tested for the postseason, figures to put the Crusaders at the top of the heap celebrating their third state championship in school history.','Class C1 Season Preview','','publish','open','open','','class-c1-season-preview','','','2019-11-21 11:06:08','2019-11-21 17:06:08','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115087',0,'post','',0),
	(115111,1,'2019-11-20 17:01:59','2019-11-20 23:01:59','The early signing period came and went very quickly and there are still some very talented college prospects that remain available at the moment. There is a fair amount of talent for left for colleges of all different levels, including Division 1 as well. Here are five names that college coaches need to know!\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>Top Unsigned Seniors:</strong></span>\n\n1. 2020 6\'8 C <strong>Sela Heide</strong> (Mt. Si HS/Tree of Hope)\n<ul>\n 	<li>It is not too often that Washington sees a player of Sela\'s size, maybe once every few years at the most, and some college coach is going to be fortunate to be able to get it after the first signing period. Sela sat out the summer with a dislocated knee cap and told prep girls hoops that she will sign in the Spring.</li>\n</ul>\n2. 2020 5\'10 G <strong>Tiarra Brown</strong> (Bethel HS/Team Northwest)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Tiarra\'s club coach Vanessa McClendon announced that the athletic back court player\'s recruitment is still open. She is a Division 1 athlete and has a knack for putting the ball in the hoop.</li>\n</ul>\n3. 2020 5\'9 G <strong>Nakia Boston</strong> (Lynwood HS/NW Greyhounds)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Nakia is a talented and versatile guard that can do a little bit of everything on the floor. Her recruitment hasn\'t moved at quite the pace she would maybe like, but she would be capable of playing at multiple levels, depending on the fit she sees best for her. *Feature image</li>\n</ul>\n4. 2020 6\'2 C <strong>Ramona Jagger</strong> (Decatur HS/YEA)\n<ul>\n 	<li>One of the state\'s better post players remains available. Ramona is a high energy athlete with a developing skill set on the offensive end. She got onto the club scene pretty late and her recruitment has been mostly quiet to date, but she would be a solid pickup for the right program.</li>\n</ul>\n5. 2020 5\'7 PG <strong>Kareyna Taylor</strong> (Garfield HS/Tree of Hope)\n<ul>\n 	<li>A quick athlete with some next level speed and potential as a lock-down defender at the next level. Kareyna transferred to Garfield following multiple successful seasons at Curtis High School. The senior PG should have a strong season for the Lady Bulldogs and look to get the right offer by the end of season.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\"><em>For more players, see our 2020 class rankings:</em></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><a style=\"color: #ff0000;\" href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/washington/rankings/2020-rankings/\">https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/washington/rankings/2020-rankings/</a></span>','Top Available Unsigned Seniors!','','publish','open','open','','top-available-unsigned-seniors','','','2019-11-20 17:01:59','2019-11-20 23:01:59','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115111',0,'post','',0),
	(115128,1,'2019-11-21 05:00:06','2019-11-21 11:00:06','Preseason scrimmages are in full swing, fall sports are over with and teams should be at full strength with the season starting in 12 days. Last week, we took a look at some Seniors who are primed for big seasons. Now, let\'s take a look at some Junior ladies who are ready to make a bigger impact.\n\n<strong>Harley Paynter, Boyd County - </strong>How can a top 5 player in the class be a breakout candidate? Well after being the Robin to Savannah Wheeler\'s Batman for the last couple of years, Paynter becomes the go-to scorer for Boyd County. The sharpshooter is already committed to Morehead State and with her college choice out of the way, Harley can focus on raising her scoring numbers to fill the void left behind with the graduation of Wheeler.\n\n<strong style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">Sarah Hicks, Notre Dame Academy - </strong><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">Hicks sat out the last season after a transfer but should be ready to step in and be a big piece to the puzzle for Pandas this season. Coming off a big AAU season for Kentucky Storm Elite, Hicks possesses a high basketball IQ and will have a chance to carve out her role on a team looking to make a splash in the 9th region this season.</span>\n\n<strong>Sidney Thomas, Holy Cross - </strong>After averaging nearly 12 points and 7 rebounds as a Sophomore, Thomas continues on an upward trajectory. She has the size you can\'t teach and an improving skill level that should result in more points and rebounds per game this year. Sidney should average a double-double this season and be a defensive force in the middle for the Holy Cross defense.\n\n<strong>Sydney Raque, CAL - </strong>After modest stats as a Sophomore, Sydney could see a big uptick in her production if she gets more aggressive on the offensive end. Raque is a good shooter from deep, making 36% from three last year. She failed to get to the free throw line very often and only shot 48% from the line when she did get there. An improvement in offensive efficiency should translate to a big Junior season.\n\n<strong>Laci Reinhart, Dixie Heights - </strong>Another player looking to make some big strides after a good AAU season, Reinhart is going to be one of the main pieces for a Dixie team that graduated 7 Seniors. Laci will definitely see more shots come her way after having to make the most of her limited opportunities last year.','Juniors Ready to Break Out','','publish','open','open','','juniors-ready-to-break-out','','','2019-11-21 05:00:06','2019-11-21 11:00:06','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115128',0,'post','',0),
	(115179,1,'2019-11-20 21:19:43','2019-11-21 03:19:43','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Shawnee Mission East guard Reese Althouse is a rising prospect in the 2021 class and after a strong summer running with Next Level Eclipse is poised for a breakout junior season in 2019-20.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">At 5’5, Althouse is a smart and tough point guard who brings a high basketball IQ to the floor. She says the expectations are high this season at SM East after a strong season in 2018-19.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“ We had a much improved record from the year before, and I think we surprised some people,” she said. “I felt good about the season, but there is always room for improvement. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I have high expectations for our team this season. We have 4 returning starters as well as some new talent coming in. The sunflower league is loaded so every night is a big matchup, but Shawnee mission south is always a fun rivalry game for us.” </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Althouse says competing with Next Level Eclipse at several tournaments across the midwest from Indiana to Chicago helped her prepare for the upcoming season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Summer basketball helped me for this season by showing me what I needed to work on to up my game for this high school season,” she said.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Althouse says her parents have had the biggest influence on her basketball career to date.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“They have always been my No. 1 supporters always allowed me to follow my heart,” she said. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A fan of both men’s and women’s college basketball, Althouse says one of her favorite players in Frank Mason.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“When he was at KU, he always stepped up big and played bigger than his size,” she said.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Althouse has heard from several college college programs, including NCAA Division II schools in the  GLVC and the MIAA as well as a few others.</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Reese Althouse (2021)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-reese-althouse-2021','','','2019-11-20 21:19:43','2019-11-21 03:19:43','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115179',0,'post','',0),
	(115184,1,'2019-11-20 21:34:51','2019-11-21 03:34:51','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Fort Scott rising junior guard Ella Beth is coming off a strong sophomore campaign is looking forward to a big season in 2019-20.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">At 5’5, she says she doesn’t model her game after any player in particular but prefers an up-tempo style of play and works hard at both ends of the floor. She enjoys watching Steph Curry, Dame Lillard, Elena Dell Donne, Maya Moore and Skyelar Diggins play, among others. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I am very competitive and I don’t like to lose,” she said. “As a point guard, I want to push the ball and get my teammates involved first and try to set the tone that way, but if I need to, I will look to be more aggressive offensively looking for my shot in order to get our team going. I will do whatever my team needs me to do for us to be successful.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A year ago, Fort Scott lost in the Class 4A playoffs to eventual state champion Bishop Meige. Fort Scott was hit with several key injuries before the beginning of the season, forcing the team to look to others to step up their game. Beth was a first-team All-SEK selection and honorable mention all-state after averaging 13 points, two assists and three rebounds.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I felt our team still came to practice with a positive attitude and a mindset to work hard and get better every day,” Beth said. “Our overall record might not have shown it, but we improved a ton over the course of the season. Which I hope will be a springboard for us as we start this new season because we have several girls back who contributed at various times last season.’</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Beth spent the offseason running with Wheat State Elite and said the experience helped her game grow as she enters her junior season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I played against some really good competition that helped me to see where I can improve in my own game and I was coached by some really great people that taught me new moves or drills that I can translate into this coming season,” she said. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Beth says her expectations at Fort Scott are high this season, both for her team and for herself as a player.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I think I have grown as a player,” she says. “I gained a lot of valuable experience last year starting varsity as a sophomore. Ultimately, I want to be the best teammate I can be and fill whatever role my coach needs (scoring, rebounding, passing, defense) for our team to be successful.  In addition to that, we have our normal team goals we set at the beginning of each season. Our league (SEK) is very competitive. We want to go into this season being competitive and representing our school and community to the best of our ability.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A fan of basketball at all levels, Beth says she enjoys attending local college games, including JUCO and Division II games or watching Kansas play on TV.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I just enjoy watching and learning about basketball,” she said. “If you are not trying to improve, someone else is.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Beth says her goal is to play college basketball and her recruitment is wide open. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I have had some coaches show interest on all levels (JUCO, D2, NAIA),” she said. “In a perfect world, I would love to play in the MIAA since those are teams, I grew up watching. But in the end, the overall goal is to have an opportunity to play college ball at any level and hopefully get my schooling paid for.”</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Ella Beth (2021)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-ella-beth-2021','','','2019-11-20 21:34:51','2019-11-21 03:34:51','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115184',0,'post','',0),
	(115211,1,'2019-11-26 00:29:40','2019-11-26 06:29:40','It\'s early signing season and it sure feels good to see so many ballers from the class of 2020 getting their money. As we celebrate their success I wanted to take some time to let you know who should be signing in April to close out the 2020 class. This is part one of the series on unsigned seniors.\n\n<strong>Julia Williams</strong>, 5\'10\" Combo guard, John Carroll\n\nJulia had to deal with some injuries last season but she is healthy and ready to compete in the IAAM. Julia is fundamentally sound and a good 3 point shooter. She straps up on defense and uses her length well to disrupt. She\'s not afraid to take big shots. Check out some of her work on this <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gsvf6HPcEyU\"><strong>video</strong></a>.\n\n<strong>Samiya Esema</strong>, 6\'1\" Power Forward, Landsdowne\n\nSamiya runs the floor well for a big and has a nice motor. She\'s a great offensive rebounder and finishes well. She has range out to 15 feet and is a solid on ball and help defender. A low D1 looking for a big will probably scoop her up during the season. She is looking for a school with Exercise Science as a major. Here is a link to a short <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4k8ZFeKm7gI&amp;t=26s\"><strong>video</strong></a> of Samiya.\n\n<strong>Destiny Ryles</strong>, 5\'4\" Point Guard, St. Paul\'s School For Girls\n\nDestiny is a fun player to watch. She is lightening quick and has a nasty handle. She plays with swagger and will talk a little trash while she is blowing by defenders. She can score from all over the court and is a terror in transition. She led St. Paul\'s to the IAAM B conference championship last season. Check out Destiny giving St. Mary\'s a career high 39 points last season in this <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x9cyYTXLTSM&amp;t=18s\"><strong>video</strong></a>.\n\n<strong>Nhakaiya Smith</strong>, 5\'5\" Point Guard, St. Vincent Pallotti\n\nNhakaiya is a pass first point guard with a high IQ. She really throws some nice passes to set her teammates up. I like her toughness as she is willing to scuffle for rebounds and loose balls. She never quits on a play and has a nice pull up, mid range game. She will have a big role for Pallotti this season so she will get scooped up as they play a solid schedule. Check her out in this <a href=\"https://www.icloud.com/photos/#06KBsvlJvErl06y3lNyhWmKng\"><strong>video</strong></a>.\n\n<strong>Lillian Harris,</strong> 6\'0\" Center, Westminster\n\nAfter a pretty good summer on the Under Armour circuit Lillian has moved to Westminster High from St. John\'s Catholic Prep.\n\n<strong>Briele Owens</strong>, 5\'4\" Point Guard, Meade\n\nBriele is one of my favorite guards in the area. She attacks non stop in transition and in half court sets. The kid can get to the basket and is a good finisher. She is relentless on defense and comes up with a lot of deflections and steals. Very smart player that will be successful at the next level. Check her out in this <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KXOZ5X1CgOU\"><strong>video</strong></a>.\n\n<strong>Jourdyn Ayers</strong>, 5\'9\", Wing, New Town\n\nTough and rugged player that can play on the front court and give you back court minutes as well. She is a good rebounder and will mix it up on defense. She looks like she has put some injuries behind her and is ready for a good senior season. Check out her <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RJAnslfks0Q\"><strong>video.</strong></a>\n\n<strong>Shanysse Alexander</strong>, 5\'10\" Wing, Mt. Carmel\n\nVery versatile and intelligent player that never takes any plays off. She has very strong academics and is being pursued by some D3 schools.\n\n<strong>Jasmine Valentine</strong>, 5\'11\" Power Forward, Pallotti\n\nWhat I love about Jasmine is that she can catch the ball in traffic and finish with both hands. That seems so basic but so many players can\'t do that consistently. If you need an athletic and rugged forward that is willing to bang and can you some buckets check out Jasmine\'s <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a6PMnyb3GDk&amp;feature=youtu.be\"><strong>video</strong></a>.\n\n<strong>Thalia Stangherlin,</strong> 5\'9\", Wing/Guard, Pallotti\n\nConcussions slowed Thalia down last year but I expect her to bounce back and have a big season. Thalia is the ultimate glue player who does a little bit of everything and will do anything to help her team win. She is a crafty scorer with a nice mid range game and she will crash the boards. She is a good on ball defender that can match up with bigger players if necessary.\n\n<strong>Jazmine Washington</strong>, 5\"5\" Point Guard, Oakland Mills\n\nJaz is a scoring point guard with long range. She is a tough and physical player that will make you work for everything. She is quite capable of running an offense and getting into the paint. Check out her <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J0oKsr-8jTw\"><strong>video</strong></a>.\n\n<strong>Tiffany Manning</strong>, 5\'6\" Point Guard, Western Tech\n\nTiffany is a talented lefty point guard with a deadly 3 point stroke. She is solidly built and not afraid to mix it up. She has some nice but subtle crossover moves that help her get into the paint where she can finish and dish off effectively.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Unfinished Business: 12 Unsigned Seniors That Can Hoop','','publish','open','open','','unfinished-business-12-unsigned-seniors-that-can-hoop','','','2019-11-26 00:29:40','2019-11-26 06:29:40','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115211',0,'post','',0),
