	(115243,1,'2019-11-21 06:58:02','2019-11-21 12:58:02','The senior class in Michigan is a special one. There are elite athletes of all types at every position. Fans and scouts alike need to make sure they see them while we have the opportunity.\n\nHer are 10 examples of players from the class of 2020 that should be seen:\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-115255\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/1d340f4179db982dd267913ea5f30070-300x157.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"157\" />\n\n<strong>Kaylee Wendel (G/F, Howell)</strong>\n\nWendel is a smooth player that just looks comfortable on the floor. I really like watching her combination of height, ball skills, and shooting touch.\n\n<strong>Madison Voelker (SF, Goodrich)</strong>\n\nI believe that Voelker is primed for a huge senior season. She finds buckets and could put up big numbers.\n\n<strong>Whitney Sollom (PF, Hartland)</strong>\n\nThe future Wolverine is truly a special player. Her ability to play inside-out and outside-in is a rarity at the high school level.\n\n<strong>Gabi Saxman (PG, Schoolcraft)</strong>\n\nThrough hard work and determination, Saxman has become a premier point guard in Michigan. The Western Michigan University commit creates for herself and her teammates off the dribble.\n\n<strong>Dani Salenbien (PG, Lenawee Christian)</strong>\n\nFor old school basketball fans, Salenbien is a must see senior. She is the definition of a floor general and is committed to Hillsdale.\n\n<strong>Alicia Ortiz (SG, Dearborn Crestwood)</strong>\n\nOrtiz is an underrated player. She has a nice looking jumper and has a knack for finding space getting looks at the bucket.\n\n<strong>Gabby Elliott (SF, Detroit Edison)</strong>\n\nThe Clemson commit has to be on this list. She\'s an elite prospect in the nation and a front runner for any player of the year honors. Elliott is doing nothing short of creating a legend in the state of Michigan.\n\n<strong>Sophie Dziekan (C, Brighton)</strong>\n\nDziekan is one of the top post players in the state. If you like watching a player dominate the paint, she has to be on your list.\n\n<strong>Brooklynne Bevier (PF, Jackson Northwest)</strong>\n\nDon\'t be surprised if Bevier has a stellar senior season. She could very easily average a double-double this year.\n\n<strong>Imania Baker (C, Haslett)</strong>\n\nBaker simply dominates under the rim. She\'s one of the strongest players in any class and can clear the lane on a box out.\n\n&nbsp;','See Them Before They\'re Gone','','publish','open','open','','see-them-before-theyre-gone','','','2019-11-21 06:58:02','2019-11-21 12:58:02','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115243',0,'post','',0),
	(115246,1,'2019-11-21 08:26:04','2019-11-21 14:26:04','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Most of the Maryland high school 2019-2020 basketball season will kick off next week. This past Monday, McDonogh High jump started their season with a 58-57 win over St. Paul. Let\'s breakdown some of the top prospects from the IAAM A Division.</span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jayla-oden/\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #f75617;\">Jayla Oden | 5\'6 G | McDonogh 2021</span></strong></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-84447\" style=\"font-family: Lato, \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 1rem;\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Jayla-Oden-e1566847385999-280x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"231\" height=\"248\" /></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Junior Jayla Oden is a prospect you should know about. My prediction is that she will be highly recruited going into the 2020-2021 season but its not to late to put your chips in now. Jayla has a uptempo style of play, consistently generating plays and keeping eve</span><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif; font-size: 1rem;\">ryone on their game. She engages on defense as well and is quickly becoming one of the leaders on this team. Currently ranked #6 on Prep Girls Hoops 2021 rankings, this could be a very special season for Jayla Oden. </span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/eniya-russell/\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #f75617;\">Eniya Russell | 5\'11 G | Institute of Notre Dame 2020</span></strong></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-18350\" style=\"font-family: Lato, \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 1rem;\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Eniya-Russell-300x222.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"224\" height=\"166\" /></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">At 5\'11 playing the guard position, Eniya Russell is very tough to defend. This highly recruited athlete has already committed to the University of South Carolina as she gets ready to kick off her senior year. Total domination is what one would expect from Eniya Russell this season. She can choose to shoot over you or simply go around you, using her size as a weapon. Eniya makes everything look easy and if you leave her too much space, she will indeed drop it on you. </span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #f75617;\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/daimoni-dorsey/\">Daimoni Dorsey | 5\'7 G | St. Francis Academy 2022</a></span></strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-115286\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Daimoni-Dorsey-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"186\" height=\"186\" /></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Sophmore guard Daimoni Dorsey is currently ranked #48 on Prep Girls Hoops 2022 rankings. A role player during her freshman year, Daimoni looks to elevate her role during the 19-20 season. What makes this season special, Daimoni is pairing up with her little sister Kameryn Dorsey and rumors are swirling that this could be the best back court in the DMV. You add that to an elite roster already featuring the number one athlete in the state (<strong>Angel Reese</strong>), watch out for St. Francis Academy once again this season. </span>','IAAM A Prospects','','publish','open','open','','iaam-a-prospects','','','2019-11-21 08:26:04','2019-11-21 14:26:04','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115246',0,'post','',0),
	(115266,1,'2019-11-21 08:10:21','2019-11-21 14:10:21','<strong>Emily Cline </strong>is a prospect for fans and coaches to keep an eye on this season. She\'s a wing in the class of 2021 that played grassroots basketball with Elite Nation Basketball (ENB). <strong>Cline </strong>transferred from Holt and will attend Eaton Rapids. Last season she averaged 10.3 ppg, 5.6 rpg, and 2.2 spg.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-115281\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/c8ae4914aad0c4acbbdeddf04c48f759-300x157.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"157\" />\n\n<strong>Cline </strong>is impressive on the basketball court. She has a keen understanding of the game which serves her well on both ends. <strong>Cline\'s </strong>game is highlighted by her aggressiveness. She doesn\'t wait for the action, but takes the lead and controls it. <strong>Cline </strong>attacks both the offensive and defensive glass. She reads the ball off the rim and goes to get it. <strong>Cline </strong>is a well rounded athlete, also starring in track and volleyball.\n\n<strong>Cline </strong>is always looking for an opportunity to improve and experience big moments.  She\'s currently focused on extending her range and gaining consistency on her 3 point shot. <strong>Cline </strong>feels that winning nationals as a youth was her biggest moment in basketball so far. She\'s looking forward to a key matchup with Mason this season. The game holds extra meaning as some of her ENB teammates attend that school.\n\n<strong>Emily Cline </strong>has a lot to offer to a program at the next level. She\'s already received an offer from Acquinas to play both basketball and softball. <strong>Cline </strong>will provide a college coach with an athlete that has the drive to be the best in anything that she does. She will be a leader, both on and off the floor.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-115278\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_20191121_090638-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />\n\n<strong>Cline </strong>is working to accomplish her goals. Above all else, she wants her team to grow together and always play their best. <strong>Cline </strong>wants to set a new school record for rebounds and free throws. After basketball, she hopes to become a psychiatrist and own a large home in the country.\n\n\"My family is my greatest motivator. They have been with me through it all and have dedicated a lot of time and money into me. They push me to be the best I can at all times, even off the court.\"\n\n- <strong>Emily Cline</strong>','Prospect Spotlight:  Emily Cline (2021)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-emily-cline-2021','','','2019-11-21 08:10:21','2019-11-21 14:10:21','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115266',0,'post','',0),
	(115280,1,'2019-11-22 12:16:08','2019-11-22 18:16:08','<strong>Monday November 25, 2019</strong>\n\nSalem Baptist Christian  (Winston-Salem) v. Burlington Christian Academy (Burlington) - 6\'0\" senior Kavanna Held leads the Vikings against Burlington Christian in this battle of undefeated squads.\n\nWest Mecklenburg (Charlotte) v. Hopewell (Huntersville) - The Hawks from West Meck face a big challenge from the Lady Titans who won their opener against Harding, 84-5.\n\nFriendship Christian (Raleigh) v. The New Life Camp (Raleigh) - 5\'6\" Senior Susie Greear leads FC into this early season battle against Alex Love and New Camp Life.\n\nCuthbertson (Waxhaw) v. Ardrey Kell (Charlotte) - The Cavaliers and big 6\'1\" Senior Maddie Dellinger (23 and 8 boards in the season opening victory against Charlotte Christian) look to take down the Knights of AK who won their season opener against a scrappy Charlotte Catholic team 56-49 on Monday..\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Tuesday November 26, 2019</strong>\n\nOverhills (Spring Lake) v. E.E.Smith (Fayetteville)   - Jade Butcher and the Jaguars hope to stay undefeated against traditional power E.E. Smith.\n\nMallard Creek (Charlotte) v. Rocky River (Mint Hill) - Perennial power Creek steps outside of the conference for a big intersectional battle against the Ravens.  The Mavericks dynamic duo of Neveah Brown (Wake Forest) and Lauren Walker have been the area\'s best tandem in the early stages of the season.\n\nProvidence Day (Charlotte) v. Comenius (Fort Mill, SC) - Providence Day looks to stay undefeated as they venture out of state for a battle against Jordan Durant and the Comenius Knights.  El Ferguson (career high 22 points in the opening game win against Southlake Christian) and Andi Levitz are the heartbeat of a Knights team that once again figures to be a tough out in North Carolina 2A competition.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Wednesday November 27, 2019</strong>\n\nEast Wilkes (Ronda) v. South Iredell (Statesville) - The Cardinals of East Wilkes don\'t open the season until November 26 against Avery County.  Here they will be facing a tough back to back against junior PG Ashtyn Zeigler and the South Iredell Vikings.\n\nEast Burke (Connelly Springs) v, McDowell (Marion) - Coming off a strong start to the season with a 60-22 win over West Lincoln, the East Burke lady Cavaliers and Senior wing Josie Hise look to continue their winning ways against Madi Smith and the McDowell Titans.\n\n<strong>Friday November 28, 2019</strong>\n\nProvidence (Charlotte) v. Providence Day (Charlotte) - Off to a 2-0 start and led by Olivia Jurney, the Providence Panthers will take on super freshman Jordan Latter and the Providence Day Knights.\n\nCabarrus Charter (Concord) v. East Mecklenburg (Charlotte) - Amiya Jones and Gabrielle Tarpley will lead the Huskies of Cabarrus Charter against an East Meck team that was beaten by 35 in its season opener against Providence.\n\nVance (Charlotte) v. Butler (Matthews) - The two preseason favorites in the conference, Vance will be well served in trying to contain Butler\'s ace scorer,Michaela Lane who scored a game high 21 in a season opening victory over Hough,\n\n<strong>Saturday November 29, 2019</strong>\n\nHigh Point Christian Academy (High Point) v. Winston-Salem Christian (Winston-Salem) - Off to a strong start after a 35 point season opening victory, the Cougars of High Point Christian Academy and their high scoring junior wing, Lili Sink seek to knock off against the 3-0 Lions of Winston Salem Christian.\n\nCabarrus Charter (Concord) v. West Charlotte (Charlotte) - It\'s a big step up in competition for Cabarrus Charter\'s fabulous freshman Isabella Childs (23 points in her varsity debut against United Faith in a 71-46 victory last week). West Charlotte got off to a strong start with a 51-15 over Garinger last week.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Must See Games for the Week of November 25 - December 1','','publish','open','open','','must-see-games-for-the-week-of-november-25-december-1','','','2019-11-22 12:16:08','2019-11-22 18:16:08','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115280',0,'post','',0),
	(115292,1,'2019-11-21 09:54:01','2019-11-21 15:54:01','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">The first games of the 2019-2020 season kick off tomorrow afternoon for the IAAM B Division. With that being said, here\'s a look at a few of the top prospects out of IAAM B.</span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alex-sawyer/\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #ff6600;\">Alex Sawyer | 5\'0 G | St. Paul 2020</span></strong></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-115332\" style=\"font-family: Lato, \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 1rem;\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Alex-Sawyer-300x181.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"264\" height=\"159\" /></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Alex Sawyer and a few other members of this St. Paul backcourt are scrappy, scrappy, scrappy and they are not ashamed of it. Alex Sawyer at 5\'0 has an incredible jump shot and impeccable defense. Her court awareness allows her to penetrate the ball with ease as well as pull up at will in transition. Her shop making ability can change the tempo of the game in a heartbeat. Last year, Alex Sawyer and St. Paul beat #1 Mount de Sales in the IAAM B Championship.</span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ashlyn-bender/\"><span style=\"color: #ff6600;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Ashlyn Bender | 5\'11 W | Glenelg Country 2021</span></strong></span></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-24068\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/bender1-300x188.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"262\" height=\"164\" /></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Ashlyn Bender is one of my favorite players to watch. Her form is perfect and her basketball IQ is even better. Ashlyn has a near perfect jumper and what\'s most impressive is the way she spots up and shoots from virtually anywhere on the court. Ashlyn has the ability to shoot WNBA length three-pointers. She powers up on defense and can run down her man without hesitation. Her defensive post game is actually her best asset and is what I am really looking forward to see grow this year. </span><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"> </span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/claire-neff/\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff6600;\">Claire Neff | 6\'2 W | Maryvale Prep 2020</span></strong></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-115337\" style=\"font-family: Lato, \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 1rem;\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Claire-Neff-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"263\" height=\"148\" /></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Claire Neff looked like an elite basketball player during her junior year. She currently averages 17.3 ppg and 12.5 rebounds per game. The leader of this Maryvale team, Claire is a matchup problem for opposing teams. She constantly moves around the court and is a true wing. Claire may not find herself in the post too often, and at 6\'2 with great speed, the pick and roll destroys defenses every time. It\'s hard for coaches to place the right personnel on the court to switch off on a player like Claire, especially when Maryvale is running numerous screens. </span>','IAAM B Prospects','','publish','open','open','','iaam-b-prospects','','','2019-11-21 09:54:01','2019-11-21 15:54:01','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115292',0,'post','',0),
	(115350,1,'2019-11-21 10:24:50','2019-11-21 16:24:50','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After a strong sophomore season, Dodge City rising 2021 guard Kisa Unruh is gearing up for a big season in 2019-20.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">At 5’7, Unruh can play either guard spot and takes pride in doing whatever her team needs in the moment. She scored 292 points last season and averaged to 13.9 points per game. She has scored 496 points over her two years of high school. She also recorded 35 assists, 13 blocks, and 102 rebounds and was named All Conference First Team for the Western Athletic Conference (WAC) and honorable mention all state. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After going 8-13 last season, the Lady Demons return several key players and expectations are high for the upcoming season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Given how young our team was compared to other schools I would say we competed very well with everyone,” Unruh said. “My expectations for this upcoming season is to compete for WAC tittle against the previous WAC champs who have returned most of their players as well as other good WAC teams. Also making it to the state tournament because I really think our team will be bigger and stronger this year than we were last year.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Unruh spent the offseason competing with Game All and says the experience helped prepare her for the upcoming season and perhaps beyond.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Summer ball was a whole new experience for me,” she says. “I saw some really good competition and learned to become a more physical player. The speed of the game was much quicker then school ball and I had to step up in order to keep up.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Unruh says the biggest influence on her basketball career to date has been her dad.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I wouldn’t be where I am today if it wasn’t for everything he has taught me about basketball,” she said. “He’s the reason I started playing basketball at such a young age. He pushes me to get better every season and not settle on what I did the season before.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Unruh has heard from Newman University in Wichita after she attended their Elite basketball camp during the summer.</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Kisa Unruh (2021)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-kisa-unruh-2021','','','2019-11-21 10:24:50','2019-11-21 16:24:50','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115350',0,'post','',0),
	(115359,1,'2019-11-21 10:45:01','2019-11-21 16:45:01','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Coming off a strong summer running with Nex Level Eclipse, Olathe Northwest guard Riley Wade is looking forward to a big senior season for the Lady Owls.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A versatile player, Wade takes pride in being able to play several positions and can guard post players, wings or guards. She has played every position throughout her career and brings defensive intensity and an aggressive attitude to the court.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After a tough regular season a year ago, Olathe Northwest went on quite a ride to cap out the 2018-19 season, winning sub state as the No. 8 seed with upset wins over Shawnee Mission East and top seeded Blue Valley North, then, as the No. 8 seed at the Class 6A state tournament, beat undefeated Liberal.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Olathe Northwest went on to finish fourth with close losses to Topeka in the semifinals and Derby in the third-place game.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A year ago, Olathe Northwest entered sub-state as the No. 8 seed and upset Shawnee Mission East in the first round then defeated top seeded Blue Valley North in a tough game to advance to state.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Last high school season was my favorite year ever playing basketball. our team was so close and we played together so well … the way we ended our season was so great because we weren’t even supposed to be at state,” Wade said.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Olathe Northwest lost four seniors from last year’s team, but Wade says the expectations are high with a big senior class ready to step into new roles.    </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“The starting five will be a group of girls that have all played together since sixth grade and our group of girls will be scrappy and fast, and competitive and will fight to the end every game,” she said. “I am looking forward to play Olathe East and Shawnee Mission Northwest the most because those are our biggest rivals each year and the main  ones we want to win.”        </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Wade is coming off a strong summer running with Next Level Eclipse and coach Dru Wheatcroft. She suffered a broken wrist early in the spring and was out until July 1, but ended the summer strong.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I strengthened and worked on my left hand ball handling and drives when I couldn’t play because of my wrist,” Wade said. “When I got cleared to play I got all tourney team at two USJN Tournaments after being out for two and a half months. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I stayed in shape and played as hard as I could knowing that it was my last year playing club.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Riley Wade says her dad, Troy Wade, has had the biggest influence on her basketball career to date.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“He has always been there since day one driving me to games and practices, coaching and pushing me to be the best I can be, and teaching me the life skills basketball has brought me,” she said. “I thank my dad for everything I am today on and off the court.”    </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Wade recently committed to play at Colorado Christian University in Denver Colorado. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I am very excited to play for Coach Laster and be a cougar next year,” she says. “CCU stood out to me because the campus is very friendly and wants everyone to succeed and has the major I want to pursue. Also the team is a lot of fun and are super welcoming and seem to have a great bond. I also love the coaches and community there.”</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Riley Wade (2020)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-riley-wade-2020','','','2019-11-21 10:45:01','2019-11-21 16:45:01','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115359',0,'post','',0),
	(115367,1,'2019-11-27 15:57:49','2019-11-27 21:57:49','<strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Mark Keppel Tournament</span></strong>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">November 23, 2019</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">San Gabriel High School @ 9PM\nMain Gym</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Dominguez (0-1)</strong> San Gabriel Valley League vs. <strong>San Gabriel (0-2)</strong> Almont League\n<strong>Final Score:</strong>  <strong>Compton Dominguez HS 54</strong>, San Gabriel HS 25</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">This matchup was kind of odd even when you take a good look at it, you have <strong>Compton Dominguez</strong>, a heralded school with some talent and a long listed history of being a really good basketball team for girls in their past.  With <strong>San Gabriel,</strong> you get a team put together of kids in the surrounding area that most likely do not have the club basketball resources the other schools in the are like <strong>Mark Keppel HS</strong> would have.  We are just speculating, but most of it is probably true when it comes to the contrasting styles of these two programs in this contest.  The results are exactly what we expected to happen in this game, with Dominguez going on to win the game with a <strong>final score of 54-25</strong>.  In this matchup we will talk about the kids in both programs who performed in our opinion and we believe we should keep an eye on in the future, here we go.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Top Performers for Dominguez:</strong></span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-118225 alignleft\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/LeighaHarris3-e1574891082155-152x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"152\" height=\"300\" />2020, 6\'1, CG, Leigha Harris</strong> is one of the most dynamic combo guards with point guard vision and is one of the most athletic players on the floor at most times.  She is developing her three ball, but the midrange and getting to the basket is immaculate for her skill set at the moment.  She is long and lanky, allowing her to be able to guard positions 1-5, she\'s able to sit down and defend the point guard and harass them with the ball on the perimeter.  This kid is special, she is gonna be a steal for some ones program.  Leigha finished the game with these stats: <strong>11pts, 11rebs, 9asts</strong> and <strong>4stls</strong> in the win.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2021, 5\'9, PG, Jae\'lin Acker</strong> is a forward </span><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">with a little pop to her game, Jae\'lin is a prime rebounder for her team, she is relentless on the boards and has some great hands.  She grabbed some key boards in the game we watched, most impressed with her catch and finish skills under the rim. She will be one to watch in the near future as well.  Jae\'lin finished the game with these stats: </span><strong style=\"font-size: 14pt\">13pts, 12rebs</strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"> and </span><strong style=\"font-size: 14pt\">4stls</strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"> in the win.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2022, 5\'7, SG, Rae\'Lani Trinity-Frost</strong> is a shooter on the perimeter with a nice stroke from the outside, she can fill it up and she hit 3 of 4 three pointers in this game to help her team win.  She has nice body frame, she has a thick body type, she is strong and can run the floor and catch and shoot in transition.  She will be a force to reckon with next year as the specific player.  Rae\'Lani finished the game with these stats: <strong>15pts, 4rebs, 3asts</strong> and <strong>3stls </strong>in the win.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Dominguez vs. San Gabriel - Mark Keppel Tourney - Who Stood Out...',