	(115500,1,'2019-11-22 10:27:56','2019-11-22 16:27:56','Bishop Verot made the trip from Fort Myers up to Tampa on Wednesday night for the season opener for each team. The Vikings had a rough go of it from the beginning against a solid Phoenix team with strong chemistry. Brooks DeBartolo plays fast and they work the ball around well in a balanced attack. The first half was dominated by Brooks DeBartolo as the score was 18-8 after one period, and the score at half was 41-10 in favor of the Phoenix. BV would play better in the second half as BDCHS took their foot off the gas a bit. The final in this one ended up being 72-36 with the Phoenix securing the W.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>How do you stop Brooks DeBartolo?</strong></span>\n\nGreat question. This team should be a force in 3A after going 22-8 last season with those 8 losses coming to quality teams. They return just about everyone from that team, so they have all played together making their chemistry some of the best I\'ve seen. Brooks DeBartolo isn\'t all that tall (not that short either), but that won\'t hurt them if the other team can\'t do anything on offense with the pressure defense that the Phoenix have.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>What is Bishop Verot missing?</strong></span>\n\nBV was looking to have a very talented team before a few transfers happened (or didn\'t happen) that changed the outlook of this team. The Vikings are led by Sr. <strong>Catie Reszel</strong> (NAIA Ave Maria University commit) and So. <strong>Addison Potts</strong> (D1 Missouri commit) who are the only real scoring options on this squad that doesn\'t give them the depth or options they need. This allows oppposing teams to focus in on these two to make like difficult for them, especially a talented defensive team like Brooks. Addison Potts was being double-teamed off of any screens that were set for her, and it only allowed for her to have a few shot attempts that led to 5 points for the game. Speedy Catie Reszel led the way in scoring for Bishop Verot with 12 points on the game with a couple nice floaters and strong free throw shooting. Other contributors were So. <strong>Lauren Broomhead</strong> with 8 points on a couple of 3 pointers, and Sr. <strong>Angela Ficarro</strong> who had 8 points that could have been more with some of the looks she got in the post. District 7 is not that strong in 3A, so BV still has a great chance to make something happen this season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Is there a better Junior Class than Brooks DeBartolo\'s?</strong></span>\n\nI am sure I will miss some teams, but I think Brooks has one of the strongest trio\'s in the Junior class in the state with Triniti Youngblood, Brionna McClinton, and Amarie Godwin (with the addition of Ayonna Simmons eventually). Other teams I can think of would be Tampa Bay Tech (Peaks, Godfrey, and Murray) as the only trio, DME (Weary, Grady), Florida Prep (Sorrentino, Burks), and Plant (Cheesman, Jean), but there is a lot of talent in the 2021 class throughout the state of Florida. In this game against Bishop Verot, the juniors accounted for 53 of the 72 points for BDCHS. <strong>Brionna McClinton</strong> led the way with 21 points on three 3-pointers, and she continues to impress me even more with each game I see. <strong>Triniti Youngblood</strong> added 17 points on offense and played a great defensive game against Potts to shut her down. The last Junior is <strong>Amarie Godwin</strong> who had 15 with a couple three pointers and a bunch of assists as the team\'s facilitator. This Phoenix team is a lot of fun to watch with their intensity on both sides of the floor.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>What is Brooks DeBartolo\'s ceiling?</strong></span>\n\nBrooks is a really strong team from 1 through 5 or 6. Aside from their Junior class, Brooks has two quick guards in Sophomore <strong>Jaela Davis</strong> and Freshman <strong>Maia Lewers</strong> (8 pts). This is a very balanced team that can be carried by anyone if someone is having an off game on offense like Jaela did. She played hard and really tough defense that made a difference in the game, because everyone is bound to have tough shooting nights. Maia\'s game does not make her look like a Freshman as she\'s definitely one of the top 2023\'s in the area with her skills and poise as a young gun. They do play in a very tough District 9 with teams like Carrollwood Day, Tampa Prep, and Bishop McLaughlin so they have their work cut out for them. The Phoenix play a tough schedule this year, and we will learn a lot about them over the next couple of months for a team that should make a run this year.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Who is the biggest threat to the Phoenix in 3A?</strong></span>\n\nClass 3A is going to be a fun one to watch unfold as there are a lot of talented teams in this one with the reclassification of Florida from 9 classes to 7.The teams that stick out to me the most (other than Brooks) are: Miami Country Day, Carrollwood Day, PK Yonge, Father Lopez, Seffner Christian, and Santa Fe Catholic, but there are some sleepers in there with this loaded class.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nBrooks will have two big tests coming up with Armwood (Monday) and Seffner Christian (Tuesday) at their Thanksgiving Shootout. Bishop Verot will have a tough matchup today against a reloaded Gulf Coast squad.\n\n&nbsp;','Five Key Questions After Brooks DeBartolo vs. Bishop Verot','','publish','open','open','','5-key-questions-after-brooks-debartolo-vs-bishop-verot','','','2019-11-22 10:27:56','2019-11-22 16:27:56','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115500',0,'post','',0),
	(115502,1,'2019-11-21 20:48:17','2019-11-22 02:48:17','Start of the season is right around the corner but this weekend Bullitt East is hosting a big scrimmage featuring several of the state\'s top teams and players. Here\'s a preview of Saturday\'s games.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Central vs Meade County (10:00)</strong></span>\n\nThe action gets started early as high scoring <strong>Kendall Wingler </strong>(EKU commit) heads to Louisville to take on the tough guard Sophomore duo of <strong>Amaya Asher and Tiffanie Floyd. </strong>Expect plenty of points to be scored in this one.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Webster County vs Scott (12:00)</strong></span>\n\nWebster County is led by recent Oakland City commit <strong>Marissa Austin </strong>and Scott features one of the best players in the state in Junior <strong>Mya Meredith. </strong>Meredith is a scoring machine with her eyes set on a 10th region championship while Webster expects to be one of the top teams in the 2nd region this season.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Bullitt East vs Ryle (2:00)</strong></span>\n\nThe reigning and defending state champion Lady Raiders are led by Ms. Basketball favorite <strong>Maddie Scherr</strong>. Ryle is probably the early favorite for a repeat championship. Bullitt East has multiple players who will be college players down the road. <strong>Lexi Taylor, Emma Egan and Kennedy Griffin</strong> form a very tough trio that will be tough to top in the 6th region.\n\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Manual vs Owensboro Catholic (4:00)</span></strong>\n\nTwo of the top teams in the state, both Catholic and Manual feature multiple D1 prospects. <strong>Hannah McKay </strong>has already signed with Murray State and Manual Junior <strong>Tiarra East </strong> could join her in the future as Murray has already offered the Junior wing. <strong>Daisha White</strong> is another name to watch for the Crimson.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Sacred Heart vs Bethlehem (6:00)</strong></span>\n\nSacred Heart is one of the best teams in the city of Louisville and capable of winning state. Seniors <strong>Destinee Marshall</strong> (Radford), <strong>Erin Toller</strong> (Kentucky) and <strong>Kristen Clemons</strong> (Belmont volleyball) are hoping to finish their careers on top while Juniors <strong>Ella Thompson and Amelia Hodges</strong> are looking to return to Rupp Arena this season after falling in the Sweet 16 back in March.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Mercy vs Woodford County (8:00)</strong></span>\n\nYet another top team in the state in action as Mercy takes on Woodford. <strong>Delaney Enlow</strong> is a matchup nightmare for any opponent while Seniors <strong>Taziah Jenks and Hope Sivori</strong> are primed for big final seasons for the Jaguars. Jenks is signed to West Virginia while Sivori is one of the best available players in the state.','Weekend Preview: Bullitt East Lady Chargers Hooparama (FREE)','','publish','open','open','','weekend-preview-bullitt-east-lady-chargers-hooparama-free','','','2019-11-21 20:48:17','2019-11-22 02:48:17','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115502',0,'post','',0),
	(115518,1,'2019-11-25 10:57:12','2019-11-25 16:57:12','Over the next three weeks, we\'re going to take a look at each class in Nebraska, starting with Class D2 and ending up with Class A right around Thanksgiving weekend.  Today, we wrap up our preseason coverage with a look at Class A, which is loaded with returning talent, great teams and a great race for a state champion the first weekend in March.\n\n<strong style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">RETURNING CHAMPION: </strong><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">Millard North rode one of the craziest journey\'s in state tournament history to win the first championship in school history.  The Mustangs defeated an outstanding Papillion-LaVista squad in the first round before participating in one of the greatest games in the history of the Nebraska state tournament, a 64-57 triple overtime thriller (the first triple overtime game in state tournament history) over Lincoln Pius X.  The Mustangs finished the tournament with a resounding 62-52 victory over Lincoln Southwest, who defeated the Mustangs in the first round of the 2018 state tournament.</span>\n\n<strong>TOP RETURNING PLAYER: </strong>There are so many great players in Class A this season, but we\'re going to go with the returning Gatorade state player of the year Jayme Horan of Millard South.  The Creighton commit lead the Patriots to another state tournament, averaging 20 points and eight rebounds a game for the 21-4 Patriots, who were upset in the first round of the state tournament by the seventh-seeded Lincoln East Spartans.  Teammate Maddie Krull is also one of the best point guards the state has produced in a long time, and her game compliments Horan\'s perfectly in Millard South\'s uptempo, pressing system.\n\n<strong>TEAM ON THE BRINK:</strong> Nebraska legend Kelly Flynn has picked up right where he left off from his South Sioux City days at Fremont, and he\'s got a boatload of talent to try to lead the Tiger\'s program to new heights.  Lead by all-state sophomore Taylor McCabe and a terrific supporting cast, including seniors Sydney Golladay and Lexi Glosser, along with underclassmen Macy Bryant, Charli Earth and Sarah Shephard, the Tigers figure to make it to Lincoln for the first time since WNBA player Jessica Shephard played for the Tigers nearly half a decade ago.\n\n<strong>BEST CONFERENCE:</strong> Like Class B, Class A is limited to three major conferences, and most years the Metro Conference is usually at the top of the rankings.  However, the Heartland Conference is going to be terrific this season from top to bottom.  Along with the aforementioned Fremont, the Heartland also features new addtion Lincoln Pius X and Lincoln East (both of which were in the state semi-finals last year), with Lincoln Southwest (last year\'s state runner-up), Lincoln Northeast (with all-stater McKenna Minter) and Lincoln High (with two Division I signees).  You could have a state-championship quality team that won\'t even make the conference semi-finals this season in the conference; now that\'s depth.\n\n<strong>REGULAR SEASON GAME(S) OF THE YEAR: </strong>With so many great teams in Class A, it is almost impossible to pick out one game that is head and shoulders above everyone else, so we\'re going to do things a little differently in Class A; we\'re going to pick out the best date for games this season.  Ironically, that date is February 14th, a great day to fall in love with girls basketball here in Nebraska.  Millard South will be Omaha Westside, while Lincoln Southwest will be at city rival Lincoln East.  Also, Papillion LaVista will be at Milard West.  Terrific day of hoops in the state!\n\n<strong>\"SUPER SEVEN\" INDIVIDUAL PLAYERS IN CLASS C1:</strong> Jayme Horan, 6\'0\" F, Millard South (22.6 ppg, 7.8 rpg, Sr.)/ Maddie Krull, 5\'11\" PG, Millard South (15.6 ppg, 3.5 rpg, 3.5 spg, 5.0 apg, Sr.)/ Nicole Avila-Ambrosi, 5\'8\" G, Millard North (13.4 ppg, 4.6 rpg, 2.0 spg, Sr.)/ McKenna Minter, 5\'8\" PG, Lincoln Northeast (16.3 ppg, 4.9 rpg, Sr.)/ Taylor McCabe, 5\'9\" G, Fremont (18.2 ppg, So.)/ Alexis Markowski, 6\'3\" C, Lincoln Pius X (13.5 ppg, 8.5 rpg, 2.0 bpg, Jr.)/ Ella Wedergren, 5\'9\" G, Omaha Westside (12.9 ppg, 4 apg, 40% 3 pt. shooter, Sr.)\n\n<strong>\"ELITE EIGHT\" IN LINCOLN THE FIRST WEEKEND IN MARCH: </strong>I am going to explain a couple of things about the Class A field before giving my picks.  Class A is absolutely loaded, with perhaps half of the class having a legitimate argument that they have a chance at the state tournament.  Class A is also different than the other classes, where they have seven district champions and one wild card team that qualifies based on regular season points based on strength of schedule.  There is also an added wrinkle of having traditional Class B powers Elkhorn and South Sioux City joining Class A for post-season competition, but playing a regular season largely consisting of Class B competition.  So, here is how I see things coming into the Class A season:\n\nContenders: Lincoln High, Omaha Burke, Millard North, Omaha Marian, South Sioux City, Elkhorn South, Millard West\n\nDistrict Champions: Millard South, Lincoln East, Westside, Papillion LaVista, Lincoln Northeast, Fremont, Lincoln Pius X\n\nWildcard Qualifier: Elkhorn\n\n<strong>PRE-SEASON STATE CHAMPIONSHIP PICK: </strong>What a loaded field!  As I said, half of Class A could stake a claim to a tournament birth, and many of those could have a logical argument as to why they should be cutting down the nets.  The tournament will come down to match-ups and health, but with all of that being even, the most talented roster is Millard South.  Horan and Krull lead the way, but with talented scorer McKenna Bray and a loaded freshman class, the Patriots are in line to win their first state championship since 1996 if they are able to set aside recent state tournament disappointments and catch the necessary breaks to win the title.','Class A Season Preview','','publish','open','open','','class-a-season-preview','','','2019-11-25 10:57:12','2019-11-25 16:57:12','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115518',0,'post','',0),
	(115537,1,'2019-11-21 17:25:29','2019-11-21 23:25:29','Continuing the excitement of the Mavs Fall Classic the <strong>Waxahachie Indians</strong> took on the <strong>Randall Raiders</strong>. The game nearly became a battle of styles as the Raiders fundamental game clashed with the Indians athleticism. As always, the game had its standouts and did it ever make for a good game to watch.\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115541 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/thumbnail-10-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Cassidy Beck\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Randall’s disciplined game ran through <strong>Cassidy Beck</strong> a long combo forward with an active game. She doesn’t need to dominate the ball to control the game she stays in the lane on defense. She the ultimate fast break player running the floor well or starting the break with pinpoint lead passes. Beck scores on the block with ease with dives to the block from off-ball screens. She gets to the free-throw line multiple times a game thanks to her patience.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><img class=\"alignright wp-image-115544 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_9949-e1574378432431-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Macayla Warren\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Macayla Warren</strong> is a ball hawk. She’s easily one of the best on ball defenders in the Mavs Classic swarming ball handlers with her long arms and quick feet. She mirrors moves, gets around screens, and balances being aggressive and containing players with great detail. She’s a defender first but no slouch on the offensive end when the ball swings to her high arcing shot race through the net.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115545 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_9951-e1574378443730-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Ainsley Velasquez\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Sophomore <strong>Ainsley Velasquez</strong> put together an impressive performance as one of the younger players on this Randall team. She already posses the defensive IQ to stay in the correct spots on defense. On offense, she shows the ability to be a competent scorer with the ball in her hands as displayed by her ability to attack from the triple threat. When she does Velasquez finishes at the rim with touch.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>When the dust settled Waxahachie emerged victoriously led by their fantastic backcourt and post player; <strong>Rayna Ross</strong>, <strong>Mya Williams</strong>, and <strong>Madison Crossno.</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignright wp-image-115546 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_9953-e1574378455590-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Rayna Ross\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Ross brings premiere size to the combo guard standing 5-10. The ball is safe in her hands and when it leaves 9 out of 10 times, it’ll end in a smart play or a basket. Her handle opens up her game and the floor as she creates opportunities for everyone wearing her jersey. Her first instinct is to score and those points can come from all three levels.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-115547 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_9954-e1574378467314-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Mya Williams\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Williams is a very physical guard for someone only 5-7. She’s so strong that many of her points come from the block where she bullies her way to the basket as defenders fall by the wayside. She’s just as capable on the perimeter thanks to tight handle that allows her to navigate deep into the paint. She finishes at a high level and is always in a position to score thanks to high IQ.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"alignright wp-image-115548 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/IMG_9955-e1574378479666-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Madison Crossno\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Crossno is a slender 6-1 post player that holds her own when matched up against others her size. Her length allows her to stay in a position to affect shots and protect the paint. She shoots it well out to 15-18 feet and combines encouraging mobility to her game.</div>','Mavs Classic: Waxahachie vs. Randall','','publish','open','open','','mavs-classic-waxahachie-vs-randall','','','2019-11-21 17:25:29','2019-11-21 23:25:29','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115537',0,'post','',0),
	(115551,1,'2019-11-22 17:44:28','2019-11-22 23:44:28','<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Oxford Academy Tournament 2019</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Fairmont Prep (2-0) San Joaquin League vs. Foothill HS (2-0) Crestview League</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Oxford Academy Gymnasium</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Cypress, California</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">November 21, 2019</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Game Time: 6pm\nFinal Score: <strong>Fairmont Prep HS 54</strong>, Foothill HS 43\n\n</span>\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Fairmont Prep HS - Top Performers:</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2020, 5\'6, SG, Milan Robinson - </strong>She was a utility player as well, sweet lefty that finished at the rim and hit the midrange.  She fought hard for her team last night and it showed by her pure effort on the court.  Robinson ended the game with <strong>7 points</strong>.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2021, 6\'0, SF, Makaila Glynn</strong> - She was a solid body forward that was agile and can handle the ball well. She had a great ability to chase down players and block their shots as well block shots off the pullup.  This girl was as solid as they come for a high school player.  Glynn ended the game with <strong>7 points</strong>.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2021, 5\'6, CG, Kayla Ishibashi</strong> - She was their go to player, shoots it from all three levels and can facilitate as well. Knocked down about 3 or 4 three pointers in this game and was able to get to the rim and hand some decent vision to be a facilitator.  Ishibashi ended the game with <strong>15 points, hit (3) three pointers.  </strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Ishibashiforthree.mov\">IshibashiThree</a></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2021, 5\'6, PG, AnLing Su Vera</strong> - She was a an all purpose guard with all around game, she ran the point guard to perfection for her squad, she did not turnover the ball much and she is a crafty little scoring threat, knocked down threes, got to the rim and finished.  Su Vera ended the game with <strong>11 points</strong>. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/AnLingSuVera-Jumpshot.mov\">SuVera for Three</a></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2021, 5\'10, SF, Mia Yamamoto</strong> - She was a nice size forward that could finish and rebound very well for team, she did all the dirty work for her team, set screens, rolled to the basket for finishes and hit a couple of midrange shots to boot.  Yamamoto ended the game with <strong>15 points</strong>.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\">Foothill HS - Top Performers:</span>\n</strong></span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2020, SG, Haley Vela</strong> - She was a spot up shooter that hung around and moved off the ball to get to her spots for three pointers.  Vela ended the game with <strong>3 points</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2020, PG, Nicole Pena</strong> - She was a little frame guard that can shoot the open shot and make it.  Pena ended the game with <strong>3 points.</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2020, 5\'7, SG/SF, Megan Jones</strong> - She was Foothills goto player all night, she played that short corner, high post position and found seams in the defense all night to score.  Jones ended the game with <strong>15 points. </strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/MeganJonesFoothill.mov\">Megan Jones Foothill - Jumpshot</a></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2021, 5\'4, PG/SG, Paige Jang</strong> - She was an aggressive guard that relies on the drive and kick game to get off. Ability to break down her man and finish thru contact at the rim.  Jang emded the game with <strong>11 points.</strong></span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[robo-gallery id=116024]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Oxford Academy Tournament - Game #3 - Fairmont Prep vs. Foothill','','publish','open','open','','oxford-academy-tournament-game-3-fairmont-prep-vs-foothill','','','2019-11-22 17:44:28','2019-11-22 23:44:28','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115551',0,'post','',0),
	(115561,1,'2019-11-23 13:14:17','2019-11-23 19:14:17','<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Oxford Academy Tournament 2019</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">St. Anthony HS (2-0) Del Rey League vs. Tesoro HS (2-0) South Coast League</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Oxford Academy Gymnasium</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Cypress, California</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">November 21, 2019</span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Game Time: 7:30PM\nFinal Score: <strong>St. Anthony HS 59</strong>, Tesoro HS 34</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nIn this matchup, <strong>St. Anthony</strong> was just too much for <strong>Tesoro</strong>, the guard play was the matchup problem in our opinion watching this game. With superb guard play from <strong>Emily Perez with 22 points, Hannah Bailey with 12 points and Drew Sharp 9 points</strong> it was difficult for <strong>Tesoro</strong> to keep up with the pace and trapping defense of <strong>St. Anthony</strong>.  Do not get me wrong the talents of <strong>Katie Schwan with 12 points</strong> and<strong> Celine Castaneda with 16 points</strong> were impressive as well, but not at the level of Perez and Bailey in this game.  <strong>St. Anthony</strong> is primed to have a good season this year and we will be watching them closely and bringing you news and information about players on their team.  <strong>Tesoro</strong> is young and they will find their way, the talent is there, but the experience on the floor has not caught up yet.  Great game by two teams and we look forward to seeing them both this season a little more.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>St. Anthony High School - Top Performers\n</strong>\n\n<strong>2020, CG, Kira Smith</strong> - She was a long body guard that could run the floor and finish. Did some special things for her team, set screens and did the dirty work no one sees.\n\n<strong>2020, PG, Emily Perez</strong> - She is an aggressive lefty guard with a solid body. Did it all for her team, true leader on the floor for her team. Knocked down threes and got to the rim thru contact.  She was impressive, had never seen her play before, worth watching again, coaches, she is solid.\n\n<strong>2020, SG, Drew Sharp</strong> - She was a small framed body but really athletic guard, quick and defended well and has a nice stroke from outside.  She pushed the ball down the floor and found her teammates for shots or finished at the rim.\n\n<strong>2022, F, Alahnie Tunu</strong> - She was a nice athletic forward with a great defensive skills and relentless on the boards.\n\n<strong>Tesoro High School - Top Performers:</strong>\n\n<strong>2020, 6\'0, F, Katie Schwan</strong> - She was their goto player and put in the most work with 8 of the 12 pts in the first qtr. Tough post player with a nice bag of tricks, did everything for her team, set screens, sealed her opponents in the paint and finished.\n\n<strong>2021, 5\'7, G, Ava Pinto</strong> - She was a scrappy forward with some game in her bag, she took care of the ball. She was able to get to the rim and finish, set up her teammates for easy baskets, was a decent facilitator.\n\n<strong>2021, 5\'6, G, Aysia Castaneda</strong> - She was an aggressive forward with some decent defensive skills, picked a few guards in the game.  Was impressed with her control on the floor and speed, she was a bonefide guard with some special skills.\n\n<strong>2023, 5\'5, PG, Celine Castaneda</strong> - She was a freshman and she impressed us with her play, she shot the ball well, she facilitated, she defended and was a solid all around point guard on the floor.  The fact that she is a freshman is impressive, she has a lot more ceiling in her game, she will be special for years to come.','Oxford Academy Tournament - St. Anthony vs. Tesoro','','publish','open','open','','oxford-academy-tournament-st-anthony-vs-tesoro','','','2019-11-23 13:14:17','2019-11-23 19:14:17','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=115561',0,'post','',0),
	(115580,1,'2019-11-22 17:00:33','2019-11-22 23:00:33','With the season getting underway today, we are going to by cycling through a ton of coverage today. You saw the Preseason Team rankings at noon, Games of the Week at 1PM, and the Class 1A-3A PGH Preseason All-State teams, now we are announcing our 4A all-state picks. When selecting players we look at overall skill, but also we look at overall importance to their team. Thus that will be reflected in the All-State Teams. For each class, we will have a first through fifth team followed by our preseason player of the year at the end of the article. Additionally, players are in alphabetical order within their “team”.  Look for the 5A All-State picks at 6PM to kick off the season!\n\n<hr />\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\">4A First Team</span></strong></p>\n\n<table class=\"tablepress\" cellspacing=\"10\" cellpadding=\"10\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\"><strong>Name</strong></td>\n<td valign=\"top\"><strong>High School</strong></td>\n<td valign=\"top\"><strong>Class</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\">Abbie Draper</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">Waverly-Shell Rock</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">2021</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\">Adrianna Katcher</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">Center Point-Urbana</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">2020</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\">Ava Hawthorne</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">Gilbert</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">2022</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\">Katie Keitges</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">Knoxville</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">2020</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\">Kayba Laube</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">Marion</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">2020</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\">4A Second Team</span></strong></p>\n\n<table class=\"tablepress\" style=\"width: 100%;\" cellspacing=\"10\" cellpadding=\"10\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 39.1072618254497%;\" valign=\"top\"><strong