	(119471,1,'2019-12-01 13:29:37','2019-12-01 19:29:37','<strong>THE WEEK THAT WAS:</strong> Many teams across the state opened up their seasons over the last week, either right before or right after Thanksgiving, with their traditional jamboree games.  There was alot of cross-class match-ups, especially in the Omaha-Lincoln area.  The concept of the jamboree exhibition started about ten years ago, and it is a really nice way for teams to get in a uniform and play against someone else before the games start for real this coming weekend.\n\n<strong>GAME OF THE WEEK --&gt; LINCOLN-OMAHA CORRIDOR:</strong> There are quite a few nice match-ups in the opening weekend, but the 4-Team Classic featuring Fremont, Lincoln Northeast, Omaha Westside and Bellevue West ought to be very good.  Three of these teams project out to have a great chance at the state tournament, and Bellevue West is always a competitive program.  These teams will see what they are made of right on the opening weekend.\n\n<strong>GAME OF THE WEEK --&gt; STATE-WIDE:</strong> We are going to go to Class B for this match-up.  On Saturday, defending state champion Grand Island Northwest goes on the road to take on Norris, who will be a difficult match-up for the Vikings.  All-state guard Whitney Brown will try to lead the Vikings past the Titans, who feature returning all-state post player Breanna Stai, along with a strong returning group of players that are hungry to get back to Lincoln.  The champions have a tough weekend, with a semi-final rematch against Waverly, who had a sixteen point lead in that game before Northwest came storming back.\n\nHonorable Mention: Loomis at Overton (Friday, 12/6), Fillmore Central at Milford (Friday, 12/6), Hastings St. Cecilia\'s at Bishop Neumann (Saturday, 12/7), Bennington at Wahoo (Saturday, 12/7)\n\nAlong with these features, I plan on highlighting a \"Player of the Week\", along with other observations about teams and individuals.  Look for those features in this column in the coming weeks!\n\n<strong>CLASS A ELITE EIGHT: </strong>Millard South, Lincoln East, Westside, Papillion LaVista, Lincoln Northeast, Fremont, Lincoln Pius X, Elkhorn\n\n<strong>CLASS B ELITE EIGHT: </strong>Grand Island Northwest, Crete, Norris, Beatrice, Sidney, Bennington, Scottsbluff, York\n\n<strong>CLASS C1 ELITE EIGHT: </strong>Broken Bow, North Bend-Central, Lincoln Chrisitan, Milford, Ogallala, Wahoo, O\'Neill, Omaha Roncalli\n\n<strong>CLASS C2 ELITE EIGHT: </strong>Hastings St. Cecilia, Crofton, Fillmore Central, Grand Island Central Catholic, Nebraska City Lourdes, Oakland-Craig, Centennial (Utica), Superior\n\n<strong>CLASS D1 ELITE EIGHT: </strong>CWC, Weeping Water, Pleasanton, Dundy County-Stratton, Humphery/ Lindsay Holy Family, Johnson-Brock, Overton, Pender\n\n<strong>CLASS D2 ELITE EIGHT: </strong>Falls City Sacred Heart, Ewing, Humphery St. Francis, Wynot, BDS, Loomis, Lawrence-Nelson, Cody-Kilgore\n\n&nbsp;','This Week in Nebraska Girls Basketball-December 1st, 2019','','publish','open','open','','this-week-in-nebraska-girls-basketball-december-1st-2019','','','2019-12-01 13:29:37','2019-12-01 19:29:37','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119471',0,'post','',0),
	(119476,1,'2019-12-01 13:00:41','2019-12-01 19:00:41','We are done with the first week of the season and that means Player of the Week voting! Each week we will be taking five of the top performers from the last week and letting you vote for the Player of the Week! The poll will be posted each Sunday at 1PM and voting ends on Tuesday at 12PM. Let\'s meet the five candidates below.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong>Grace Boffeli | 2020 | North Scott | 2 games, 71 points, 27/39 FG, 23 rebounds </strong>\nBoffeli opened the season with a 37 point, 10 rebound performance in a 69-61 win over Cedar Rapids Kennedy. She was efficient from the floor as she hit 15-of-23 from the field. Boffeli followed that up by going 12-of-16 from the floor and 10-for-11 at the line in a 59-55 win over Xavier at \"Rivalry Saturday\". The 34 point performance set the record for most points scored in a game at the event. Boffeli also had 11 rebounds in the game.\n\n<strong>Karsyn Stratton | 2020 | Clear Creek-Amana | 1 game, 31 points, 13/23 FG, 11 rebounds</strong>\nStratton had a tremendous start to the season as she scored 31 points and pulled down 11 rebounds in an opening win over Solon 58-43. Six of her rebounds were offensive boards. Stratton played well on both ends as she also had three assists and three turnovers.\n\n<strong>Helaina Hillyard | 2020 | Mediapolis | 1 game, 17 points, 7/15 FG, 13 steals, 7 rebounds, 6 assists</strong>\nHillyard had one of the most dominating games of the young year as she did everything in their win over Winfield-Mt. Union and more. Hillyard filled the stat sheet in a 64-32 win. It was a great performance that showed her versatility on both ends of the floor.\n\n<strong>Jordan England | 2021 | Lenox | 1 game, 12 points, 3/12 FG, 26 rebounds</strong>\nEngland took over the boards in the Lenox win over Clarinda. Lenox won the game 36-30 and England almost had as many rebounds as Clarinda had points in the game. The 26 rebounds was the highest total in an Iowa High School game since Amanda Chizek had 27 rebounds on 12/19/2017.\n\n<strong>Anna Deets | 2020 | Mason City | 3 games, 81 points, 25/48 FG, 21 rebounds</strong>\nDeets had a tremendous start to the season for Mason City. Deets had 39 points and 10 rebounds in their 83-61 win over Ankeny. Deets hit six 3-pointers in that game to lead them to a win. In their second game of the year, Mason City beat Des Moines North 69-31. Deets had 27 points in that game and hit four 3-pointers. In a 57-49 win over Waverly-Shell Rock Deets scored 15 points and had eight rebounds. It was a very good all-around week for her as Mason City pulled in a couple of big wins.\n\nhttps://poll.fm/10470765','PGH Iowa Week 1 Player of the Week Voting','','publish','open','open','','pgh-iowa-week-1-player-of-the-week-voting','','','2019-12-01 13:00:41','2019-12-01 19:00:41','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119476',0,'post','',0),
	(119508,1,'2019-12-01 17:18:40','2019-12-01 23:18:40','Each week on PGH Ohio, I will be posting and updating a Power Poll of teams in this Dayton area. The top five teams based on performance will be released every Sunday evening except for this week, which will be Monday morning due to the games last night at the Journey to the Tourney.\n\n<strong>Week 2 (week ending Dec. 1)</strong>\n\n<strong>Division 1</strong>\n\n<strong>1. Fairmont (2-0)</strong> remains the #1 team in Division 1 in the Dayton area after a big weekend al Lakota West. No games last week, but three big games this week including Fenwick tonight, at Springfield on Wednesday and a huge showdown at Wayne on Saturday night a game that will be covered by PGH Ohio.\n\n<strong>2. Wayne (3-0)</strong> struggled in the first half on Saturday night against Tecumseh, only to turn it on in the third quarter and take the lead, cruising to a 66-47 victory. The Warriors travel to Beavercreek on Wednesday and as mentioned, host #1 ranked Fairmont on Saturday night.\n\n<strong>3. Springboro (1-0)</strong> off last week, but comes back strong on Monday as they host perennial power Mason on Monday night. They also host Northmont on Wednesday and Miamisburg on Saturday.\n\n<strong>4. Centerville (1-1)</strong> an easy 74-48 win over New Albany on Friday moved them to 1-1 on the young season. Amy Velasco led the Elks with 23, Cotie McMahon added 17, Emma Stanley 11 and Kendal George scored 10. The Cincinnati Trailblazers come to town on Tuesday night and then they host Springfield on Saturday.\n\n<strong>5. Bellbrook (3-0)</strong> A tough opening stretch to open the season sees the Eagles 3-0. They defeated Waynesville 58-53 last week in their lone game. Bellbrook hosts Dunbar on Monday and Franklin on Saturday.\n\n<strong>Division 2</strong>\n\n<strong>1. Carroll (1-1)</strong> lost to Purcell Marian in their season opener 42-33 but remains #1 when they bounced back against Roger Bacon 43-38 for the win. Junior Megan Leraas led with 16 point including 5 from beyond the arc. Sarah Ochs added 14 points. The Patriots travel to Wyoming Monday night, then play at Fenwick on Wednesday.\n\n<strong>2. Jonathan Alder (2-0)</strong> played once last week, and cruised past Bishop Ready 84-26 to remain unbeaten on the season. The Pioneers host Graham on Wednesday and then bring in Kenton Ridge on Saturday. Seniors Sydney Bourquin and Abby Jones continues to lead the way for JA.\n\n<strong>3. Chaminade Julienne (3-1)</strong> big win against Legacy Christian, a top five D4 team 47-36 as Staci Greene led with 14 points. They also beat a previously unbeaten Badin team 48-42 behind Jordan Varise with 14 points. CJ travels to Alter on Wednesday night for a huge rivalry game, then McNicholas comes to down on Saturday. They moved up spot from last week.\n\n<strong>4. Valley View (1-2)</strong> lost to D1 Miamisburg 49-43 to drop their second game of the season before bouncing back with a 68-23 victory over Brookville on Saturday morning. Big game Monday night as Valley View travels to Edgewood before hosting Oakwood on Thursday and head to Monroe on Saturday.\n\n<strong>5. Trotwood Madison (1-0)</strong> opened their season with a 22-point victory against Kenton Ridge as Quanitaijah Huffman led the attack with 24 points with freshman Raeven Raye-Redmond added nine points in the win.\n\n<strong>Division 3</strong>\n\n<strong>1. Versailles (3-1)</strong> Remains #1 this week. Solid week for the Tigers as they defeated Delphos St. John and Covington. They defeated DSJ 71-54 as Brooke Stonebraker led with 19, Lindsey Winner 12 and Caitlin McEldowney 11. In a 59-26 win over Covington, Winner led with 15, McEldowney added 14. Play Fort Recovery and Miami East this week.\n\n<strong>2. West Liberty Salem (3-0)</strong> big win against D2 ranked Tippecanoe team last week 40-35 as Selena Weaver led with 18 and Emily Hollar added 15. WLS then defeated Miami East on Saturday behind Weaver again. She is a 6-foot junior who has vastly improved. Huge game Tuesday against Fort Loramie, then Thursday at Triad, Saturday vs Northeastern.\n\n<strong>3. Arcanum (3-1)</strong> won twice last week, including a 71-45 win against Lehman Catholic on Saturday. The Trojans travel to Bethel on Thursday for a CCC matchup. They move up one spot from last week.\n\n<strong>4. Waynesville (1-2)</strong> lost to Bellbrook last week 58-53 despite 17 points from Leah Butterbaugh, 13 from Carli Brown and 12 from Isabella Cassoni. Second loss in a row for the Spartans. Looks to get back on the winning track Tuesday hosting Madison, Thursday vs Shawnee and Saturday at Northridge.\n\n<strong>5. Anna (2-0)</strong> the Rockets won their first two games of the season. They defeated Botkins 42-29 last week as 6-2 senior Lauren Barhorst scored 16, Kiplyn Rowland scored nine and Ella Doseck pitched in eight. They play Lehman Monday, New Bremen on Tuesday and Russia on Saturday.\n\n<strong>Division 4</strong>\n\n<strong>1 (tie). Tri Village (4-0)</strong> earned two more wins last week including a 76-34 win over Bradford, as Rylee Sagester led with 21, Maddie Downing 15, Morgan Hunt 14 and Meghan Downing 10. They also defeated Ansonia 75-16 as Maddie Downing had 22, Sagester 17, Hunt 14, Meghan Downing 12. They return to action Thursday at #3 ranked Franklin Monroe in a huge game.\n\n<strong>1 (tie). Fort Loramie (3-0)</strong> their defense has not allowed more than 19 points in a game the first three games of the season. Their defense is suffocating and are so balanced its scary. Dominated Fairlawn 84-17 as Marissa Meiring had 15, Dana Rose and Kenzi Hoelscher each with 12, Riley Heitkamp with 11. On Saturday they destroyed Russia  71-15 behind Rose with 15, Hoelscher 11 and Meiring 10. Due to their incredible start, they are moving up and sharing the top spot in D4 with Tri Village.\n\n<strong>3. Franklin Monroe (3-0)</strong> what an incredible game on Saturday against ranked Legacy Christian as FM wins 38-37 in a game covered by  PGH Ohio. Corina Conley showed why she is ranked in the top 25 in Ohio in her class. Balanced perimeter attack with Belle Cable and Audrey Cable. FM hosts #1 Tri Village on Thursday.\n\n<strong>4. Mechanicsburg (4-0) </strong>the Indians enter the rankings after a strong 4-0 start to the season. They have been led by senior Kasey Schipfer <span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><strong>(pictured above) </strong></span>and junior Grace Forrest. Mechanicsburg travels to West Jefferson on Thursday and hosts Triad on Saturday.\n\n<strong>5 (tie). Legacy Christian (1-2)</strong> drops to the #5 spot after a pair of losses to ranked CJ and ranked FM. They look to get back on the winning track this week with a league game against Jefferson.\n\n<strong>5 (tie). Minster (2-1)</strong> after a win against Celina, the Wildcats return to action this week against Parkway and Jackson Center.','Dayton area Power Poll- Week 2','','publish','open','open','','dayton-area-power-poll-week-2','','','2019-12-01 17:18:40','2019-12-01 23:18:40','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119508',0,'post','',0),
	(119523,1,'2019-12-02 08:16:13','2019-12-02 14:16:13','Collinsville held on for the victory in a hard fought Championship game in the Nashville Thanksgiving tourney. Collinsville had the lead late in regulation but 3-pointers by <strong>Alyssa Cole</strong> and <strong>Emily Schnitker</strong> got them right back in it. Collinsville had the last shot but could not convert so the game went to Overtime. When <strong>Kristyn Mitchell</strong> hit a tough driving left handed layup to put Collinsville up 2 points it gave the Lady Kahoks the edge they needed. They hit just enough free throws and got enough stops to secure the victory. Here are a few key questions from the game.\n<ol>\n 	<li><strong>Does Collinsville have enough depth?</strong> Collinsville has a very solid starting 5 but they get a bit young once they go to the bench. They played 2 freshman, both of them provided some help and seemed to handle to the pressure of a big game. <strong>Jordan Gary</strong> is very athletic and seems most ready to handle the level of play that will be needed from the bench. She is an excellent athlete that can play at the pace that Collinsville would like to go. <strong>Jenna Scheller</strong> is a big bodied 6\'2 post player that showed good touch around the rim. She is best in the half court game so Collinsville likely needs to slow the pace a bit when she is in the game. Jenna can be counted on in short stints to provide depth. The only other player to play in every game has been Senior <strong>Natalie Becker</strong>. Natalie is a 5\'6 guard that has not contributed much to the box scores yet. Because of the aggressive nature of their defense Coach Billy will have to develop this bench to cover foul trouble.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Who is the go to scorer for Nashville?</strong> Everyone needs to have multiple players scoring to have the best team, but, most teams have a go to scorer that they can count on in tight games. Nashville may still be figuring out who that is or what type of play works best for them when they have to have a basket. They ran some effective sets that forced Collinsville to make a decision on where/ how they wanted to help and it led to an open 3 that was converted. But, they still seemed unsure of who could get a shot on their own if needed. To me that person is <strong>Alyssa Cole. </strong>Alyssa has really developed her game coming into her sophomore season. She can hit the 3 and when she is crowded she can take you off the dribble. She has become more of a power wing than a post player as her game grows. At 5\'8 Alyssa cannot live in the paint but is effective at taking defenders into the paint off the dribble.</li>\n 	<li><strong>How far can the Collinsville senior class take them? </strong>The three senior starters, <strong>Faith Liljegren</strong>, <strong>Caite Knutson</strong> and <strong>Kristyn Mitchell</strong> will play a big part in determining how far Collinsville can go this year. Liljegren is the point guard and is the “captain” of their offense. She is a SEMO commit for soccer and is an excellent athlete. She handles the ball well, is calm under pressure and sees the floor well.Mitchell is a post player that can score inside and outside along with gathering rebounds. She is capable of creating her own shot off the dribble this year which came in clutch against Nashville in overtime. Knutson is a jack of all trades. She can play offense and defense both inside and outside. She can defend just about anyone on the court. Offensively she has nice moves inside the lane while also having the ability to hit the jump shot out to the 3-point line. These three will determine how far Collinsville can go. To get big wins during the conference season and come tournament time all three will have to be dependable scorers to get it done. Without a deep bench these ladies will have to be consistent and stay out of foul trouble. If they can do that, second place in the conference and a Regional title are possible for this group.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Who was the best defender on the floor? Rylee Luechtefeld </strong>and Caite Knutson were both fun to watch on the defensive end. Rylee was showing off her ability to change the game by blocking every shot, it seemed. Caite is so versatile that she can change the game on defense. In this game she was responsible for guarding Rylee. Rylee is 6\'1 and has long arms so on offense she can be tough to stop inside but she is also capable of stepping away from the basket to score on the outside. That did not phase Caite at all. She can use her strength inside and athletic ability when the player goes outside. In the end Caite had the better night as Rylee was held to 6 points which is well below her expected output. These are two are fun to watch and college coaches should pay attention.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Who were the top college prospects in this game? </strong>The 2020 players mentioned above can all play at the next level. Liljegren is playing soccer but Knutson and Mitchell from Collinsville are both JC up to NAIA prospects at this point to me. Mitchell is a great student is a classic fit at the D3 level if that is what she chooses. She can play at the next level because of her ability to score the ball at all 3 levels. She can stretch the floor by hitting the three but will also use her dribble to get to the rim. Knutson is a 2/3/4 player depending on the level and the style of play. She is more than capable of defending all three spots and is a versatile offensive player too. She is a good fit at the JC level because of the upside she has to improve her offensive game with the daily routine of college basketball. Luechtefeld is a also a great fit at the JC level because if she can improve her lateral quickness and ball handling in tight spaces she has a low level D1/high D2 body and skill set for a stretch 4. Rylee can also choose to play at the NAIA or D3 level and make an impact. <strong>Astacia Bush</strong> from Collinsville is 2021 power guard that has potential at a lower level. She has the body and tough nosed, she could develop into a more consistent offensive threat with time. Another power guard/small forward at a lower level could be Cole from Nashville. Alyssa is a 2022 that came into her freshman year feeling most comfortable with her back to the basket. She has developed a good outside shot that she can hit from 3 and does a good job driving to the hole. At 5\'8 she is somewhat limited in where she can play as she will not have the athletic ability to play guard at the D1 level but she can certainly play in college. The freshman mentioned above from Collinsville can certainly develop in college players as they have either the size or athletic ability that translates. Also Nashville has some young guards that I saw for the first time so I cannot tell where they fit yet.</li>\n</ol>\nAll in all, this was a great game with some real talent to watch. I am excited to follow these two programs throughout the season.','Collinsville vs Nashville: 5 Key Questions','','publish','open','open','','collinsville-vs-nashville-5-key-questions','','','2019-12-02 08:16:13','2019-12-02 14:16:13','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119523',0,'post','',0),
	(119527,1,'2019-12-01 16:00:28','2019-12-01 22:00:28','Each Sunday we will be previewing the best games in the upcoming week. It is the first full week of games and there are going to be some very good matchups. Below you can find the top ten games around the state for Week #2.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong>Monday</strong>: Aplington-Parkersburg (0-0) vs. BCLUW (2-0) @ 6:15PM\nOne of the top games on Monday pits two of the top 2A teams against one another. Aplington-Parkersburg is looking to start their season on a high note and BCLUW is going to look to prove that they are legit. BCLUW has gotten off to a quick 2-0 start, but this would be a huge win for them.\n\n<strong>Tuesday: </strong>Bettendorf (2-0) @ Davenport Assumption (2-0) @ 6:00PM\nBoth of these teams have gotten off to similar 2-0 starts and are looking to add a big win to their resume. The Bettendorf win over Linn-Mar and the Assumption win over Xavier don\'t look particularly good right now but later in the year they likely will. Whoever wins this one could set the stage for a great year.\n\n<strong>Tuesday: </strong>Ames (0-1) @ Mason City (3-0) @ 6:15PM\nBoth of these results by these teams may have surprised some early in the year. Not many saw Ames losing to Waukee by 19 in their opener and I\'m sure after losing Megan Meyer to graduation, not many people would have thought that Mason City would start 3-0. This game will be a good sign of what\'s to come for these two squads.\n\n<strong>Tuesday</strong>: Bishop Heelan (0-0) vs. Lewis Central (1-0) @ 7:00PM\nA Tuesday night matchup between two of the strongest 3A programs in the state is on tap for Tuesday night. Bishop Heelan opens their season as one of the top teams in 3A after dropping down from 4A and Lewis Central is as strong this year on paper as they have been in years. It\'s a big week for Lewis Central as they have this game and then Red Oak on Saturday.\n\n<strong>Tuesday: </strong>Davenport North (1-0) vs. North Scott (2-0) @ 7:30PM\nDavenport North had a big win over Cedar Rapids Washington in their season opener and now take on a strong team as they head to North Scott. North Scott sits at 2-0 after wins over Xavier and Cedar Rapids Kennedy. Davenport North likely has the only singular player in the state that can stop Grace Boffeli so this game will be very interesting to watch.\n\n<strong>Thursday: </strong>Center Point-Urbana (0-0) vs. Waverly-Shell Rock (0-1) @ 6:00PM\nDefending 3A state champ Center Point-Urbana gets their season underway at Waverly-Shell Rock in a game that is sure to be very good. Waverly-Shell Rock lost their first contest but hope to gain some momentum with a huge win. This will be a really good game to see two of the top players in the state.\n\n<strong>Friday: </strong>Gilbert (1-1) vs. North Polk (0-2) @ 6:00PM\nBoth of these teams are looking to regroup and get back on track. After a sloppy win to start the year against Ballard, Gilbert fell to Iowa City West. North Polk has not looked good to start the year and fell to Johnston and took a big loss to Dallas Center-Grimes. Whoever wins this one will be glad they did.\n\n<strong>Friday: </strong>Iowa City West (1-0) vs. Prairie (1-0) @ 7:30PM\nIowa City West looked better in their first game of the year than many expected and got a very solid win over Gilbert. Prairie struggled a little in their game with Muscatine but came out on top. This is a big early-season contest between two teams who are looking to prove themselves to the doubters.\n\n<strong>Saturday</strong>: Dallas Center-Grimes (2-0) @ Des Moines Christian (2-0) @ 6:00PM\nThis might be the top game of the week as both of these teams have looked good in the early going. Dallas Center-Grimes has had two really nice wins and Des Moines Christian had a tough win over Creston and an easier win against Grinnell. Both of these teams will be in it till the end this year so seeing them matchup early will be fun.\n\n<strong>Saturday: </strong>Glenwood (1-0) vs. Carroll (1-0) @ 6:00PM\nGlenwood might be the surprise of 3A this year as they are very solid. This game is going to be one where they can prove themselves against a solid 4A program. Carroll is going to have to play better offensively after escaping with a win against Webster City. This is going to be a statement win for either team.','Games of the Week: Week 2','','publish','open','open','','games-of-the-week-week-2','','','2019-12-01 16:00:28','2019-12-01 22:00:28','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119527',0,'post','',0),
	(119528,1,'2019-12-01 18:16:45','2019-12-02 00:16:45','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Mo County Mo County! New season new same action in the Montgomery County region. Let\'s put the spotlight on some of the top talent across the region. </span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/nia-newman/\"><span style=\"color: #f75617\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\">Nia Newman | 5\'6 W |  Rockville 2022</span></strong></span></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">The excitement is real in Montgomery County. One half of the Newman twins, 5\'6 Wing Nia Newman, was a solid addition for the Rockville Rams her freshman year. The dynamic duo of <strong>Nia and Naila Newman</strong> went on to lead #2 Rockville to the Sweet 16 of the MPSSAA State Championship last year. Nia is ranked #44 on Prep Girls Hoops 2022 rankings, her sister Naila is ranked #33.</span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/chase-bell/\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color: #f75617\">Chase Bell | 5\'7 G | Sherwood 2022</span></strong></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">5-7 Guard Chase Bell plays like she\'s 6\'0. Bell is an intelligent elusive guard for the #1 ranked Sherwood Warriors and can certainly fill up a stat sheet. Bell seems to always be around the ball and is always looking to facilitate when coming up the court. She also has a clutch outside jump shot and comes up big on boards. Chase Bell is quickly finding herself as one of the leaders of this Sherwood basketball team.   </span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-clausen/\"><span style=\"color: #f75617\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\">Paige Clausen | 5\'11 W | Urbana 2021</span></strong></span></a>\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000;font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Paige Clausen is on the come up in the Montgomery County region. Currently ranked #9 on Prep Girls Hoops 2021 rankings, Paige can be recognized as one of the best Wings in the state. Paige plays with an extreme amount of hustle while making it all look easy. I\'m looking forward to seeing Paige develop an even better inside game as she goes into her Junior season. </span>\n\n&nbsp;','Montgomery County Spotlight','','publish','open','open','','montgomery-county-spotlight','','','2019-12-01 18:16:45','2019-12-02 00:16:45','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119528',0,'post','',0),
	(119534,1,'2019-12-01 16:43:05','2019-12-01 22:43:05','With the 2019-20 girls basketball season right around the corner, let’s take a look back/forward at how things shook out and what to look forward to in each of Colorado’s conferences. Here’s a snapshot of the Pikes Peak League.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>How it all shook out in ’18-19</strong></span>\n\nAir Academy has dominated this league for the past three years to the tune of three straight conference championships, 40-2 combined league record over the past three seasons and back-to-back unbeaten conference seasons in ’17-18 and ‘18-19. The Kadets ran the table with seven points being their smallest margin of victory in any conference game.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>Which playoff team advanced the farthest?</strong></span>\n\nThis category also clearly goes to Air Academy, as the Kadets played their way into the Final Four of the 4A state tournament. Their run ended there, unfortunately, with a 45-42 loss to eventual runner-up Pueblo South.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_103791\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"203\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-103791\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Kylee-Blacksten-2-Air-Academy-CU-photo-203x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"203\" height=\"300\" /> Kylee Blacksten[/caption]\n\n<span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>A few returning players to watch</strong></span>\n\n<strong>Kylee Blacksten, 2020, 6-3, G, Air Academy</strong>\n\nThe University of Colorado commit was incredible in ’18-19, finishing second in the league behind Ashton Prechtel in scoring with 14.6 points per game. Nearly impossible to stop as a 6-foot-3 perimeter player, she also averaged 7.2 rebounds, 2.3 assists, 2.5 steals and 1.8 blocks throughout her junior season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Hannah Burg, 2021, 5-8, G, Falcon</strong>\n\nA big-time stock riser, Burg broke out in a big way last winter. As a sophomore, she was third in the league with 14.2 points per game to go with 3.8 rebounds and 2.4 steals. Lightning quick and aggressive, Burg has looked in the preseason like she’s ready to take yet another step forward as a senior alongside teammates Billie Fiore (2022), Kayla Harkema (2021), Trinity Grant (2020) and Kilee Wood (2021).\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Nikki Derrell, 2021, 5-2, G, Sand Creek</strong>\n\nSand Creek has one heck of a backcourt with Derrell and senior teammate Krystina Hagood, who is PGH Colorado’s 27<sup>th</sup>-ranked player in the 2020 class. Ranked No. 16 in her own graduating class, Derrell has been on the radar since her freshman year and has <em>career</em> averages of 14.1 points, 3.1 rebounds, 2.4 assists and 2.3 steals over 43 varsity games. She actually shot the 3-pointer better as a freshman (35 percent) than she did her sophomore season, during which she went 47 for 175 for an average of 27 percent. Also keep an eye on Sand Creek senior Malena Portillos, a 5-foot-4 shooting guard who shot 32 percent from long range last winter.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Sydney Day, 2020, 6-1, F, Palmer Ridge</strong>\n\nForming a solid one-two punch with teammate Eden Bonser, Day was no scoring machine last season but did nearly average a double-double. She was counted on for a nightly 8.6 points and 7.7 rebounds. Bonser averaged 8.5 points a game.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong>A quick, early look to ’19-20</strong></span>\n\nAir Academy graduated three of its four leading scorers but the Kadets haven’t lost Blacksten to CU just yet, and it’s hard to pick against them when she’s still on the roster. Discovery Canyon took a big hit when Prechtel, who is playing well at Stanford, walked out the door on graduation day. Sand Creek has some exciting players. Susanna Robinson (2021) and Vista Ridge could be better, as could Ally Delange (2020) and Lewis-Palmer. Palmer Ridge is seasoned and Falcon has lots of young talent. Still, it’s hard to pick against the Kadets so we won’t.','Season Preview: Pikes Peak League','','publish','open','open','','season-preview-pikes-peak-league','','','2019-12-01 16:43:05','2019-12-01 22:43:05','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119534',0,'post','',0),
	(119538,1,'2019-12-03 07:58:36','2019-12-03 13:58:36','When <strong>Aniyah Finger</strong> of Hopewell goes 13-23 from the field and scores 31 points as she did in Saturday\'s victory over the Burlington School, it\'s easy to recognize her value.  Though, what about the subtle foot soldiers who quietly do the little things crucial to victory?  Although most of these ladies weren\'t the headliners for their teams, their respective contributions were invaluable to their teams\' success this past weekend at the CHC.\n<ol>\n 	<li><strong>Marlow Chapman</strong> - Providence.  The 5\'10\" Senior Forward was huge in the first half as Providence Day jumped out to an early 16-7 advantage. Chapman kept the Panthers in the game with timely baseline jumpers and a great overall floor game.  She did just enough to help Providence survive until the big guns took over and carried them home.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Eva Butler - </strong>Providence. The 5\'7\" Sophomore Guard is silky smooth and plays much older than her age would indicate she should. She was the primary reason Providence was able to overcome a 29-28 halftime deficit and start the 3rd quarter on a game deciding 14-0 run. She hit a huge three and had multiple steals during the run hat sealed PD\'s fate.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Anastasia Sinclair </strong>- South Mecklenburg High School. The 5\'6\" Freshman Guard may have not stuffed the stat sheet (2 points, 1 rebound and 1 assist), but when given an opportunity to play because of the injury to Senior <strong>Shakyra Harley</strong>, she displayed great poise and provided a spark during the first half of South\'s 49-34 win over Victory Christian.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Nyomi Ndango - </strong>South Mecklenburg. The 6\'1\" Junior Post player displayed controlled aggression that set a tone of physicality that was needed against the tall front line of Victory.  She is definitely an intriguing prospect to watch moving forward.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Trinity Moreland </strong>- Vance - A 6\'2\" Sophomore Post with great feet, Moreland played a big role in Vance\'s 64-46 destruction of Butler Friday night.  She moves incredibly well for a prep big and has a soft touch from the paint and the line.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Tanajah Hayes </strong>- Vance - This 5\'6\" Wing was the best player on the floor Friday night.  After a sluggish 1st quarter that Butler led 4-3, Hayes came on the court and left me and the other spectators wondering why she wasn\'t a starter.  She immediately put her stamp on the game.  Her quickness and handle and court smarts turned a competitive game into a rout.  According to some parents, she has been slowed by injuries.  When she is healthy, Vance is going to be a formidable opponent for anyone they face.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Meghan Rogers</strong> - Ardrey Kell. Although her taller, flashier teammate <strong>Eva Miller (</strong>16 points, 5 rebounds and an assist) was voted Player of the Game, I felt the real MVP of Kell\'s 46-44 come from behind victory was Rogers.The 5\'6\" Senior floor general had 10 points 7 assists and 5 rebounds and made all the clutch plays down the stretch.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Lucy Vanderbeck </strong>- Ardrey Kell. Vanderbeck, a 5\'10\" Junior Wing also came up huge for the Knights against Cannon with 11 points 4 assists and 3 steals. Despite Cannon leading 44-40, Kell finished on a 6-0 run to end the game and Vanderbeck was a catalyst.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Naya Clamp - </strong>Myers Park - The 5\'6\" Junior Wing had 7 points and 3 huge steals.  Her defense was instrumental in holding Cuthbertson to a season low 39 points.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Mia Xerras </strong>- Myers Park - The 5\'6\" Freshman sensation was the best player on the court in the 4th quarter of MP\'s 52-39 victory against Cuthbertson.  With star <strong>Taylor Henderson</strong> saddled with 4 fouls, Xerras took control of the reins, ran the team smoothly and hit a huge 3 to dagger the Cuthbertson ladies.</li>\n</ol>','\"And The Best Supporting Actor Goes to ......\" - 10 Unsung Heroes at the CHC','','publish','open','open','','and-the-best-supporting-actor-goes-to-10-unsung-heroes-at-the-chc','','','2019-12-03 07:58:36','2019-12-03 13:58:36','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119538',0,'post','',0),
	(119542,1,'2019-12-01 17:14:17','2019-12-01 23:14:17','With the season starting Monday night, there have been several Miss Basketball campaigns started already across the state. So we pose the question, who should be the favorite for 2020 Kentucky Miss Basketball? Vote Below! Poll closes at noon on Friday!\n\nhttps://poll.fm/10470844','POLL: Preseason Miss Basketball Favorite','','publish','open','open','','poll-preseason-miss-basketball-favorite','','','2019-12-01 17:14:17','2019-12-01 23:14:17','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119542',0,'post','',0),
	(119568,1,'2019-12-01 18:32:25','2019-12-02 00:32:25','Here we go again. Just one week into the season and Mother Nature has already been playing havoc with the girls basketball schedule. More than a dozen games were cancelled this week on Tuesday and Saturday. Crosby-Ironton was a participant in the Twin Cities Thanksgiving Tipoff at the University of St. Thomas until district administrators summoned the Rangers home due to impending stormy weather – insert eye-roll emoji and what-happened-to-hardy Minnesotans rant here – which left Totino-Grace without an opponent. Regardless, the show went on for the most part and it was a pretty good show at that.\n\nOn Monday I saw St. Agnes at Fridley. On Tuesday it was Spring Lake Park at Roseville. We were off Wednesday and Thursday for the holiday. On Friday I saw all seven games at the Pat Patterson tournament at Hamline University. On Saturday I was at the University of St. Thomas most of the day, stopped in at Concordia-St. Paul for their afternoon encounter with the University of Jamestown, and then caught the final two games of the tournament at Hamline. As is often the case, the final game of the week was the best game of the week. More on Farmington vs Stillwater in a coming article.\n\nHere’s the best of what I witnessed during the Week That Was #2.\n\n<strong>A TALE OF TWO ANNAS</strong>\n\nIt’s not easy facing the Hopkins juggernaut. Just ask <strong>Anna Tauer</strong> of Rosemount and <strong>Anna Mutch</strong> of Apple Valley. Both of their teams were given a thrashing by the Royals at the Pat Patterson tournament. Tauer, a 5’6 freshman, and Mutch, a 5’8 senior, demonstrated the very best way to handle such difficult circumstances: Never, never, never give up. Both players were still diving for loose balls, defending as hard as possible and playing with maximum effort even when things were well into running time. Mutch has been an all-in competitor for years now; Tauer is showing that she’s made of similar stuff.\n\n<strong>PLAYER OF THE WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Winner – <strong>Paige Kindseth</strong>, 5’10 junior guard, Farmington. We’ll have more on Kindseth in our recap of the Farmington-Stillwater encounter in a day or two. The #10-rated player in the class of 2021 has been very good for a long time, but her performance this weekend was next-level awesome. At least one high-major recruiter was in the house watching and others are on the Kindseth quest, as well.</li>\n 	<li>Runner-up – <strong>Mackenzie Kramer</strong>, senior guard, St. Michael-Albertville. There was plenty of buzz in the gym this weekend about the play of 2023 #3 <strong>Tessa Johnson </strong>of STMA, and rightly so. The kid is an amazing talent, but Kramer (#4 in 2020) is still the Knight with the shiniest armor for now. Kramer had 43 points and Johnson had 40 as STMA scored a pair of wins at Hamline.</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>NEWCOMER OF THE WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Winner – <strong>Olivia Olson</strong>, 8th grade guard, Benilde-St. Margaret’s. We’ll have more on her in our recap of the Twin Cities Thanksgiving Tipoff at St. Thomas. For now let me just say, ‘Holy cow!’ This kid is going to be very, very good.</li>\n 	<li>Runner-up – <strong>Tyreana Reliford</strong>, 8th grade guard, Benilde-St. Margaret’s.</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>TEAM OF THE WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Winner – Farmington. The Tigers scored two impressive wins at Hamline.</li>\n 	<li>Runners-up – St. Michael-Albertville, Waconia</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>COACH OF THE WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Winner – <strong>Drew Reiter</strong> of Fridley. When I arrived at Fridley on Monday evening I wasn’t aware there had been a coaching change so it came as a surprise to see Drew and Steve Reiter on the sidelines during warmups. Just a few minutes into the opening half of the Tigers’ encounter with St. Agnes it became obvious that the son and father were already putting their stamp on the program. The Tigers played hard, they were well-organized, they were disciplined on defense and they communicated constantly. This shouldn’t be too surprising given that living-legend Steve was the head coach at Blaine for 25 years before moving to the college ranks at Bethel University. It’s obvious the proverbial apple hasn’t fallen far from the tree with Drew. To accomplish what the Reiters have accomplished in just a handful of practices is nothing short of remarkable. I was impressed with junior guard <strong>Cadence Hanson</strong>, who made five threes and scored 21 points. <strong>Ah’Janay Yancy</strong> is a high-scoring senior with terrific instincts for the game. Sophomore guard <strong>Juliana Harris</strong> impressed us with her energy and athleticism. This is a team we’ll be paying attention to.</li>\n 	<li>Runner-up – <strong>Dustin Neibauer</strong> of Waconia. Neibauer, who took over this season from Carl Pierson, pulled all the right levers this weekend as the Wildcats rebounded from an 0-2 start to score nice wins over Roseville and Lakeville South at Hamline. The strategic cat-and-mouse game between Neibauer and Roseville’s Jeff Crosby was classic. In the end Waconia staved off a furious Raiders’ comeback to get the 62-60 win.</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>MILESTONES</strong>\n\nSenior <strong>Nneka Obiazor</strong> of Eden Prairie topped the 1,000 career points milestone this week, as did Waconia’s <strong>Tess Johnson</strong>. The senior scored 9 of the final 10 Waconia points in a win over Lakeville South, enabling her to become the 8th player in school history to reach 1,000. <strong>Anna Schmitt</strong>, who went on to have an outstanding college career at Concordia-St. Paul,  tops the list. Meanwhile, <strong>Paige Bueckers</strong> became the all-time leading scorer for Hopkins on Friday night, surpassing <strong>Leslie Knight</strong>, whose career mark had stood for 15 years. A couple of coaches also reached milestones this week as Stillwater’s Willie Taylor collected his 500th win (most of those at St. Paul Central) and Winona Cotter’s Pat Bowlin won his 600th.\n\nSend us milestone achievements as they happen – 1,000 points or more, school records, individual game milestones, etc. We’ll publish them here every week.\n\n<strong>AT THE NEXT LEVEL</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>What a week it was for the Division 1 mid-majors as there were upsets all across the country. In South Dakota State’s defeat of Notre Dame, Henry Sibley graduate <strong>Tori Nelson</strong> had 15 points and 13 rebounds. The freshman, who played AAU ball for the Minnesota Stars, was a top-10 player in the Prep Girls Hoops Class of 2019<strong>. Lindsey Theuninck</strong> (Mankato Loyola), <strong>Kallie Theisen</strong> (Wayzata) and <strong>Sydney Stapleton</strong> (Centennial) also played key roles in the Jackrabbits’ win.</li>\n 	<li>The University of South Dakota, whose starting lineup includes Win-E-Mac graduate <strong>Madison McKeever</strong> and <strong>Hannah Sjerven</strong> of Rogers, scored a convincing win over Ohio State and beat the University of South Florida. The 7-1 Coyotes have defeated three high-major squads this season.</li>\n 	<li>At the junior college level, #3-ranked NIACC continues to roll. Cretin-Derham Hall alum <strong>Autam Mendez</strong> had 27 points and 11 rebounds in a big win over Grandview. It was Autam’s ninth career double-double. Minneapolis Edison graduate <strong>Sierra Morrow</strong> and Robbinsdale Cooper’s <strong>Sierra Lynch</strong> had 18 points apiece.</li>\n</ul>\nThere are too many games and players to keep track of so if you know of athletes doing great things at the next level please let us know and we’ll pass it along.\n\n<strong>THE WEEK AHEAD</strong>\n\nUnless you have a specific rooting interest in one team or another – the team your kid plays on, for instance – there’s no question that the premier contest on the docket this week is Hopkins at Farmington on Friday night. We’ll have more on that in a day or two.\n\nOn Monday I’ll be in Medford to watch <strong>Emma Kneifel</strong> and the Tigers play host to Lake Crystal-Wellcome Memorial featuring <strong>Olivia Harazin</strong>, <strong>Lexi Cloyd</strong> and <strong>Lakesha Carter</strong>. Tuesday I’ll be checking up on freshmen <strong>Emily Christenson </strong>and <strong>Grace Knupp</strong>, and sophomore <strong>Britt Carlson</strong>, three youngsters who are expected to some make noise for East Ridge this season. The Raptors will play at Roseville.\n\nWednesday I’ll be at Minneapolis Southwest to see <strong>Virginia Johnson</strong>, <strong>Jhanae Greene</strong> and company face Cristo Rey Jesuit. On Thursday I’m planning to see <strong>Erika Lane</strong> and Brainerd at Cambridge-Isanti. Hopefully <strong>Mikayla Aumer</strong> is back in the Bluejackets lineup after nursing a broken right hand for the past few weeks. On Saturday I’m off to the Big South Showcase at Jackson County Central for six games. The field includes Waseca (<strong>Gus Boyer</strong>), Redwood Valley (<strong>Haley Garman</strong>), Marshall (<strong>Jordyn Hilgemann</strong>) and St. Peter (<strong>Morgan Kelly</strong>).\n\nHere are a few more games you may want to check out this week.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Monday – Dover-Eyota, featuring sophomore standout <strong>Malia Nelson</strong>, travels to Byron where they’ll face one of the biggest players in Minnesota in 6’3 junior post <strong>Sacia Vanderpool</strong> and sharp-shooting sophomore guard <strong>Riley Schnell.</strong></li>\n 	<li>Tuesday – Prior Lake travels to Eden Prairie for a 5:30 p.m. game. It’s also a 5:30 start at Holy Angels where the Stars meet up with Minnehaha Academy. Wayzata will be in Maple Grove for a battle of two of the state’s 4A powers.</li>\n 	<li>Friday – If you can’t make it to the Farmington-Hopkins encounter, the Alexandria at Fergus Falls game promises to be a good one. Ditto for Elk River at St. Michael-Albertville and Northfield at Red Wing, which is always a fun rivalry to witness.</li>\n 	<li>Saturday – Totino-Grace travels to Hill-Murray; Lakeville South is at Rochester John Marshall.</li>\n</ul>\nIf you have news to share please send me a direct message on Twitter (@gmachoops) or via email (<a href=\"mailto:gmachoops@gmail.com\">gmachoops@gmail.com</a>). See you in the gym!\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><em>Top photo: Senior guard Tess Johnson helped Waconia win twice this weekend in tournament play while passing the 1,000-career points milestone. (Photo courtesy of StarTribune)</em></span>','The Week That Was #2: Giving thanks for good basketball','','publish','open','open','','the-week-that-was-2-giving-thanks-for-good-basketball','','','2019-12-01 18:32:25','2019-12-02 00:32:25','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119568',0,'post','',0),
	(119577,1,'2019-12-01 18:41:47','2019-12-02 00:41:47','<img class=\"wp-image-119591 aligncenter\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_10191-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"404\" height=\"265\" />\n\nI must tip my hat off to Terry Parker high school on a well hosted 4th annual Smile for Mitch Memorial Basketball Event. The 4 game event started at 10 a.m. and the final game tipping off was at 4 p.m.\n\nTeams from Duval County area came in and competed at a high level, and left it all on the floor. The 4 game 8 team event matched up Lee vs Paxon, First Coast vs Mandarin, Ribault vs Jackson, and the host team Terry Parker vs Sandalwood.\nThe games had a lot of diamonds in the rough, but I’m going to focus on the All-Tournament team from the event, based on the observers. Each team had one player that was recognized for their on the court efforts.\n\n(Lee High School) <strong>Shanyia Winn</strong>, 2020\nThis guard shot lights out the entire game. She had powered Lee to a commanding league that they never relinquished. Paxon never was able to recoup from the hot shooting of Shanyia Winn and she unloaded her shot from everywhere on the floor. While she wasn’t utilizing her hot shooting, she was finding a way to keep her team involved in other ways.\n\n(Paxon High School) <strong>Irene Kabassubabo</strong>, 2022\nAlthough the Eagles struggled mightily to the Generals, Irene was a shining star in the dark. Irene was gritty and kept her foot on the gas, although the team was never able to gain any ground on the Generals. The Eagles were overmatched but Irene wasn’t going down without a fight.\n\n(First Coast High) <strong>M. McWhite</strong>, 2021\nDuring this defensive struggle ball game, M. McWhite was engaged the entire game. McWhite did all the things that you can ask of a basketball player she rebounded, blocked shots, got tip-ins, ran the floor and played hard. Although her play didn\'t result in a Buccanneers win, McWhite was a sight to watch.\n\n(Mandarin High) <strong>Ellie Jackson</strong>, 2022\nThis was a hard-fought defensive game but Ellie found a way to score buckets in multiple ways she was able to use her size and wit to rebound the ball and get buckets. She has a knack for the game in the post. She positions herself well and has a very nice touch around the basket this is a sophomore I want to see more of.\n\n(Andrew Jackson) <strong>X. Jackson</strong>, 2023\nOne of two freshmen to make the All-tournament team, and it\'s well-deserved, despite the Tiger\'s efforts to keep up with the Trojans. X. Jackson is a player to keep your eyes and ears open for. She has a soft touch from the free-throw line in. She plays with her back to the basket, but once she learns the game to its entirety she will be a force in the Duval County area.\n\n(Ribault High) <strong>Asiana Britt</strong>, 2023\nAsiana was a sight to see. Asiana is a little beyond her years when it comes to knowing the game. She makes the right plays and has a natural ability. She is considered young in class but her consistent motor separates her from the average. She lets the game come to her and she plays at her own pace. This freshman will make noise this upcoming season.\n\n(Sandalwood High) <strong>Amari Wright</strong>, 2020\nAmari Wright impresses every time I see her. Amari, a Seton Hall signee, was exciting and in tuned the entire game. She never lets her opponents see her sweat. She does the right things on the court all the time. Amari plays the game at her own pace, she doesn’t get rattled or sped up, unless she wants to hit the gas. Seton Hall has a player that can flat out hoop.\n\n(Terry Parker) <strong>Janell Johnson</strong>, 2022\nJanell is a Baller with a capital B. The Saints were a little too much for the host team the Braves, but Janell single-handedly kept the Braves in the match. Janell is a leader on the court and gets the job done. She got to the basket and shot deep range threes, but the Saints weren’t letting the Braves steal this one.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOnce again shout out to Terry Parker for being gracious hosts, and a major shout out to these girls who got game.','Smile for Mitch Girls Basketball Tournament (Jacksonville, FL)','','publish','open','open','','smile-for-mitch-girls-basketball-tournament-jacksonville-fl','','','2019-12-01 18:41:47','2019-12-02 00:41:47','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119577',0,'post','',0),
	(119582,1,'2019-12-01 19:29:30','2019-12-02 01:29:30','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Centennial High School kicks off the 2019-2020 season for the Howard County region with a game set against Oakdale High (Central Maryland) tomorrow night. Before we tip off, here is a quick glimpse at a few of Howard County\'s top prospects.</span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jasmine-washington/\"><span style=\"color: #f75617;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Jasmine Washington | 5\'4 G | Oakland Mills 2020</span></strong></span></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Jasmine Washington averages 12 points a game going into her senior year. One of the best players on this Oakland Mills team, Jasmine is known for strapping up some of the best point guards in Howard County. No challenge is too difficult for Jasmine as she has been the elite force behind the Scorpions success the last three years.</span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tiffany-hooker/\"><strong><span style=\"color: #f75617;\">Tiffany Hooker | 5\'4 G | Reservoir 2020</span></strong></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Tiffany Hooker is ranked #82 on Prep Girls Hoops 2020 rankings but I have mentioned before how she will be one of the states top guards by the end of the season. Tiffany Hooker is dominate and it is not a mystery how Reservoir advanced to the Top 8 in last years playoffs. Tif has an old school get the ball in the basket style of play and that is highlighted by her unorthodox but rather marvelous jump shot. </span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/division-4a-howard-high-spotlight/\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #f75617;\">Marisa Sanchez-Henry | 5\'3 G | Howard 2020</span></strong></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Marisa Sanchez-Henry is a fundamentally sound player who I believe has perfected her game. Of course there is so much more for her to learn in her young career, but this senior season will be the year Marisa puts it all together. When you see Howard High ball out, they have such great chemistry and the head of the pack is Marisa Sanchez-Henry. </span>','Howard County Spotlight','','publish','open','open','','howard-county-spotlight','','','2019-12-01 19:29:30','2019-12-02 01:29:30','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119582',0,'post','',0),
	(119594,1,'2019-12-01 19:07:48','2019-12-02 01:07:48','Duval County is loaded in all classes, but these young ladies in 2023 are coming in and they want their names to be known. These young ladies are young in class but they can hoop, regardless of their classification.\n\nI\'ve had the privilege to see these 2023 girls and I\'m shouting them out and telling all recruiters to put them on your radars. These are my top eight freshmen to watch:\n\n(Nease) <strong>Sophie Rueppell</strong>: A flat out shooter, she knows her sweet spots on the floor and she knows how to get to them. She can play on and off the ball. She has an outstanding basketball IQ.\n\n(Spruce Creek) <strong>Tyja Beans</strong>: Nice post player, finishes well around the basket. You have to account for her when she\'s on the floor, a lot of upside to her game. Soft hands and passes out of the post well.\n\n(Sandalwood) <strong>Jada Jones</strong>: She is a force inside. Can play facing or back to basket. She runs the floor like a deer and finishes well amongst crowds. All major D1 programs will be calling on her services.\n\n(Bolles) <strong>Taliah Scott</strong>: Arguably one of the best players in Duval County already, When you see her you\'re going to love her. When girls\' basketball is mentioned in Duval County if Taliah Scott\'s name is not attached to it, it has no meaning. She can PLAY!\n\n(Jackson) <strong>Xaniyah Jackson</strong>: Great feel for the game. She has a soft touch and positions herself well. Rebounds the ball and also defends the paint. Good size and runs the floor well.\n\n(Jackson) <strong>Kamryn Newsome</strong>: Nice size she actually can play multiple positions but she\'s listed as a SG. Stays active on both ends of the floor. Can also step out and shoot the deep ball.\n\n(Ribault) <strong>Asiana Britt</strong>: Great defender and has a non-stop motor, plays at a high level on both ends of the floor. Very aggressive guard that imposes her will on smaller guards and finishes amongst crowds. Good rebounder and will step out and shoot also.\n\n(Lee) <strong>Yakiya Milton</strong>: Nice height and very smooth around the basket. Finishes with both hands effectively. Although she has a thin frame she rebounds and defends the paint. Nice shot blocker and has great footwork. She has a high ceiling and I can\'t wait to see her get to her full potential.\n\n&nbsp;','2023 Finest: Quality Young Talent in Duval','','publish','open','open','','2023-finest','','','2019-12-01 19:07:48','2019-12-02 01:07:48','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119594',0,'post','',0),
	(119596,1,'2019-12-01 19:07:22','2019-12-02 01:07:22','Though this face-off between the Raiders and the Titans on November 23, 2019 was a scrimmage, top performers on both sides left it all on the floor. Despite New Town’s players being from both JV and Varsity squads, they more than held their own against the larger, older, and more experienced Atholton team.\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jourdyn-ayers/\"><strong>Jourdyn Ayers</strong></a> (#2): This New Town guard was the overall best player on the court. Her aggression on both ends of the floor set the tone for the younger members of her team. Fouled six times while shooting, Ayers could not be stopped on both the offensive and defensive glass. Clearly also possessing a high basketball IQ, she demonstrated her excellent court vision with her ability to run the fast break and adept passing skills. Finishing with 15 points, Ayers impressed in this scrimmage, and it is clear she will be crucial on this New Town team as the season gears up.\n\n<strong>Jalane Campbell</strong> (#10): As New Town’s point guard, she is an athletic defender with strong footwork. Finishing with seven points, she will prove to be a strong leader on the court along with Ayers this season.\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2018/11/conference-preview-big-south-east-is-loaded-with-talented-prospects/\"><strong>Madison McCabe</strong></a> (#15): An all-around player for Atholton, McCabe demonstrated her versatility with her inside-outside game. Despite only finishing with four points, she was a tenacious rebounder and demonstrated a confident jump shot.\n\n<strong>Tiara Kidd</strong> (#25): Atholton’s strongest post presence, Kidd capitalized on her size advantage over the undersized New Town guards, frequently scoring on drop step moves and quick drives to the hoop. Also successfully executing a pick a roll option, she showed her court awareness and leadership skills, finishing with five points.\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/10/under-the-radar-guards-from-oakland-mills-fall-ball/\"><strong>Mia Hargrett</strong></a> (#27): Though Atholton had a lot to demonstrate in the post, Hargrett proved that the Raiders’ guard-play is not to be overlooked. She is Atholton’s strongest guard, despite finishing with three points, it is clear she has a practiced 3-point shot and quick defensive hands to match.\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/class-4a-season-preview-sectionals-13-16/\"><strong>Erica Morton</strong></a> (#5): Another strong guard for the Raiders, Morton was successful from the floor in this scrimmage. Finishing with eight points, Morton was Atholton’s leading scorer and her confidence with her jump-shot is sure to only improve as the season progresses.\n\n<strong>Laila Cowsette</strong> (#45): Another key player in this Atholton varsity squad, she was also unafraid to show her dominance in the paint against the smaller New Town team. Also confident with her jump shot, Cowsette expanding her already promising inside-outside game this season will be key for the Raiders’ success.','Top Scrimmage Performers: Atholton High School v. New Town High School','','publish','open','open','','top-scrimmage-performers-atholton-high-school-v-new-town-high-school','','','2019-12-01 19:07:22','2019-12-02 01:07:22','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119596',0,'post','',0),
	(119612,1,'2019-12-02 20:41:48','2019-12-03 02:41:48','Though Dulaney High School’s game against Kenwood High School on November 25, 2019 was only a scrimmage, the Lions showed many reasons why their season will prove promising.\n\n1) <strong>Standout Player</strong>: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/2021-watch-list-juniors-to-see-this-season/\"><strong>Sammy White</strong></a> (#14): The Lions’ clear star player—both athletically and instinctively—White proved that her performance will be crucial to Dulaney’s success this season. A junior committed to Northwestern University to play lacrosse, it is evident her natural abilities as a leader and team-player assist her on the basketball court as well. Though she was the most skilled player on the floor, she often also showed the most hustle and aggression, diving for loose balls and converting defensive rebounds into buckets across-court. Despite her limited playing time, as the game was a scrimmage, White managed to score an impressive 20 points for the Lions.\n\n2) <strong>Guard Play</strong> – Besides White’s obviously dominant guard play, the Dulaney squad is composed of a mighty group of guards who will only improve their chemistry as the season progresses. Though much of Dulaney’s scoring was from put-backs and fast-break opportunities, <strong>Maggie Else</strong> (#3) proved Dulaney can drain jumpers too, finishing the scrimmage with seven points.\n\n3) <strong>Fast-Break</strong> – The overall athletic ability of the Lions’ squad allowed them to effectively convert fast-breaks into buckets. Dulaney guard, <strong>Annie Lodge</strong> (#11), showed her leadership on the floor with her strong instincts. She was often able to create scoring opportunities for her teammates, never first looking for her own success. She finished with 8 points, three of which were 3-pointers.\n\n4) <strong>Inside-Outside Game</strong> – Though Dulaney is an undersized team, this did not pose a problem compared to Kenwood’s even smaller squad. Dulaney inside players, such as <strong>Haley Greten</strong> (#10) and <strong>Amalia Hobbs</strong> (#15), displayed their fearlessness posting up the small, yet aggressive, Kenwood opponents, finishing respectively with five points and seven points.\n\n5) <strong>Press</strong> – Opponents should watch out for Dulaney’s sneaky full and ¾ press. A team full of quick, athletic guards, with sharp court instincts, led by <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/2021-watch-list-juniors-to-see-this-season/\"><strong>Sammy White </strong></a>(#14), were able to force many turnovers and pin-point weaknesses in the opponent’s guard-play. Against stronger ball handlers this year, it is unclear how this press will hold up, but for right now, it was the fuel Dulaney used to jump-start their unwavering, fast-break offense.','5 Reasons to for Watch Dulaney High School','','publish','open','open','','5-reasons-to-for-watch-dulaney-high-school','','','2019-12-02 20:41:48','2019-12-03 02:41:48','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119612',0,'post','',0),
	(119614,1,'2019-12-04 19:55:13','2019-12-05 01:55:13','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #000080;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>McNamara Falls To Hamilton Heights (TN) As New Star Emerges</strong></span></span></p>\nBishop McNamara took out Hamilton Heights a year ago today when they stood as the nation\'s top team.  In the rematch the Hawks were out for revenge.  The Hawks led 9-8 and never looked back and went into the half with a 27-23 lead.  In the second half the Hawks use their huge size advantage inside to take a 46-32 lead heading into the fourth quarter.  The Mustangs went to the bench trying a variety of combinations even bringing in a couple of their freshmen for help.  In the end it was all Hamilton Heights walking away with a 58-45 victory.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>Standout Players:</strong></span></span>\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Aliyah Pitts - 5\'11\" - Wing - Bishop McNamara</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121014\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121014\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0438-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Aaliyah Pitts[/caption]\n\nAliyah was the brightest spot for the Mustangs and at times was the best player on the court for either team.  She made plays both inside and out.  She finished with a team high 18 points as the Woodbridge transfer showed why she was the Virginia Player of the Year last season.  Pitts will play a huge part in the Mustangs success this season as the new star on the team.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Kamilla Cardoza - 6\'7\" - Post - Hamilton Heights</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121015\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121015\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0464-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Kamilla Cardoza[/caption]\n\nThe Mustangs had no answer for Kamilla Cardoza, quite honestly not many teams in the nation have an answer for the size an skill that she possess.  Cardoza ran the floor and finished at the rim.  She showed soft hands to receive the entry pass and turn with a soft touch.  On one play she was quadruple teamed and still received the pass and scored.  She finished with a game high 22 points and shot 100% from the field.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Taylor Gibson - 6\'2\" - Post - Bishop McNamara</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121016\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121016\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0436-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Taylor Gibson[/caption]\n\nTaylor gave the Mustangs their only lead of the game finishing a backdoor cut for the opening score of the game that resulted In a three point play.  She finished with nine points and played tough inside matching up most of the game with a player six inches taller than her.  Taylor was one of the players that continued to show effort as the game started getting out of hand.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Treasure Hunt - 6\'1\' - Wing - Hamilton Heights</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121018\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121018\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0456-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Treasure Hunt[/caption]\n\nTreasure went on a tear in the third quarter with eight straight points to break the game open.  She made the Mustangs pay for leaving her open on the perimeter but also knocked down on of her three triples while being grabbed with a hand in her face.  She finished with13 points scoring them all in a short span between the 2nd and 3rd quarters.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Yonta Vaughn - 5\'8\" - Point Guard - Bishop McNamara</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121019\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121019\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0442-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Yonta Vaughn[/caption]\n\nYonta brought in experience coming off the bench after starting every game a year ago as a freshman.  She scored 8 points in the game and as Coach Oliver tweaks the lineup I expect Yonta to play a big role with her high level of skill and IQ.','McNamara Falls To Hamilton Heights (TN) As New Star Emerges','','publish','open','open','','mcnamara-falls-to-hamilton-heights-tn-as-new-star-emerges','','','2019-12-04 19:55:13','2019-12-05 01:55:13','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119614',0,'post','',0),
	(119677,1,'2019-12-03 12:55:04','2019-12-03 18:55:04','One of the most fun things to do is see how players that have moved onto the college level are performing in comparison to their high school ranking. Rankings are an imperfect science no matter how someone tries to dice it up, but the final 2019 rankings were based on potential as a college player and overall impact at the high school level. Although it is early into the college season, some players are outperforming others in their freshman season. Here\'s how the class of 2019 would be ranked based on their college production thus far.\n\n5. <strong>Brooke Walling</strong> (Fresno State) *Previous ranking: 5\n<ul>\n 	<li>The Prairie High School grad is averaging a decent amount of playing time as a freshman, but she is registering just .6 points per game and 1.6 rebounds. Fresno State is currently 5-3.</li>\n</ul>\n4. <strong>Jacinta Buckley</strong> (UNLV) *Previous ranking: 4\n<ul>\n 	<li>The first team all state performer at Lewis and Clark High School is still adjusting to the college game and averaging a little over 8 minutes per game and recording 1.4 points per game. She played a season high 21 minutes versus Southern Utah. UNLV is 2-4 on the season.</li>\n</ul>\n3. <strong>JaQuaya Miller</strong> (Washington) *Previous ranking: 1\n<ul>\n 	<li>Miller held the number one ranking throughout her high school career. The 6\'4 post saw a lot of playing time in her first few games, but has seen her minutes dip to 13, 9 and 5 in their most recent games. She is averaging 4 points and 2.7 rebounds for the 6-1 Huskies.</li>\n</ul>\n2. <strong>Oumou Toure</strong> (Butler) *Previous ranking: 3\n<ul>\n 	<li>Toure has seen her minutes go up as the season has gone along for the Butler Bulldogs. She is averaging nearly 18 minutes per game and averaging 6.2 points, 5 rebounds, 2 steals and 2 blocks. She also recorded her first career double-double already this season. Toure has started one game for Butler and has seen playing time in big moments. One of the most impressive stats is her 77% mark from the free throw line, as this is an area she has really improved in since high school. Butler is 5-2.</li>\n</ul>\n<ol>\n 	<li><strong>Brynna Maxwell</strong> (Utah) *Previous Ranking: 2</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Brynna has continued the momentum she built up at Gig Harbor High School into her freshman season at Utah. In each of her last three games, she has put up 15, 22 and 18. She is averaging 14 points per game in the first 7 games of the season. She has started in each of those games, helping Utah to a 4-3 record.</li>\n</ul>','Re-Ranking The Top 5 For Class of 2019','','publish','open','open','','re-ranking-the-class-of-2019-top-5','','','2019-12-03 12:55:04','2019-12-03 18:55:04','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119677',0,'post','',0),
	(119695,1,'2019-12-02 06:21:16','2019-12-02 12:21:16','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Now that we\'ve spent the last month previewing the 2019-2020 season, I wanted to switch it up and throw out some end of preseason predictions. These preseason awards were an attempt at honoring girls who I thought stood out in Division 2A. This category is broken down based on opinion as well statistical data and national rankings.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>Division 2A Preseason Individual Awards:</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Most Valuable Player: Forward, Saniha Jackson, 2020, River Hill</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Toughest Player: Forward, Janae Dublin, 2020, Gwynn Park</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Motor: Forward, Charia Roberts, 2020, Pikesville</span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_27105\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"216\"]<img class=\" wp-image-27105\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/DSC_0120-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"216\" height=\"143\" /> <em>Janae Dublin, Gwynn Park</em>[/caption]\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Shooter: Guard, Jacqueline Dianis, 2020 Gwynn Park</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Scorer: Guard, Saylor Poffenbarger, 2021, Middletown</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Passer: Wing, Savannah Brooks, 2022, Francis Scott Key</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Rebounder: Forward, Janae Dublin, 2020, Gwynn Park</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Shot-Blocker: Forward, Janae Dublin, 2020, Gwynn Park</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Defender: Guard, Amayah Frazier, 2022, Pikesville</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Most Versatile: Wing, Kayla Cabbagestalk, 2021, Chesapeake</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Stock Riser: Guard, Janelle Fields, 2020, Westlake</span>\n\n&nbsp;','2019-2020  Division 2A Preseason Awards','','publish','open','open','','2019-2020-division-2a-preseason-awards','','','2019-12-02 06:21:16','2019-12-02 12:21:16','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119695',0,'post','',0),
	(119714,1,'2019-12-02 07:30:29','2019-12-02 13:30:29','Fall sports are coming to a close, making way for winter sports to take the stage. As the sports seasons change, we are beginning to see all of the \"Dream Team\" announcements for various sports. Well, let\'s take a look at my preseason \"Dream Team\", highlighting the sophomore class.\n\nThis \"Dream Team\" is deep, athletic, and skilled at every position. They would be versatile, having players that can excel on various parts of the floor. There are athletes, shooters, and powerful players in the paint. This team could feasibly field 3-4 different starting lineups.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-119720\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/c0b3667b6fc2bf733106e3fa552807a9-300x157.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"157\" />\n<h4>Starters</h4>\nPG:  <strong>Damiya Hagemann (PG, Detroit Edison)</strong>\n\nHagemann is an elite floor general. She can put a pass on a dime and can deliver it with flare.\n\nWing:  <strong>Morasha Wiggins (Wing, Kalamazoo Central)</strong>\n\nWiggins is as aggressive as they come on both ends of the floor. She causes chaos for the opposing offense.\n\nWing:  <strong>Breanne Salenbien (Wing, Lenawee Christian)</strong>\n\nSalenbien is an elite wing. She\'s smooth and fast getting up and down the floor and finishes in transition.\n\nPF:  <strong>Alana Micheaux (PF, Wayne Memorial)</strong>\n\nMicheaux can absolutely dominate in the paint. She\'s an elite post defender and rebounder.\n\nF/C:  <strong>A.J. Ediger (F/C, Hamilton)</strong>\n\nEdiger can score in a variety of ways and is a double-double machine.\n<h4>Bench</h4>\n<strong>Kenzie Bowers (G, Kent City)</strong>\n\nBowers provides the team with a pure shooter. She\'s one of the best 3 point shooters in the state regardless of class.\n\n<strong>Jillian Brown (CG, East Grand Rapids)</strong>\n\nNot starting? I know, but trust me, she\'d get starter minutes. Her ability to play either guard spot, shoot, and defend would make her one of the most valuable pieces on the team.\n\n<strong>Kailee Davis (PG, Detroit Renaissance)</strong>\n\nDavis is a waterbug style guard. She\'d be a playmaker and an energy player for this squad.\n\n<strong>Kaybriana Hallman (F, East Kentwood)</strong>\n\nHallman\'s versatility and athleticism would be a huge value on the \"Dream Team\".\n\n<strong>Ally VanTimmeren (F, Jenison)</strong>\n\nShe is another one that I had a hard time not starting. VanTimmeren would be a force and add rebounding off the bench.\n\n&nbsp;','Preseason Junior Dream Team','','publish','open','open','','preseason-junior-dream-team','','','2019-12-02 07:30:29','2019-12-02 13:30:29','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119714',0,'post','',0),
	(119716,1,'2019-12-02 09:10:39','2019-12-02 15:10:39','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Now that we’ve spent the last month previewing the 2019-2020 season, I wanted to switch it up and throw out some end of preseason predictions. These preseason awards were an attempt at honoring girls who I thought stood out in Division 3A. This category is broken down based on opinion as well statistical data and national rankings.</span>\n\n<strong>Division 3A Preseason Individual Awards:</strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Most Valuable Player: Guard, Dasia Towns, Poly, 2020</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Toughest Player: Wing, Camryn Beaver, Northern, 2021</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Motor: Guard, Aniyah Wilson, Oxon Hill, 2020</span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_71136\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"232\"]<img class=\"wp-image-71136\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/DSC_0140-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"232\" height=\"154\" /> <em>Dasia Towns</em>[/caption]\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Shooter: Wing, Kalani Corkeron, Wilde Lake, 2020</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Scorer: Guard, Tiffany Hooker, Reservoir, 2020</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Passer: Guard, Naila Newman, Rockville, 2022</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Rebounder: Forward, Nakeya Hall, Great Mills, 2022</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Shot-Blocker: Forward, Lillian Harris, Westminster, 2020</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Defender: Guard, Jasmine Washington, Oakland Mills, 2020</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Most Versatile: Forward Tristen Deveaux, Aberdeen, 2020 </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Best Stock Riser: Guard, Natalie Johnson, North Point, 2022</span>','2019-2020 Division 3A Preseason Awards','','publish','open','open','','2019-2020-division-3a-preseason-awards','','','2019-12-02 09:10:39','2019-12-02 15:10:39','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119716',0,'post','',0),
	(119717,1,'2019-12-02 08:14:19','2019-12-02 14:14:19','The excitement I captured at the Texas Girls Jamboree can be described in multiple ways so I\'ve decided to break it down into various segments. Keep in mind I\'m still going to recap both the Peggy Whitley Classic as well as the McDonald\'s Texas Invitational and with multiple tournaments coming up, December will be filled with joy, as far as coverage.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_119724\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-119724 size-medium\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Bobiana-Hill-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Bobiana Hill[/caption]\n\nI didn\'t get a chance to catch the first two games however<strong> \'21 Gwen Rippeto (Bellaire Episcopal)</strong> and <strong>\'20 Bobiana Hill (Wheatley)</strong> were named outstanding players from game one while<strong> \'22 Samyra Thomas (Kashmere)</strong> and<strong> Jasslyn Rogers (KIPP Sunnyside)</strong> earned that same recognition for game 2 which from what I hear was a thriller as the game went into overtime and both teams finished with less than 5 players I\'m going to jump some games and recognize one of the best offensive battles from opposing players I\'ve seen all season in the Jack Yates Lions vs Kinkaid Falcons overtime thriller and if you missed it, you can view that, as well as the other games on Baller TV.\n\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-119729\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Malon-Garner-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120090\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-120090 size-medium\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0217-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Malon Garner[/caption]\n\n<strong>Malon Garner-guard (Yates)</strong> I\'ve seen this young lady do some amazing things with the basketball and she is a true UNDER THE RADAR player and after dropping 36 from a variety of ways, you have to ask yourself, why is this kid unsigned and the answer is, because someone isn\'t doing their job(s). I always have and will keep it real, that nonsense about if you can play they will find you is just that, nonsense and with the abundance of \"fake news\" floating around social media on the internet about players doing this or that, some talented players will continue to be overlooked. I asked her before the game if she was ready, her response was \"oh yeah\" and I knew I was in a for a show as she was simply unconscious from everywhere including the long ball in pressure situations. After the game I asked about her situation, this is how I found out she was available and I was even more blown away to learn she #1 in her class.\n\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-119742\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Nakeeya-McCardell-300x196.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"196\" />\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120092\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"200\"]<img class=\"wp-image-120092 size-medium\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0216-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" /> Nakeeya McCardell[/caption]\n\n<strong>Nakeeya McCardell-guard (Kinkaid)</strong> talk about \"her name preceded her\" well \"her game preceded her\" as well and one of her teammate\'s dads gave me the rundown a while back. She didn\'t play club ball which is one of the reasons I missed her and after finding out her dad is a former NFL player, much of what she showed me on the court put things in perspective. Her offensive skill set is smooth and under control, she has one of the best mid-range games in the area I\'ve seen and her stop and pop being while being tightly defended is second to none on her way to dropping 22 points. She anticipates well and made some huge plays playing the passing lane. I would call her a true UNDER THE RADAR player as well however she has decided to play lacrosse in college\n\n<strong>*TRUE UNDER THE RADAR</strong> means they would be among the PGH Texas Top 100 plus and one more time, \"talent is everywhere if you know what you\'re looking at\" and please absorb this, \"it\'s not what you do, it\'s who you do it against\"','Girls Texas Jamboree pt 1 Individual Offensive Battle','','publish','open','open','','girls-texas-jamboree-pt-1-individual-offensive-battle','','','2019-12-02 08:14:19','2019-12-02 14:14:19','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119717',0,'post','',0),
	(119741,1,'2019-12-02 09:24:50','2019-12-02 15:24:50','Florida Prospects hosted a Thanksgiving tournament that lasted two days and featured 19 teams in total this weekend. I attended the event all day on Saturday to see 16 of those teams play at Dr. Phillips HS. Here are some of the top players I saw in the first half of the day in Orlando:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Game 1 - Father Lopez defeats Boone to move to 5-0 (54-40)</em>\n\n<strong>Khadija Faye 6\'4 Sr. - </strong>She was the best player of the morning session as she came alive in the second half to lead the Green Wave to a 20-8 outscoring of the Braves in the third quarter. The first half was all Boone, but Khadija lifted her team with her shot blocking and rebounding ability against a smaller Boone team. Khadija, a Texas Tech commit, finished with 16 points in a strong victory for her Daytona Beach team.\n\n<strong>Gabby Watson 5\'6 Sr. -</strong> She is the best guard on this team and showed it on Saturday. Gabby contributed 16 points with 9 of those coming from behind the arc. I like her game and think she has the skill and IQ to play at the next level.\n\n<strong>Tiera White 6\'1 Sr. -</strong> TT did not have her strongest offensive game, but she had some BIG blocks and rebounds that helped secure the win after their impressive second half. The two bigs for Father Lopez were just too much to handle for Boone. Tiera, a Quinnipiac commit, ended with 9 points in the victory.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Maddy Morales 5\'7 Sr. -</strong> She was the best shooter in this game and played a very strong first half. Madeline is committed to Florida Southern Conference and you can certainly see why. Her shooting was big, but she also moved well off of the ball and played tough defense.\n\n<strong>Leilani Guion 5\'9 Sr. - </strong>Another Senior in this game that possesses a lot of skill. She was the best athlete in this one, and also the best ball handler. She scored 6 points, but assisted on a lot of the other baskets with her ability to drive and create. Leilani will continue her basketball career at Eastern Florida State College.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Game 2 - Raines gives Colonial their first loss (50-43)</em>\n\n<strong>Nyla Allen 5\'7 Sr. -</strong> She was the best player in this game and took over after a slow start for the Vikings. One of the few seniors in this one, Nyla put up 23 points on strong free throw shooting and the ability to get around any opponent with her speed and handles. They simply couldn\'t stop her in this scrappy matchup.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Milan Santos Fr. -</strong> This Colonial team is very young compared to Raines who has a nice group of upperclassmen. The top 3 players for the Grenadiers are Freshman who are going to learn a ton this season. Milan was the most impressive for me even though she did not lead the team is scoring with 6 of her 10 coming for the charity stripe. She is small, but I think there is some potential with this team consisting of Milan, Sophya Barreiro, and Anaya Brown.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Game 3 - Seffner Christian dominates Haines City (79-59)</em>\n\n<strong>CC Mays 5\'7 Sr</strong>. <strong>-</strong> Triple-double alert! CC had 19 points, 17 boards, and 10 assists in a message sending win. She didn\'t miss a free throw and did just about everything right. CC, a Marshall commit, is tough to stop when she drives to the hoop, and she also hit a couple threes to cap off her big day.\n\n<strong>KK Davis 5\'7 Sr. -</strong> As one of the two Western Carolina commits at this tournament, KK is one of the best passers in the entire state. She scored 10 points and always assists on a big chunk of the Crusaders buckets in each game. She also racks up a lot of steals that turn into offensive output for Seffner.\n\n<strong>Chimera Iloanya 6\'0 Jr. - </strong>I think her goal is to bank-in a three pointer at each game I attend. As the only impactful post player for this team, she carries her weight as she added 15 points in this one. Her mid-range game is fantastic and she can even score from behind the arc with a great looking shot. I have to imagine she is on a lot of college\'s watch lists.\n\n<strong>Kali Barber 5\'7 Sr. -</strong> Another Senior on this squad who is committed to play at the next level at Maine Maritime Academy. I love the energy she brings to this team and the scoring when she needs to. Kali had 11 points and is a quality shooter on this balanced team.\n\n<strong>Nini Davenport 5\'5 Fr. - </strong>The best shooter of the early session, without a question. Nini had 19 points on six 3\'s. She was hitting from DEEP. One of the best shooting strokes/forms I have seen from this class of 2023 shooter who puts it up in rhythm and knows her role as their shooter.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Jasmine Edwards 6\'1 Sr.</strong> <strong>-</strong> The Hornets were very shorthanded with only 6 players, so Jasmine did not see the bench very often. She put up a lot of shots, but made the most of them by scoring 33 points. Jasmine is a scorer, through and through, and she can do it at all three levels. She will play her college ball at Jackson State.\n\n<strong>Jada Garbutt 6\'2 Sr. - </strong>Haines City didn\'t do a very good job of getting Jada involved, so she only finished with 7 points in this one. Jada, a Palm Beach Atlantic commit, has a great frame and is a talented athlete who can get up for a rebound on either end. The Hornets will need to work on their chemistry and get her involved if they want to be successful against quality teams like Seffner.\n\n&nbsp;','Impact Players at Florida Prospects Thanksgiving Classic in Orlando (Part One)','','publish','open','open','','impact-players-at-florida-prospects-thanksgiving-classic-in-orlando-part-one','','','2019-12-02 09:24:50','2019-12-02 15:24:50','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119741',0,'post','',0),
	(119798,1,'2019-12-02 09:54:57','2019-12-02 15:54:57','November 29<sup>th</sup> – December 1<sup>st</sup> saw Hall of Fame Huddle host the first ever Holiday Hoopla. There was a nice line-up of 13 competitive games for this event –  featuring teams from all over Ohio. The event was organized and Walsh University was a top-notch host for the weekend.\n\nLet’s take a look at some of the top performers and great games following the weekend at Walsh.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><u>5 Great Players (+ a few more):</u></strong>\n\nKira Philpot – Stow\n\nKira finished with 22 points in an impressive 63-45 victory over Solon. The front-court player is impressive around the rim. She plays with a high motor and has the ability to single-handedly change the game as a rebounder when she decides to hit the glass.\n\nKarli Anker and Rylee Bennett – Akron Manchester\n\nThere was a point in the last decade where Manchester was one of the top small-school programs in the state of Ohio. They haven’t enjoyed that kind of success in recent years, but if there is a duo that can help them get back to that point, it is Anker and Bennett. Anker – one of the top guards in Ohio – finished with a dominant performance of 28 points, 17 rebounds and a handful of assists. Bennett – only a freshman – finished with 23 points and 10 rebounds in a 61-44 win against Columbiana.\n\nZoe Miller, Morgan Yoder and Brynn Mullet – Berlin Hiland\n\nThese 3 juniors are all scholarship-level kids. Miller is headed to Bowling Green, Yoder to Ashland and Mullet – with a handful of offers – is still undecided. They balance each other and lead their team so well. Miller is a relentless rebounder in the paint who also possesses great touch for a post player. Yoder runs her team as good as anyone in the state and has a knack for making big shots when her team needs them. Mullet is a silky-smooth shooter with unlimited-range on her jumper.  In the win over Cornerstone Christian, Miller finished with 16 points and 9 rebounds, Yoder had 13 on 4 3-pointers and Mullet ended with 12.\n\nLexi Lemire – GlenOak\n\nLexi has waited her turn – serving as a serviceable bench player during her first 3 years at GlenOak behind some outstanding guards. She is smooth with the ball in her hands and can finish with a number of different floaters and runnners. She is also a great 3-point shooter with her feet set. Lemire had 18 points in GlenOak’s win over Tusky Valley.\n\nDanielle Vuletich and Alyssa Serensky – Western Reserve\n\nThe duo combined for 51 points in the only real blowout of the weekend. Vuletich’s length is a problem for most teams around the basket. Serensky really impressed – the Bethany commit has improved a lot. Her play down the stretch is vital if WR wants to return to the regionals and have a shot at beating the Cornerstone Christians and Daltons of the D4 world.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><u>5 Great Games:</u></strong>\n\nOlentangy Liberty – 48                                   Akron Buchtel – 47\n\nAkron Buchtel and Olentangy Liberty battled in the finale of the Holiday Hoopla and they certainly didn’t disappoint. This contest was tied at the end of the 3<sup>rd</sup> quarter and ultimately regulation – giving area basketball fans an overtime game to finish their Thanksgiving weekend. It was Buchtel who went coast-to-coast to take a 2-point lead with 17 seconds left, before Liberty raced the ball down the court and hit a walk-off 3-pointer as time expired.\n\nBerlin Hiland – 59                                             Cornerstone Christian Academy – 39\n\nThese two small-school powers – who have eyes on Columbus and the State Final 4 in March – battled for 4 quarters in a game that was much closer than the final score would indicate. Cornerstone was actually up 6 points entering halftime and only down 1 at the end of 3 quarters, before Hiland’s depth (playing up to 12 girls in a given game) carried them to a 20-point victory and early season statement.\n\nWest Branch – 50                                             Louisville – 48\n\nA much improved Louisville squad give West Branch all that they could handle in another overtime classic. It took both teams a little while to settle in – with an 8-8 stalemate at the end of 1. Louisville was actually down 9 points entering the 4<sup>th</sup> quarter – going on a huge run to force extra time. West Branch drained a long jumper to go up 2 and Louisville was unable to get a good look at the basket on their baseline out of bounds play to end the game. <strong>Peyton Alazaus (pictured above; photo credit - Morning Journal)</strong> led the way with 19 points for West Branch.\n\nSoutheast – 50                                                  Waynedale – 42\n\nWaynedale jumped out to a quick start – leading 11 to 7 at the end of the first frame. It was all Southeast the rest of the way. The Pirates – who won a district championship a year ago – led 28-21 at the end of the 1<sup>st</sup> half and 39-31 at the end of the 3<sup>rd</sup> quarter. Waynedale, behind stellar guard play, did keep it close – getting to within a few baskets at numerous times in the 4<sup>th</sup>, but it wasn’t enough to get the victory.\n\nGlenOak – 64                                                     Tusky Valley – 44\n\nIn another game that was much closer than the final score shows – Tusky Valley, who most would probably have considered a big-time underdog coming in, was tied at the end of both the 1<sup>st</sup> quarter and the 1<sup>st</sup> half. The 2<sup>nd</sup> half showed why GlenOak was a State Final 4 team in Division 1 a year ago and also shows glimpses of enough firepower to get them back there this winter. The Golden Eagles are still a very deep and talented squad.','2019 Holiday Hoopla at Walsh University','','publish','open','open','','2019-holiday-hoopla-at-walsh-university','','','2019-12-02 09:54:57','2019-12-02 15:54:57','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119798',0,'post','',0),
	(119818,1,'2019-12-02 11:06:50','2019-12-02 17:06:50','Each week on PGH Ohio we will provide our opinion on the top 5 teams for each division in Northeast Ohio.\n\nThe power rankings for this week are determined by games completed prior to December 1<sup>st</sup> and all teams listed belong to the Northeast District board and subsequent sectional and district tournaments.\n\n<strong>Division 1</strong>\n\n1. Medina\n\n2. GlenOak\n\n3. Stow\n\n<strong>(Kira Philpot is pictured above rebounding over Wadsworth\'s Steph Andrews - photo credit: MyTownNEO)</strong>\n\n4. Hoban\n\n5. Wadsworth\n\nYet again, Division 1 is loaded in Northeast Ohio. There are teams like Aurora, Eastlake North, Massillon Jackson and Canton McKinley that did not even crack these initial rankings. As these teams play more games - we are anxious to get more clarity and see how these teams stack up with one another.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 2</strong>\n\n1. Laurel\n\n2. Gilmour Academy\n\n3. Akron St. Vincent St. Mary\'s\n\n4. Southeast\n\n5. Perry (Lake)\n\nLaurel has certainly looked tremendous in their two wins over Lutheran East and Cleveland Villa-Angela St. Joseph\'s. The Gators are deep and they have 5 different players averaging double-figures offensively - led by stud freshman Mari Bickley, who is scoring nearly 18 points per night.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 3</strong>\n\n1. Chippewa\n\n2. Elyria Catholic\n\n3. Loudonville\n\n4. Champion\n\n5. Smithville\n\nThe Chippewa Chipps, last year\'s regional champions, have been short-handed to start this season - playing without their 2nd leading scorer Taylor Thomas and freshman guard Abby Henegar. When they return to full-force, they should be a clear #1 - with familiar foes Elyria Catholic and Loudonville on their heels.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 4</strong>\n\n1. Cornerstone Christian Academy\n\n2. Dalton\n\n3. Western Reserve (Berlin Center)\n\n4. Newton Falls\n\n5. Louisville St. Thomas Aquinas\n\nA loss to Berlin Hiland doesn\'t hurt Cornerstone Christian here, although Dalton, Western Reserve and Newton Falls have all really impressed in early season victories.','Northeast Ohio Power Poll - 12/2/2019','','publish','open','open','','northeast-ohio-power-poll-12-2-2019','','','2019-12-02 11:06:50','2019-12-02 17:06:50','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119818',0,'post','',0),
	(119820,1,'2019-12-02 14:18:17','2019-12-02 20:18:17','Florida Prospects hosted a Thanksgiving tournament that lasted two days and featured 19 teams in total this weekend. I attended the event all day on Saturday to see 16 of those teams play at Dr. Phillips HS. I will be doing a separate write-up for the powerhouse battle between Miami Country Day and Lake Highland Prep. Here are some of the top players I saw in the second half of the day in Orlando:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Game 5 - Winter Haven beats Dr. Phillips with a balanced attack (58-34)</em>\n\n<strong>Trinity Hardy 5\'9 Jr. - </strong>She was the leading scorer and rebounder for the Lady Blue Devils with 18 and 11 to notch a strong double-double. Trinity shot really well from inside of the arc and grabbed boards on both sides on the floor. Her game is solid all around as she added a couple of assists and steals to boot.\n\n<strong>Kayla Smith 5\'10 So. - </strong>She is a really smooth player with her lengthy frame, and scored at all three levels on Saturday with 12 points on a couple of three pointers. Kayla\'s stock has risen in 2019 and once you see this lefty in person, you will understand why. I am excited to see how she develops during her career.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Game 6 - Miami High puts it on shorthanded West Orange (56-39)</em>\n\n<strong>Darria Whitley 5\'7 Sr. - </strong>She was the most impressive overall player in this game. Darria ended with 9 points and can score from anywhere on the floor. I really liked her defense and athleticism in this one.\n\n<strong>Jeannine Scott 5\'5 Sr. -</strong> The usual scorers didn\'t put up their total (Colleen Bucknor had 4 points but rebounded well and Kiara Cruz had 2 points), so Jeannine stepped it up on offense. She made it rain from behind to arc to give the Stingarees a big advantage through 3 quarters of the game.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Camryn Siemer 5\'5 Sr. -</strong> The Warriors were without Ajalon Gillard (broken finger) and Paris Pickett for 3 quarters, so Camryn had a lot of weight on her shoulders. She contributed 12 points with a lot of those coming from the line, but she didn\'t have a 3 which is her bread and butter.\n\n<strong>Lakada Bryant 6\'1 Jr. - </strong>She really stepped up with Paris Pickett out most of the game. Lakada had 10 points and was strong inside the paint against Miami HS. Her rebounding was crucial, and I think she had the best overall game for West Orange in this matchup.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Game 7 - Florida Prep holds on against Spruce Creek (59-57)</em>\n\n<strong>Emma Risch 6\'0 Fr. -</strong> She showed why she is one of the best Freshman in the state by hitting two free throws with 5 seconds left to take a 2-point lead. She\'s got ice in her veins. Aleah Sorrentino sat this one out, so Emma stepped up for her team and scored 17 points on 3 three pointers in a game that the Falcons were up 15 at half. Emma flirted with a double-double by bringing down a team-leading nine rebounds too.\n\n<strong>Emani Burks 6\'2 Jr. -</strong> She had to step up with Aleah out, and she did just that against a smaller Spruce Creek team. Emani controlled the boards with 8 rebounds and put up 10 points with her nice mid-range game. This is a lengthy 2A squad that will give teams fits all season long.\n\n<strong>Shamya Joiner So. -</strong> She is one of the best hustlers and grinders that I\'ve seen this season. Shamya scored eight, had nine assists, and seven boards with a steal and a big charge taken. I really like the energy and slashing ability she brings to the Falcons squad.\n\n<strong>Paige McDonald 5\'11 So. - </strong>She is another Sophomore who won\'t fill it up on points (she had 8), but she will do everything else for this team to make them successful. Paige had three assists, a steal, and multiple pass deflections by using her length at the top of the zone.\n\n<strong>Alonya Waldon 5\'4 Fr. -</strong> I really liked the energy and play from Alonya. She was all over the floor on both sides and distributed the ball well to her team. Alonya had six points and two assists with good minutes in this game.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Peryonna Sylvester 5\'5 Sr. -</strong> She is one of the best point guards in the state and showed why on Saturday. Peryonna, a North Florida commit, is a quick guard who has great court vision to find  her teammates or score it herself. She ended with 10 points on the night, and helped will this team back into the game in the second half. She sustained an injury at the end of the game, so everyone hopes it isn\'t anything serious.\n\n<strong>Emma Perna 5\'5 Jr. - </strong>She had some big 3\'s and free throws that brought the Hawks back into this game after a slow first half. Emma led her team in scoring with 15 points on 3 three pointers.\n\n<strong>Kacie Oelkers 5\'7 Jr. - </strong>This girl has a really nice shot and uses her frame well against bigger opponents. She finished with 9 points and is a key part to the team and how much success they will have.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Game 8 - Timber Creek jumps on Lake Minneola early (59-49)</em>\n\n<strong>Savannah Henderson 6\'1 So. - </strong>It\'s no shock that Savannah is one of the best 2022\'s in the state. The Hawks did not have an answer for her, and she scored whenever she pleased. She finished with 15 points and 6 rebounds for the night in a game that wasn\'t as close as the final score indicates. Savannah is a high level prospect that is going to have a stellar career at her size and her ability to score at all three levels.\n\n<strong>Jourdan Avery 5\'5 Sr. -</strong> This is a girl that everyone should want on their team. She scored 14 points, had 7 rebounds, 4 assists, and 4 steals which made for a pretty stat line. Jourdan is a scrapper who will outwork just about anyone.\n\n<strong>Sarah Napoli 5\'6 Sr. -</strong> She is the primary shooter on this team who ended with 9 points on a couple of threes with a couple of steals too. Sarah will continue her career at Embry Riddle as a nice guard piece who is very unselfish on the floor.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Josiany Canales 5\'7 Sr. - </strong>She is the main source of scoring for the Hawks and she did just that with 16 on the night. Josiany has a nice shot when she gets set and has a strong drive to the right side. Her stat line also consisted of 5 rebounds, 4 assists, and 3 steals as the leader of this team.\n\n<strong>Analiese Harris 6\'0 Jr. - </strong>She is the best post on this team, and the team looked a lot better when she was on the court. Analiese scored 10 and brought down 5 boards on the evening.\n\n&nbsp;','Impact Players at Florida Prospects Thanksgiving Classic in Orlando (Part Two)','','publish','open','open','','impact-players-at-florida-prospects-thanksgiving-classic-in-orlando-part-two','','','2019-12-02 14:18:17','2019-12-02 20:18:17','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119820',0,'post','',0),
	(119876,1,'2019-12-02 12:12:36','2019-12-02 18:12:36','Each week on PGH Ohio we will provide our opinion on the top 5 teams for each division in Northwest Ohio.\n\nThe power rankings for this week are determined by games completed prior to December 1<sup>st</sup> and all teams listed belong to the Northwest District board and subsequent sectional and district tournaments.\n\n<strong>Division 1</strong>\n\n1. Notre Dame Academy\n\n<strong>(NDA standout Grace VanSlooten is pictured above in last year\'s state semi-final. Photo Credit; Toledo Blade)</strong>\n\n2. Southview\n\n3. Northview\n\n4. Perrysburg\n\n5. Findlay\n\nNotre Dame Academy is the class of the Northwest Ohio region in Division I. There aren\'t too many teams in NWO D1 (20 teams total), but Southview and Northview from Sylvania have had impressive starts and although Perrysburg lost to Bellevue and Southview - they were competitive, which landed them on these early-season rankings.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 2</strong>\n\n1. Bellevue\n\n2. Napoleon\n\n3. Willard\n\n4. Shelby\n\n5. Perkins\n\nNo more Zia Cooke and Madison Royal-Davis at Toledo Rogers means that DII is wide open in the Northwest region of Ohio. Bellevue and the Santoro sisters are the front-runner to start the season, however - all 4 of the other teams on this list could knock them off on any given night. Willard will get their chance to do just that, this week.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 3</strong>\n\n1. Hopewell Loudon\n\n2. Margaretta\n\n3. Ottawa Glandorf\n\n4. Liberty Benton\n\n5. Wynford\n\nHopewell Loudon is a game-changer in Division III and the addition of Kaia Woods has only made that more clear. They have come out of the gates strong - as have Margaretta and Ottawa Glandorf. Liberty Benton enjoyed long post-season runs in their fall sports, so they are getting a late start.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 4</strong>\n\n1. Ottoville\n\n2. Minster\n\n3. Fort Recovery\n\n4. Buckeye Central\n\n5. Lucas\n\nEven with a tough loss to Van Wert, Ottoville has looked impressive to start the season, as have Fort Recovery and Lucas. Although Minster has stubbed their toe and Buckeye Central took an early-season loss to Wynford, both teams are battle-tested and have enough talent to make deep post-season runs.\n\n&nbsp;','Northwest Ohio Power Poll - 12/2/2019','','publish','open','open','','northwest-ohio-power-poll-12-2-2019','','','2019-12-02 12:12:36','2019-12-02 18:12:36','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119876',0,'post','',0),
	(119898,1,'2019-12-02 12:35:15','2019-12-02 18:35:15','The 4th annual Duke Johnson Classic featured quality competition for girls basketball in South Florida. Orlando Jones high school women\'s basketball team traveled down to compete in the event. One of the players from Jones I noticed right away was #15, class of 2020 Amani Fitzgerald. Just from the eye test alone, (where players catch the eye of potential coaches, scouts and evaluators) she passed. Fitzgerald\'s body frame displays toned arms and an athletic build, which makes you wanna see more.\n\nTheir first challenge was against one of South Florida\'s dominate programs Palm Beach Lakes. We got to see just how physical Fitzgerald was. She rebounded, drove through the lane and displayed an energetic presence for her team. She was able to lead her Jones to victory over the talented Lady Rams.\n\nSecond challenge was against another dominate program of South Florida, the Miami Norland Lady Vikings. Although the Lady Tigers came up short, Fitzgerald tallied a double double with points and rebounds. Her relentless pursuit of rebounds helped will her team to get second chance opportunities and trips to the foul line for her. She showed her ability to handle the ball, hit the mid range shot, attack the boards and her leadership qualities.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nWhen asked some of the things she will do to help her team, throughout the rest of the year, Fitzgerald responded, \"we have to get more cooperation from the whole team together, we have to get stronger and develop more as a team.\"\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"></p>','Amani Fitzgerald stands out at the 4th Annual Duke Johnson Classic in Miami','','publish','open','open','','amani-fitzgerald-stands-out-at-the-4th-annual-duke-johnson-classic-in-miami','','','2019-12-02 12:35:15','2019-12-02 18:35:15','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119898',0,'post','',0),
	(119943,1,'2019-12-02 13:49:39','2019-12-02 19:49:39','The first day of the 2019-20 girls basketball season has finally arrived.\n\nMany of Colorado’s top teams scheduled great matchups to kick off the season in this opening week. Several of the state’s truly elite programs have chosen to begin the season by taking on top national competition in other states. Let’s take a look at five exciting games in Colorado on different nights this week that should get the new season off to a flying start.\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong><em>Monday</em></strong></span></p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_96842\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-96842\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Makayla-Hemingway2-300x234.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"234\" /> Makayla Hemingway[/caption]\n\n<strong>Cherokee Trail at Rangeview, 7 p.m.</strong>\n\nCherokee Trail enters this opener sitting at No. 10 in the CHSAANow.com preseason poll, and Rangeview is coming off a 20-win season last winter.\n\nThe main draw for Cherokee Trail is Colorado State-signee <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/makayla-hemingway/\">Makayla Hemingway</a>, an all-around guard who is an early contender for player of the year. The Cougars have more than Hemingway, however, and look like a lock to improve on their 12-13 record from last season. Senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dominique-rodriguez/\">Dominique Rodriguez</a> is a solid point guard recruit who has the strength and speed to get to the best, as well as good court vision. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/destinee-paulk/\">Destinee Paulk</a> is another athletic Cougars guard, giving them plenty of weapons who can attack the basket along with up-and-coming backcourt players like <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mia-collins/\">Mia Collins</a> (2021) and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sierra-culbreath/\">Sierra Culbreath</a> (2022).\n\nOn the Rangeview side, the Raiders graduated a good one in Angel Broadus last season but her absence opens the door for younger players like sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/nyera-west/\">Ny’Era West</a> to step into the limelight. As a freshman last season, West averaged 11.8 points, 5.7 rebounds, three assists and 3.3 steals, and looks like she’s ready for a big sophomore campaign. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brianna-linnear/\">Brianna Linnear</a> (2021), Genesis Sweetwine (2022) and Grace Solarin (2022) also should make a bigger impact this season.\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong><em>Tuesday</em></strong></span></p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_96446\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-96446\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Jada-Moore-1-300x227.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"227\" /> Jada Moore[/caption]\n\n<strong>Doherty at Regis Jesuit, 7 p.m.</strong>\n\nRegis Jesuit reached the 5A Final Four last season. Doherty went 16-9 last season advanced to the second round of the state tournament.\n\nThis will be the first look at Regis Jesuit in the post-Fran Belibi era. That means all eyes will turn straight to senior Kansas State-commit <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jada-moore/\">Jada Moore</a> and junior guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/avery-vansickle/\">Avery Vansickle</a>. Moore is among the most athletically-gifted, all-around players in Colorado and Vansickle is a deadly sharpshooter with excellent range.\n\nAt Doherty, there is another void to be filled with the graduation of last year’s leading scorer Brionna Mcbride. The seemingly obvious first option to step into that primary scoring role is sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/payton-sterk/\">Payton Sterk</a>, who averaged 11 points per game and is PGH Colorado’s No. 11-ranked 2022 player. The Spartans also only graduated Mcbride, so they have a ton of experience returning players like Aujanne Latimer (2020), Makenzie Noll (2021), Caylee Dewitt (2020) and Erin Capell (2020).\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong><em>Wednesday</em></strong></span></p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_117379\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-117379\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/D5A8C75D-2179-4367-A861-6843CD956437-300x200.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> Alyssa Wells[/caption]\n\n<strong>Arapahoe vs. Holy Family, 5 p.m.</strong>\n\nPlaying at the Horizon Tournament, this will be the first game of the season for both teams in a cross-classification battle between 4A Holy Family and 5A Arapahoe. Holy Family reached the 4A Final Four last season and Arapahoe made it to the second round in 5A before losing to eventual champion Cherry Creek.\n\nThe Holy Family girls won 21 games last season but their leading scorer from 2018-19 transferred and now plays for rival Erie. That just provides more opportunities for players like junior forward <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/cecilia-aanerud/\">Cecilia Aanerud</a>, who averaged 6.3 points and 7.5 boards last season. Others like juniors <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dylan-sanders/\">Dylan Sanders</a>, Tyler Whitlock, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alyssa-wells/\">Alyssa Wells</a>, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/daniella-hren/\">Daniella Hren</a>, or sophomore Maggie Dooley, could also emerge.\n\nThe Arapahoe Warriors certainly are a team to watch coming into this season with a solid core of <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kali-march/\">Kali March</a> (2020), Kathleen Wortman (2020), Maky Smahelova (2020), <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sam-crispe/\">Sam Crispe</a> (2022) and Jayden Staab (2020) returning. March and Crispe, in particular, give the Warriors a dynamic guard-forward tandem and it will be exciting to see how they look to start the campaign.\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong><em>Thursday</em></strong></span></p>\n<strong>Grand Junction Central vs. Denver South, 3:30 p.m.</strong>\n\nPlaying at the Palmer Tournament, this is a matchup of two 5A playoff teams from last season with exciting up-and-coming players on both sides.\n\nAt Denver South, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/timaya-guevera-2/\">Timiya Guevara</a> was a revelation last season. Just an undersized sophomore, she put up 21 points, 6.1 assists, 4.3 steals and 4.7 rebounds a game and who knows what she’ll do for an encore. Guevara (2021) and teammate <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/carly-dilworth/\">Carly Dilworth</a> (2020) will make for an exciting duo to watch this season.\n\nGrand Junction Central has its own dynamic duo in a pair of guards who led the team in scoring as sophomores last season. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/leah-redding/\">Leah Redding</a> (12.6 ppg) and Mya Murdock (10.4) each scored in double figures and accounted for over half of the Warriors’ points. It will be interesting to see if they have taken a step forward in the offseason.\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #3366ff; font-size: 14pt;\"><strong><em>Friday</em></strong></span></p>\n\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_99188\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-99188\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/D4A19796-5025-4FFE-A677-CE25FFEA4E9A-300x241.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"241\" /> Olivia Waufle[/caption]\n\n<strong>Ralston Valley at Horizon, Best in the Nest, 6:30 p.m.</strong>\n\nThese two teams met up in the 5A Sweet 16 last season and Horizon got the better of Ralston Valley, 58-40. Think they remember?\n\nThe Horizon Hawks may have won the last high-stakes contest between these two teams but this year’s Horizon team will look very different than last year’s. The Hawks graduated their top four scorers from last season and those were some of the best players in the state. They’ll be looking to see what they get from players like senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/olivia-waufle/\">Olivia Waufle</a> and sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/audra-vine/\">Audra Vine</a> when they are thrust into much larger roles on Friday.\n\nOver at Ralston Valley, the Mustangs won’t be dealing with any of the same problems as Horizon since they return the bulk of their roster from last season. That includes six-foot guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sydney-bevington/\">Sydney Bevington</a>, junior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brooklyn-seymour/\">Brooklyn Seymour</a> and sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/saya-sabus/\">Saya Sabus</a>, to name a few. The Mustangs enter the 2019-20 campaign ranked sixth in 5A by the CHSAANow.com poll.','Games of the Week: Opening Week','','publish','open','open','','games-of-the-week-opening-week','','','2019-12-02 13:49:39','2019-12-02 19:49:39','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119943',0,'post','',0),
	(119987,1,'2019-12-02 16:45:10','2019-12-02 22:45:10','I really enjoyed spending the time to watch all 4 of the games at Nashville Saturday. By watching the 7th,5th,3rd and 1st place games I got a chance to see every team. Many of these teams it was my first opportunity to see them play. I walked away continuing to understand there are many girls in Southern Illinois that can play at the college level, they just need the exposure. Well, here we go with some players that I had not seen or am very confident most of you have not seen.\n\nOkawville has a couple of exciting 2023 guards that are worth tracking. <strong>Megan Rennegarbe and Briley Rhodes </strong>both start and play as many minutes as they can. Megan is 5\'7 and Briley is 5\'3. Megan had a very good game in the 3rd place game with 14 points. She does a nice job off the bounce getting into the lane where she was able to finish in the mid range and at the rim. She is long and lanky at this point and uses that frame well. Briley made all tourney and turned some heads with her play. She is shorter and looks a little quicker. She has a nice shot from behind the arc and handles it very well.\n\nPinckneyville has a couple of recognizable names, especially <strong>Kenzie Rushing</strong> who is a high scoring 2021 guard coming back off of knee surgery. I was impressed with a couple of other players that showed some potential. <strong>Payton Morgan </strong>is a 6\'0 2021 post that had an excellent 4th quarter in the game I saw. She does a good job of using her strength to establish a deep position and then is able to finish around the basket. Payton did a good job of keeping the ball high, not wasting a dribble and making a quick decisive move. At her height and strength she should be able to help a JC/NAIA/D3 team. Keep her on your radar. <strong>Madison Morgenthaler </strong>is a 5\'9 2023 guard that came off the bench and did a good job. She has a long frame and has good athletic ability for a young wiry player. She has a nice shot and a good feel for how to play the game. She made smart passes and played good defense. She is another player that has solid potential to be a good player in the 2023 class.\n\nCollinsville played two freshman quite a bit in the championship game and both showed potential. <strong>Jordan Gary </strong>is a very athletic 5\'6 2023 guard. She showed the ability to guard and play at the pace of a varsity game. She did not have many offensive chances in this game but has scored in 3/4 games she has played. She looked comfortable with the ball in her hands and can finish in the lane. <strong>Jenna Scheller </strong>is a 6\'2 2023 post that shows some good touch around the rim. Jenna is a big strong girl that can establish position in the lane and finish. She is a good option to give Coach Billy a few minutes at a time but will need to get in better shape to go for extended minutes.\n\nMascoutah is a program that has struggled the last few years but is showing some signs of getting better. Their leading scorer for the tourney was <strong>Alanna Brooks </strong>a 5\'6 2021 guard. Alanna can score in the mid range and off the 3-point line very well. She scored 18 per game and finished the tourney on a sprained MCL. She is very tough and is trying to find a way to stay on the floor. <strong>Sophia Louden </strong>is a 5\'11 2023 forward that was full of energy and effort on Saturday. College coaches near me took notice of how hard she was playing. She does an excellent job of rebounding and playing defense. I think she has more room to grow over 6ft before she is done. Sophia works very hard with a trainer to improve her offensive game. She is one to watch.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOther underclassmen to watch are <strong>Bailey Bell, Emily Schnitker and Kennady Hayes. </strong>Bell is a 5\'7 2021 guard from Wesclin. In the game I saw I thought she did an excellent job as a slasher that could get in the lane and find ways to score. She handles it well and defends well. Schnitker is a 5\'6 2022 guard from Nashville that made her mark in this game with her 3-point shot. She hit two big shots late in the game when they were most important. She plays with more heralded players but Schnitker could end up making a place for herself.Hayes is a 5\'8 2022 guard from Mt. Vernon. Hayes showed the ability to score in multiple ways. She has a nice size for her position and used a very effective runner to score off one of her drives.\n\nTwo seniors caught my eye that do not seem to be on the radar for many coaches. <strong>Mady Wallace </strong>is a 5\'5 guard  from Benton. She is left handed and can handle the ball well and will defend. Mady can score inside and outside with a knack for getting hot. Once she gets on a roll she is hard to stop. She is crafty at getting into the lane and finishing over bigger players. <strong>Annibelle Harrison </strong>is a 5\'7 guard from Mt. Vernon. Annibelle led the team in scoring and seemed to be a steady influence throughout the game. She can handle the ball and defend while also finding ways to score. She uses her defense to create offense and had a big 3rd quarter in the game I saw which was when Mt.Vernon pulled away for the win. She is someone that can play small college ball if she can find the right fit.\n\nAll in all this was a great event that I really enjoyed Saturday. Good Luck to all of the teams as they continue the season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Nashville Thanksgiving Tourney: Under the Radar Prospects','','publish','open','open','','nashville-thanksgiving-tourney-under-the-radar-prospects','','','2019-12-02 16:45:10','2019-12-02 22:45:10','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=119987',0,'post','',0),
	(120011,1,'2019-12-03 14:23:28','2019-12-03 20:23:28','Florida Prospects gathered a bunch of good teams to play for their Thanksgiving Classic, but these two may have been the best of the bunch. Miami Country Day opened the season as a Top 25 team in the country even after losing some talent, and Lake Highland Prep is a top 5 team in the state who didn\'t back down to the challenge. Both of these schools are playing tough schedules, so this was an exciting early season matchup to see between these powerhouses stacked full of college basketball prospects. The Highlanders came out strong and took control with a 14-7 lead in the first quarter, and managed to stay ahead by a score of 27-23 at the half with a little run by the Spartans. Both of these teams are incredibly deep with each of them having at least 5-6 players that have D1 potential. After the half, Lake Highland Prep controlled the 3rd even more so than they did in the 1st quarter. MCDS would play well in the 4th by pressing LHP, but it would be too little too late with the final being 57-46 in favor of Lake Highland Prep. My favorite stat of the game was that Lake Highland shot a productive 16 for 17 from the free throw line. Here were some of the standout players from this exciting matchup:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><em>Lake Highland Prep (5-0)</em></span>\n\n<strong>Zanoria Cruz 5\'10 Sr. - </strong>As one of the few seniors and committed players in this game, she really stood out as a leader with experience in this battle. She ended up with 12 points, 5 assists, and 4 rebounds with the best overall game out of anyone. Zanoria hit some big free throws, had a pretty jumper, and dialed in a trey in this balanced performance for the Highlanders. She will continue her career at Western Carolina after this big season.\n\n<strong>Nyla Harris 6\'2 So. - </strong>She may be the biggest prospect in this game, and you can tell why when you see her in person. Nyla is an incredible athlete at her height with a college ready frame. She had 12 points and 2 big blocks in this matchup. The sky is the limit for this kid who finishes strong after getting to the rim and has a nice mid-range game.\n\n<strong>Eleecia Carter 5\'8 Fr. - </strong>She is one of the best Freshman in the state, and she proved that on a big stage this weekend. Eleecia scored 11 points for her team with a couple three pointers and a strong and-1 finish. I am excited to watch her continue to develop as she is already a smooth operator who looks poised as a newcomer.\n\n<strong>Sierra Godbolt 5\'6 So. - </strong>Another key Sophomore on this team is Sierra who passed the ball well, and slowed down the guard play of the Spartans. Sierra contributed 8 points in this one, but she means more to this team than just points with all of the scorers they have.\n\n<strong>Stefanie Ingram 5\'7 So. - </strong>Here is my MVP of the game. Stefanie took care of the ball as the point, and was a pest on defense. She also had 8 points and added 3 steals to that line with a ton of great passes to her teammates. I like how she attacked the glass on both ends as a guard too.\n\n<strong>Kayla Blackshear 6\'1 Jr. -</strong> A top 2021 in the state, Kayla didn\'t need to score a lot in this one to help her team. She put up 4 points, grabbed 6 boards, and had 3 steals. Kayla is hard to stop when she is around the hoop and rebounds at an elite level.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><em>Miami Country Day (2-1)</em></span>\n\n<strong>Sydney Shaw 5\'9 So. - </strong>She had the strongest offensive game in this one, and it may have been a blow out if it wasn\'t for her playmaking. Sydney finished the game with 19 points on five 3\'s. I was really impressed with her ability to create her own shot as LHP couldn\'t stop her. She\'s a top 2021 in the state right up there with Nyla Harris.\n\n<strong>Emani Theodule 5\'6 So. - </strong>This game was loaded with 2021 talent, and Emani is another one of those stars. She had 13 points with 3 treys from all over. Emani will have to be a leader on this young team that will be tough to beat after the taste this one left in their mouths.\n\n<strong>Andrea Daley 6\'1 Jr. - </strong>She has a really nice vertical and was the most athletic player in this monster of a game. Andrea struggled from the free throw line, but she has some strong moves around the hoop and used her strength and athleticism to get by whoever defended her.\n\n&nbsp;','Early Season Power Matchup: Lake Highland Prep Tops Miami Country Day','','publish','open','open','','early-season-power-matchup-lake-highland-prep-tops-miami-country-day','','','2019-12-03 14:23:28','2019-12-03 20:23:28','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120011',0,'post','',0),
	(120034,1,'2019-12-02 16:16:04','2019-12-02 22:16:04','Last Tuesday evening I received a message from one of my spies who was in the gym watching Benilde-St. Margaret’s open its season against St. Anthony Village. “<strong>Olivia Olson</strong>, 8th grade point guard for Benilde,” it read. “Wow! She’s the best player on that team. Is she on the radar? She has to be one of the top 8th graders.” Yes my friend, Miss Olson is on the radar. This weekend at the Twin Cities Thanksgiving Tipoff Olivia’s radar blip was big enough to cover most of the screen. When the first ranking of the Prep Girls Hoops class of 2024 prospects is released 10 months from now she will no doubt be near the north end of the list.\n\nIf you watch Olson play there are several things that jump out at you immediately. One is her length. At about 6 feet tall with a huge wingspan, Olivia definitely passes the eye test. Think <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/cassidy-carson/\">Cassidy Carson</a></strong> of Eastview if you are trying to visualize. The second thing is how smoothly she runs. Some players just look so natural going up and down the floor. Olivia is one of those players. Perhaps not quite as fluid as <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tessa-johnson/\">Tessa Johnson</a></strong> of St. Michael-Albertville, but maybe longer. ‘Gazelle’ is the word that comes to mind.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120045\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"405\"]<img class=\"wp-image-120045\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Olivia-Olson_StarTribune-300x212.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"405\" height=\"287\" /> Olivia Olson (right) is a multi-talented athlete.[/caption]\n\nOlson’s skills are also very well-developed. Yes, she needs to work on her left hand, but what 8th grader doesn’t. She can shoot it, finish it and her body control on the way to the rim is impressive. She also has very good court vision and Olson’s leaping ability is excellent. Olson is not the best player in the Benilde lineup quite yet. That honor would belong to top-20 senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/patience-williams/\">Patience Williams</a></strong>, a Division 1 prospect who is serving as a good mentor for her rookie teammate. Patience leads the team in scoring through three games at nearly 16 points per game. Sophomore <strong>Anisah Wolf</strong> – another young player who had a very good weekend – is at 12.3 ppg. Olson scored 12 against St. Anthony, 9 versus Providence Academy and 12 in Saturday’s win over Holy Family.\n\nBottom line: Olson is an elite athlete, a 6-foot point guard with the potential to play at the highest levels of college basketball. One word of caution: Olivia is also an elite soccer goalkeeper who will likely have options when it comes to college athletics. We’re told basketball is the top priority, which makes me happy.\n\nOlson wasn’t the only varsity rookie who stood out at the Thanksgiving holiday tournaments over the weekend. Bloomington Kennedy freshman <strong>Ashley Burchette</strong> definitely made her presence felt at the Pat Patterson tournament at Hamline University. Kennedy is really young, and Burchette is carrying the lion’s share of the load for the Eagles.\n\nKennedy graduated three players who moved on to college basketball: <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/destinee-oberg/\">Destinee Oberg</a></strong> (Arkansas), <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/zaraya-march/\">Zaraya March</a></strong> (ND Science) and <strong>Kianna Cox</strong> (Bethany Lutheran). Veterans <strong>Amaya Graf</strong> and <strong>Samantha Husting</strong> also aged out. That’s 50 points per game lost and pretty much all of the team’s experience. Now coach Quinton Johnson is having to play a roster full of youngsters and Kennedy has taken some lumps over the first two weeks of the season. Burchette, however, has been a bright spot.\n\nThe point guard is quick and athletic, gets to the rim through contact, and can really handle the basketball. In Friday’s tournament opener against Orono, Burchette demonstrated some terrific one-on-one skills, with the ability to break down defenders and use her superior first step to leave them behind. Burchette has skills, and will no doubt be a factor in the 2023 class. Kennedy scored just 25 points in its season opener at the Tipoff Classic last week. Burchette had 15 of them. At Hamline Ashley had 14 of Kennedy’s 40 points against St. Paul Como Park. That’s pretty good, but there’s a lot more to Burchette’s game than just putting the ball in the cylinder.\n\nHere are four more rookies who stood out at the Thanksgiving holiday tournaments.\n\n<strong>Tyreana Reliford – 8th grade guard, Benilde-St. Margaret’s</strong>\n\nSaturday’s encounter with Holy Family was the first time we have seen <strong>Tyreana Reliford</strong> play, but the Reliford name is certainly familiar. Her older sister is 2021 point guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jayla-reliford/\">Jayla Reliford</a></strong> of Robbinsdale Cooper, a talented athlete we have written plenty about over the years. Tyreana is much longer than Jayla and not quite as crafty… yet. The younger sister played significant minutes Saturday for first-year head coach Michael Swann. Reliford’s willingness and ability to defend is a big factor in that, and she has proved to be solid and reliable thus far.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-knudson/\">Lauren Knudson</a> – freshman guard, Orono</strong>\n\nOrono’s improvement this season is palpable, and the majority of the credit for that will likely go to transfers <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kaila-youngs/\">Kaila Youngs</a></strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/haley-paulson/\">Haley Paulson</a></strong>, who came over from Delano. The improvement of junior point guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/julia-knudson/\">Julia Knudson</a></strong> is also a major factor, but the arrival of Julia’s younger sister <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-knudson/\">Lauren Knudson</a></strong> should not be overlooked. The #44-rated player among the 2023s, Lauren is a highly-skilled guard with wonderful court vision and a sense of confidence that is serving her well. Lauren was first off the bench in Thursday’s opener against Kennedy. She showed outstanding ball handling and the ability to defend with intelligence and intensity.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/drew-johnston/\">Drew Johnston</a> – freshman guard, Roseville</strong>\n\nAt this time last year Roseville was starting two highly experienced senior guards who are now playing college basketball. <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kaylee-nelson/\">Kaylee Nelson</a></strong>, a top-20 player in the class of 2019, is at the University of Minnesota Duluth. Point guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jada-hood/\">Jada Hood</a></strong> is at Kilgore College in Texas. Having a 9th grader running the show is a whole different animal but <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/drew-johnston/\">Drew Johnston</a></strong> has been up to the task. Drew is a top-30 prospect in the class of 2023, and the younger sister of Roseville senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jayda-johnston/\">Jayda Johnston</a></strong>. Drew has advanced skills, distributes effectively and possesses a sound understanding of the game. She can also shoot it, and that three-point threat is going to be crucial for the Raiders if they are going to reach their standard 20+ wins.\n\n<strong>Sophie Zay, 8th grade guard, Holy Family</strong>\n\nSaturday at St. Thomas was the first time I have seen <strong>Sophie Zay</strong> play. She was inserted into the game for Holy Family shortly after the tipoff and played quality minutes. The stocky 5’7 guard is not flashy but she is more than capable. The first thing that became immediately apparent is how Zay pounds the ball on her dribble. I love that. She got to the rim frequently and was not deterred by Benilde’s size inside. It’s clear that Zay can also shoot it. Although her high-profile top-20 freshman teammate <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophi-hall/\">Sophi Hall</a></strong> is drawing most of the attention on a young Fire squad, Zay’s impact will probably be nearly as important. Coming off an outstanding 7th grade season on JV, Zay is going to be an impact player.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><em>Top photo: Freshman Ashley Burchette has been a bright spot for Bloomington Kennedy. (Photos courtesy of StarTribune)</em></span>','Tournaments recap: Talented rookies who impressed','','publish','open','open','','tournaments-recap-talented-rookies-who-impressed','','','2019-12-02 16:16:04','2019-12-02 22:16:04','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120034',0,'post','',0),
	(120071,1,'2019-12-03 15:45:14','2019-12-03 21:45:14','<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Ocean View HS - Hawk Holiday Classic 2019</strong></span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Ocean view HS - Jim Harris Gymnasium</strong></span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Day -1 Report on Games</strong></span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Scores and Results from the Game:</strong></span>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>St. Pius St. Matthias HS vs. Calvary Chapel Santa Ana</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Final Score:  St. Pius 40</strong>, Calvary Chapel (Santa Ana) 32</span>\n\n<strong>\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">St. Pius Top Performers in the Game:</span></strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2020, 5\'6, F, Lauren Cabrera</strong> - Lauren is a tweener in my opinion, she can play and rebound down low in the paint as well step out to the perimeter and stroke the three pointer with some consistency.  She worked down low for her team last night and did a great job, she slashed to the rim off the pick and roll and finished her layup in the paint.  She also made some good passes to teammates for baskets as well and played some solid defense for her team.  </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2020, 5\'3, SG, Michelle Reynoso</strong> - Michelle is a scrappy hard-nosed guard on the floor that loves to mix it up and get down and dirty in the game we have watched her.  She is an excellent defender and always is ready to lock down the best player from the other team and also terrorize the opponent on the offensive side.  She shoots the ball decent and is working on becoming more consistent, but her best attribute is her heart on the floor, she never gives up.  </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2022, 5\'5, CG, Sadye Martinez</strong> - Sadye is also a scrappy hard-nosed combo guard who can handle the rock and attack the defenses with her ability on the floor.  She has a good skill set for attacking the rim and finshing thru contact, but she is getting better at distributing the ball to her teammates, she will need to master this skill if she wants to play in college.  Her defensive ability is remarkable, she is a defensive stopper as well when she wants to be, look for great things from her in the near future.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Calvary Chapel Santa Ana Top Performers in the Game:</strong></span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2023, 5\'6, PG, Holli Hendrix</strong> -  Holli was a remarkable point guard on the floor, her skill set was good, she could handle in the open court and finish thru contact at the rim.  She had a nice body type for a guard, she could keep her defender off her body while handling the ball.  She could shoot the midrange consistently and her three pointer is developing at great rate, but this kid could play the game, we were very impressed, she ended the game with 15 points.  </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>2023, 5\'5, SG, Chloe Zazueta</strong> - Chloe was an enforcer on the floor, she was aggressive and used it to her advantage on the floor on the defensive side of the ball.  Chloe could drive to the basket, she could handle the ball and had a pretty good change of direction move that got her to the rim most times.  She shot the ball well from midrange and made some good assists for her teammates to make baskets.  We were impressed with her game and she finished with 9 points.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOcean view HS - Hawk Holiday Classic Results from Day 1:\n\n&nbsp;\n<table class=\"alignleft\" style=\"width: 99.3212%\" border=\"2\" cellspacing=\"2\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 6.69014%\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Date</span></td>\n<td style=\"width: 6.8662%\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Time</span></td>\n<td style=\"width: 33.6268%\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Home</span></td>\n<td style=\