	(120873,1,'2019-12-04 14:06:04','2019-12-04 20:06:04','On opening night of official games in Colorado, the Cherokee Trail Cougars and Rangeview Raiders kicked off the new campaign against one another. In the teams’ 2019-20 opener, Cherokee trail pulled away in the second half to leave Rangeview High with a 79-61 victory.\n\nLet’s dive into some early takeaways from the game.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_97349\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-97349\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Dominique-Rodriguez-1-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Dominique Rodriguez[/caption]\n\n<strong>Dominique Rodriguez is serious about scoring more</strong>\n\nDuring the preseason, Cherokee Trail senior point guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dominique-rodriguez/\">Dominique Rodriguez</a> told PGH Colorado that she wanted to take on more of a leadership role and show that she can score more as a senior. Apparently, she wasn’t just blowing smoke.\n\nIn the Cougars’ season opener on Monday night, Rodriguez led all scorers with 25 points in game that featured a number of talented players who can put points on the board. A strong ball handler and passer, as well as a solid defender, Rodriguez scored double figures in 15 of 25 games last winter. She already looks stronger and more aggressive as a senior, and without losing her ability to set up her teammates within the Cougars’ offense.\n\nThe 5-foot-6 guard has been in contact with several schools at the JUCO, D-II and D-III levels including Texas A&amp;M International in Laredo, Texas.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_97440\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-97440\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/AD64A14C-9B82-42BC-A4BC-189F3DD4093F-300x298.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"298\" /> Ny\'Era West[/caption]\n\n<strong>Ny’Era West is a future star, and might be one already</strong>\n\nRangeview’s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/nyera-west/\">Ny’Era West</a>, the No. 9 2022 in PGH Colorado player rankings, showed up ready for varsity high school basketball as a freshman last year and averaged 11.8 points, 5.7 rebounds, three assists and 3.3 steals per game. Looking like she has grown an inch or two since then, West played on Monday night like she’s determined not to disappoint those eagerly awaiting her sophomore encore.\n\nWest led Rangeview in scoring with 19 points on 7-for-12 (58 percent) shooting from the field. She was aggressive on defense and came away with a pair of steals, though she did foul out of the game, and also used her driving ability to get to the free-throw line where she went 4 for 7. West was 6 for 6 on 2-point attempts and 1 for 6 on 3-point attempts.\n\nThat’s a solid a season opener for a sophomore and the fact that West has yet to approach her ceiling is truly scary.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120590\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-120590\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/3F66CB26-D2AD-4B1F-89E5-CC0A1DEDD561-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /> Genesis Sweetwine[/caption]\n\n<strong>… and that’s great news for a promising Rangeview squad</strong>\n\nDespite graduating leading scorer Angel Broadus after last school year, the Rangeview Raiders return six of the 10 primary varsity players from last year’s roster.\n\nThat includes West, junior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brianna-linnear/\">Brianna Linnear</a>, sophomore Genesis Sweetwine, sophomore Grace Solarin, senior T’airra Champliss and sophomore Amya Winfrey, all of whom contributed significantly to the Rangeview effort on Monday night. Sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/daijah-watkins/\">Daijah Watkins</a> and junior Amari Bullock (6 points, 7 rebounds) also gave the Raiders quality minutes.\n\nChampliss was second on the team with 15 points, going 7 for 12 from the field and Grace Solarin scored seven points. The shots weren’t falling for Sweetwine, but she did show off her range with a long step-back three in the third quarter.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120562\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-120562\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Autorriah-Thomas-Cherokee-Trail2-300x233.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"233\" /> Autorriah Thomas[/caption]\n\n<strong>Don’t expect another .500-type season from Cherokee Trail</strong>\n\nIn five of the past seven seasons, Cherokee Trail girls basketball has hovered within one to four games – above or below – of the .500 mark.\n\nThat’s not likely to be the case this winter, as the Cougars enter 2019-20 ranked No. 10 in the CHSANow.com preseason poll. With Colorado State-bound senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/makayla-hemingway/\">Makayla Hemingway</a> entering her senior season and players like Rodriguez stepping up, it appears a window is opening for the Cougars to do some real damage in ’19-20.\n\nOf course, the Centennial League offers little relief or mercy with teams like Grandview, Cherry Creek, Mullen and plenty of others offering a challenge on a nightly basis. Hemingway scored 20 points on Monday night and Autorriah Thomas put up 16, and others like <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/destinee-paulk/\">Destinee Paulk</a> and Natalia Leu-Pierre give the Cougars a depth of talent to make them a threat to those other teams as well.\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_97441\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-97441\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/CA2CBAB8-FD96-4E1A-B0E4-414E95022686-300x205.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"205\" /> Amya Winfrey[/caption]\n\n<strong>Amya Winfrey looks to have taken a big step forward</strong>\n\nIn a game filled with talented players, Rangeview’s 6-foot-1 forward Amya Winfrey made her own case as a compelling young player on a team full of them.\n\nThe sophomore held fast as a defensive presence in the post and did well for a post player when she was forced to play perimeter defense, at one point even stealing the ball at the top of the key and taking it back the other way for a layup. If Winfrey continues to develop, she will give Rangeview’s young core of sophomores yet another dynamic for the present and the future.\n\n[robo-gallery id=\"120619\"]','Five Takeaways: Cherokee Trail at Rangeview','','publish','open','open','','five-takeaways-cherokee-trail-at-rangeview','','','2019-12-04 14:06:04','2019-12-04 20:06:04','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120873',0,'post','',0),
	(120879,1,'2019-12-04 15:57:17','2019-12-04 21:57:17','I was treated to an excellent matchup between the Prosper Eagles and the Hebron Hawks Tuesday night. Hebron maintained a small lead through the first three quarters, but every time it felt like they were beginning to pull away, Prosper managed to string together a few stops and get back into the game. However, every run that the Eagles went on was answered by the Hawks, and they finally took control of the game in the fourth quarter. Hebron ultimately came out on top and won the contest 54-41.\n\nHere are five takeaways from the game:\n<h5><strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sierra-dickson/\">Sierra Dickson</a> is the Real Deal</strong></h5>\nHebron\'s senior point guard was selected to play in the 2020 McDonald\'s All-American Game the day after this matchup took place, and that makes all the sense in the world after seeing her play. Dickson has a tremendous all-around game. She has elite level handles and excels at getting defenders off-balance so that she can blow by them. She showed that she can hit the three ball, but she is at her best when she is in attack mode. The Texas State commit was able to get inside at will vs. Prosper, and she also displayed her excellent passing ability during several offensive possessions. Furthermore, she is a two-way player with great defensive instincts. Dickson finished the game with 27 points. She is going to be a problem at the next level.\n<h5><strong>Hebron is a Very Good Defensive Team</strong></h5>\nThe Hawks got a ton of breakaway layups as a result of their efforts on the defensive end. They thrive off getting steals and turning them into easy points. Their backcourt duo of Dickson and <strong>Demauria Miles</strong> are stingy on-ball defenders, and forward <strong>Camille Thomas</strong> moves very well and uses her length to come away with a ton of steals. They made Prosper work extremely hard just to get the ball into the paint, forcing them to instead settle for threes. Hebron has plenty of weapons on offense, but they will be a true threat in class 6A so long as they play like this defensively on a consistent basis.\n<h5><strong>Prosper\'s Starting Backcourt is the Strength of Their Team</strong></h5>\nProsper may have lost this game, but they competed hard and impressed me in a number of areas. Their backcourt\'s offensive production really caught my eye. Junior point guard <strong>Chandler Browning</strong> might be one of the shortest players on the Eagle\'s roster, but she also might be the toughest. When her team was trailing, she took it upon herself to get into the paint and was rewarded with high percentage shots and/or free throws. Senior shooting guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madison-cleary/\"><strong>Madison Cleary</strong></a> is a knockdown three-point shooter who is also a very accurate passer. She is scary talented offensively. These two are the heart of this Eagles team.\n<h5><strong>Madison Cleary Can Light it Up Offensively </strong></h5>\nCleary isn\'t going to blow you away with her speed and athleticism, but she is a threat to score from just about anywhere. She lets the game come to her and never forces shots. It\'s clear that she has a high basketball IQ. She has deep range and can shoot the three from the catch or off the dribble. The Senior guard can also do some damage with her pull-up game from mid-range. Additionally, the North Texas commit is a taller guard at the high school level which allows her to see over the defense and make some really difficult passes look easy. I also like the way Cleary attacks the glass at both ends. There is a lot to like about her game.\n<h5><strong>Hebron\'s Ability to Get High-Percentage Shots Was the Difference in This Game</strong></h5>\nI mentioned this in my second takeaway, but Hebron was so good when it came to preventing Prosper from getting good looks inside the three-point line. In addition to that, the Hawks got a ton of good looks in transition and made most of their offensive possessions count in the half court. They refused to settle for threes. Both teams made their fair share of three pointers, but Hebron took way more high percentage shots, and that proved to be the difference in this contest. Dickson and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/courtylyn-loudermill/\"><strong>Courtlyn Loudermill </strong></a>were particularly effective at getting into the teeth of the defense for close-range looks. I know it sounds simple, but winning basketball games isn\'t rocket science. The team that takes better shots is usually going to score more points, and Hebron did exactly that Tuesday night.','5 Takeaways: Prosper vs Hebron','','publish','open','open','','5-takeaways-prosper-vs-hebron','','','2019-12-04 15:57:17','2019-12-04 21:57:17','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120879',0,'post','',0),
	(120885,1,'2019-12-04 17:44:43','2019-12-04 23:44:43','I had the opportunity to attend the Independence(Mint Hill, NC) Ardrey Kell(Charlotte NC) game last night at Ardrey Kell High School. It was a highly contested well coached contest. Ardrey Kell led early and jumped out to a halftime lead of 27-19. Most of the night AK used precise passing and tremendous execution in their offensive sets to obtain the lead. Indy, offensively had great looks at the basket but were unable to convert. Junior guard Braylyn Milton couldn\'t buy a basket as the ball kept rolling off the rim. She managed to get tremendous looks but wasn\'t quite able to finish. More about Milton later! Senior guard Trinity Thompson took over in the third with numerous steals and making threes to give Indy a 1 point lead at the end of three. The crowd was really engaged at this point as the teams battled hard in trying to get the win. UNC Wilmington commit Evan Miller of AK kept her team in the mix while Thompson led her Indy troops. It was back and forth to the final end. Miller scored to give AK the lead under a minute but on the following possession Indy scored to take the lead right back! Miller had a chance late to win the game as she drove the right side of the lane but missed a shot I\'m sure she would like to have back. Indy won 44-43! It was a great atmosphere and a great game to watch. Here are my 5 Takeaways from the game!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n1.Ardrey Kell\'s ball movement is awesome. I love the way they share the ball. Junior point guard Trinity Palmer does a great job setting the table for her teammates. She manages the position well as she deals with the hardest decision in the game as a point guard, that is when to pass and when to shoot. She makes sure she has her team in the right play as well as making sure the floor is balanced. She is starting to find her shots in the offense and making smart plays. I predict she will get more comfortable creating her own offense while running the offense. The team does an excellent job of making the extra pass, cutting and making the right play. Every shot may not go in but you can appreciate the discipline on offense in efforts to get the best look. Any team that plays AK must be prepared to talk on defense and stay patient because AK will make you work on defense.\n\n2. Junior guard Mariah Milton has a great deal of potential.  As I mentioned earlier she had a number of good looks but wasn\'t able to get much to fall. This was my first time seeing her play and even though she didn\'t get into a grove offensively I can see the potential. She is fearless and she can create offense. She is long and able to handle the ball very well while running the offense. She had some point blank shots that she missed but I\'m sure she is able to make those normally. What impressed me the most is that she didn\'t get down or frustrated and stayed with it. She continued to find other ways to contribute to the win. She will be one to keep and eye on the rest of the season.\n\n3. UNC Wilmington commit Evan Miller is going to be the key to the success of AK. Miller can score and does a great job letting the game come to her. She isn\'t selfish or demanding but what I like is that she knows when its time to step up. Late in the game last night Miller stepped up and took the last two shots to try and give her team the win. Yes she fell a little short but she had the heart to take the shots and give her team the best chance to win. Going forward Miller will need to continue to pick her spots and step up when needed. It wouldn\'t hurt to possibly assert herself a little more throughout the course of the game and set a tone that way as well. I will continue to watch Miller the rest of the season.\n\n4. Trinity Thompson, senior guard for Independence was very impressive last night. There were moments in the game where Independence needed a lift, specifically coming out of the half and Thompson had an 8 point run late in the third that turned the game around. With multiple steals and a few three pointers she took control of the game in the third which led to a classic fourth. At 5-5 she doesn\'t have a lot of height but she is able to get her shot off. She has a nifty handle and is able to fade away a little getting her left handed shot off in the paint. Overall she is a pretty good three point shooter and seems to have the heart to try and make big plays. Defensively she gets her hands on balls and creates conflict for the opponent. I\'m looking forward to watching her play again later this season.\n\n5. What we learned from this game is that there is a lot of hidden talent in Charlotte and surrounding areas. As long as these ladies keep working and developing, they can earn a chance to play on the next level. Players like Milton and Palmer need to keep developing and working on their games in efforts to be major difference makers. Both teams have the potential to have solid seasons at worst. Both can make a run for the playoffs. As they both gel, develop and manage sports adversity, they will give their opponents major issues on the court. They are not easy outs! Independence is now 3-1 and AK 3-3. I look forward to watching both teams the rest of the way.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','5 Takeaways From The Independence vs Ardrey Kell Match!','','publish','open','open','','5-takeaways-from-the-independence-vs-ardrey-kell-match','','','2019-12-04 17:44:43','2019-12-04 23:44:43','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120885',0,'post','',0),
	(120897,1,'2019-12-04 15:10:59','2019-12-04 21:10:59','On opening night of official games in Colorado, the Chaparral Wolverines and Overland Trailblazers kicked off the new campaign against one another. It was the second year in a row the teams played their first games against one another and in the 2019-20 opener, Chaparral prevailed with a 48-32 victory at Overland High.\n\nHere are three observations from the game.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120511\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-120511\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Avery-Bang-Chaparral2-300x259.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"259\" /> Avery Bang[/caption]\n\n<strong>Chaparral’s Bang twins pack plenty of punch</strong>\n\nHow many teams in Colorado can say they have not one but two 6-foot-1 sophomore forwards with Division-I potential?\n\nOne.\n\nChaparral’s duo of twins <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/avery-bang/\">Avery Bang</a> and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/payton-bang/\">Payton Bang</a> took the floor to kick off their 10<sup>th</sup>-grade campaign with the Wolverines on Monday night. Both players started a little slow, missing some easy shots early on, but eventually got on track during a second half in which Chaparral outscored Overland, 32-20.\n\nBoth player who can handle the ball and run the floor well for bigs, Payton and Avery Bang are also developing the ability to shoot from 3-point range. On Monday night, Payton finished with 14 points and seven rebounds while Avery had 10 points and eight rebounds.\n\n“The biggest thing with them is learning to play with those heavy minutes and use their length,” Chaparral coach Tony Speights said. “Once we get in a rhythm, they will be really tough at the defensive end and they love to run the floor so we’ll be in good shape.”\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120483\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-120483\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Amaya-Charles-Overland2-300x218.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"218\" /> Amaya Charles[/caption]\n\n<strong>Overland’s backcourt has plenty of firepower</strong>\n\nAgainst Chaparral’s imposing frontcourt, the Overland Trailblazers countered by attacking with their pair of speedy guards.\n\nSenior Naomi Stapleton, who averaged 9.3 points last season, got into the paint regularly and showed off an arsenal of dribble moves that kept defenders off balance. Sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amaya-charles/\">Amaya Charles</a>, who averaged 8.7 points as a freshman, was a threat from the perimeter and also stayed on the attack with the ball in her hands. Both guards are small but effectively quick and catalyzed the Overland offense in Shawn Taylor’s first game as head coach on Monday night.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120505\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-120505\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Jessica-Formento-Chaparral-300x223.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"223\" /> Jessica Formento[/caption]\n\n<strong>Jessica Formento flashed as de-facto point guard</strong>\n\nUnexpected occurrences during the offseason left several openings in the Chaparral rotation.\n\nJunior guard Tia Slade, who was third in scoring on last year’s Wolverines team, transferred to Highlands Ranch. Teja Tsangarakis, a junior point guard who was last year’s fourth-leading scorer, tore her ACL at the end of the summer season and will miss the 2019-20 season.\n\nTsangarakis’ injury in particular forced senior Jessica Formento into the point guard role, which wasn’t too hard of a transition for her to make considering she is a four-year starter and a team leader already. A bigger-bodied guard with excellent length at 5-foot-9, Formento helped spark the Wolverines in the second half and finished with 12 points and four boards.\n\n“When she’s on the floor, we can do a whole lot with her,” Speights said.\n\nFreshman <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/keegan-armetta/\">Keegan Armetta</a> also did a solid job at the point guard position when she was called upon.\n\n[robo-gallery id=\"120619\"]','Three observations from Chaparral at Overland','','publish','open','open','','three-observations-from-chaparral-at-overland','','','2019-12-04 15:10:59','2019-12-04 21:10:59','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120897',0,'post','',0),
	(120954,1,'2019-12-04 16:51:24','2019-12-04 22:51:24','With 42.36% of the vote,  Helaina Hillyard of Mediapolis was voted the Iowa Player of the Week. Hillyard impressed in a victory over Winfield Mt-Union and helped lead her team to a 64-32 season-opening win. In the game, Hillyard was outstanding as she scored 17 points. She grabbed a double-double by swiping 13 steals and she was also able to add in seven rebounds and six assists. It was an all-around tremendous performance and the definition of someone stuffing the stat sheet.\n\nMediapolis now sits at 2-0 with a win to start this week. They are getting contributions from all over but the play of Hillyard has really spurred them. This season should be a solid one with a senior-laden roster. Mediapolis has five seniors on the team and all of them have played together for their entire lives. This is something that Hillyard exclaimed that she was very excited about and even though it\'ll be a fun year, they have their eyes on making a run to Wells Fargo Arena at the end of the season.\n\n<span class=\"css-901oao css-16my406 r-1qd0xha r-ad9z0x r-bcqeeo r-qvutc0\">\"I’m looking forward to working hard with my best friends and it hopefully paying off,\" she said. \"My teammates are awesome. They’re my best friends and we’ve been playing together since first-grade Y-ball, we all trust in each other so it’s so much fun. </span><span class=\"css-901oao css-16my406 r-1qd0xha r-ad9z0x r-bcqeeo r-qvutc0\">Our goal is to win the conference and then later make it to state.\"</span>\n\nHillyard had a great start to the year and after a 14-point, eight steals, seven assists performance in game two, expect her to have a couple of triple-doubles on the season. She is the definition of a high-level multi-sport athlete as she has signed to play Divison I volleyball at Western Illinois. Once again, congratulations on winning the Player of the Week amongst some tremendous other athletes!\n\n&nbsp;','PGH Iowa Week 1 Player of the Week: Helaina Hillyard','','publish','open','open','','pgh-iowa-week-1-player-of-the-week-helaina-hillyard','','','2019-12-04 16:51:24','2019-12-04 22:51:24','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120954',0,'post','',0),
	(120989,1,'2019-12-05 06:11:10','2019-12-05 12:11:10','<strong>Alaina Diaz </strong>is one of the most talented sophomore guards in Michigan and is ready to have a big season. She\'s is prepared to help her Hudsonville High School team reach their goals. We caught up with <strong>Diaz </strong>to talk about her role, her teammates, and more.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_120998\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-120998\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_20191204_194422-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> 2019-2020 Hudsonville Basketball[/caption]\n\nQuestion:\n\nWhat\'s the biggest strength of your game?\n\n<strong>Alaina Diaz:</strong>\n\nI think my biggest strength is my defense. I love to shut the best player down. It’s a challenge. On offense, to get the ball in the hole, whether it’s me or my teammates, and seeing the whole floor.\n\nQuestion:\n\nWhat do you envision your role being on your high school team?\n\n<strong>Alaina Diaz:</strong>\n\nIm only a sophomore, but I think when it’s a team it’s important for everyone to be a leader regardless of age. That’s what makes a productive team.\n\nQuestion:\n\nDo you have any personal goals for this season?\n\n<strong>Alaina Diaz:</strong>\n\nTo continue to grow in the game and be the best I can be for the team. Be a leader and help bring us to a state championship.\n\nQuestion:\n\nWhat are your teams\' goals this year?\n\n<strong>Alaina Diaz:</strong>\n\nOur teams\' goal is to of course go to State! That would be amazing. But even more so to come together and work together. We’re family.\n\nQuestion:\n\nWho are a few teammates of yours that fans should look out for?\n\n<strong>Alaina Diaz:</strong>\n\nA few teammates to look for is everyone who steps on that floor. We’re all important. Basketball is a team sport not an individual sport. Every person plays and important role. We need to be encouraging on the floor and off. Constantly cheering for each other.\n\nQuestion:\n\nWhat do you think will be your teams strengths?\n\n<strong>Alaina Diaz:</strong>\n\nAs a team...we have so many athletic talented players so we need to utilize that and work like a machine together.\n\nQuestion:\n\nAny games your looking forward to this season?\n\n<strong>Alaina Diaz:</strong>\n\nI am looking forward to playing East Kentwood and Rockford. Yes. Looking forward to those two for sure.\n\nQuestion:\n\nWhat makes your coach a great leader?\n\n<strong>Alaina Diaz:</strong>\n\nCoach Glass really is passionate about his team and each girl that steps on the floor. I love that he trusts me and pushes me to be the best I can be on the floor and in life. Each coach on the bench plays an important role and I’m thankful for that.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Alaina Diaz (2022):  Preseason Interview','','publish','open','open','','alaina-diaz-2022-preseason-interview','','','2019-12-05 06:11:10','2019-12-05 12:11:10','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120989',0,'post','',0),
	(120992,1,'2019-12-04 22:36:38','2019-12-05 04:36:38','Last night Prep Girls Hoops Minnesota was in Elk River to watch the Spectrum Sting take on the Mora Mustangs in an early-season non-conference matchup that at the half was quite the matchup, but not so much in the end.\n\n<strong>Recap</strong>\n\nThis game was deadlocked at the half at 25 as it was anyone\'s game. Mora as a team that didn\'t have a star presence depended on solid showings from <strong>Anna Athey </strong>(2021), <strong>Jaiden Robb </strong>(2022r) and others to stay in the game. As for the Sting, they got a great start from <strong>Abby Thompson</strong> (2020) who lead all scorers with 7 points in the first half even though she struggled through the middle and the end of the half with her outside shooting. She blossomed in the 2nd half and at one point scored more points than the entire Mora team and ended her night with 21 points, with 14 in the 2nd half tying the total amount of points Mora had in the 2nd half. Another strong performance from the Sting came from <strong>Adrienne Foell</strong> (2021) who chipped in double digits with 10 points as well. Those two alone scored 31 points, while Mora\'s whole roster scored 39 in the entire game which is why the Sting got a strong win, 55-39 over the Mustangs of Mora.\n\n<strong>Five Takeaways</strong>\n\n<strong>Stockriser: Now On My Radar</strong>\n\n<strong>Adrienne </strong><strong>Foell </strong>(2021) was not a player I had on my players to watch list from my preseason team preview on the Spectrum Sting but now is a player to watch in the MCAA. She offered a great 2nd option with Abby Thompson and was a key player in the victory over Mora last night.\n\n<strong>Only Double-Digit for the Mustangs</strong>\n\nThat nod goes another 2021 prospect Mora\'s <strong>Anna Athey</strong> as she led the charge for the Mustangs offensively. She was key as far as getting rebounds and giving the Mustangs some good second-chance points against the Sting defense.\n\n<strong>Play of The Game</strong>\n\nMy favorite play in last night\'s game in Elk River was on a fast break when <strong>McKenna Ritter</strong> (2022) used her excellent court awareness to find <strong>Adrienne Foell</strong> (2021) for a key lay in to punch the Sting\'s ticket to victory against the tired Mora defense in the 2nd half.\n\n<strong>Key Contributors for the Mustangs</strong>\n\n11 points may not sound like much to some, but good contributions from <strong>Peyton Oslin </strong>(2021) and <strong>Jaiden Robb </strong>(2022) was the equivalent of almost 29% of the Mustangs scoring yesterday. There is a lot of potential from the Mustangs class of 2021 and 2022, to say the least, so Oslin and Robb should feel proud of their young contributions to the Mustangs roster.\n\n<strong>But Seriously, How Good is Abby Thompson?</strong>\n\nSitting currently in the 134th spot of our 2020 rankings is <strong>Abby Thompson</strong> of Spectrum. In what I saw last night, the Hamline commit has a great potential to push closer to 100 with her 21 points she had in the game last night. She didn\'t just score at will in the 2nd half last night, she did \"other great things besides scoring,\" Coach <strong>Cory Hund</strong> told PGH Minnesota after the game. Thompson is also the happiest player I\'ve ever watched play the game of basketball even after the physical, aggressive play the Mustangs brought on Tuesday night in Elk River.\n\nSpectrum (2-0) will head north to Braham (1-1) who got a win against McGregor on Monday, 44-30.\n\nMora (1-1) will go back home to play Moose Lake-Willow River (1-1) who features 2022 PGH Minnesota prospect <strong>Natalie Mikrot </strong>who is averaging 23 ppg for the Rebels and should be a tough matchup for the Mustangs.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Spectrum Outlasts Mora in the Second Half: Game Recap/Five Takeaways','','publish','open','open','','spectrum-outlasts-mora-in-the-second-half-game-recap-five-takeaways','','','2019-12-04 22:36:38','2019-12-05 04:36:38','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=120992',0,'post','',0),
	(121011,1,'2019-12-04 19:44:50','2019-12-05 01:44:50','With teams opening the 2019-20 season on Monday and Tuesday night, the PGH Colorado crew hit a couple of games around Colorado. Then we hit MaxPreps.com today to see who kicked off the new campaign by putting up some some big numbers in the scoring column.\n\nHere are the top scorers from the first couple nights of hoops around the state.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_97432\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-97432\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/9E542E3B-8896-461C-8380-915E6BFE441D-300x229.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"229\" /> Grace Talbot[/caption]\n\n<strong>Grace Talbot – Chatfield</strong>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/grace-talbot/\">Grace Talbot</a> opened her sophomore season with a bang, dropping 25 points in a 55-44 win over Boulder. Along with Cherokee Trail’s Dominique Rodriguez also putting up 25 points, this was the highest scoring number we’ve seen reported thus far. Talbot, who entered the season with high expectations after scoring 13.1 points a night as a freshman, was 8 for 18 from the field and shot 63 percent (5 for 8) from behind the 3-point arc. That definitely counts as starting the season on a high note.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Katelynn Ralston – Cheyenne Mountain</strong>\n\nRalston put up 22 big points for the Indians in a 70-59 win over Widefield on Tuesday. The 5-foot-9 senior forward shot 50 percent (7 for 14) from the field and also pulled down eight rebounds in the win. Ralston getting off to a hot start is a good sign for an Indians club looking to improve on a 7-16 season in 2018-19. Freshman shooting guard Alena San Augustin nearly matching Ralston with 22 points of her own while shooting 67 percent from the field and going 3 for 4 from 3-point range should give Cheyenne Mountain even more reason for optimism.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112123\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"280\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112123\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/St.-Marys9-280x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"280\" height=\"300\" /> Josephine Howery[/caption]\n\n<strong>Josephine Howery – St. Mary’s</strong>\n\nA 24-point scoring outburst should come as no surprise from the reigning 3A Player of the Year, and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/josephine-howery/\">Josephine Howery</a> wasted no time reminding everyone that she and the Pirates are back for their third straight state title with a 75-22 win over Resurrection Christian. Howery made nine of 16 shot attempts and the Pirates had four players – Howery, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/seneca-hackley/\">Seneca Hackley</a> (17), <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ellie-hartman/\">Ellie Hartman</a> (13) and Brooklyn Valdez (12) – score in double figures.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Emily Sanchez – Sheridan</strong>\n\nA third player to kick of the season with 24 points, Sanchez began her sophomore year with the Rams by hitting six 3-pointers and shooting 7 for 16 overall. Sheridan lost 50-44 to Denver North but their sophomore captain scoring over 20 points and coming up with five steals was a bright spot in the defeat.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_95561\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-95561\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Brooke-Murrell-Thomas-Jefferson-300x263.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"263\" /> Brooke Murrell[/caption]\n\n<strong>Brooke Murrell – Thomas Jefferson</strong>\n\nA freshman scoring 24 points in her first-ever high school game is something to behold, and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brooke-murrell/\">Brooke Murrell</a> did exactly that in a loss to a strong Sierra club. The 6-foot-1 forward also had 15 rebounds to kick off her high school career with a double-double. She and shot 8 for 17 from the field and was 8 for 16 at the free-throw line.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Emma Rich – Broomfield</strong>\n\nRich never scored more than six points in 31 varsity games prior to Monday night’s 22-point outburst in the eighth-ranked Eagles’ 79-20 win over Northglenn. This is what her final line read: 22 points, five assists, four rebounds and five steals. Rich did her scoring on 7-for-9 shooting and hit four of the five 3-pointers she attempted. That’s quite an auspicious beginning to her junior season.','Top Scorers from Monday and Tuesday','','publish','open','open','','top-scorers-from-monday-and-tuesday','','','2019-12-04 19:44:50','2019-12-05 01:44:50','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121011',0,'post','',0),
	(121026,1,'2019-12-04 22:02:35','2019-12-05 04:02:35','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;color: #000080\"><strong>Standouts as Crusaders Outlasts Tigers In #1 vs #2 Battle</strong></span></span></p>\nThe top ranked New Hope Tigers faced an early marker game against second ranked Riverdale Baptist Crusaders.  The two local teams had a down to the wire meeting in the fall league as New Hope played without star Jada Walker, the Crusaders were able to edge them.  In this regular season rematch both teams were full strength on a neutral court.  The Crusaders took the lead by Liz Martino (Rutgers) who had 8 of her 10 points in the first half and Kaylah Ivey who 7 of her team high 16 point in the half.\n\nThe Crusaders had a commanding 28-17 lead at halftime, however, the Tigers still had fight picking up the defense and going on a 12-0 run in the third.  The Crusaders regained the lead and held a 4-6 point lead for the majority of the fourth quarter.  New Hope\'s Delicia Pinnick knocked down a couple of bombs from three and Walker found Maria Gakdeng in the closing seconds to send the game into overtime.  In the end it was Riverdale Baptist with the overtime victory 50-49.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #0000ff\"><strong>Standout Players:</strong></span></span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000;text-decoration: underline\">Kayla Thomas - 6\'3\" - Post - Riverdale Baptist</span></span></strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121074\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121074\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Kayla-Thomas-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Kayla Thomas[/caption]\n\nKayla came up big (literally) in the game with 13 points and around 10 boards.  The transfer was a factor on both ends and was one of the main reasons that Riverdale one the game.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Jalyn Brown - 6\'0\" - Wing - Riverdale Baptist</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_27567\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-27567\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/DSC_0367-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Jalyn Brown[/caption]\n\nThe sophomore played with a lot of confidence and aggression attacking the basket and getting to the rack and picking up fouls.  Her efforts netted her seven free throw attempts and a bucket all in the first half finishing with 7 points.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Jada Walker - 5\'7\" - Point Guard - New Hope</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121076\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121076\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Jada-Walker-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /> Jada Walker[/caption]\n\nJada was spectacular leading the game with a high of 17 points.  She showed good vision with the willingness to give up the ball for a better shot even when she had the hot hand.  Her speed was the key for her as she continually beat her defender off the dribble and weaved through traps.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Maria Gakdeng - 6\'3\" - Post - New Hope</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121079\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121079\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Maria-Gakdeng-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Maria Gakdeng[/caption]\n\nMaria scored all of her 7 points in the fourth quarter and overtime before fouling out.  She scored the tying bucket to send the game into overtime but, could only watch in the final minutes.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Elizabeth Martino - 5\'11 - Guard - Riverdale Baptist</strong></span></span>\n\nElizabeth opened the game with a basket and a three point play.  She finished the game with 10 points and set the tone early as the majority of her point came in the first quarter.  The Rutgers commit left no doubt that she has fully returned from a knee injury that kept her out the entire 2018-19 season.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Delicia Pinnick - 5\'8\" - Guard - New Hope</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121080\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121080\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Delicia-Pinnick-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /> Delicia Pinnick[/caption]\n\nPinnick came alive in the second half after going scoreless in the first.  She started attacking the basket and then unleashed her signature 3-pointer late in the fourth and again in overtime to cut the lead to one point.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><span style=\"color: #800000\"><strong>Kaylah Ivey - 5\'9\" - Point Guard - Riverdale Baptist</strong></span></span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_17977\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-17977\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/DSC_0860-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /> Kaylah Ivey[/caption]\n\nKaylah finished the game with 16 points and she proved again that she is one of the best free throw shooters in the area making eight of them without the ball touching the rim.  She controlled the game at the end scoring six points in overtime for the win.','Standouts as Crusaders Outlasts Tigers In #1 vs #2 Battle','','publish','open','open','','standouts-as-crusaders-outlasts-tigers-in-1-vs-2-battle','','','2019-12-04 22:02:35','2019-12-05 04:02:35','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121026',0,'post','',0),
	(121033,1,'2019-12-07 01:11:49','2019-12-07 07:11:49','The high school season is finally here and we are all ready for it. I will post updated rankings for the 695 Beltway area every couple of weeks or so. Here is the first edition based off early season results, fall league action and player movement.\n\n1. St. Frances Academy\n\nThe Panthers start out where they finished last year, number one. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/angel-reese/\">Angel Reese</a> had a great off season, winning a Nike national championship and commiting to Maryland. She should have another dominant season. Her main sidekick is junior guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/aniya-gourdine/\">Aniya Gourdine</a>. Damoni Dorsey and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/cori-barnes/\">Cori Barnes</a> should play bigger roles this season. The defending champs will not go down easily, if they go down at all.\n\n2. Baltimore Poly\n\nPoly should win 3A this season. Coach Peace brings back the core of her team including senior point guard Cache Wilson (MD- Eastern Shore), senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jada-gross/\">Jada Gross</a>, and senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dasia-townes/\">Dasia Townes</a> (VCU). She is also adding senior post <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ajae-petty/\">Ajae Petty</a> (LSU) who transferred in from IND and a couple of impact freshmen in Da\'Bryia Clark and Trinity Massenburg. The team is talented and deep.\n\n3. Roland Park\n\nLast year\'s IAAM runner up should be right back in the mix. Senior Mir Mclean (UConn) is enough to keep them competitive in most games. She will get help back in the form of senior point guard Rain Greene (VCU) who should be back from her ACL tear in January. They also have junior wing <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophia-diehl/\">Sophia Diehl</a> who transferred in from Westminster.\n\n4. St. Vincent Pallotti\n\nPallotti has been the talk of the off season with five transfers coming in. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/eniya-russell/\">Eniya Russell</a> (South Carolina) comes in from IND and junior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauryn-russell/\">Lauryn Russell</a> comes in from Howard. Vashae Rideout transferred from Western and the Sydnor sisters, Larrin and Larri left Catonsville. The Panthers return senior guard Janiah Hall (Monmouth), senior forward Jasmine Valentine and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/makayla-waleed/\">Makayla Waleed</a>. The team is definitely talented and deep but can they put it all together in time? Time will tell.\n\n5. McDonogh\n\nCoach Brad Rees has a very talented but young squad this year. Junior guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jayla-oden/\">Jayla Oden</a> will lead the way and she will have help from sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/nekhu-mitchell/\">Nekhu Mitchell</a> and talented freshmen Makaela Quimby and Paris Locke. Look for this team to improve as the year goes along reach the IAAM final four.\n\n6. Howard\n\nHoward brings back two potential Howard County player of the year candidates is <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/marisa-sanchez-henry/\">Marisa Sanchez-Henry</a> (Wagner) and Anii Harris (Salem). This back court will be tough to deal with every game. Sophomore Gabby Scott will hold it down in the paint.\n\n7. PIkesville\n\nPikesville has two potential Baltimore County player of the year candidates in Kristen Sterling and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/charia-roberts/\">Charia Roberts</a> (Loyola-MD). That duo will be tough to deal with but they will be without sophomore point guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amayah-frazier/\">Amayah Frazier</a> who tore her ACL in the fall. Nakiya Bland, a junior guard transfer from Cape Cod will take up some of those minutes along with senior Francis Glover-Bey. They are now in 2A so their road to the final four will be a little different.\n\n8. River Hill\n\nCoach Teresa Waters brings back her core that won last year\'s 2A title. Sophomore guard Anhiya Smith and seniors Kennedy Clark and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/saniha-jackson/\">Saniha Jackson</a> will lead the charge.\n\n9. Western\n\nWestern returns their dynamic sophomore guard duo of Ny\'ceara Pryor and Gabby Johnson and that gives them a shot in most games. Junior guard Sanaya Gray is back and healthy and the Doves got a talented scorer in Mya Henson via transfer from City.\n\n10. South River\n\nCoach Zivic brings back guards Julia Fitzwater and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/harley-herndon/\">Harley Herndon</a> as they try to win the Anne Arundel county championship and make noise in 4A.\n\n11. Old Mill\n\nOld Mill will be in the thick of things in Anne Arundel county with seniors Deja Atkinson and Mikiyah Mallett leading the charge. Both can score and have big game experience.\n\n12. Coppin Academy\n\nJunior forward <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/nyshae-weaver/\">Nyshae Weaver</a> is a big time talent and she is paired with senior Kayla Henderson who is closing in on 1500 career points. They add six foot post Aniya Hills from Randallstown so this should be the year they win 1A.\n\n13. St. Paul\'s\n\nI expect this team to rise up the rankings week by week. Senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/destiny-ryles/\">Destiny Ryles</a> is a handful and hard to stop from scoring and this is a well coached group.\n\n14. Archbishop Spalding\n\nNew coach Lisa Smith has rebuilt the excitement around this program and has some ballers to work with. The sister act of Koi and Kamari Sims is legit and they are joined by freshman Mariah Sanabia who looks like a big time talent.\n\n15. Reservoir\n\nCoach Deb Taylor has lost a lot, 8 players in all but she still has senior guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tiffany-hooker/\">Tiffany Hooker</a> who will be in the conversation for Howard county player of the year.\n\n16. Mt. Carmel\n\nCoach Rob Long has built the program to legitimate B conference contender status. Can they take the next step and reach the finals? 6\'3\" post Hawa Doumbaya and sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tsion-smith-2/\">Tsion Smith</a> will play big roles alongside senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/shanysse-alexander/\">Shanysse Alexander</a> and Tam Stanford.\n\n17. Western Tech\n\nTech will scrap and stay in the mix for the Baltimore county championship. Tiffany Manning and Destini Ward will lead the way\n\n18. Mt. Hebron\n\nSenior Satori Valentine is good enough to keep the Vikings competitive in Howard County. If she gets any help they surprise some people.\n\n19. Forest Park\n\nEvery year we overlook Forest Park, but coach Jermaine Dunn always comes up with a group that surprises us. I have a feeling this year will be the same. He lost a lot but picked up some out of town transfers.\n\n20. St. TImothy\'s\n\nSt. Tim\'s has some young talent that is ready to step in and help them win some games. Aryss Mactoon and Andrea Cherisier are legit and should get step into heavy minutes right away.\n\n&nbsp;','The 695 Top 20 Early Edition','','publish','open','open','','the-695-top-20-early-edition','','','2019-12-07 01:11:49','2019-12-07 07:11:49','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121033',0,'post','',0),
	(121042,1,'2019-12-04 20:46:17','2019-12-05 02:46:17','For the Desert Mountain Wolves girls’ basketball team, the season may have just begun, but there are already two clear leaders on the court. <strong>Jaedyn O’Reilly </strong>and <strong>Sophie Gerber</strong> have wasted no time stepping into the leadership position and taking control of the team on the court.\n\nAt the Hoop Hall Classic, O’Reilly and Gerber absolutely tore up the court in the Wolves 55-16 route of the Arcadia Titans. Together, the duo combined for 30 of the team’s total points. They also were largely responsible for the team’s defensive attack and forced a handful of turnovers on the night.\n\nCoach Alicia Sanchez said that it’s been an adjustment getting to this point and that it was a rough start to the season, mostly because the team is so new. As the season continues to progress, she fully expects them to continue growing and gaining that team chemistry that makes things work, but she says that O’Reilly and Gerber will be the centerpiece of it.\n\n“To see them grow and kind of take control and leadership over the team has been pretty rewarding to see. They still have their kinks, but they lead by example, they lead with their voices and they’re really great players.” Coach Sanchez said.\n\n“We have a really new team, so we are still working with them, but I’m glad I get to be a captain. I get to lead them. I feel like both Sophie and I know what’s right. We’re good leaders and we can help them do what’s right,” O’Reilly said.\n\nFor O’Reilly had 12 points for Desert Mountain on the night. She was pleased with the team’s defensive attack on the night and said it’s really something they’ve been focusing on in practice. Hustling for the ball and forcing a deflection or getting the steal is something that O’Reilly says Coach Sanchez really drills into them about every single day.\n\n“If I’m doing my best and I know I’m hustling a lot, I know I’m making her proud, and that motivates me to work hard,” O’Reilly said.\n\nO’Reilly knows that teamwork is what makes the dream work, so that’s what she’s looking forward to improving on the most as the season continues.\n\n“We’re all good individually. We can do our own stuff, but when we come together, I feel like we can do very good things. I feel like as the season progresses, we’re going to get a lot better and we’re going to be beating teams by a lot more and it’s just going to look a lot nicer,” O’Reilly said.\n\nMeanwhile for Gerber, she had 18 points of the night. Her performance was enough to earn her the coveted Hoop Hall Classic MVP game ball. She has a unique preparation tactic that seems to work for her. Gerber says before every game, she goes into the gym in the morning and works on her shooting to get ready for the game. But even with the success she’s having this year, she knows there are still a lot of areas of her game that she’d like to improve on.\n\n“Defensively, I need to step up and be more active on defense. I’m still working on that, and just being aware offensively of where I am on the court.”\n\nCoach Sanchez said she’s looking forward to seeing the seniors grow in their overall confidence as the season continues to unfold.\n\n“They’re so hard on themselves, they want to do well every single game. They’re pretty much perfectionists. I just want them to kind of relax, play the game, have fun and enjoy their last year as high school basketball players,” Sanchez said.\n\nDesert Mountain will look to close out the rest of 2019 strong with its remaining three games before the winter break rolls around. They’ll take on Gilbert on December 5<sup>th</sup>, Williams Field on December 12<sup>th</sup> and Notre Dame Prep on December 13<sup>th</sup>. Look for Gerber and O’Reilly to lead the Wolves’ attack in these upcoming games.','Jaedyn O’Reilly, Sophie Gerber emerge as leaders for Desert Mountain','','publish','open','open','','jaedyn-oreilly-sophie-gerber-emerge-as-leaders-for-desert-mountain','','','2019-12-04 20:46:17','2019-12-05 02:46:17','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121042',0,'post','',0),
	(121043,1,'2019-12-10 10:00:46','2019-12-10 16:00:46','Many of the top recruits in Colorado’s 2020 class have already committed to play college basketball, and many of them will play at the Division-I level. Many of them will also play their college ball right at home in Colorado. But plenty of the Centennial State’s talented seniors remain uncommitted or are still in search of offers.\n\nFor a refresh, check out <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/10/five-top-2020s-in-co-who-are-still-available/\">Part 1</a> and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/top-co-2020s-who-are-still-available-part-2/\">Part 2</a> of this list. Here are four more Colorado seniors who are still available.\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_112155\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-112155\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Thornton-300x288.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"288\" /> Shamahra Henderson[/caption]\n\n<strong>Shamahra Henderson, 5-8, W, Thornton</strong>\n\nWord is she’s leaning towards the JUCO route, but many believe <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/shamahra-henderson/\">Shamahra Henderson</a> has the ceiling of a Division-II player at this point. As a junior, she was a stat machine, averaging 17 points, 11.7 rebounds, 2.8 assists, 4.4 steals and 3.0 blocks per game. Henderson is still weighing her options as she plays through the early portion of her senior season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Dominique Rodriguez, 5-6, G, Cherokee Trail</strong>\n\nRodriguez has drawn interest from several JUCO, D-II and D-III schools, including Texas A&amp;M International in Laredo, Texas. As a junior, she averaged 11.4 points, 2.6 assists, 1.8 rebounds and 1.8 steals while scoring double figures in 15 of 25 games. The 5-foot-6 guard in quick and strong, and is looking to score more as a senior this winter. She backed that up with 25 points in the Cougars’ season-opening win over Rangeview.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_99183\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-99183\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/F3801D2A-1EA6-40D5-81C1-246AB984948E-300x228.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"228\" /> Krystina Hagood[/caption]\n\n<strong>Krystina Hagood, 5-7, G, Sand Creek</strong>\n\nHagood is still sitting out there and is counting on a strong senior season to push her recruiting stock. The high-energy guard averaged 11.6 points and eight rebounds as a junior last season. She has a bunch of up-and-coming teammates with whom to share the scoring load with this winter and will be looking to show her versatility. In a 88-41 win over Pueblo South in the season opener, Hagood put up seven points, four rebounds, three assists and four steals while playing limited minutes in the blowout.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Carly Dilworth, 5-6, G, Denver South</strong>\n\nRanked No. 30 in the PGH Colorado 2020 player rankings, Dilworth averaged 12.3 points, 3.3 rebounds and two steals per game. Helping lead the Denver South girls on a 17-8 season in 2018-19, the senior sharpshooter shot nearly 50 percent (75 for 151) from behind the 3-point arc. Dilworth is still looking for a program in need of a sharpshooting guard.','Four More 2020\'s Who Are Still Available','','publish','open','open','','four-more-2020s-who-are-still-available','','','2019-12-10 10:00:46','2019-12-10 16:00:46','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121043',0,'post','',0),
	(121050,1,'2019-12-11 10:00:30','2019-12-11 16:00:30','Liberty High School’s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lydia-marshall/\">Lydia Marshall</a> might not pass the eye test in the way some other players do when simply walking into a gym.\n\nBut her talent becomes apparent when Marshall starts playing.\n\n“Lydia has, I think, a strong chance of being the player of the year in our league,” Liberty head coach Monty Taylor said. “Her basketball IQ is one of the highest that I’ve had in all the years that I’ve been coaching, both boys and girls. She’s capable of posting up, shooting the three, handling the ball and she doesn’t make many mistakes. She just makes everyone around her better.”\n\nGoing into her senior season, this will mark the third year Marshall has been a captain and Taylor said he can depend on her to get practices going and keep the team on track. In games, Marshall can score with either hand. She can, in fact, even shoot 3-pointers with either hand, the result of her continuing to play through a previous shoulder injury by shooting with the other hand.\n\nAs a junior last winter, Marshall averaged 13.4 points, 6.3 rebounds, 2.8 assists and 2.7 steals. The 5-foot-8 guard shot 33 percent (37 for 112) from 3-point range and 84 percent at the free-throw line. Overall, she shot 42 percent from the field.\n\n“She’s one of those kids that’s going to get overlooked and that’s going to be to the detriment of the teams that are overlooking her because I think she’s only going to get stronger,” Taylor said.\n\nA Division-II or NAIA type player, Marshall has been accepted to UCCS, Concordia University, Nebraska, Concordia College and Chadron State, and is looking to play basketball at one of those schools or at another if the right fit came along at the Division-II level. She has a strong academic resume, carrying close to a 4.0 in college prep classes.','Recruiting Report: Lydia Marshall, Liberty 2020','','publish','open','open','','recruiting-report-lydia-marshall-liberty-2020','','','2019-12-11 10:00:30','2019-12-11 16:00:30','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121050',0,'post','',0),
	(121103,1,'2019-12-05 01:07:46','2019-12-05 07:07:46','The Perry Pumas opened the 2019-2020 season up with a statement 63-38 win over the Chaparral Firebirds at the Hoop Hall Classic. It was an all around team effort, but three players specifically looked outstanding offensively for the Pumas. At the start of the fourth quarter, <strong>Tatyanna Clayburne</strong>, <strong>Madison Conner </strong>and <strong>Nicole Smith </strong>all had racked up double digits for the Pumas. Overall, the Pumas saw a ton of success with their three-point shooting, hitting ten on the night.\n\nClayburne finished the night with 15 points on the night. Offensively she was able to shoot the ball from all over the court, hitting a three-pointer to open up the game. She followed that up with solid field goals and layups and was four-for-five from the free throw line.\n\n\"It was more of a team effort. We all took our time almost every day before talking about how we were going to defend. We were mainly prepped for defense, and offense handled itself afterwards,\" Clayburne said.\n\nConner was the Pumas\' leading scorer on the night, finishing with 22 points. Conner was not only hitting shots from all over the court tonight as well, but she also played a great game defensively, which is something that Coach Andrew Curtis said can absolutely not be overlooked.\n\n\"She can score. Everyone knows that, but what I think everyone should have seen tonight is the way she defended. She held one of the best players in the state to, I don\'t know, five points? She scores, yes, we all know that but her defense, her rebounding, I think that\'s what\'s going to set our team apart,\" Coach Curtis said.\n\nFor Conner, her outstanding performance earned her the game\'s MVP award, but she refused to take any solo credit for her performance.\n\n\"I definitely think it was a whole team effort. We really prepared for this game and it showed, just by making everybody a part of the game, not just taking one dribble and then a shot,\" Conner said.\n\nSmith was an integral part to Perry\'s outstanding shooting from behind the arc. She hit five of Perry\'s ten three-pointers tonight, four of them coming in the second quarter of the game. Smith finished the night with 17 total points, but also had a handful of steals and assists on the night to help elevate the Pumas\' play.\n\n\"Coach prepared us really well for this game. We were out shooting every day before this,\" Smith said. \"It just worked out. My shot was falling and we just kept going with it. It kept coming back to me.\"\n\nOverall, the entire trio all gave it up to the team effort on the court tonight for setting them up for success. The team\'s ability to pass the ball with precision and set each other up for shots was what created the opportunity for them to score.','Trio of juniors lead Perry to big win at Hoop Hall Classic','','publish','open','open','','trio-of-juniors-lead-perry-to-big-win-at-hoop-hall-classic','','','2019-12-05 01:07:46','2019-12-05 07:07:46','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121103',0,'post','',0),
	(121118,1,'2019-12-05 10:00:03','2019-12-05 16:00:03','On Tuesday night in northern metro Denver, the Legacy Lightning and Brighton Bulldogs squared off. Legacy came out on top with a 37-30 victory at Brighton High for its first win in 2019-20, but not without some late drama and a big night from a player who was sorely missed in the Lightning\'s first game of the new campaign.\n\nHere are three observations from the game.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_117278\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-117278\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Halle-Mackiewicz-300x218.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"218\" /> Halle Mackiewicz[/caption]\n\n<strong>Halle Mackiewicz is an elite soccer player, but also great at hoops</strong>\n\nHonestly, based on raw athleticism and natural poise, Legacy senior Halle Mackiewicz could probably play just about any sport she wanted. Soccer is her true love and she will play it at Clemson University next season. But Mackiewicz also led the Lightning girls basketball team with 19.1 points, 6.8 rebounds and 1.6 steals per game in 19 games last season while splitting time between basketball season and her commitments to club and Team USA soccer.\n\nIf nothing else, Lightning head coach Jody Welch said Mackiewicz brings a competitive edge and a veteran calmness to the Lightning, largely a result of all her experience with high-level competition in multiple sports.\n\nA 5-foot-10 forward who drives like a guard and defends like a Division-I goalkeeper, Mackiewicz led all scorers with 18 points on Tuesday night. She also made a clutch inbounds pass immediately after Brighton\'s Nikki Antonopoulos cut the lead down to three by sinking a 3-pointer with a minute left, heaving a three quarters-court overhand pass to sophomore teammate Kendall Aragon for a layup that basically iced the game.\n\nCheck out that throwing arm!\n\nhttps://twitter.com/PGHColorado/status/1202071451966287873\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121111\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121111\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Nikki-Antonopoulos-Brighton2-300x210.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"210\" /> Nikki Antonopoulos[/caption]\n\n<strong>Watch out when Brighton’s Nikki Antonopoulos dials it in</strong>\n\nNot for lack of trying, Brighton junior guard Nikki Antonopoulos only hit one 3-pointer on Tuesday night. That three ball was, in fact, the Bulldogs’ lone long ball of the game as a team.\n\nBut is sure was a big one.\n\nAs mentioned above, Antonopoulos’ long distance bucket gave Brighton a chance late in Tuesday’s game when it was at risk of getting away from them. Several of her other attempts throughout the evening looked good coming out of her hand and narrowly missed. Of course it’s easy to claim that lots of shots “almost went in,” but Antonopoulos, who led the Bulldogs with nine points, gets a bit of a pass for just having an off night as the Bulldogs’ top returning scorer at 8.8 points per game last season and having shot 39 percent (28 for 71) from 3-point range as a sophomore in \'18-19.\n\nThe Bulldogs have a solid group including sophomore Payton Gagon, who scored eight points, junior Tori Hendricks and Carly Pomrenke, and they\'ll need Antonopoulos to establish herself as a perimeter threat in order to give the offense balance. It seems likely that Antonopoulos finds her range sooner than later.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121105\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121105\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Amanda-Byrnes-Brighton-300x220.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"220\" /> Amanda Byrnes[/caption]\n\n<strong>Brighton has something in freshman Amanda Byrnes</strong>\n\nWhen Amanda Byrnes takes the court for the Brighton Bulldogs, it comes with a certain level of surprise for several reasons. She’s an imposing figure at 6-foot-1 with an athletic frame, the Bulldogs haven’t had her type of height in some time, and despite her height and length, Byrnes is just a freshman.\n\nByrnes didn’t light the world on fire in her debut, scoring one point on Tuesday night. But she didn’t disappear in her first taste of varsity high school basketball either, rebounding well, playing tough defense and affecting Legacy shots in the paint, and even bringing the ball up the floor on several occasions.\n\nWith her play in the preseason, Byrnes made an impression on Brighton head coach Jim French and it looks like she’ll get plenty of run this winter. As she continues to adjust to the high school game, expect the Bulldogs freshman to quickly become a factor in the East Metro League.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121109\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"272\"]<img class=\" wp-image-121109\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Katie-Paredes-Legacy-300x218.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"272\" height=\"198\" /> Katie Paredes[/caption]\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121112\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"298\"]<img class=\" wp-image-121112\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Payton-Gagon-Brighton-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"298\" height=\"198\" /> Payton Gagon[/caption]','Three Observations from Legacy at Brighton','','publish','open','open','','three-observations-from-legacy-at-brighton','','','2019-12-05 10:00:03','2019-12-05 16:00:03','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121118',0,'post','',0),
	(121134,1,'2019-12-05 06:01:37','2019-12-05 12:01:37','That old saying \"the good thing about freshmen is that become sophomores\" never made much sense to me but old sayings are dated, unless they come from me because at some point you have to use logic and if you\'re doing something over and over, you should get better each season, no matter what classification. In the early part of the century, many high school coaches wouldn\'t even put their freshmen on varsity, let alone start them however talent was also deeper and it\'s useless in me trying to explain something from the past many won\'t or can\'t comprehend but this is the now so I\'ll go with that. I spoke about Memorial\'s standout freshmen <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/mcdonalds-texas-invitational-d2/\">Abigail Tomaski and Riley McCloskey</a> </strong>in an article I did on the players from the McDonald\'s Texas Invitational D2 and I also dropped <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/mcdonalds-texas-invitational-d2-pt-2/\">Pearland Dawson’s freshmen backcourt</a> </strong>TAKEAWAY on <strong>Jalayah Ingram and Kennedy Ford</strong> also from the D2 side and although I didn\'t see <strong>Dalanna Carter (Barbers Hill)</strong> play but I know she went off based on some of the buzz and I\'m not surprised because when I saw her in the <a href=\"https://girlzprepreport.blogspot.com/2015/06/4th5th-grade-tip-sheet-2015-summer.html\">4th or 5th grade</a>, guess what I said? #D1Lock and over the years her explosiveness off the dribble, her ability to create and shoot, from anywhere as well as her ability to run a team cements what I stated but here are some others\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121150\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121150\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Brandy-Jones-TXINV-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Brandy Jones[/caption]\n\n<strong>Brandy Jones- 5\'8 PG (North Crowley)</strong> the game starts at the one and no one would know she\'s a freshman by just watching her. She\'s poised on the court, gets to the rim whenever she wants and has a nice pull-up while being contested. Her ballhandling and passing skills were on full display and her upside is through the roof because, on top of everything I\'ve said,  she\'s athletic, powerful and thinks the game\n\n<strong>Chelsea Singleton-5\'7 F (Cy Ranch)</strong> when you\'re a starter on a squad with three D1 signees, you have to find ways to \"fit into the system\" and she is showing a different side of her game which will be huge in the long run. I saw her score off the dribble as well as the short jumper over the summer but her defense is standing out and she\'s making the transition nicely\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121151\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121151\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Gisella-Maul-TXINV-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Gisella Maul[/caption]\n\n<strong>Gisella Maul-5\'10 G (Cedar Park)</strong> another player I labeled \"can\'t miss\" before middle school and it didn\'t take long for me to know what I was looking at. She can score multiple ways, her long-range has expanded somewhere close to the timeline but her ability to play the passing lane are layups going the other because, with her length and athleticism, she can bring some heat on both ends of the court\n\n<strong>Angel Tumberello-5\'4 G (San Antonio Johnson)</strong> already one of the best long ball shooters in her class and she showed that during the club season but she\'s adding even more to her offensive game. Ball handling and taking defenders off the dribble are solid but she\'s creating her shot, under pressure and showing that she can knock down the midrange as well\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121152\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"180\"]<img class=\" wp-image-121152\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Janae-Tucker-TXINV-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"180\" height=\"118\" /> Janae Tucker[/caption]\n\n<strong>Janae Tucker-5\'5 G (Dobie)</strong> made her first <a href=\"https://girlzprepreport.blogspot.com/2015/06/4th5th-grade-tip-sheet-2015-summer.html\">Tip Sheet</a> after finishing the 4th grade and always remember \"I don\'t guess\" so watching her make the transition smoothly doesn\'t surprise me. The midrange is solid, attacks from every angle and her ballhandling and ability to not only see the floor but make the right passes continue to standout but her upside is definitely impressive\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121153\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"260\"]<img class=\" wp-image-121153\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/JaShelle-Johnson-TXINV-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"260\" height=\"171\" /> Ja\'Shelle Johnson[/caption]\n\n<strong>Ja\'Shelle Johnson-5\'3 PG (San Antonio Johnson)</strong> one more time #sizedontmatter when you can play and my overused phrase \"when you see JJ, Good Times are coming\" as she adds to the list of players with those initials that are a hit. Her maturity on the court impressed me a few years ago and that has set the foundation for now as she attacks relentlessly, can score from mid to long and knows how to control the tempo and I\'ll close with the game has and always will start at the one and she\'s showing it','Freshmen standouts from Texas Invitational','','publish','open','open','','freshmen-standouts-from-texas-invitational','','','2019-12-05 06:01:37','2019-12-05 12:01:37','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121134',0,'post','',0),
	(121161,1,'2019-12-08 19:42:03','2019-12-09 01:42:03','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Every year, a number of players change schools and put on for their new squads. Throughout the season, I want to highlight some of these names and keep us refreshed on whose doing what for their new team. Most of these players you might see reunite in the AAU circuit. </span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #f75617\"><strong><a style=\"color: #f75617\" href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/keante-lewis/\">Keante Lewis</a> | 5\'9 G | St. Frances Academy | 2021</strong></span>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/keante-lewis/\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color: #f75617\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-121178\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Keante-Lewis-169x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"173\" height=\"307\" /></span></strong></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/keante-lewis/\">Keante Lewis</a> is going from one championship team to another. The Pikesville High transfer is now teamed up with <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/angel-reese/\">Angel Reese</a></strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/aniya-gourdine/\">Aniya Gourdine</a></strong> and the St. Frances Panthers. Keante was one of the leading scorers for Pikesville her sophomore year and will be more of a supporting player with St. Frances. Expect Lewis to come off the bench and even cut into some of the starters time as the season goes on. Keante averaged 9.8 ppg and 4.9 rebounds per game with the Panthers last year.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #f75617\"><a style=\"color: #f75617\" href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/vashe-rideout/\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\">Vashae Rideout | 5\'7 G | Pallotti | 2021</span></strong></a></span>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-20956\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/DSC_0743-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"216\" height=\"143\" />\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Vashae Rideout is a Western transfer playing for Pallotti this season. Here she teams up with standout Guard <strong>Nhaikyia Smith.</strong> Expect Nhaikyia to penetrate the ball down the court and set Vashae up on the perimeter. Rideout has a nice outside shot and also drives hard to the lane. I expect these two to play off each other as Pallotti continues to build their overall team chemistry.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #f75617\"><strong><a style=\"color: #f75617\" href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jenesis-massenburg/\"><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\"> </span></a><a style=\"color: #f75617\" href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jenesis-massenburg/\">Jenesis Massenburg</a> | 5\'4 G | Capital Christian Academy | 2022</strong></span>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-41043\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/DSC_0907-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"214\" height=\"142\" />\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jenesis-massenburg/\">Jenesis Massenburg</a> brings a ton of speed to the Red Storm. Massenburg should find plenty of playing time on Capital Christian\'s 8 man roster. Jenesis racked up 7.9 ppg last year with Bowie High School. </span>','Same Face New Place | Part1','','publish','open','open','','same-face-new-place-part1','','','2019-12-08 19:42:03','2019-12-09 01:42:03','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121161',0,'post','',0),
	(121248,1,'2019-12-05 11:15:24','2019-12-05 17:15:24','There will be very few games this winter when it might be possible for an opponent to upset powerhouse Hopkins and upend their quest for a second straight perfect season. This is one of those games. Friday night in Farmington, the Tigers will host the Royals in the biggest contest of the 2019-20 Minnesota high school season to date.\n\nFarmington is a program on the rise. When Liz Carpentier took over as coach in the fall of 2015 the team was coming off a three-win season. They doubled their number of wins the next year, became a .500 team the year after that, and last year went 24-4. Farmington is off to a quick start, winning all three games so far and demonstrating clearly, both as individuals and collectively, that they are much better than they were when the last season ended in March.\n\nLast Saturday at the Hamline University tournament, Farmington illustrated its capabilities clearly in a challenging 79-74 win over Stillwater. The Ponies’ <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amber-scalia/\">Amber Scalia</a></strong> staked her team to a 10-2 lead out of the gate, but Farmington went on a 19-0 run to seize control. Stillwater’s <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alexis-pratt/\">Alexis Pratt</a></strong> put on a stunning second-half display to put her team in a position to win before Farmington, which out-rebounded Stillwater by a 2-1 margin, sealed the deal with a couple of big plays in the waning moments. It was heady stuff. Farmington’s big three – senior guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/molly-mogensen/\">Molly Mogensen</a></strong>, junior post <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophie-hart/\">Sophie Hart</a></strong>, and junior guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-kindseth/\">Paige Kindseth</a></strong> – were simply outstanding, and the supporting cast did their jobs very, very well. Now comes the hard part.\n\n<strong>Q&amp;A with Farmington coach Liz Carpentier</strong>\n\nWe have written at length over the past couple of years about Farmington’s rise and the development of the Tigers’ top players. Heading into, perhaps, their biggest game of the current era, we thought it would be interesting to get the coach’s perspective on her players, the team, and the opportunity to face the very best team Minnesota has to offer. We spoke with Tigers’ head coach Liz Carpentier on Wednesday. Our conversation has been edited for brevity. Enjoy!\n\nQ: I’d like to talk first about your team leaders one by one. Let’s start with your point guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/molly-mogensen/\">Molly Mogensen</a>. Obviously she’s a senior, but she really is the heart and soul of your team, is she not?\n\nA: Her leadership is second-to-none. She has done two things for us that I think are really key for our program, and that’s why we have seen success. Number one, she has embraced the process. As a point guard so much is put on your shoulders, and being a starting point guard as an 8th grader was not an easy task for her. There was so much learning going on, and there were highs and lows every season. When we shared our vision with her about how we could turn this program around, she embraced that and did the things that we asked her to do. The second thing is she gets everybody involved. She is able to get all of our pieces going and I think that allows us to be really successful. We play such a team-style game. We don’t rely on one or two kids. Her doing those two things has not only completely changed our culture but it has put us on the map as a high-level basketball team that can compete. She has been totally on board and it has been fun.\n\nQ: If you are going to be a great team you obviously need a great point guard, but it doesn’t hurt to have a 6’4 post player, either. Give us your thoughts on <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophie-hart/\">Sophie Hart</a>.\n\nA: Watching her this season in practice, and then in our first three games, she is way better than she was last March. She is so assertive. She has been just commanding the paint both offensively and defensively. She has been working hard on her shooting mechanics, and I think that has really helped her. I know she gets a ton of offensive rebounds but she has to work for those. I think she is finishing so much better around the basket because she is working hard at it in practice. I also see her emerging as a leader now. She is vocal. I didn’t see that as much last year, and she is providing leadership through her play, too. She is getting stronger all the time and is being more assertive.”\n\nQ: It seems to me that going to the tryouts in Colorado for Team USA was maybe a turning point for Sophie. I think she came back from there feeling really good about herself. Would you agree?\n\nA: Definitely. We sat down when she came back and she said how hard it was. It was such high-level talent. She was challenged every day, every minute, in every drill, in whatever they were doing. I think, looking back, she felt really good afterword about her performance. I think she said, ‘Hey, I know now that I am one of the top players in the nation.’ She also realized what she needed to do to get better. I like that about her, that she knows she is a work in progress – she’s going to do the work – but I think she gained a lot of confidence from that, too.\n\nQ: I have liked <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-kindseth/\">Paige Kindseth</a> for a long time, and I have had the good fortune to watch her a lot, but it has taken some time for people, including college coaches, to see just how good she can be. In your first few games it seems as though Paige has kind of gone to a whole new level. Would you agree?\n\nA: Yes. We talked with Paige in the off-season and told her that she needs to show, within the flow of the game, that she can dominate. And she can. We talked about consistency. You can’t score 8 points one game and have 20 the next. She needs to play at a high level all the time, and use the things that she is good at. We have been on her constantly to attack and drive to the basket. She has embraced that and taken it to a whole new level like you said. She really has just come out of her shell this year. There are so many facets to her game where she can be impactful. She needs to show that she can dominate without being selfish. I think she’s done a great job.\n\nQ: That is essentially what she did in Saturday’s game, is it not? I mean, she asserted herself in every possible way, and scored some big buckets at big moments. I think her ability to create space and get her shot up in traffic is as good as anyone. She kind of reminds me of <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-jensen/\">Lauren Jensen</a></strong> in that way. There are not a lot of players who can do that.\n\nA: I tell Paige all the time that she can get into any gap she wants, more so than anyone on our team, and she elevates higher than anyone on our team. I tell her, ‘Paige, there is nobody that can stop your shot.’ She’s going to get into the paint, she’s going drive through a crease, and she’s going to be able to elevate and shoot it. Her mid-range is unbelievable and that’s where we want to utilize her. That and her rebounding ability. That also changes the game. You know we’ll be watching her during the game, and she’s just doing her thing, and then all of a sudden she’ll make the most unbelievable play. That’s the thing that I love about her. It’s so fun to watch.\n\nQ: Let’s talk about <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/peyton-blandin/\">Peyton Blandin</a></strong>. When she was younger, Peyton was a top-20 or top-25 prospect in that class. After that I think she kind of flat-lined for a while, but over the last 12 months, with the success that you’ve had, I think she has been on an upward trajectory. Last weekend I feel that her confidence level was higher than I’ve seen it for a long, long time.\n\nA: I agree with you 100 percent.  We worked with her in the summer, and we wanted to get her to the point where she was comfortable attacking the basket and pulling up for a jump shot. We didn’t want her to be just two-dimensional – either taking the three-point shot or going all the way to the hoop. She has added that to her game. She has the green light to shoot it. She can drive by anybody. We just want her to be more assertive. She’s not as vocal as everybody else. That’s OK – that’s her personality – but we don’t want her to defer this year and kind of hide behind in the shadows. She is a really important piece to our success. In big games she is very poised, she’s composed, and I don’t think she is afraid this year. She is playing fearless, which is good to see.\n\nQ: You have a very good supporting cast. Most good high school teams have kids that are high school players who maybe aren’t going to play in college, or maybe they are going to play another sport, but they have to contribute a lot if you are going to be successful. I think you would be hard-pressed to find a better player in that niche than <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/katelyn-mohr/\">Katelyn Mohr</a></strong>, would you not?\n\nA: Yeah, she is so valuable to us. First of all, she is a great leader and is one of our three captains, and she is so coachable. She has fundamentally worked on her shooting, she has worked on her jump shot, she has worked on just understanding the game more. Her growth in those areas, and her just being a phenomenal athlete, has allowed her to play big-time minutes. She is really contributing in a positive way. She rebounds, she’s not afraid to get in there and get scrappy and be aggressive. On Saturday she made some big-time plays, diving on the floor, getting a couple of big steals, that big layup she made. She is clutch. She has such a strong mindset that allows her to perform in big games. Even when she is making mistakes she is able to just battle back confidently, and her shot is beautiful. Those are all things that just add so much value to our team, and she is a great teammate. She is definitely playing her role.\n\nQ: The rest of your supporting cast is important to your success, too, primarily <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/morgan-ebel/\">Morgan Ebel</a></strong>, <strong>Rose Wille</strong> and <strong>Maleah Scott</strong>. I know you probably want to talk about them, too, but in the interests of brevity we’ll stick with the starters in our conversation because we need to talk about Hopkins and I don’t want to run out of time. Obviously, there are very few games that Hopkins goes into where we think that they might not win. This is one of those games. How do you feel about it in the big picture, about the opportunity, the game and what it means?\n\nA: In terms of the big picture, if you look at where we were five years ago, I would never have scheduled this game. As a whole, as a program and how we’ve evolved, this is a huge opportunity for our kids. I absolutely believe we can win. I will not be surprised if we win because I have confidence in my kids. I know their talent and ability. I know they have put together games before where maybe we weren’t supposed to win and we’ve done it. And I just know that they are gamers, they’re going to get up for the big games. Having Hopkins at home is an advantage for us, too. I think we’re going to have good fan support.\n\nI like the fact that right now we know we belong and that’s how we play and that’s how we act. This game for us is just another game. We’re not preparing any differently than we normally would, and I think they are going to rise to the challenge. That doesn’t mean that it’s not going to be tough. I mean, Hopkins is a phenomenal team. They have my utmost respect. It’s going to be fun to see how our team does now that we aren’t young anymore – he we compose ourselves, how we stay poised, how we play together as a team and not get rattled. That’s where you want to see your team grow. I have already seen that from our kids in the first three games. I think it’s great for Farmington basketball and it’s going to be a fun game. Our kids deserve this. They’re ready, and I think it’s going to be a fun challenge.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><em>Top photo: Farmington\'s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophie-hart/\">Sophie Hart</a> (middle) and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-kindseth/\">Paige Kindseth</a> (right) were interviewed by broadcaster Mike Peden following Saturday\'s win over Stillwater. (Photo courtesy of  TSB Television)</em></span>','The Friday night special: Farmington vs Hopkins','','publish','open','open','','the-friday-night-special-farmington-vs-hopkins','','','2019-12-05 11:15:24','2019-12-05 17:15:24','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121248',0,'post','',0),
	(121252,1,'2019-12-05 12:05:11','2019-12-05 18:05:11','As we enter the 2019/2020 high school basketball season in Kansas.  Prep Hoops will preview some of the Kansas City Area high schools.  These preview articles will give you details on key players, season expectations and more.\n\nIn this article, we preview the Olathe East Lady Hawks. The defending Sunflower Conference Champions who posted a 18-5 record a season ago.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Players to Watch</strong></span>\n\nMolly Kaemmer, Forward, Senior, (2020)\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121273\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"150\"]<img class=\"wp-image-121273 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Molley-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /> Photo Cred: LWJ[/caption]\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">The 6 foot senior is a returning all-league player from a year ago.  Molly averaged 11 pts &amp; 9rbs in her junior year and will look to add to her production in the 2019-20 season.  Kaemmer has great size and strength on the interior.  A great rebounder, with a soft touch around the basket.  Look for her to be a key contributor in her final year at OE.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\"> </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSavanna Perez, Guard, Senior, (2020)\n\nPerez is returning starter from last year’s conference championship team. A smooth, crafty guard with great shooting range. Handles well enough to get to her spots on the floor a for mid-range jump shot or to the basket. Perez has a good ball IQ and should be a leader for the Lady Hawks after playing a competitive summer with Precision Athletics.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nRae Richardson, Guard, Junior, (2021)\n\nRichardson, among the league leaders in assist a year ago in the Sunflower returns, more experienced in her junior season looking to be more effective for the Hawks.  A crafty pg with exceptional vision and court awareness.  Reads plays and defenders ahead of time which allows her to dish to open teammates.  Good perimeter shooter and can finish around the basket.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOlathe East has returning seniors such as Courtney Kearney &amp; Ally Biddison that will play a pivotal role for this year\'s team along with key players. Junior, Kaylee Taylor also should be able to step and contribute for OE as well.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Upcoming Games </span></strong>\n\nFriday December 6th, 2019 away at Olathe North. (5:30pm)','Team Preview: Olathe East Lady Hawks','','publish','open','open','','team-preview-olathe-east-lady-hawks','','','2019-12-05 12:05:11','2019-12-05 18:05:11','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121252',0,'post','',0),
	(121275,1,'2019-12-10 10:17:59','2019-12-10 16:17:59','<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Lauren Langley (2020)</strong></span>\n\n<strong>Lauren Langley</strong> is a 5\'11\" forward for Oscoda. <strong>Langley</strong> averaged 15.7 points and 10.6 rebounds per game last season. <strong>Langley</strong> is looking to increase her averages this season as she has already had a game high of 31 points against AuGres this year. <strong>Langley</strong> is a well-rounded athlete willing to take on new challenges and learn new skills. Recently, she has committed to join the University of Michigan Rowing team.\n\n<hr />\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/abi-tarrant/\">Abi Tarrant</a> (2021)</strong></span>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/abi-tarrant/\">Abi Tarrant</a></strong> is a 5\'9 guard for Bay City John Glenn. <strong>Tarrant </strong>is already scoring big this season with 25 points in a win over Swan Valley.\n\n<hr />\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Macey Fegan (2023)</strong></span>\n\n<strong>Macey Fegan</strong> is a 5\'10\" forward from Standish-Sterling. This young freshman has already made quite an impression. In her first varsity game, <strong>Fegan</strong> scored 22 points. I predict that she will be one of the top players in the state come 2023.\n\n<hr />\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Adelyn Moore (2023)</strong> </span>\n\n<strong>Adelyn Moore</strong> is a 5\'8\" guard from Caro. <strong>Moore</strong> is also a freshman who made an impression on her varsity debut by scoring 26 points in a win over Marlette. Stay tuned this season to watch her progress.\n\n<hr />\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Alexys Carlstrom (2020)</strong></span>\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"252\"]<img src=\"https://www.ogemawherald.com/uploads/original/20191206-212510-41-Macey.jpg\" alt=\"Image result for macey fegan basketball&quot;\" width=\"252\" height=\"379\" /> <span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><strong>Macey Fegan</strong> (#30) Photo Credit l Julie Elliot, Ogemaw County Herald</span>[/caption]\n\n<strong>Alexys Carlstrom</strong> is a 5\'6\" guard from Harrison. Carlstrom averages 16.7 points and 5.7 rebounds per game.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-laures/\">Lauren Laures</a> (2020)</span></strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-laures/\">Lauren Laures</a></strong> is a senior from Pinconning.  <strong>Laures</strong> averaged 15 points and 7.1 rebounds per game last year.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/macy-bisballe/\">Macy Bisballe</a> (2021)</span></strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/macy-bisballe/\">Macy Bisballe</a></strong> is a  5\'11\" forward from Houghton Lake.  Bisballe is considered a \"must-see\" player and has been named Division 3 All-State.\n\n<hr />\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Aydan Dalak (2022)</strong></span>\n\n<strong>Aydan Dalak</strong> is a 5\'7\" guard from Roscommon . <strong>Dalak</strong> averages 13.2 points and 2.8 assists per game. As <strong>Dalak</strong> continues to grow and develop, she should be at the top of your watchlist as well.\n\n<hr />\n\n<span style=\"color: #000000\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Jordan Phillips (2020)</span></strong></span>\n\n<strong> Jordan Phillips</strong> is a 5\'8\" guard from Midland. Phillips averaged 15.3 points per game last season. <strong>Phillips</strong> is already starting the season out strong by being one of the area\'s top scorers.\n\n&nbsp;','Chelsea Sturm\'s Start of Season Watchlist: Northeast Michigan','','publish','open','open','','chelsea-sturms-start-of-season-watchlist-northeast-michigan','','','2019-12-10 10:17:59','2019-12-10 16:17:59','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121275',0,'post','',0),
	(121286,1,'2019-12-05 12:57:33','2019-12-05 18:57:33','In the midst of high school season, there is still a lot of recruiting news swirling around the state. In the most recent news, three girls that are being targeted by Pacific Northwest schools are moving along with the recruitment process. We also have one commitment that has recently taken place.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><strong>Two NW schools checking in on a top 2021:</strong></span>\n\n<strong>Haley Huard</strong> attracted a good amount of college attention after this Spring and Summer and multiple schools have made her a priority this Winter as well. The University of Idaho is targeting the 6\'1 junior and will be in to watch her play for Eastlake this Friday. Idaho recruits the state of Washington very well and it has helped them turn Idaho into one of the top programs in the Big Sky. Idaho has already picked up a commitment from Huard\'s teammate from this summer, 2021 <strong>Ashlyn Wallace</strong>. Huard attended Idaho\'s junior day in the Fall along with Wallace and MJ Bruno of Central Valley High School (More on her below). Washington State University will also be watching Huard this Friday. Both of Haley\'s parents were standouts at the University of Washington with Brock Huard in football and Molly (Hills) Huard in basketball.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><strong>Pac-12 visits top 2022:</strong></span>\n\nAs I previously reported, Oregon State University went and saw <strong>Drea Brumfield</strong> at WF West High School yesterday. Just the night before, a staff member was present for <strong>Talia von Oelhoffen</strong>\'s game at Chiawana High School. Oregon State does a solid job of recruiting some of the better players the PNW has to offer. Drea has multiple Pac-12 schools in touch with her.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\"><strong>Portland Picks up 2021 Commitment:</strong></span>\n\nCentral Valley High School\'s MJ Bruno had a strong summer with the Spokane Stars and had the interest of multiple schools before deciding Portland was where she would like to play her college ball. Bruno is an energy giver and really competes at a high level. She is the third player from the GSL to commit to Portland, following 2020\'s <strong>Tyler</strong> and <strong>Jacksen McCliment-Call </strong>at University High School. *MJ Bruno third from left in featured image','Quick Recruiting Update','','publish','open','open','','quick-recruiting-update','','','2019-12-05 12:57:33','2019-12-05 18:57:33','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121286',0,'post','',0),
	(121303,1,'2019-12-06 08:00:00','2019-12-06 14:00:00','As we enter the 2019/2020 high school basketball season in Kansas.  Prep Hoops will preview some of the Kansas area high schools. These preview articles will give you details on key players, season expectations and more.\n\nIn this article, we preview the <strong>Lawrence </strong><strong>Lady Lions </strong>who are led by sixth-year <strong>Head Coach Jeff Dickson</strong>. Coach Dickson and his squad are coming off an overall record of 12-10 and 6-6 record in the Sunflower League last season. The <strong>Lady Lions</strong> suffered some major losses due to 4 out of the 5 starters graduating. Most of last season Coach Dickson\'s starting lineup consisted of Seniors which is a luxury to have that kind of experience leading your team. Do not count the <strong>Lawrence Lady Lions </strong>out because they are young on paper. The<strong> Lady Lions </strong>program is looking to improve on last year\'s record this season.\n\nThe <strong>Lady Lions </strong>have a lot of pride and their expectations for every season is to be one of the top teams in the Sunflower League and in the State of Kansas. Coach Dickson and his Lady Lions will be tested early this season with their young lineup that will be on display. Let\'s take a look at some key players for the <strong>Lady Lions </strong>this season that will be contributing to the <strong>Lawrence High Lady Lions</strong> as they look to take the necessary steps to get on that road to State.\n\n<strong>Lady Lions Seniors: </strong>These four <strong>Lady Lions</strong> will need to be leaders and big contributors for <strong>Lawrence High</strong> this season in order for them to get that elusive road to State.\n\n<strong>Ella Stewart,  5\'9\" Wing </strong>is earning some interest from some colleges, look for her to be a major contributor this upcoming season.\n\n<strong>Paiden Bell, 5\'9\" Wing </strong>who has also earned some interest from some colleges, will also be a major contributor this season.\n\n<strong>Sophie DeWitt, 5\'3\" Guard </strong>who has some Varsity experience will help anchor her team on the defensive end of the floor for the <strong>Lady Lions.</strong>\n\n<strong>Lexi Dutcher, 5\'3\" Guard</strong> will contribute on the defensive end of the floor at the guard position where it looks like <strong>Lawrence </strong>will be loaded at the guard position with talent.\n\n<strong>Lady Lions Key Contributors, Youngsters and Freshmen to Watch:</strong>\n\n<strong>Ozi Ajekwu, 6\'2\" Forward, Class of 2021 </strong><strong>#63 </strong>in the<strong> </strong><strong>Kansas Prep Girls Hoops Rankings </strong>could be one of the best forwards in the state. <strong>Ozi </strong>Sunflower League Honorable Mention last season, look for her to boost her stock and climb up in the rankings this season.\n\n<strong>Kayla Galbreath, 6\' Center/Forward, Class of 2021 </strong>will be earning some solid minutes for the <strong>Lady Lions </strong>this season. <strong>Kayla </strong>has some nice size and she uses it to control the boards on both ends of the floor.\n\n<strong>Layla Harjo, 5\'5\" Guard, Class of 2022 </strong>has a little bit of Varsity experience, she will be a big contributor this season at the guard position. <strong>Layla</strong> is a shooter, if she gets going early it could be a long night for opposing defenses trying to stop her. Look for <strong>Layla</strong> to bust into<strong> the Kansas Prep Girls Hoops Rankings</strong> and earn some interest from some colleges this season.\n\n<strong>Amaya Marshall, 5\'6\" SG, Class of 2023 #13 </strong>in the <strong>Kansas Prep Girls Hoops Rankings</strong> will come right in and fit into the <strong>Lawrence Lady Lions </strong>style of play. <strong>Amaya </strong>has a high basketball IQ, she\'s scrappy on defense and if her team needs her to run the point she can slide over and do so. <strong>Amaya Marshall </strong>has a well-rounded game, look for to help lead her team this season.\n\n<strong>Serenity Keo, 5\'4\" Guard, Class of 2023 </strong>will be earning some quality minutes this season and looking to make her way onto the <strong>Kansas Prep Girls Hoops Rankings.</strong> <strong>Serenity </strong>is another 2023 that has some high basketball IQ and she\'ll use that to her advantage by playing her role.\n\n<strong>Hailey Ramirez, 5\'5\" Guard, Class of 2023 </strong>will also be earning some quality minutes this season and looking to make her way onto the <strong>Kansas Prep Girls Hoops Rankings. Hailey\'s </strong>high basketball IQ is right there with her Freshman teammates who will be getting quality Varsity minutes.\n\nIt will be an interesting season for the <strong>Lady Lions</strong> and <strong>Coach Jeff Dickson </strong>as they figure out their roles as they hunt for that elusive road to the Girls 6A Kansas State Championships.\n\nUpcoming games: 12/06/2019 @Topeka High 7:30 pm\n\n12/10/2019 @Blue Valley Northwest 7:00 pm\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Team Preview: Lawrence Lady Lions','','publish','open','open','','team-preview-lawrence-lady-lions','','','2019-12-06 08:00:00','2019-12-06 14:00:00','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121303',0,'post','',0),
	(121317,1,'2019-12-05 13:26:43','2019-12-05 19:26:43','<b>#1 Valley Vista 3-0</b>\n\nValley Vista remains the top ranked team in 6A. In their first 3 games they have looked absolutely dominant. Their overall team defense, size, and athleticism looks like it is going to be a major problem for opposing teams. Marisa Davis-Jones is playing at another level this season and Jennah Isai looks healthy and more aggressive than ever.\n\nLiberty 81-12 W\n\nRed Mountain 67-20 W\n\nMater Dei 66-57 W\n\n<b>#2 Perry 2-0</b>\n\nPerry is right on Valley Vista’s heels, coming in at a very close #2 spot! Thus far, the team has looked very nice and has won by 20+ points in each of their games so far. The duo of Clayburne and Conner is looking strong, as expected. The overall team depth is what really sells me on this team!\n\nWestview 84-36 W\n\nChaparral 63-38 W\n\n<b>#3 Hamilton 3-0</b>\n\nAnother deep team is Hamilton! Thus far, Hamilton has had 3 strong showings against some talented teams, like Mountain Pointe. They just have to keep it up and keep doing what they are doing to see their power ranking go up!\n\nTolleson 89-33 W\n\nQueen Creek 54-27 W\n\nMountain Pointe 46-27 W\n\n<b>#4 Chandler 5-1</b>\n\nChandler has already faced a ton of good teams and shown that they can beat them. Their only lose this far, came against Sabino. They have beaten teams like Chaparral, Pinnacle, and stayed very competitive with Sabino. This Chandler team could make some serious noise this season!\n\nBoulder Creek 54-41 W\n\nChaparral 69-58 W\n\nPueblo 73-26 W\n\nPinnacle 67-58 W\n\nSabino L\n\nBoulder Creek 61-37 W\n\n<b>#5 Pinnacle 4-2</b>\n\nWhile Pinnacle has 2 losses so far into the season, they came against two very good teams in Sabino and Chandler. Looking at the rest of their team schedule, I don’t expect them to lose very many games going forward. I think this team will really pick it up and show they’re a force to be reckoned with in 6A.\n\nSabino 52-46 L\n\nDesert Ride 59-27 W\n\nGilbert 77-37 W\n\nSkyline 78-43 W\n\nChandler 67-58 L\n\nHorizon 58-34 W','Power Rankings: 6A','','publish','open','open','','power-rankings-6a','','','2019-12-05 13:26:43','2019-12-05 19:26:43','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121317',0,'post','',0),
	(121354,1,'2019-12-05 15:16:36','2019-12-05 21:16:36','This game was out of hand from the tip. Lewisville Farmers ran away with the win against Faith Family Academy Eagles. It quickly became a display for both teams\' best prospects. Lewisville’s size and athleticism opened a hole that not a single soul could close. But cream rises to the top in any situation and that’s exactly what the young ladies listed below did.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121359\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"150\"]<img class=\"wp-image-121359 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Dz3Dhn6WkAUsSAl-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /> via LHS Girls Basketball Twitter[/caption]\n\nLaila Lawrence, the most capable of any player on the court had a relatively quiet game. The 5-11 forward combined her physical tools and defensive discipline to produce solid plays. On the offensive end, she flexed her footwork abusing defenders with drop steps and a nifty up and under. Lawrence even showed off a passing acumen throwing a few skip passes that hit teammates right in their hands.\n\nDeucee Reed applied defensive pressure to the eagles every minute she was on the floor. The sophomore finished the game with 5 steals, three from reading passing lanes and 2 from picking her matchup’s pocket. She finished through contact and displayed calm leadership.\n\nJessica Clemons is a Swiss Army knife with enough size to guard 4 positions. Clemons length and motor allow her to patrol the court like a free safety being in just the right place when needed. She had a trio of steals to tack on to the Farmers\' strong defensive performance.\n\nHaley Allen is a ball of energy on the floor. As a combo guard, she can live behind the arc knocking down open three or create opportunities for teammates. Following the trend of long athletic players has the frame and quickness to be a solid defender.\n\nSydney Savage is a long athlete that plays with a lot of hustle. She finished well around the rim absorbing contact. She showed some leadership skills when breaking up an altercation.\n\nAlivia Wilson stands out on the court thanks to her size. Hovering around six feet tall Wilson is strong and physical. She uses those traits to make an impact on defense and offense. Still a bit raw but she shows fundamentals when scoring around the rim.\n\n<img class=\"alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-121358\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1154-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Nyah Morgan of Faith Family is the walking definition of upside. The freshman is listed at 5-7 with a slight build she’s moves well on the defensive end of the court. Morgan provides help-side rim protection and contained quick guards. The post also showed some shooting potential hitting a short corner jumper from about 18 feet.','Lewisville VS. Faith Family Academy Standouts','','publish','open','open','','lewisville-vs-faith-family-academy-standouts','','','2019-12-05 15:16:36','2019-12-05 21:16:36','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121354',0,'post','',0),
	(121405,1,'2019-12-06 14:11:30','2019-12-06 20:11:30','The top game on a light Thursday slate was the matchup between two top 10 programs in 4A as you had Center Point-Urbana traveling to take on Waverly-Shell Rock. It was a slow start to the game as the halftime score was 22-14 in favor of the hosts. Center Point-Urbana\'s press really hurt Waverly-Shell Rock early in the third as they used it and created points off turnovers. They went on an 11-1 run to open the period to take the lead before Waverly-Shell Rock took back over.\n\nCenter Point-Urbana kept crawling back in the game, however, and after a corner three from senior Adrianna Katcher, the game was tied at 34-all with under five minutes to play. It would stay that way as the teams traded turnovers until senior Britney Young converted a 3-point play with 3:28 to play. A corner 3-pointer the following trip down the floor by senior Peyton Kriegel would tie it back up with 3:12 left in the game. After a Waverly-Shell Rock free throw, Katcher would put the away team in front on a basket and would add a free throw with 1:20 left to give Center Point-Urbana the 40-38 lead. That would be the final point of the game as Center Point-Urbana held Waverly-Shell Rock to no points in the final 2 minutes of the game. You can view the 10 Best from the game below.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong>MVP: Adrianna Katcher (Center Point-Urbana)</strong>\nKatcher struggled shooting the ball in the game but she made shots when it counted as she hit the shot to put her team on top and then a free throw to  put her team up by two. Katcher shot just 25% from the floor and ended the game with 11 points. She was instrumental on the defensive end, however, and was able to keep her man at bay. A really solid all-around game for her even when she wasn\'t at her best.\n\n<strong>Best Offensive Player: Abbie Draper (Waverly-Shell Rock)</strong>\nDraper was 6-for-10 from the floor in the game and really spurred her team as she was looking to score on every touch. She finished the game with 15 points and eight rebounds but also added in two assists. She did foul out late in the game but overall she was the best offensive player in the game. She was just 3-of-8 from the free-throw line in the game but her ability to score at the rim kept Waverly-Shell Rock in the game.\n\n<strong>Best Defensive Player: Ryley Goebel (Center Point-Urbana)</strong>\nFrom the start of her freshman year, Goebel\'s calling card has been her defense. Now in her sophomore year, that defensive aggression has carried over and she continues to be a thorn in the side of opposing teams. Goebel had three steals in the game, which is on the low end for her. She also had four blocks in the game at the rim. Goebel added in nine rebounds as well to cement herself defensively.\n\n<strong>Best Passer: Camryn Grawe (Waverly-Shell Rock)</strong>\nGrawe was excellent at finding open teammates as she dished off five assists. She has a very high basketball IQ and has the ability to pass her teammates open. I thought that she was a key piece for Waverly-Shell Rock with her ability to pass and control the ball. She\'s going to be a paramount piece for them this year.\n\n<strong>Best Shooter: Britney Young (Waverly-Shell Rock)</strong>\nYoung knocked down 3-of-5 from behind the arc and all of them came at huge times in the game. She finished with 12 points in the game but her shooting ability really stood out. Young has a smooth looking jumper from the arc and it was working for her this evening. A big game from her at home.\n\n<strong>Best Intangibles: Bryn Hadsall (Center Point-Urbana)</strong>\nHadsall\'s stat line would strike you as her having a bad game as she went 0-of-3 from the floor and added in 3 rebounds. But she did exactly what her team needed from the point guard spot. She plays the game hard, gets herself in good spots on the floor, and is a leader out on the court. She\'s a really solid point guard who doesn\'t make a ton of mistakes.\n\n<strong>Best Non-Starter: Trinidee Moore (Waverly-Shell Rock)</strong>\nMoore came off the bench and immediately made an impact. She scored four points off the bench but also played solid defense and facilitated the ball well. Moore is someone you can rely on with the ball in her hands as she makes good decisions with it. I really liked how poised she was under pressure as Center Point-Urbana threw a press at her.\n\n<strong>Best Underclassman: Laine Hadsall (Center Point-Urbana)</strong>\nHadsall was impressive because of her aggressiveness off of the bench she looked to score the ball when she got it and knocked down a 3-pointer. She is a solid shooter off the catch and as she continues to get more comfortable with the high school game she should be able to take off. Hadsall was very impressive as she was definitely understanding of her role and what she was supposed to do on the floor.\n\n<strong>Best Under-The-Radar Performance: Peyton Kriegel (Center Point-Urbana)</strong>\nKriegel hit a big 3-pointer to tie the game up for Center Point-Urbana late in the game and that was the only shot that she hit. She proved to be the ultimate competitor in the game as she was continually getting to the loose balls and getting the offense going. She had two assists and two steals in the game as well and played a bigger role in the win than most would think.\n\n<strong>Best Intriguing Prospect Not Mentioned: Emma DeSmet (Center Point-Urbana)</strong>\nDeSmet is a 5\'11 wing who didn\'t play a ton but is a prospect because of her size and length. She has a lot of mobility and her length forces opponents to change their shot. DeSmet was active on the floor and was able to lock her man down on the defensive end. It will be fun to see how she grows this season.','10 Best: Center Point-Urbana vs. Waverly-Shell Rock','','publish','open','open','','10-best-center-point-urbana-vs-waverly-shell-rock','','','2019-12-06 14:11:30','2019-12-06 20:11:30','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121405',0,'post','',0),
	(121415,1,'2019-12-06 21:25:38','2019-12-07 03:25:38','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">59-50 was the final score in Thursday night\'s battle between The Patriot Pioneers and the Brooke Point Black Hawks. Patriot came out swinging, dominating on defense forcing 10 turnovers in the first half. Sophomore <strong>Elena Bertand</strong> of Patriot was the hot hand in the first half grabbing two steals and had a nice and-one play early in the first quarter. Patriot was able to take advantage of bad ball control all night by Brooke Point and was very successful running half court press in the first half. Although it was only a six point margin by halftime, Patriot left major points on the board after goin 2-8 from the free throw line in the last 40 seconds. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Third quarter action was in Brooke Point\'s favor as senior<strong> Guard #32 </strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/zamaria-hutchinson/\"><strong>Zamaria Hutchinson</strong></a> and sophomore <strong>Forward #22 Jaylyn Pressley</strong> started taking over. The two fed off each others energy and Jaylyn found herself at the free throw line a lot throughout the second half after multiple put back attempts. The Black Hawks would cut the game back down to one by the end of the third quarter but it didn\'t take long for the Pioneers to regain momentum. Patriot got off to a 10 point lead early in the fourth quarter after <strong>Elena Bertand</strong> knocked down a big 3 pointer. The final 3 minutes was an up and down defensive battle, with the lead consistently fluctuating between 6 and 10 points . Brooke Point looked as if they were going to close the deficit after multiple defensive rebounds off missed shots late in the third, but similar to Patriot\'s performance in the first half, Brooke Point would too go 2-8 from the line in the last few minutes of play. Pioneers would go on to serve Brooke Point its first lost of the season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">On to The Best......</span>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121441\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"137\"]<img class=\"wp-image-121441\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Elena-Bertrand-209x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"137\" height=\"196\" /> <span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\"><em>Elena Bertrand, Patriot </em></span>[/caption]\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\">MVP: </span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\">Elena Bertand (Patriot) 2022</span></strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Elena Bertand played at a high level both sides of the floor last night. Patriot had a 17-8 lead at the end of the first quarter and that was largely due to Elena\'s defense and assist off turnovers. By the fourth quarter, Elena seemed to hit a second wind and once again take control, coming up with 2 steals and hitting a big 3 pointer early in the fourth. Elena finished the game with 13 points, 3 assist, and 4 steals. The sophomore player has owned her role on this team and will be the catalyst to their success going forward.</span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\">Best Offensive Performance: Lauren Moore (Patriot) 2021 </span></strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Lauren Moore quietly dropped 18 points and had 12 rebounds, five rebounds being offensive in which she scored 6 points off of. She also went 1 for 2 from the three point line, cashing in a baseline jumper to put her team up by 10 in the fourth quarter. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>Best Defensive Performance: Elena Bertand (Patriot) 2022</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Elena Bertand and junior <strong>Guard Caitlin Blackman</strong> led the Black Hawks in steals with four each, but it is Elena\'s three assist that make me give her this award. Elena had some big steals that led directly to fast breaks to help sustain the lead against Brooke Point.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>Best Play: Zamaria Hutchinson (Brooke Point) 2020</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Late in the fourth quarter, Brooke Point cut the lead down to six points thanks to two great plays by Zamaria Hutchinson. Hutchinson dove for a loose ball, forcing a turnover. She then received the following inbound pass, driving to the lane for a lay-up, forcing the foul on the play. And 1!!</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>Best intangibles: Jaylyn Pressley (Brooke Point) 2022</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Pressley was dominate in the paint and there\'s no denying her knack for getting to the ball. At 6\'0, the forward knows when to turn around and take the shot, when to kick it out, and when and how to draw the foul. Pressley has big play ability and with that, drew the foul on the majority of her shots. The sophomore did miss a number of free throws during the game but this is something we expect her to improve on as the season continues.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>Best Under the Radar Performance: Zamaria Hutchinson (Brooke Point) 2020</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Zamaria was the life line for the Black Hawks offense tonight. Turnovers ultimately led to their lost but Zamaria came up with multiple big drives to the basket to keep it a tooth and nail match. Brooke Point never took full control of this game, but when surges were needed, specifically at the end of the 2nd quarter, Zamaria was the driving force. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>Best Stock Riser: Caitlin Blackman (Patriot) 2021</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Caitlin took a number of shots this game but they were all calculated. Caitlin is very good at coming off the screen, looking for the best shot or pass possible. She is not afraid to pull the trigger and her teammates encourage her. Caitlin had 17 points in this one and shared the wealth on defense, racking up 4 steals. She\'s doing what she does year end and year out, but her stat sheet could be even fatter this year. </span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\">Best Underclassman: Elena Bertrand (Patriot) 2022</span></strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">The sophomore dropped 13 points Thursday and 19 in Wednesday\'s season opener. Elena looks like she\'s already ready to take on a leadership role for these Pioneers. These last two performances were very impressive and it looks like Elena is picking up right where she left off last season. Elena averaged 13 ppg, 3 rebounds per game, and 2.7 steals per game her freshman year with Patriot.</span>\n\n&nbsp;','Takeaways From Patriot vs. Brooke Point Early Season Battle','','publish','open','open','','takeaways-from-patriot-vs-brooke-point-early-season-battle','','','2019-12-06 21:25:38','2019-12-07 03:25:38','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121415',0,'post','',0);
