	(121429,1,'2019-12-06 10:20:21','2019-12-06 16:20:21','<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Game Summary</strong></p>\nCAL and Butler are both very talented offensively but in this matchup defense was the main focus. Both teams were struggling to score the ball throughout the game but defense is what kept the game close. After 1 Quarter, Butler led CAL, 21-12. With 1:27 to go in the first half, CAL cut the lead to 5, which led to a Butler timeout. At halftime, Butler led CAL, 31-26. Not much scoring in the first half due to stellar defense from both ball clubs. In the 3rd Quarter, defense really picked up as both teams could not buy a basket. Heading into the 4th Quarter, 40-34 Butler. In the 4th, CAL switched up their defensive scheme and ran a high 2-3 zone, which gave Butler big problems. CAL went on to win the game despite Butler leading pretty much the entire game. <em>Final: CAL 52, Butler 46.</em>\n\n<strong>Defense Defense Defense </strong>\n\nThis game was a lot about defense for these teams. Butler started off with great defense in the first half with great size down-low with Junior Tiarra East &amp; Sophomore Tamesha Dozier. They kept constant pressure in the 1st Quarter and recorded multiple steals throughout the Quarter. For the rest of the game, they lost track of their identity on defense. CAL really came out of halftime with a goal and that was to confuse the Butler offense and run a zone. In the 3rd Quarter they went with a 2-3 Zone on defense and that had Butler putting up difficult shots. In the 4th Quarter, CAL still ran a 2-3 Zone but a high 2-3. This caused a lot of turnovers for Butler and the main reason why CAL went on a run and had won this Thursday night matchup.\n\n<strong>Jaya McClure (CAL):</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-121434\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/mcclure-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nSophomore point guard Jaya McClure led all scorers with 16 points. She hit four big time free throws down the stretch to seal the game for CAL. Her game is nice but needs work. She had 7 turnovers, including multiple \"carry\" calls. She needs to limit those turnovers as she is the one running the show for CAL. The point guard can also shoot the ball really well. She made two 3-pointers and made some nice mid-range jumpers. She is very shifty with her movement on the court. She also has excellent dribbling skills. Even though she is only a sophomore, I could sense she is going to be the leader for this team going forward.\n\n<strong>Shelby Calhoun (CAL):</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-121571\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/shelbycal-1-300x197.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\n<em>Virginia Tech commit</em> Shelby Calhoun did not have her best night shooting the ball but she still managed to record a double-double. She ended the game with 10 points and 10 rebounds. Calhoun is very patient with the ball. She makes sure that she is going to make the right decision while dribbling and scanning the defense. She can finish at the rim with ease because of her great size and length. Her defense was also something worth noting, as she recorded 2 blocked shots and 4 steals. Shelby Calhoun is looking to have a great Senior year for CAL.\n\n<strong>Tiarra East (Butler):</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-121564\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/tiarraeast-300x197.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nJunior Tiarra East is a big body that can really handle the ball and finish at the rim. She loves to attack the paint as most of her points came inside. East ended with 14 points and 9 rebounds. She recorded 6 turnovers throughout the game, so that is going to have to change in order for this Butler team to become successful because the ball is in her hands quite a bit. This Butler team is mainly made up of talented Juniors. They only have 2 Seniors and they did not contribute as much as the Juniors did. Tiarra East is the glue for this team. There are going to have to be times where Butler just needs to give her the ball and let her go to work. She\'s going to have a massive year.\n\n<strong>Dynastee White (Butler):</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-121583\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/dynwhite-300x197.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nJunior point guard Dynastee White is the floor general for this Butler team. She can score the ball in many ways but she likes to attack by penetrating through the defense and scoring under the basket. She ended the game with 10 points with 6 of those points coming from the free throw line. She is going to have to be the leader and vocal point on the offense for Butler this season. She can get her points but she also has to get her teammates involved. Tiarra East, Tamesha Dozier, <span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Khiara</span> Shelburne, and Leslie Baxter are probably going to do most of the scoring for this ball club, but in order for that to happen Dynastee White has to take control and feed them the rock.\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Recap:</strong></p>\nThis was a great matchup. Fairly even teams that showed great defensive strides. I am sure in other games this season both teams will score the ball easier than they did Thursday night. Butler had this game under control until about the 2 minute mark in the 4th Quarter. They had some costly turnovers and got lazy on the defensive end. Sophomore Jaya McClure stepped up and had 9 points in the last 2 minutes, including 4 free throws that sealed the game for CAL. Impressive showing from both squads, but CAL walks away with the victory making them, 2-0. CAL will be traveling to Memphis, TN Friday night to face Whitehaven High School. This was Butler\'s first game of the year, making them 0-1. They will travel to Lexington, KY this Saturday for the <em>Henry Clay: Top Prospect Classic</em> as they take on Conner High School. I will be in attendance and covering this <em>Classic</em>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Five Takeaways: CAL 52, Butler 46','','publish','open','open','','five-takeaways-cal-52-butler-46','','','2019-12-06 10:20:21','2019-12-06 16:20:21','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121429',0,'post','',0),
	(121437,1,'2019-12-05 21:51:39','2019-12-06 03:51:39','<b>#1 Millennium 1-0</b>\n\nMillennium comes in at #1 in our preseason rankings and in our first official power rankings of the season. They just had a monster win against Notre Dame Prep! Expect this team to be at the #1 spot for a while!\n\nNotre Dame Prep 86-11 W\n\n<b>#2 Casteel 2-0</b>\n\nCasteel started off at the #2 spot in the preseason rankings and are undefeated this far into the season. I think it’ll be very hard for teams to top the #1 and #2 teams in 5A.\n\nCienega 62-29 W\n\nCentennial 46-34 W\n\n<b>#3 Cactus Shadows 5-1</b>\n\nCactus Shadows has been playing very well and they’ve beaten some solid teams. The only team they have lost to is Shadow Mountain, one of the top teams in state. Cactus Shadows and Williams Field play tonight so we’ll see what happens!\n\nWestview 53-28 W\n\nShadow Mountain 60-41 L\n\nNorth 40-35 W\n\nWestwood 73-56 W\n\nSunrise Mountain 52-42 W\n\nSierra Linda 55-15 W\n\n<b>#4 Williams Field 3-1</b>\n\nWilliams Field comes in at #4. I was very torn between Cactus Shadows and Williams Field for the #3 and #4 spot. Coincidentally, these teams play tonight so next weeks rankings could shake up a bit!\n\nCorona Del Sol 59-24 W\n\nMountain View 58-55 W\n\nMesa 54-53 W\n\nWillow Canyon 60-57 L\n\n<b>#5 Sunrise Mountain 3-2</b>\n\nSunrise Mountain has been very impressive this season. They have looked a lot better than I expected. Furthermore, they played Shadow Mountain very close! If they had beaten Cactus Shadows, they would likely be in the #3 spot. However, unfortunately for them, they lost to Cactus Shadows in a close game.\n\nArcadia 64-23 W\n\nAgua Fria 63-20 W\n\nShadow Mountain 59-42 L\n\nCactus Shadows 52-42 L\n\nLiberty 53-16 W','Power Rankings: 5A','','publish','open','open','','power-rankings-5a','','','2019-12-05 21:51:39','2019-12-06 03:51:39','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121437',0,'post','',0),
	(121469,1,'2019-12-09 22:41:32','2019-12-10 04:41:32','The latest refresh of class rankings started reaching public eyes Friday, December 6, beginning with the class of 2020.  The six players listed below rocketed up the ranks since that August refresh after information about their play over the summer continued flow in.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ashton-verhulst/\">Ashton Verhulst</a>, 6\'2\", F, Bishop Miege, Next Level Eclipse</strong> - Verhust advanced 21 places to #7 and has committed to University of Central Florida.  Last season she was selected to the Sports In Kansas 4A all-state tournament team following Miege\'s state championship.  She was a Kansas Basketball Coaches Association (KBCA) class 4A honorable mention and Eastern Kansas League first team selection as well. With a solid game on both ends of the floor Verhulst can play inside, step out for a three, run the floor well, and use her length to her advantage to alter shots. She averaged 11.5 points and 4.9 rebounds a contest.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_73293\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"243\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-73293\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Taylor-Jameson-Ohlde-Elite-2020-Pink-Wichita-Heights-watched-by-WSE-Chaos-2020-Kadyn-Cobb-Salina-Central-243x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"243\" height=\"300\" /> Wheat State Elite - Chaos\' 2020 guard Kadyn Cobb (Salina Central) watches Ohlde Elite 2020 Pink\'s point 2020 guard Taylor Jameson during their Reign the Plains game at Wichita Sports Forum.[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/taylor-jameson/\">Taylor Jameson</a></strong><strong>, 5\'5\", G, Wichita Heights, Ohlde Elite</strong> - Jameson advanced 15 spots to #8 and has committed to George Mason University. <span data-sheets-value=\"{&quot;1&quot;:2,&quot;2&quot;:&quot;Second team all-City League. 30\' three point range. Jump shooter who gets shots off quickly. Very quick first step with a strong crossover to dribble drive. Quick hand speed for steals. Fast with the ball in transition. Able to hit pull-up 8\'-10\' jumper in transition. Able to finish athletically around the basket from either side. Reign the Plains (July 2019) - Excellent speed, quickness, and talent to defend opposing PGs 1-on-1 full court. Constant threat to steal. Showed three point range with the ability to penetrate. Two game averages of 6 ppg (1/3 from three), 2 rpg, 1 apg, 1 spg. World Exposure Report: \\&quot;She can rebound well for her position, loves to play uptempo, good court vision, super quick. Players have a hard time defending her. Range to the Arc.  Extremely coachable.\\&quot;&quot;}\" data-sheets-userformat=\"{&quot;2&quot;:12801,&quot;3&quot;:{&quot;1&quot;:0},&quot;12&quot;:0,&quot;15&quot;:&quot;Verdana&quot;,&quot;16&quot;:10}\">She was also a Greater Wichita League second team selection.  Jameson\'s stock grew substantially in the past year.  She has 30\' three point range, can get shots off quickly, and has jump shooting ability. On both ends of the floor she has elite quickness.  She uses it, along with a strong crossover dribble, to beat people off the bounce.  Along with her great hand speed she uses it get her share of steals. She is also one of the few players who can keep elite point guards in front of them 1-on-1.  James is fast with the ball in transition and is able to athletically finish on either side of the basket or quickly pull up for a 8\'-10\' jumper.\n</span>\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/camille-evans/\">Camille Evans</a></strong><strong>, 5\'7\", PG, Schlagle, Next Level Eclipse</strong> - Evans advanced 18 spots to #15 and has committed to Missouri Western State University.  Evans was a <span data-sheets-value=\"{&quot;1&quot;:2,&quot;2&quot;:&quot;Topeka Capital Journal 5A third team all-state. Three-point threat and is athletic around the basket off the drive. Described by her high school coach as having high basketball I.Q., great speed and bounce, and runs the show. 9.7 apg, 8.7 ppg, 7.7 rpg, 5.5 spg.&quot;}\" data-sheets-userformat=\"{&quot;2&quot;:4609,&quot;3&quot;:{&quot;1&quot;:0},&quot;12&quot;:0,&quot;15&quot;:&quot;Verdana&quot;}\">Topeka Capital Journal 5A third team all-state and a Kansas City-Atchison League first team selection. A three point threat who is athletic around the basket off the drive, Evans has terrific handles including a strong change of pace. She has been described by her high school coach as having high basketball I.Q. and strong ability to run the show.  Given that she qualified for the 5A state track meet for the 100m (15th), 200m (7th), and 4x200m relay, Evans has great transition speed with or without the ball.  This past season she averaged 9.7 assists, 8.7 points, 7.7 rebounds, and 5.5 steals per game.\n</span>\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lakyn-schiefereke/\">Lakyn Schiefereke</a></strong><strong>, 5\'8\", G, McPherson, Wheat State Elite</strong> - Schiefereke advanced 19 spots to #47 and has committed to Washburn University. This past season she was a Topeka Capital Journal third team 5A all-state and A<span data-sheets-value=\"{&quot;1&quot;:2,&quot;2&quot;:&quot;First team Ark Valley Chisholm Trail League Div III. Topeka Capital Journal third team 5A all state. Fast in transition with the ball, can run the point, and is a three point threat. Is aggressive on defensive end and is a steady defender and defensive rebounder. Court vision needs improvement, cross court and swing passes are the primary ways she turns the ball over. Torn ACL in May, not expected back until Jan. 1.&quot;}\" data-sheets-userformat=\"{&quot;2&quot;:12801,&quot;3&quot;:{&quot;1&quot;:0},&quot;12&quot;:0,&quot;15&quot;:&quot;Verdana&quot;,&quot;16&quot;:10}\">rk Valley Chisholm Trail League Div III second team selection.  Schiefereke is fast in transition with the ball, can run the point, and is a three point threat. Reliable and aggressive on the defensive end she also is a strong rebounder.  After suffering an ACL tear in May, Schiefereke is expected to return to the floor during the second half of the season.\n</span>\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madelyn-hutley/\">Madelyn Hutley</a></strong><strong>, 5\'5\", G, Wabaunsee</strong> - Hutley advanced 30 positions to #49 and has also committed to Washburn University.  This past season Hutley was selected as <span data-sheets-value=\"{&quot;1&quot;:2,&quot;2&quot;:&quot;KBCA 2A second team all-state. Sports In Kansas 2A state tournament team. Averaged 13.9 points per game.&quot;}\" data-sheets-userformat=\"{&quot;2&quot;:4609,&quot;3&quot;:{&quot;1&quot;:0},&quot;12&quot;:0,&quot;15&quot;:&quot;Verdana&quot;}\">KBCA 2A second team all-state, Sports In Kansas 2A all-state tournament team, and first team Mid-East League. Last season she averaged 13.9 points on a team that finished third at the state basketball tournament.\n</span>\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/khylee-massey/\">Khylee Massey</a></strong><strong>, 6\'0\", PF, Northern Heights, Wheat State Elite</strong> - Massey advanced 14 positions to #58 and has committed to Johnson County Community College.  Selected first team all-<span data-sheets-value=\"{&quot;1&quot;:2,&quot;2&quot;:&quot;Flint Hills League first team all league for third year. Honorable mention all-state for second year. Averaged 16 ppg (51.5% fgp), 7.2 rpg, 2.2 spg, 2.1 apg. Reign the Plains (July 2019) - Battles for position on both ends of the floor. Goes up strong inside and can finish with contact. Good ball skills, spun inside to get away from defender. Three game averages of 3.6 ppg, 2 rpg.&quot;}\" data-sheets-userformat=\"{&quot;2&quot;:4609,&quot;3&quot;:{&quot;1&quot;:0},&quot;12&quot;:0,&quot;15&quot;:&quot;Verdana&quot;}\">Flint Hills League for the past three years, Massey also was a KBCA 2A honorable mention all-state selection for the second year.  This past season she averaged 16 points (51.5% FG%), 7.2 rebounds, 2.2 steals, and 2.1 assists.  At July\'s Reign the Plains event in Wichita she showed that she goes up strong inside and can finish with contact.  She also has good ball skills to help create space inside.\n</span>\n\n<em>Featured image: Ulysses\' <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madison-haney/\">Madison Haney</a> reaches for a pass back to the point from McPherson\'s Lakyn Schiefereke during their January, 2019, Mid America Classic tournament contest.</em>','6 Major Movers in the 2020 Rankings','','publish','open','open','','6-major-movers-in-the-2020-rankings','','','2019-12-09 22:41:32','2019-12-10 04:41:32','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121469',0,'post','',0),
	(121475,1,'2019-12-06 11:32:58','2019-12-06 17:32:58','In an important early SCC matchup Carlinville traveled to Hillsboro Thursday night. Carlinville jumped out to an early lead but with a strong second and third quarter Hillsboro took control of the game. They were able to cruise through the 4th and ultimately come away with a 60-40 victory. The following are 5 Key Takeaways from the game.\n<ol>\n 	<li>One critical piece of the puzzle for Hillsboro this season is figuring out how to replace the scoring of Sammi Matoush. In this game the answer was by committee. <strong>Nikaya Harston </strong>had 12 points to lead the way. She did a good job of scoring in the paint. The key for her was establishing good position on the block and also her motor and effort on the boards. Harston is strong and tough in the post. <strong>Emily Reynolds </strong>had 10 points to be the other player in double figures. Emily did most of her damage off mid range jumpers. She was able to finish off the bounce and off the catch. <strong>Claire Tester </strong>was active around the basket and in the lane getting 9 points. Claire has a strong body so she can post up smaller wings, but if you try to defend her with a big she can put the ball on the floor and drive by them. At 5\'8 Claire is a \"tweener\", but she can figure out a way to score. <strong>Haley Major and Layne Rupert </strong>each scored 8 and 7 points from their guard spots.</li>\n 	<li>On a similar note, Carlinville came into the season needing to find a way to replace the leadership and scoring of Rachel Olroyd. In this game, they did not seem to have that answer. <strong>Corin Stewart </strong>was in double figures  with 13 but the left hander could not find the range on her shot. <strong>Jill Stayton </strong>has shown signs of being a good outside shooter but was also having a hard time finding her range. Hillsboro spent 2 1/2 quarters in a 1-2-2 and Carlinville had plenty of good looks, they just could not hit them. That ability to score consistently will be something Carlinville will have to work out.</li>\n 	<li>After such a successful season last year and having to replace their whole starting lineup the question coming in was, how good can Hillsboro be? The answer is they are still a tough team. They are a different team but still capable of winning games. This team is led by the inside play of Harston and the wing tandem of Tester and Reynolds. All 3 girls are capable scorers and good rebounders. Reynolds had a very good AAU season with the Predators and has come in prepared to have a good senior campaign. Harston is strong and athletic in the post and tough to stop once she gets the ball.</li>\n 	<li>Carlinville waited until late in the game to try to press Hillsboro and it reminded me that last year they seemed most comfortable going at break neck speed. I wonder if they might be better off trying to play the same way this year. Hillsboro is big and tough inside and maybe Carlinville played into their game by slowing it down. I don\'t know Coach DeNeve\'s team the way he does and I don\'t want to second guess him. I would have liked to see what <strong>Gracie Reels, Sarah DeNeve, Eryn Seal and Elise Baker </strong>could have done by making the front line of Hillsboro play at a fast pace the whole game. It seems like that may be the preferred way to play for that team. We will see as the season goes forward.</li>\n 	<li>While this may be a re-tooling year for Hillsboro they should be working towards a good season next year too.Seniors Reynolds and point guard <strong>Shelby Houchlei </strong>are starters and <strong>Maci Blankenship </strong>comes off the bench to provide help in the post, but they have a very deep junior class. Harston,Tester, Major, <strong>Maddy Rupert </strong>and <strong>Vanessa Compton </strong>are all contributors from the 2021 class and Layne Rupert is a 2023. So while they are looking to have a good season this year, they should be ready for another big season in 2020-21.</li>\n</ol>\nThis conference is very competitive and teams may not be as good as they look one night nor as \"bad\" as they look one night. I am sure this was not what Carlinville expected of themselves. It will be interesting to see how each team does moving forward.','Carlinville vs Hillsboro: 5 Key Takeaways','','publish','open','open','','carlinville-vs-hillsboro-5-key-takeaways','','','2019-12-06 11:32:58','2019-12-06 17:32:58','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121475',0,'post','',0),
	(121492,1,'2019-12-06 06:04:14','2019-12-06 12:04:14','It was the first game to christen the new gymnasium at Northridge High School, and it was a Southwestern Buckeye League battle between the host Northridge Polar Bears and Oakwood Lumberjills. In past years, Oakwood has been a competitive team in Division 2, and they showed good things against Northridge, who is working to turn their program around after some rough years.\n\nOakwood jumped out to a 19-point lead after the first quarter, and cruised to a 60-25 victory as 12 players scored for the Jills. Some takeaways from the game:\n\n<strong>Game MVP- </strong>it was difficult for me to pick a game MVP in this contest due to the fact that everyone played a lot of minutes which in this type of game was good for the kids to get some added experience. Nobody scored a lot but I thought while she was in there, junior Margie Conrath had a solid all-around game with eight points, four rebounds and a pair of threes. Conrath is a solid guard with good court awareness and can score from many angles. Shoots well from the perimeter and can get to the rim.\n\n<strong>Offensive Player of the Game- </strong>Nobody stood out offensively in this game, but the one kid who caught my eye with her play off the bench was the production of sophomore Olivia Grant. She came off the bench and scored ten points to lead everybody in this game with a variety of shots. Scored from the perimeter and in transition.\n\n<strong>Defensive Player of the Game- </strong>Oakwood senior Kylie Neff (5-foot-10 wing) did an outstanding job defensively when she was in there. She was aggressive to the ball and forced her opponent into mistakes. Always seemed to be around the ball and create havoc.\n\n<strong>Northridge Stretch of the Game-</strong> It came in the fourth quarter trailing 54-16, as they came out and really controlled a three minute span where they outscored Oakwood 7-0 behind the scoring of Leslie Lane (5-8 senior) and a three point shot by Diamonique Story (5-7 junior). The game was out of reach, but the kids didn\'t quit and controlled that part of the game.\n\n<strong>Run of the Game- </strong>the entire first quarter was a big run for Oakwood, as they scored the games first 18 points to set the tone. Conrath scored eight seconds into the game for the Jills and they never looked back.\n\n<strong>Key passer-</strong> it was good to see Oakwood senior Kylie Foos <strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">(pictured above) </span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt\">back out on the court after having to deal with injuries for a lot of her career. She saw the floor very well as a point guard, pushed the ball in transition and did what a true point guard is supposed to do, find the best shot for her team. Good leader on the floor, and has signed with Wittenberg for next year.</span></span>\n\n<strong>Off the Bench- </strong>the kid who impressed me the most off the bench was Oakwood\'s Grant. She had a stretch in the first quarter where she scored the majority of her points.  She hit a pair of three\'s within a minute span and really played well as Oakwood built their lead.\n\n<strong>One to Watch- </strong>Northridge had a 5-5 sophomore Maycee Harris who wasn\'t flashy but really worked hard on the floor. I liked her motor and effort as she scored a season high six points. Her numbers aren\'t gaudy by any means, and she likes to shoot the three which I like her aggressiveness trying to get the team going.\n\n<strong>Intangibles- </strong>What a beautiful new gymnasium in a brand new school for Northridge. I would have thought the seating would be a bit more, but the gym itself is tremendous and both scoreboards were state of the art. Coach Michael Paige has some work to do to get them into contention with the rest of the SWBL, but his kids work hard and that\'s half the battle.','Oakwood 60 Northridge 25 in SWBL action','','publish','open','open','','oakwood-60-northridge-25-in-swbl-action','','','2019-12-06 06:04:14','2019-12-06 12:04:14','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121492',0,'post','',0),
	(121493,1,'2019-12-06 06:01:57','2019-12-06 12:01:57','Opening round games are usually one-sided in tournaments, keep in mind I\'m talking about bracket play where teams are seeded and to have a competitive game toward the end of the evening to get my adrenaline up for a long ride home, or wherever I may be heading, is icing on the cake for me since I don\'t drink coffee with my cake, Cedar Ridge overcame a double-digit deficit to defeat El Paso Eastlake with a huge 3 by one of the smallest players on the court. Always remember, a close game does not mean it was a good game, this was a good game and here are some of the TAKEAWAYS\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121494\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\" wp-image-121494\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0178-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Cheyanne Bonilla[/caption]\n\n<strong>Cheyanne Bonilla shouldn\'t be UNSIGNED</strong>\n\nI don\'t just blow smoke, I don\'t even vape and when I say something regarding talent, I mean what I say and Bonilla put on an impressive offensive performance for El Paso Eastlake against a very talented team, one more time, it\'s not what you do, it\'s who you do it against and in the first half, she was virtually unstoppable dropping at least 3 threes, I may have missed some going to the hospitality room, as well as attacking the basket from every angle imaginable. Her midrange and ballhandling were also on display\n\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121495 alignright\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0168-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\n<strong>Eastlake gets after it</strong>\n\n<strong>Vanessa Herrera</strong> showed me on the opening play that she was ready and her acrobatic moves to the basket to go along with her pinpoint passes for assists were a big reason Eastlake was in control for most of the game. Another, along with Bonilla\'s scoring, was the fact that<strong> Edith Ramirez</strong> went into BEAST MODE early and stayed there most of the game battling inside on both like there was no tomorrow. Solid play from several other players including<strong> Alexis Landeros</strong> was huge\n\n<img class=\" wp-image-121504 alignleft\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0163-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"282\" height=\"185\" />\n\n<strong>Cedar Ridge\'s veteran leadership</strong>\n\n<strong>Paetynn Gray</strong> is showing some pre-Cal State Northridge skills in her senior year. She left me speechless during the club season watching her defensive effort including playing the passing lane and rebounding but her long ball shooting was on full display and that, combined with her college-ready body at 6\'2 created some problems. <strong>Malaysia DePrisco</strong> has gone from a defensive standout to use her athleticism well on the offensive end, attacking from everywhere and the inside play from <strong>Tajanna White </strong>played a big part in their run\n\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121505 alignright\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0246-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\n<strong>Sophomores stepping up</strong>\n\n<strong>Alex Neimeth</strong> has been more than just a pleasant surprise as she joins <strong>Lexi Alexander</strong> in the starting lineup. Neimeth offense has taken off, that midrange is clicking, and along with her solid defense, she has been more than a pleasant surprise. Alexander can bring power on the inside or face the basket and score while <strong>Timasha Hamilton</strong> and <strong>Jakayla Thompson</strong> are sparks off the bench and can provide heat on both ends of the court\n\n<strong>SIZE DON\'T MATTER when you can play</strong>\n\nAnother sophomore, <strong>Ta\' Kerria Hamilton</strong>, played a big part off the bench as she and <strong>Mikayla Johnson</strong> igniting rallies more than once. Hamilton\'s attacking of the basket relentlessly as well as the long ball definitely had something to do with her teams\' impressive comeback but Johnson who has hit several big-time baskets in front of me nailed the huge 3 that proved to be the game-winner. Both guards are small but both guards are fearless\n\n&nbsp;','Takeaways from Cedar Ridge vs El Paso Eastlake in Katy Classic','','publish','open','open','','takeaways-from-cedar-ridge-vs-el-paso-eastlake-in-katy-classic','','','2019-12-06 06:01:57','2019-12-06 12:01:57','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121493',0,'post','',0),
	(121527,1,'2019-12-06 08:33:30','2019-12-06 14:33:30','Basketball season has tipped off in Michigan. The state has elite talent and plenty of depth. Now is the time when memories are made and stars are born. There were big games, top talent, and excellent performances already in the first few days of the season.\n\nHere are 4 players that stood out to me on Thursday night:\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-121538\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/aff322a087c919817ebefa078e59ee2a-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\n<strong>Nevaeh Williams (2022, G, Mount Clemens)</strong>\n\nWilliams led her Mount Clemens squad to a huge win over Old Redford by a score of 70-7. She had 37 points, 9 steals, and 7 assists on the night. While her offensive numbers were staggering, it was her defense that opened the floodgates. Williams read the offense and stepped in passing lanes, creating chaos for the offense. She did a nice job finishing in transition off the turnovers.\n\n<strong>Mya Petticord (2022, G, Arbor Prep)</strong>\n\nPetticord led her Arbor Prep team to a hard fought victory over Clarkston. She led the way with 22 points, 6 rebounds, and 6 steals. Petticord\'s game is so mature that it\'s hard to remember that she\'s just a sophomore. Her footwork is better than most nationwide. She used her combination of ball handling skills and fast feet to keep Clarkston defenders off balance.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/cheyenne-mcevans/\">Cheyenne McEvans</a> (2020, G, Southfield A&amp;T)</strong>\n\nMcEvans helped Southfield A&amp;T secure a 52-39 over a game Avondale team. She notched 25 points, 11 rebounds, and 2 assists. McEvans looks to be making an early season statement:  She\'s undoubtedly one of the top prospects in Michigan. She used an instant change of speed on the dribble to blow by defenders all night. McEvans was able to attack the bucket from the top of the key, all the way to the baseline.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jenna-harrison/\">Jenna Harrison</a> (2021, G, Kent City)</strong>\n\nHarrison paced Kent City in their 78-30 win over Coopersville. She did it in typical Kent City style as well by hitting 8 three pointers en route to 27 points. Just like last year, Harrison showed a pure stroke from behind the arc and couldn\'t be left with any breathing room. She looks to be another game changer on a talented roster.\n\n&nbsp;','4 Big Thursday Performances','','publish','open','open','','4-big-thursday-performances','','','2019-12-06 08:33:30','2019-12-06 14:33:30','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121527',0,'post','',0),
	(121556,1,'2019-12-11 21:02:36','2019-12-12 03:02:36','<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Another edition of \"Same Face New Place\", highlighting some of the top prospects who transferred schools this year. These players look to help their clubs obtain success this season. Let\'s take a look at who they are.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color: #f75617\"><strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jeanene-collazo/\">Jeanene Collazo</a> | 6\'0 F | Rosedale Baptist 2021</strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color: #f75617\"><strong> <img class=\"alignnone wp-image-124226\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Jeanene-Collazo-300x300.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"198\" height=\"198\" /></strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Ranked #67 on Prep Girls Hoops 2021 rankings, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jeanene-collazo/\">Jeanene Collazo</a> has a chance to shine this year with the Panthers. The Institute of Notre Dame transfer already has a couple big games under her belt as Rosedale has gotten off to a .500 start this season. Rosedale Baptists just had their 4 game win streak snapped after a loss to Mount Airy Christian Academy yesterday. Rosedale looks to bounce back in tomorrows rivalry game verse Carrol Christian. I expect Jeanene\'s rebound game to climb as the season goes on.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #f75617\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophia-diehl/\">Sophia Diehl</a> | 6\'0 W | Roland Park 2021 </span></strong></span>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-124227\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Sophia-Diehl-300x168.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"246\" height=\"138\" />\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophia-diehl/\">Sophia Diehl</a> will continue her career at Roland Park after spending the last two years at Westminster. She joins another elite squad, this time with one of the best players in the state, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mir-mclean/\">Mir McLean</a></strong>. Sophia attacks the basket with finesse and I wouldn\'t be surprised if she runs the point in key matchups this season. Sophia will certainly be a rebounding machine for Roland Park this year.</span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #f75617\"><strong><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif\">Anha Thomas | 5\'9 G | Bowie 2021</span></strong></span>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-124228\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Ahna-Thomas-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"222\" height=\"222\" />\n\n<span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif\">Anha Thomas is a great basketball player and her room to grow is tremendous. She possess all the intangibles, hop-steps when driving, has a fabulous form and plays excellent defense. Anha played for Bowie her freshman year before transferring to New Hope Academy. With the lost of <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jenesis-massenburg/\">Jenesis Massenburg</a></strong> to Capital Christian Academy, Anha rejoins Bowie at the perfect time.</span>','Same Face New Place | Part 2','','publish','open','open','','same-face-new-place-part-2','','','2019-12-11 21:02:36','2019-12-12 03:02:36','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121556',0,'post','',0),
	(121563,1,'2019-12-06 12:12:50','2019-12-06 18:12:50','We\'ve almost finished the first week of the 2019-2020 season and I\'d like to take a minute and break down some surprising results and impressive performers.\n\nThe biggest surprise to me actually occurred off the court as South Laurel\'s <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rachel-presley/\">Rachel Presley</a> </strong>was ruled ineligible until February despite having played varsity volleyball all fall. It hasn\'t slowed South Laurel down yet as they rolled through Lincoln County on Monday but there will be occasions when Presley\'s size and low post presence will be missed.\n\n<strong>Mercy absolutely dismantling Eastern. </strong>Our Ryan Moore provided a tremendous breakdown of the game that you can find <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/12/five-takeaways-mercy-83-eastern-41/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">HERE</a>. But no one could have predicted Mercy would come out and more than double up the Eagles in their season debut. The Jaguars appear to be motivated this year after falling short of their goals last year. They followed that win with another big win over Bardstown.\n\n<strong>Ballard beating Collins by 10 at Collins. </strong>Collins won the 8th last season and look capable of winning it again this year. Meanwhile, Ballard was predicted to be a middle of the pack team in a loaded 7th region. <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kiarah-carney/\">Kiarah Carney</a> </strong>went for 33 points for Ballard and continues to prove herself as one of the most underrated Seniors in the state. On a positive note, Collins Senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/olivia-federle/\">Olivia Federle</a></strong> scored her 2,000th career point for the Titans this week.\n\n<strong>Scott County\'s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/morgan-defoor/\">Morgan DeFoor</a> dominanting through two games. </strong>The Morehead State signee is off to a running start this year as she scored 28 in a win over Lexington Catholic and then followed that with 17 points on Wednesday in another win. With graduation and transfers to Great Crossing, there was some uncertainty around the Lady Cards roster. Morgan has stepped up in a big way and looks ready to make a run at 11th region player of the year.\n\n<strong>CAL knocking off Butler. </strong>Sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jaya-mcclure/\">Jaya McClure</a> led the Centurions as 3 players finished in double figures and another ended with 9. They only shot 33% from the field but an ugly win is a win nonetheless. CAL continues to establish themselves as a force in the 6th region.\n\n<strong>Simon Kenton beating Ryle by 27. </strong>Ryle losing at all this early is an eyebrow raiser but the fact that they were so thoroughly dominated makes this season look even more open than it already appeared to be with so much talent in the Senior class. Simon Kenton plays Sacred Heart on Saturday at Dixie Heights. If the Lady Pioneers take that game too, there may not be a more impressive set of wins this season.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Recruiting News:</strong></span>\n\nSpeaking of Simon Kenton, Senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/maggie-jones/\">Maggie Jones</a></strong> made her commitment to Thomas More this week. Jones is one of the best players in the 8th region and will be a nice player at Thomas More.\n\nSouth Warren\'s <strong>Brooke Stevenson</strong> was offered by Milligan College last week. Centre and Bellarmine have previously offered Stevenson.\n\nBarbourville Senior <strong>Abbagail Smith</strong> is off the board to Union College so she won\'t need to go far to get to her college classes. Smith is a good scorer who is one of the better Class A players in the 13th region.\n\nSouth Laurel sharpshooter <strong>Syndie Hall</strong> committed to Lindsey Wilson. She chose Lindsey over a handful of other offers. One of Kentucky\'s top shooters, Hall is the third South Laurel Senior to commit and sign this season.','Opening Week Surprises, Top Performers And Recruiting News','','publish','open','open','','opening-week-surprises-top-performers-and-recruiting-news','','','2019-12-06 12:12:50','2019-12-06 18:12:50','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121563',0,'post','',0),
	(121570,1,'2019-12-06 10:22:16','2019-12-06 16:22:16','I love good stories and happy endings and really love when players just go out and prove doubters and haters wrong so with Under The Radar <strong>Geonna \"Gi Gi\" Waddell</strong> signing early with <strong>Doane University,</strong> the #sizedontmatter guard shows what hard work and determination will do. Transferring to Lutheran North as a junior, she helped lead her Lions squad to their first state championship game and although they came up just short, they were in it. Her skills were on full display at the Girls Texas Jamboree\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121585\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"280\"]<img class=\" wp-image-121585\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0064-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"280\" height=\"184\" /> Victoria Noack[/caption]\n\n<strong>Lutheran North Takeaways </strong>\n\nWaddell and <strong>Jaelyn Compton</strong> had been providing most of the offense for the Lions every time I caught them last season, Waddell\'s pull-up in transition as well as blowing by defenders with an explosive first step have both improved but the thing with her is that she\'s always trying to add something. Compton is a scorer, she finds ways to put the ball in the basket and she can attack powerfully or sink the mid to long-range consistently. <strong>Victoria Noack</strong> got the team nod for MVP as she showed a variety of ways to create her shot under pressure and speaking of pressure, she nailed some big ones. <strong>Kinsie Kim</strong> was another pleasant surprise and I\'ll be catching them again soon\n\n<strong>High scorers were  Victoria Noack 16, Jacelyn Compton 14, Geonna Waddell 14, Kinsie Kim 12</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121586\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-121586\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0063-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Ajailah Ogiemwonyi[/caption]\n\n<strong>John Cooper Takeaways </strong>\n\n<strong>Katelyn Wood</strong>,<strong> Aalyssa Rogers</strong>, and <strong>Jorynn Ross</strong> all impressed me at the<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/john-cooper-bright-spots-shine-at-lady-broncos-classic/\"> Lady Broncos Classic</a> </strong>a couple of weeks ago. Yes Wood can nail the mid to long-range consistently , yes Rogers uses her powerful body to be an \"and one waiting to happen\" and Ross, well she showed even more with the huge \"drop step\" for and ones so as usual, I was accurate and fair about my assessment because one more time, I\'m an EVALUATOR of talent, that\'s an accurate statement as well but\n\nsimply went off and was named team MVP. She\'s athletic and attacks strongly and finishes powerfully, nice moves on the inside, handles the ball under pressure but get this, she out rebounds taller opponents on both ends, consistently and brings the heat on defense\n\n<strong>High scorers were Ajailah Ogiemwonyi 18, Jorynn Ross 14, Kaetlyn Wood 10</strong>\n\n<strong>Cooper wins 63-62</strong>','Takeaways from John Cooper vs Lutheran North #GirlsTXJamboree','','publish','open','open','','takeaways-from-john-cooper-vs-lutheran-north-girlstxjamboree','','','2019-12-06 10:22:16','2019-12-06 16:22:16','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121570',0,'post','',0),
	(121577,1,'2019-12-06 11:57:29','2019-12-06 17:57:29','<strong>MONTICELLO --</strong> Last night Prep Girls Hoops Minnesota was in Monticello to watch their 63-47 win over Rocori. Here are some standouts we watched in this one.\n\n<strong>Lauran Zwack, Guard, Monticello (2020)</strong>\n\nZwack was the best sideline to sideline guard I\'ve watched so far this season. She runs the court extremely well and has the speed and endurance to get to the bucket without much trouble from the Rocori defenders. A UW- La Crosse track commit, Zwack was one of the leading scorers with 14 points for the Magic to secure their win against Rocori.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121596\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"270\"]<img class=\"wp-image-121596\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC0021-300x197.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"270\" height=\"177\" /> Lauran Zwack chipped in nicely in the Magic\'s win over Rocori. Credit: Jared Hines, Monticello Magic[/caption]\n\n<strong>Laney Griffin, Guard, Rocori (2020)</strong>\n\nGriffin was the smallest guard from both teams at 5\'3, but that didn\'t stop her motor from running. Even when the Spartans were down by 20+ points, Griffin still was a grinder for this Spartans offense. I look for her to be the leader of this Spartans team this season as she chipped in a 12 point outing last night in Monticello.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121601\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"269\"]<img class=\"wp-image-121601\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC0047-300x200.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"269\" height=\"179\" /> Laney Griffin was the lone bright spot for the Rocori Spartans last night. Credit: Jared Hines, Monticello Magic[/caption]\n\n<strong>Katelyn Lindberg, Guard, Monticello (2022)</strong>\n\nThe youngest star in this one was Katelyn Lindberg. I heard about her before tip-off on how she had a good last game for Monticello but I still had her as my diamond in the rough player, as I hadn\'t watched her yet. She put together a very consistent 14 point outing for the Magic and was a good player to watch as she started but also with the Magic up, helped the younger players get better while they were getting some minutes in a lopsided contest.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121640\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"270\"]<img class=\" wp-image-121640\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC0009-1-300x197.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"270\" height=\"177\" /> Katelyn Lindberg gets my \"Stockriser\" Award as she put together a nice outing against Rocori. Credit: Jared Hines, Monticello Magic[/caption]\n\n<strong>Cat Terres, Center, Monticello (2020)</strong>\n\nThe Rocori defense could not match up with Cat Terres down low, giving her easy buckets and hitting double digits when it comes to scoring. The guard player of <strong>Zwack </strong>and <strong>Lindberg </strong>found Terres with obvious mismatches all night long and Terres played the post with ease.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121644\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"270\"]<img class=\" wp-image-121644\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC0017-300x200.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"270\" height=\"180\" /> Cat Terres of Monticello overpowered the Rocori defense in the paint in last night\'s 63-47 win. Credit: Jared Hines, Monticello Magic[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/anna-olson/\">Anna Olson</a>, Forward, Monticello (2020)</strong>\n\nOlson proved why she is a top 25 2020 prospect in Minnesota. The Vermont commit played with her length especially with grabbing boards. At 6\'1, she grabbed tough rebounds, scored at will inside, and overpowered Rocori yet again in his senior year. Monticello played more of a team game last night from some of the scores I\'ve seen Olson put up in the past. They had four of their five starters in double figures with <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/anna-olson/\">Anna Olson</a></strong> being one of them.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_121641\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"270\"]<img class=\"wp-image-121641\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC0002-300x200.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"270\" height=\"180\" /> Vermont Commit <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/anna-olson/\">Anna Olson</a> proved again how strong she is against the Rocori Spartans. Credit: Jared Hines, Monticello Magic[/caption]','Rocori-Monticello Standouts','','publish','open','open','','rocori-monticello-standouts','','','2019-12-06 11:57:29','2019-12-06 17:57:29','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121577',0,'post','',0),
	(121578,1,'2019-12-06 11:17:15','2019-12-06 17:17:15','There will be college prospects all over the gym on Saturday, as the top two D1 teams in the Dayton area meet at 1:00 in Huber Heights. Fairmont and Wayne both come into the game unbeaten as the two GWOC schools will meet for the first of their two meeting this season. Currently, they are ranked #1 and #2 in the latest Dayton area power poll for D1.\n\nBoth teams have bigtime D1 college recruits and other players who have the skill to play at the next level. It all starts with the stars:\n\n<strong>Best vs Best: </strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Madeline Westbeld</span>, the #1 2020 in the latest PGH Ohio rankings, will lead the way for the Fairmont Firebirds as the Notre Dame recruit has been off to a fast start this young season. She scored 36 points against the nations #2 ranked Hamilton Heights team out of Tennesee, and had 29 last week against Springfield.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Bree Hall</span> is also ranked #1 in the PGH Ohio rankings in her class of 2021, as the multidimensional guard can do it all. She can take over a game with her athleticism, get to the rim, and lately has strengthened her perimeter game and is a threat from behind the arc.\n\n<strong>Another D1 duo: </strong>While Westbeld runs the show from the guard spot, <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Madison Bartley<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"> <span style=\"color: #000000;font-size: 10pt\"><strong>(pictured above/photo Gene Peters) </strong></span><span style=\"color: #000000\">is also having a fast start to the season. The 6-foot-4 Belmont University signee has polished her game and is a threat from midrange into the paint. Bartley is strong enough to dominate the boards and control the paint defensively. </span></span></span>\n\nWayne also has another D1 signee as <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Nyla Hampton <span style=\"color: #000000\">will head to Bowling Green after she graduates this summer. Hampton can control the tempo of the game with her guard play, great handles and has deadly range from the three. </span></span>\n\n<strong>Backcourt Duo: </strong>Fairmont will bring in a pair of talented senior guards with <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Makira Webster <span style=\"color: #000000\">and <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Kierra Thornton<span style=\"color: #000000\">. Webster has the capabilities to score, yet does a great job distributing the ball and controls the game for the Firebirds. Thornton does a good job on the boards and bring a lot of leadership to the Firebirds.</span></span></span></span>\n\n<strong>Welcome to the Show: </strong>Two newcomers who look to make contributions for Wayne are <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Alyssa Hall</span> and <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Jacquel Bronaugh</span>. <span style=\"color: #000000\">Hall has made a bigger offensive impact for the Warriors, but Bronaugh is starting to get settled in and should help in the paint for Wayne. Hall moved over from Beavercreek and Bronaugh comes in from Northmont. </span>\n\n<strong>Don\'t forget about us: </strong>Fairmont also has two players who has flown under the radar so far, but will be impact players through the season. <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Kyndall Ketterer <span style=\"color: #000000\">moved over to Fairmont from Oakwood and seems to be healthy, adding a versatile game to their attack. Ketterer can score from the perimeter or is physical enough to score underneath. <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Mallory Hullinger <span style=\"color: #000000\">is only a sophomore and has been a pleasant surprise for Fairmont.</span></span></span></span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #000000\">Making a name: </span></strong><span style=\"color: #000000\">Both <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Jaida Wolfork </span>and <span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Lovie Malone <span style=\"color: #000000\">are players who have had good moments so far this season. Wolfork had a big night against Toledo Notre Dame, can score from the perimeter or put the ball on the floor. Malone is a rising junior with some college offers, and she is more of a versatile guard who can score if needed. </span></span></span>\n\n&nbsp;','Saturday Showdown Preview- #1 Fairmont v #2 Wayne','','publish','open','open','','saturday-showdown-preview-1-fairmont-v-2-wayne','','','2019-12-06 11:17:15','2019-12-06 17:17:15','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121578',0,'post','',0),
