	(121631,1,'2019-12-09 14:41:41','2019-12-09 20:41:41','It\'s not often that big time matchups actually live up to expectations. However, that certainly was the case in Cardinal Newman\'s thrilling 49-45 victory over Cannon in Concord Friday night. Of course, everyone was looking forward to the much anticipated matchup between ESPN\'s Class of 2022 top ranked player <strong>Ashlyn Watkins</strong> and Cannon\'s fabulous <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/reigan-richardson-2/\">Reigan Richardson</a></strong>. Those two players definitely put on a show, but \"the others\" also showed up and that made for high quality basketball and a thrilling finish. A few observations:\n<ol>\n 	<li><strong>Audrey Meyers</strong> is the best \"Robin\" I have seen this year.  If Meyers decided to change her name to Scottie Pippen, it would be understandable.  Clearly because of her overwhelming talent level, Watkins is the alpha, but Meyers is the perfect compliment to the brilliance of Watkins. The 6\'0\" Senior Wing scored 20 of the team\'s 49 points but that doesn\'t begin to tell the whole story.  Her overall floor game is magnificent.  She is long and skilled with an exceptional handle and she plays under control.  In addition, she is a willing and able defender who shot the gap on multiple occasions and made key steals. This young lady is a superstar in her own right and has an incredibly bright future.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Zoe Edwards</strong> of Cannon is a winning player. The 5\'6\" Junior Guard is tough as nails and is a big shot taker and a big shot maker.  A great decision maker and a fiery leader, she was instrumental in bringing Cannon back from the deficit they faced for much of the game.  She finished with 11 points, 4 rebounds and an assist. Honestly, when I saw her at the Charlotte Hoops Challenge last month, she appeared tentative as Cannon squandered a late lead in a 2 point loss to Ardrey Kell.  There were no such issues on Friday.  She was decisive and a real difference maker for the Cougars and Head Coach Kelvin Drakeford.</li>\n 	<li>Speaking of Coach Drakeford, he coached his tail off on Friday night.  He astutely started out with long and talented freshman <strong>Trinity Mathis</strong> on Watkins.  Mathis used her 5\'10\" frame and long arms and actually bothered Watkins somewhat in the first half.  Once Watkins started having success, Drakeford switched his best defender, Richardson, onto Mathis.  Not only did it give us the matchup we all came to see, the switch ignited a mini run for Cannon.  Because she was able to rest on defense for much of the game, Richardson had late energy down the stretch when she was asked to defend Watkins and scored the majority of her game high 23 points in leading Cannon\'s comeback effort.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Ashlyn Watkins </strong>(21 points) is a phenomenal talent who literally made three or four plays that left the crowd speechless. Obviously, I haven\'t seen all the best in the Class of 2022, but I can\'t imagine a better prospect than Watkins.  She combines preternatural athleticism with strong fundamentals that leave you amazed at the maturity of her game.  Polished - that is the word that kept coming to mind.  She is an incredible player who\'s only weakness (and I use the term in the relative sense) appears to be somewhat inconsistent foul shooting.  The sky is truly the limit for this amazing athlete.</li>\n 	<li>All of that being said, <strong>Reigan Richardson </strong>stood toe to toe with Watkins and showed she belongs on a national stage.  Richardson\'s game is very well rounded.  She boards, handles, scores, creates offense for others and defends.  When I saw her play Ardrey Kell, she appeared to wilt under the pressure of an intense game.  A couple of costly late turnovers allowed <strong>Eva Miller</strong> and Kell to rally for the victory. Yet, when faced with the challenge of dealing with Watkins, she more than answered the bell.  I cannot wait to see her later this school season and during the spring when the AAU calendar is upon us.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Sydney Wood </strong>is capable of being Cannon\'s third scorer and she will need to be for this team to reach it\'s potential.  Wood, the 5\'7\" Junior Guard is a skilled ballhandler and has a nice shot.  She had a great game on the defensive end, but needs to contribute more on the offensive end than the 3 points she scored on Friday.  If she doesn\'t become the third scorer, then promising freshmen Mathis (4 points) and <strong>Anyia Brooks-Manning </strong>(5\'9\" Guard/Forward) (2 points) will be required to grow up very fast for Coach Drakeford.</li>\n 	<li>Finally, these type of out of conference, intersectional games are great for our sport.  From strictly a basketball standpoint, it\'s invaluable experience for Watkins and her teammates like <strong>Erin Boyer </strong>(2 points) and <strong>Alyce Etter</strong> (6 points) to go on the road, in a hostile environment, against quality competition and learn how to close games and win.  In addition, games like this are great exposure for all of the players on the court.  I saw staff from at least 5 division one schools including 3 ACC schools.  They saw some really good players and were treated to a very well played contest.</li>\n</ol>','\"Big Guns Blazing\" - Cannon Falls To Cardinal Newman 49-45 - 12/6/19.','','publish','open','open','','big-guns-blazing-cannon-falls-to-cardinal-newman-49-45-12-6-19','','','2019-12-09 14:41:41','2019-12-09 20:41:41','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121631',0,'post','',0),
	(121634,1,'2019-12-07 09:38:04','2019-12-07 15:38:04','There are quite a few 2023\'s that are making an impact on the varsity level early in the season. Here I will try to give a you a quick run down of who is out there getting it done.\n<ul>\n 	<li><strong>Shannon Dowell </strong>is a 5\'9 guard from O\'Fallon. Shannon started the opening game and has done a good job early on for Coach Knolhoff. She is averaging 9 points per game and is shooting 75% from the free throw line.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Laylah Jackson </strong>is a 5\'6 guard from Belleville East. Laylah is  the second leading scorer for the Lady Lancers at 12.3. She has shown deep range on her 3-point shot and the ability to get into the lane off the bounce.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Kylie Kisgen </strong>is a 5\'6 guard from Freeburg. Kylie got off to a very fast start with 11 and 19 in her first two games. Her scoring has leveled off some, but she is still providing good depth for the Lady Midgets.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Addie Wright </strong>is a 6\'0 forward from Oakwood. She is providing another option as teams concentrate on Murray St commit Kate Young. Addie is averaging 8 points, 6 rebounds, 2 assists and 2 steals per game.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Grace Heckert </strong>is a 5\'8 guard from CHBC(Crowden-Herrick/Beecher City). Grace is giving scoring punch off the bench for now, averaging 6 points and 2 assists. She had a nice game of 10 points this week vs Neoga.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Lee Triplett </strong>is a 5\'11 forward from Charleston. She is another player getting looks as other teams concentrate on a D1 player, Shae Litttleford. Lee is scoring 14 per game and grabbing 10 rebounds.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Sophia Loden </strong>is a 5\'11 forward from Mascoutah. Sophia has a high motor with excellent defense and rebounding skills. She is developing her offensive game and had a career high last time out of 10 points.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Haley Ottenschneider </strong>is a 5\'6 guard from Breese Central. Haley is providing a spark on offense off the bench. She had a high of 13 points last time out vs Salem. She gets to the basket well and can finish in the lane.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Shakara McCline </strong>is a 5\'5 guard from East St. Louis. Shakara has been the leading scorer in the majority of the games so far this year. She is very aggressive at getting to the hole and is averaging just over 10 per game.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Jailah Pelly </strong>is a 5\'10 guard from East St. Louis. Jailah has also been a big part of the early success of the Lady Flyers. She has done a good job at getting to the foul line and converting. She is averaging just under 10 per game with a high of 18.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Trinity Tingley and Kendra Young </strong>are both guards from Paris. Tingley is 5\'5 and Young is 5\'11. Both girls are getting minutes off the bench for a very talented team. Tingley is putting up 6 points and 2 assists per game while Young is averaging 5 points and 4 rebounds. Both girls could be starting on many teams.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Jordan Gary </strong>is a 5\'6 guard from Collinsville. Gary is not putting up highlight stats but is providing valuable minutes off the bench for a team that lacks some depth. She can defend and play the pace they want. Jordan is averaging 2.2 points and 3.2 rebounds per game.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Megan Rennegarbe and Briley Rhodes</strong> are guards from Okawville. Megan is 5\'7 and Briley is 5\'3. Briley was named All-Tourney at Nashville and Megan had a nice game with 14 in the 3rd place game. Megan is best slashing to the basket and finishing in the lane, while Briley seems to be hot from the 3-point line early on this season.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Audrey Sabol </strong>is a 6\'0 post from Nokomis. Audrey has been a valuable addition putting up 9.7 points and 8.1 rebounds per game. She has done an excellent job on defense against some of the better post players in the area.</li>\n</ul>\nI am sure there are plenty of girls not on my radar yet, so we will keep updating this list throughout the season.\n\n&nbsp;','2023\'s Making An Early Impact','','publish','open','open','','2023s-making-an-early-impact','','','2019-12-07 09:38:04','2019-12-07 15:38:04','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=121634',0,'post','',0),
