	(122396,1,'2019-12-08 08:06:18','2019-12-08 14:06:18','The second part of the event gave me a chance to capture some additional players I knew absolutely nothing about, well except one,<strong> Duchesne\'s Catherine Van Pelt</strong> who will be on my Top Performers story from the event  coming up next but the Cristo Rey vs Duchesne just kept me glued primarily because of the effort despite the outcome of the event\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_122405\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-122405 size-medium\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0142-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Meta Sapien &amp; Kimberly Fuentez[/caption]\n\n<strong>Duchesne\'s supporting cast </strong>\n\nVan Pelt is the glue, no question about that but steady play from 2021 guard <strong>Aleyna Ozcelik</strong> played a big part in their win. The team ran the press efficiently and that provided several baskets going the other way however they also had a couple of players that showed they could shoot it from long range, 2020 guard <strong>Meta Sapie</strong>n as well as<strong> Vivian Vann</strong>, also a 2020 guard. Throw in some solid inside play from senior <strong>Marissa Lundvall</strong> who finished and rebounded\n\n<strong>Cristo Rey\'s effort</strong>\n\nThe team started the game off with only 5 players and put up a good fight before Duchesne put together several big runs but this squad never gave up. 2020 <strong>Daisy Garcia</strong> plays bigger than she is, doesn\'t mind battling against taller players but despite being down, I enjoyed seeing them play through it. 2023<strong> Ximena Escobedo</strong>,2020 <strong>Aracely Lopez</strong>, and 2021<strong> Isabella Gillette</strong> were serviceable players but seniors<strong> Bianca Carrizal</strong> and <strong>Kimberly Fuentez</strong> provided most of the firepower. Carrizal just goes hard, attacks and plays the passing lane and she found ways to score while Fuentez used her body well for baskets and did a good job rebounding\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_122407\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"200\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-122407\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0221-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" /> Eliza Holt[/caption]\n\n<strong>St John\'s vs Kinkaid</strong>\n\nDue to time restraint, I had to leave this game early but St Johns was putting up a great fight fueled by the play of senior <strong>Emily Holt.</strong> Holt sees the floor, understands the game and just made plays but her length and ability to shoot the midrange consistently caught my eye. Kinkaid got off to slow start offensively, <strong>Olivia Sullivan</strong> kept them in striking distance dropping multiple shots from long range however despite a great comeback, the team lost in overtime\n\nThe Village School defeated St John\'s in the championship game and I\'ll come back and drop some of the top performers from the event including UNSIGNED and UNDER THE RADAR players that continue to show they can play at some level of the next level','Houston Tip Off Classic pt 2','','publish','open','open','','houston-tip-off-classic-pt-2','','','2019-12-08 08:06:18','2019-12-08 14:06:18','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122396',0,'post','',0),
	(122397,1,'2019-12-08 11:36:47','2019-12-08 17:36:47','The <strong>Lady Trojans</strong> and the <strong>Lady Lions</strong> played on 12/06/2019 at <strong>The Dungeon</strong> in Topeka, Kansas. In the first a couple of minutes of the game, it was looking like it would be one for the memory books. Six Freshmen got introduced to their first High School game of their career on this night. Two of these Fabulous Freshmen earned the start for their respective teams, <strong>Amaya Marshall, 5\'4\" PG/SG, Lawrence, #13 </strong>in the class of <strong>2023</strong> <strong>Kansas Girls Prep Hoops Rankings</strong> and <strong>KiKi Smith, 5\'7\" SG, Topeka, #31 </strong>in the class of <strong>2023 Kansas Girls Prep Hoops Rankings. </strong>Here\'s the deal, the best player on the court on this night was not a senior in my opinion. I covered this game knowing it would be an interesting matchup due to both teams roster boasting a lot of underclassmen. The <strong>Lady Lions</strong> struck first and then something happened after about 3 minutes ran off the clock, the <strong>Lady Trojans </strong>introduced to everyone watching the game to <strong>KiKi Smith!</strong>\n\n<strong>KiKi Smith </strong>is strong, athletic, she\'s quick, she\'s unselfish and I\'m telling you now, <strong>KiKi Smith </strong>is a <strong>Certified Baller! </strong>I don\'t know if she took the rankings personal or if she wanted to remind everyone that we should love <strong>KiKi </strong>for her basketball game and that she is the <strong>2019 Jr. NBA Championships MVP and Champion. </strong>She opened her high school career with a 21 point showing. <strong>Ms. KiKi Smith </strong>put her stamp of approval all over this game and she did so on both ends of the floor for the <strong>#1 ranked Topeka High Lady Trojans. </strong>Get your tickets, your popcorn and your beverages ready for the next time <strong>KiKi Smith </strong>laces her shoes up, it\'s a must that you go see the <strong>Lady Trojans </strong>play their brand of basketball.\n\n<strong>Amaya Marshall </strong>got the start at the point guard position for the <strong>Lady Lions </strong>against the loaded <strong>Lady Trojans. </strong>This was not an easy task for <strong>Amaya </strong>because the opposing team kept pressuring her at 94 feet and it came from at least 4 different players. <strong>Ms. Marshall </strong>handled the pressure well at numerous times throughout the game, she is a high IQ player that knows how to run a team. I love her energy and toughness she brings to the game, with all the pressure and different looks Topeka High was giving <strong>Amaya </strong>she didn\'t shy away from her point guard duties. <strong>Amaya Marshall </strong>may have only scored 2 points for the game but she helped her team in all facets of the game. Keep your eye on <strong>Amaya Marshall</strong> this season, she\'s a coach\'s daughter that, of course, has a High Basketball IQ.\n\n<strong>Hailey Ramirez, 5\'5\" SG,</strong> came off the bench for the<strong> Lady Lions</strong> to get her first taste of high school basketball in her freshmen campaign. The way the flow of the game was in <strong>Hailey </strong>checked into the game was at a hectic pace, it did not faze her, <strong>Hailey </strong>came right in playing her role and ended the night with <strong>6pts </strong>on <strong>2</strong> for <strong>3</strong> from the field and 1 for 1 from the line. <strong>Hailey Ramirez</strong> has some good basketball IQ, she can shoot the 3 with good range, she has nice form on her shot and she moves well on defense. Remember the name <strong>Hailey Ramirez, </strong>she will be earning more quality minutes for the <strong>Lady Lions </strong>this season. <strong>Class of 2023 </strong><strong>Kansas Girls Prep Hoops Rankings Alert!</strong>\n\n<strong>Serenity Keo, 5\'4\" SG, </strong>came off the bench for the <strong>Lady Lions </strong>to start off her freshmen season. <strong>Keo </strong>checked into the game for <strong>LHS </strong>and went right to work.<strong> Serenity\'s</strong> night ended with her going <strong>1 </strong>for <strong>4 </strong>from the field and <strong>4</strong> for<strong> 5 </strong>from the line for <strong>6pts. </strong>You can tell right away that <strong>Keo</strong> was not intimidated by the moment when she checked in because she immediately went into attack mode. <strong>Serenity </strong>has a good basketball IQ, she can create off of the dribble to get her shot off or set up her teammates for an easy look. Marked down <strong>Serenity Keo </strong>in your notebook or wherever but just don\'t forget her name. <strong>Keo </strong>will be earning some more meaningful minutes for the <strong>Lady Lions, </strong>I\'m sure of that. <strong>Kansas Girls Prep Hoops Rankings Alert!</strong>\n\n<strong>Faith Shields, 5\'8\" Guard, </strong>came into the game after sitting on the bench for most of the game and did the same thing when she got on the court, sat down on defense. <strong>Faith</strong> moves her feet very well and if she comes in and continues to play her role, she will start getting easy buckets due to her defense. <strong>Faith Shields </strong>has some nice size, good speed, and some good athleticism that fits well with the scheme of the <strong>Lady Trojans. Kansas Girls Prep Hoops Rankings Alert!</strong>\n\n<strong>Adisyn Caryl, 5\'8\" Wing, </strong>came off the bench late in the game to get the first varsity minutes of her high school career. From what I have seen <strong>Adisyn </strong>has some good basketball IQ, she came in and made some good reads on the offensive end of the floor. With some work on getting quicker and having the advantage of having an older sister(<strong>Zoe Caryl,</strong> class of 2021) on the team <strong>Adisyn Caryl </strong>will get better with time. Most of her minutes will probably be on the Junior Varsity team for the <strong>Lady Trojans. Kansas Girls Prep Hoops Rankings Alert!</strong>\n\nOne night, six freshmen, two teams playing in the Dungeon memories were made and lives were changed during a game of basketball. The season is here and these <strong>Fabulous Freshmen</strong> are ready to make a name for themselves and make their marks in the history books for their respective schools.\n\n&nbsp;','Six Fabulous Freshmen from the Topeka Lady Trojans vs the Lawrence Lady Lions showdown','','publish','open','open','','six-fabulous-freshmen-from-the-topeka-lady-trojans-vs-the-lawrence-lady-lions-showdown','','','2019-12-08 11:36:47','2019-12-08 17:36:47','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122397',0,'post','',0),
	(122413,1,'2019-12-08 09:17:18','2019-12-08 15:17:18','Heading into the huge Division 1 showdown on Saturday between Dayton\'s #1 Fairmont and #2 Wayne, most people expected the game to come down to the last minute. With four minutes left, Wayne led 47-40 before Fairmont stormed back thanks to <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madison-bartley/\">Madison Bartley</a>\'s five points in the next two minutes.\n\nAs <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madelyn-westbeld/\">Madeline Westbeld</a>, the #1 2020 in Ohio, tied the game with 30 seconds left on a short jumper, it would all come down to the possession with Wayne getting the final shot. The state\'s top 2021 Bree Hall would come up clutch with the game winning move through the defense to knock down the winning shot as time expired to give the Warriors a 51-49 victory.\n\nSome takeaways from the big game:\n\n<strong>Game MVP- </strong>it took her a little while to get going offensively, but when she did, she showed why she is the best junior in Ohio. After a mortal-like first half, Hall exploded for 16 points in the second half to end with 25 points and as the clock was winding down, she took the ball at the top of the key, battled against Westbeld and made a move and tossed it up toward the basket and after it bounced around, it fell through to give Wayne the GWOC victory.\n\n<strong>Offensive Player of the Game- </strong>one of the more steady performers on the day was Westbeld, being productive in each quarter. She opened the game with six points in the first five minutes to give Fairmont an early 8-2 lead, then in the third period with the Firebirds battling to hold onto the lead, she hit two bigtime reverse moves blanketed by a defender and a short 5-foot jumper in the paint. She finished with 17 on the night.\n\n<strong>One shot and out- </strong>One thing Fairmont did that helped control the first half was only allowing Wayne to one shot. They did a great job on the boards to contain the explosive Warriors offense, keeping them from additional opportunities.\n\n<strong>Play of the Game-</strong> of course it is easy to say that Bree Hall\'s game winner was the Play of the Game, as it should be considered the biggest shot of the game. But back in the second quarter, a huge couple of possessions came at the 4:17 mark with Fairmont leading 18-8 and on a 6-0 run, it was junior Alyssa Hargrove-Hall that essentially got Wayne back into game. She badly missed a three, shaking her head in disgust she came right back and buried a three, and her big play of the game came on the next possession that she created herself. She swiped the steal from the Firebirds, went coast-to-coast blanketed by a defender and scored to cut the Fairmont lead to 18-13. That turned the momentum to Wayne who ended up getting the 22-20 lead at halftime.\n\n<strong>Off the Bench- </strong>both teams had key bench players in this game. Wayne\'s 6-2 junior Jacquel Bronaugh did some good things being physical underneath, as her game continues to develop. She moved over from Northmont during the summer and has fit in with the Warriors scheme of being strong underneath to compliment their solid guard play. Fairmont also has a newcomer as 5-10 senior Kyndall Ketterer who is multidimensional. She can score from the perimeter as shown by a huge three from deep in the corner that gave Fairmont a three-point lead late in the third period. She can also get to the rim and is strong enough to play physical and get to the line.\n\n<strong>Prospects- </strong>Both team obviously have bigtime college prospects with Westbeld (Notre Dame), Bartley (Belmont) and Hampton (Bowling Green) choosing their schools. Plus Bree Hall will go wherever she wants. But there are plenty of other players worth noting who will play at the next level.\n\nWayne boasts unsigned senior Jaida Wolfork, a 5-10 forward with a good inside-outside game with three-point range. Also watch for junior Alyssa Hargrove-Hall who is a 5-6 long guard who can run the floor and create plays. Lovie Malone is a 5-10 junior guard who has offers and is a steady player who gets the job done. Fairmont has Ketterer who is still unsigned but has a D2 offer. Makira Webster is a strong and skilled guard who can score and run the offense. She is also an unsigned senior as is Kierra Thornton who has really developed into a good prospect. Both Webster and Thornton worked well together in the backcourt for the Firebirds. Another one to watch down the road is 5-8 sophomore who I saw for the first time and she will be their main threat next year. She continues to grow her game and get better.\n\n<strong>Rematch set- </strong>these two teams will play again at Fairmont on January 29.','#1 2021 Hall hits buzzer beater for big win','','publish','open','open','','1-2021-hall-hits-buzzer-beater-for-big-win','','','2019-12-08 09:17:18','2019-12-08 15:17:18','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122413',0,'post','',0),
	(122426,1,'2019-12-09 07:38:03','2019-12-09 13:38:03','Each week on PGH Ohio, I will be posting and updating a Power Poll of teams in this Dayton area. The top five teams based on performance will be released every Sunday evening.\n\n<em>Week 3 (week ending Dec. 8)</em>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Division 1</span>\n\n<strong>1. Wayne (5-0)</strong> what a finish for the Warriors on Saturday in their game against previous #2 Fairmont. Trailed by five late in the third, then led by seven midway through the fourth only to have 5-11 Bree Hall (#1 2021) score the game winner at the buzzer for 51-49 win. Also defeated Beavercreek 64-43. Another big test coming Wednesday hosting Centerville.\n\n<strong>2. Fairmont (4-1)</strong> drops one spot after being #1 last week. Cruised past Springfield 86-33 earlier last week as senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madelyn-westbeld/\">Madeline Westbeld</a> (#1 2020) scored 29, senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madison-bartley/\">Madison Bartley</a> (#14 2020) added 28. Those two scored at will. Springfield senior Mickayla Perdue (reclassified to a senior) was held to 13. Travels to Beavercreek on Wednesday and hosts Centerville Saturday night.\n\n<strong>3. Springboro (4-0)</strong> impressive week with wins over Mason, Northmont and Miamisburg. Juniors <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jordan-hobbs/\">Jordan Hobbs</a> (6-1, Rice commit) and Peyton Nation (5-10) have been the offensive leaders early on for the Panthers. One game this week as they travel to Trotwood on Wednesday.\n\n<strong>4. Centerville (3-1)</strong> after a win over Springfield last week, the Elks have about as big of a week as you can have, traveling to #1 Wayne on Wednesday and #2 Fairmont on Saturday. To no surprise, 2022 #3 <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/cotie-mcmahon/\">Cotie McMahon</a> and 2021 #8 <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amy-velasco/\">Amy Velasco</a> have been the leaders, but the emergence of freshman <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kendal-george/\">Kendal George</a> has been impressive. The newcomer had five threes in their win over Springfield.\n\n<strong>5. Bellbrook (5-0)</strong> in a Division One world full of impressive GWOC schools, here is a Southwestern Buckeye League program who is just taking care of business and has won their first five games. 6-0 junior Bailey Zerby has been the early leader for the Golden Eagles, steady at 13 points per game. After that it has been a potpourri of different players who has contributed. Six players are averaging between 5-6 points per game and all of them can go double figures on any given night.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Division 2</span>\n\n<strong>1. Carroll (3-1)</strong> the defending state runner-up is off to a nice start, but will need to get their travel gear ready as they become road warriors again this week. After two games away from home last week, they play at Wilmington on Monday, at #3 CJ on Wednesday and at Badin on Saturday. An impressive start to the season for junior Megan Leraas <span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><strong>(pictured above)</strong></span>, while senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/julia-keller/\">Julia Keller</a> joins Leraas in double figures. As predicted, solid guard play from senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/allie-stefanek/\">Allie Stefanek</a>, junior Ava Lickliter and sophomore Sarah Ochs.\n\n<strong>2. Jonathan Alder (4-0)</strong> solid start to the season for the Pioneers as expected. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/abby-jones/\">Abby Jones</a> leads the team in points, rebounds, tied in steals and second in assists, while Sydney Bourquin is also averaging double figures in scoring, leads in assists and tied in steals. Bourquin also continues to set assist records at the school. The early surprise has been senior Melissa Walbom and a sophomore to watch is Mary Ferrito. JA plays at Urbana on Wednesday and hosts Bellefontaine on Saturday.\n\n<strong>3. Chaminade Julienne (5-1)</strong> impressive start for the Eagles, with wins against Alter and McNicholas last week. This will be a true test week for the Eagles, hosting Carroll on Wednesday and Roger Bacon on Saturday. A balanced team with seniors Jordyn Varise and Eve Monaghan both averaging low doubles, while senior Staci Greene is at nine. Monaghan had two double-doubles last week.\n\n<strong>4. Valley View (4-2)</strong> after a rough 0-2 start, the Spartans have started to tune things up with four straight wins. Three big wins last week over Edgewood 44-28, Oakwood 59-34 and Monroe 62-33. IUPFW signee senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/aubrey-stupp/\">Aubrey Stupp</a> currently leads the SWBL in scoring at 17.8. Valley View travels to Talawanda on Wednesday and head to Bellbrook on Saturday afternoon in a game PGH Ohio will be covering.\n\n<strong>5(tie). Eaton (4-0)</strong> a lot of early season success for the Eagles which includes solid wins against Madison, Greenville and most recently a good win over National Trail. Senior Bailey Shepherd (Indiana Tech signee) is right behind Stupp in scoring in the SWBL. 5-10 junior Lexi Miller had been strong in the early season. Tough week ahead with Ross, Bellbrook and Franklin.\n\n<strong>5(tie). Greenville (2-1)</strong> makes their debut in the top five after solid wins against D1 Troy and Fairborn. Senior Morgan Gilbert had the hot hand against Troy with 21 points and senior Haleigh Behnken (Edison State signee) added 15. They were 19-30 from the line (after going 21-40 the game prior in a two point loss) which doesn\'t help, but they the earned the win. Behnken came back with 18 on Saturday as they defeated Fairborn. Greenville hosts Butler on Wednesday and goes to Stebbins on Saturday morning.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Division 3</span>\n\n<strong>1. Versailles (5-1)</strong> Big comeback win for the Tigers on Saturday, defeating Miami East 48-37 behind 18 for 6-3 unsigned senior Brooke Stonebraker, 5-8 senior Danielle Kunk and UD volleyball recruit 6-1 senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lindsey-winner/\">Lindsey Winner</a> with nine. Miami East led 23-13 at the half. Also last week, Winner hit a 15-footer at the buzzer to give the Tigers a 42-40 victory over league foe Fort Recovery. Hosts Tipp Monday, Marion Local on Thursday and travels to Lima Bath on Saturday.\n\n<strong>2. Arcanum (4-1)</strong> after a tough loss back on opening weekend, the Trojans have won three straight including a 30 point win at Bethel. 5-8 unsigned senior Kayla O\'Daniel has been steady every night, while the youngsters <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/taylor-gray/\">Taylor Gray</a> (jr), <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madelyn-fearon/\">Madelyn Fearon</a> (soph) and Hailey Unger (soph) have all been producing at a solid rate. Arcanum hosts Preble Shawnee on Tuesday and travel to Miami East on Saturday.\n\n<strong>3. West Liberty Salem (5-1)</strong> lost to Fort Loramie in a big way last week, but bounced back with big wins over Triad and Northeastern. Junior Selena Weaver continues her hot start this season with 15 against Triad, and leads the Ohio Heritage Conference in field goal percentage. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/emily-hollar/\">Emily Hollar</a>, only a sophomore, is one to watch. WLS plays West Jefferson on Thursday.\n\n<strong>4. Greenon (3-0) </strong>makes their debut in the top 5 after starting the season with three consecutive wins. Unsigned senior Reagan Ware leads the conference in scoring at 20 ppg while 5-7 freshman Claire Henry is making a name for herself early. Senior Delaney Benedict has also played steady in the first three games. Greenon travels to Oakwood on Tuesday and heads to Southeastern Thursday.\n\n<strong>5. Anna (4-1)</strong> remains fifth despite a loss to New Bremen, after wins against Lehman and Russia last week. The Rockets return to action on Saturday against Houston.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Division 4</span>\n\n<strong>1 (tie). Tri Village (4-0)</strong> had a statement win last week with a 63-37 win against previous #3 Franklin Monroe. Freshman <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/morgan-hunt/\">Morgan Hunt</a> led with 20, freshman Riley Sagester added 14, unsigned 6-0 senior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/maddie-downing/\">Maddie Downing</a> scored 13, PGH top-5 2022 <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/meghan-downing/\">Meghan Downing</a> contributed eight, unsigned senior Trisa Porter also scored eight. Plays at Houston on Monday, hosts Mississinawa Valley on Thursday and travels to Northeastern IN on Saturday.\n\n<strong>1 (tie). Fort Loramie (5-0)</strong> this team is flat out impressive with their stifling defense. This week, they play New Knoxville and Jackson Center. They scored a school record 97 points on Saturday against Houston with sophomore Ava Sholtis scoring 19 points with five assists, Kennedi Gephart added 14 points, Taylor Ratermann and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/marissa-meiring/\">Marissa Meiring</a> each scored 12, Kenzi Hoelscher poured in 10.\n\n<strong>3. Mechanicsburg (6-0)</strong> the beat rolls on for a talented Indians squad. Wins last week against West Jefferson and Triad keep them unbeaten, and they travel to Fairbanks on Thursday and host Marysville on Saturday. Junior guard Grace Forrest is off to a solid start for Mechanicsburg, while unsigned senior Kasey Schipfer is playing at a high level.\n\n<strong>4. Minster (4-1)</strong> after a rough opener against Fort Loramie, the Wildcats have won four straight and moves up one spot. Earned wins last week against Parkway and Jackson Center. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ivy-wolf/\">Ivy Wolf</a> (#4 2021) led with 21 against Parkway, unsigned senior Averi Wolf added 12 and junior Janae Hoying scored 10. The Cats return to action this week at Delphos St. Johns on Thursday.\n\n<strong>5 (tie). Franklin Monroe (4-1)</strong> dropped a spot after a loss to co-#1 Tri Village. The Jets have been led by Kentucky Wesleyan signee <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/corina-conley/\">Corina Conley</a>, along with a plethora of outstanding perimeter guards. FM returns to action this week at Ansonia on Thursday.\n\n<strong>5 (tie). Legacy Christian (2-2)</strong> big win against Jefferson, and this week will bring high-scoring sophomore Angela Smith from Yellow Springs to battle the Knights.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Wayne takes over #1 spot in latest Dayton Power Poll','','publish','open','open','','wayne-takes-over-1-spot-in-latest-dayton-power-poll','','','2019-12-09 07:38:03','2019-12-09 13:38:03','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122426',0,'post','',0),
	(122429,1,'2019-12-08 11:12:40','2019-12-08 17:12:40','<strong>The <em>Top Prospect Classic</em> included:</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Henry Clay vs Bishop Brossart</li>\n 	<li>Campbell County vs Johnson Central</li>\n 	<li>Menifee County vs Washington County</li>\n 	<li>Notre Dame vs Dunbar</li>\n 	<li>Holy Cross (Covington) vs Jenkins</li>\n 	<li>Conner vs Butler</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>The Top Senior Performances: </strong></p>\n<strong>Kelsie Evans (Menifee County)</strong>\n\nIn Game #3, Senior Kelsie Evans took over the show. Menifee County defeated Washington County, 67-54. Evans ended the game with a game-high, 25 points. She attacked the paint with force and she easily finished with either hand under the basket. By her aggressiveness driving into the paint that sent her to the free throw line 8 times. She made 6 of her 8 free throws. She had a great shot and she was definitely the true leader for this Menifee County team.\n\n<strong>Mallory Holbrook (Campbell County)</strong>\n\nIn Game #2, Senior Mallory Holbrook was a physical force on the offensive end. Campbell County defeated Johnson Central, 72-55. Holbrook ended the game with 17 points and 4 rebounds. She was definitely the leader of this team as she had the ball in her hands the most for this Campbell County team. She was very physical on offense as she used her body to attack the inside. Her defense was also something to note as she made it very difficult for Johnson Central to score the ball down-low.\n\n<strong>Maddy Riley (Washington County)</strong>\n\nAlthough Washington County lost to Menifee County, Maddy Riley was very impressive. Riley ended the game with 20 points and 9 rebounds. She was the point guard and ran the show but she was also aggressive on the offensive glass. She was able to finish in between defenders and she also could hit the 3-ball. She tried to take control for Washington County in the 2nd Half as she scored 8 of her 20 in the 4th Quarter. I could sense she was an upperclassmen by the way she was handling the game and leading the team in points and rebounds.\n\n<strong>Maddie Cox (Henry Clay)</strong>\n\nHenry Clay was struggling as they played Bishop Brossart in the first game of the day. Senior Maddie Cox tried to lead Henry Clay back into the game but it just wasn\'t enough. Bishop Brossart ended up winning, 46-33. Cox scored all of her 12 points in the 2nd half. In fact, all of her 12 points were made up of 4 threes. She also came off the bench for Henry Clay. I wonder if Coach Sanford will decide to give her the starting spot after that shooting performance. She could really shoot the ball and tried everything in her power to pull her team back within striking distance.\n\n<strong>Tyra Murphy (Conner)</strong>\n\nIn the last game of the day, Conner lost in Overtime to Butler in a battle, 43-40. Tyra Murphy\'s performance for Conner is what kept this game close as it was the best game of the <em>Top Prospect</em> <em>Classic</em>. She ended the game with 11 points and 4 rebounds. She is a big body that uses her force inside on the defenders. She backs them down and she can finish under the basket really well. She can also shoot the ball as she had a sweet mid-range jumper. But most of her work came down-low in the post with her physical presence.\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Recap &amp; What\'s Up Next:</strong></p>\nThere were some great performances by Seniors in this <em>Classic</em>. These Seniors could really score the ball and they were the leaders out on the court whether it ended in a win or loss.\n\nUp next, I will be writing about the Top Junior Performances in this Classic.\n\n&nbsp;','Top Prospect Classic: Top Senior Performances','','publish','open','open','','top-prospect-classic-top-senior-performances','','','2019-12-08 11:12:40','2019-12-08 17:12:40','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122429',0,'post','',0),
	(122481,1,'2019-12-08 13:47:10','2019-12-08 19:47:10','We are done with the first week of the season and that means Player of the Week voting! Each week we will be taking five of the top performers from the last week and letting you vote for the Player of the Week! The poll will be posted each Sunday and voting ends on Tuesday at midnight. Let’s meet the five candidates below.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sharon-goodman/\">Sharon Goodman</a> | 2020 | Crestwood | 3 games, 87 points, 34/48 FG, 35 rebounds, 20 blocks</strong>\nGoodman was instrumental in leading Crestwood to three big wins this week. In the first game of the week, she had 29 points, 14 rebounds, and six blocks in a 48-37 win over Denver. She followed that up with 34 points, 15 rebounds, and eight blocks in a 67-44 win over North Fayette Valley. To round out the week, she had 24 points and six rebounds in a win over a very good Dike-New Hartford team. Goodman averaged 29 points a game this week and shot the ball at an insane rate in three wins.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/katie-keitges/\">Katie Keitges</a> | 2020 | Knoxville | 2 games, 64 points, 8 rebounds, 5 assists</strong>\nKeitges had 29 points, eight rebounds, and five assists in a 63-56 win over Van Meter. She then followed that up with a 35 point performance against Oskaloosa in a 66-24 win on Saturday evening. In both games, she led her team to the victory scoring the basketball.\n\n<strong>Alexa Ahrenholtz | 2021 | IKM-Manning | 3 games, 85 points, 27/41 FG, 17 rebounds, 19 steals</strong>\nAhrenholtz had three big games in her team\'s first three games of the year. She started the week off by dropping 28 points and grabbing six rebounds in the opening 70-66 come-from-behind win against Underwood. She then had 21 points and six steals in a huge win over Riverside, 74-14. Ahrenholtz followed that up the next night in a 21-point win over Panorama. In that game, she had 36 points and was 11-of-15 from the floor. She hit five 3-pointers in the game and added nine rebounds and eight steals to help her team to the win.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mallory-mcdermott/\">Mallory McDermott</a> | 2020 | Prairie | 1 game, 38 points, 14/19 FG, 8/11 3FG</strong>\nIn Prairie\'s lone game of the week, McDermott had the hot hand as she scored 38 points. She nailed eight 3-pointers in the game and helped Prarie to a big win over Iowa City West 78-52.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sasha-koenig/\">Sasha Koenig</a> | 2021 | West Branch | 3 games, 71 points, 18 assists, 19 steals</strong>\nIn the first game of the week for West Branch, Koenig had 27 points, 10 steals and 8 assists in a 70-36 win. She followed that up with 26 points and four assists the next night in a 59-40 win over Northeast. She ended her week in stellar fashion putting up 18 points, dishing out six assists, and nabbing five steals. It was a stat-stuffing weekend for Koenig.\n\nhttps://poll.fm/10474418','PGH Iowa Week 2 Player of the Week Voting','','publish','open','open','','pgh-iowa-week-2-player-of-the-week-voting','','','2019-12-08 13:47:10','2019-12-08 19:47:10','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122481',0,'post','',0),
	(122486,1,'2019-12-08 17:32:24','2019-12-08 23:32:24','<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/minnesota/more-content/high-school/team-rankings/\">Rankings</a>\n\nWith a new season comes new information, at least this season does. The ratings have been adjusted slightly, but mainly remain the same. What is new this season is the Strength of Record (SOR) value for each team. While the ratings are about what team is better if they were the play head to head, the SOR are a more accurate picture of where a team should be seeded.\n\nThe intent is provide another value for people to use when seeding teams. I will never claim to have the perfect answer for how to seed teams, but I believe this can provide more information for people to use when teams do not play similar schedules. One of the reasons I wanted to include this rating this season was because I am not a fan of using head to head to determine the seeding of teams. Can it be one piece of information? Yes. But my issue is when 25 of the 26 games a team plays are ignored because of a head to head result.\n\nIn order to come up with a method to seed teams, wins had to be given more value. What I came up with is a measurement of how difficult it would be for an average team to achieve the record each team currently has. All wins are given a positive value and all losses a negative value. Those values are assigned based on the percentage chance an average team would have to win the game.\n\nEarly season returns are solid as the team that sits with the highest SOR is Wayzata, followed by Hopkins, Rochester Lourdes, Park Center, and Marshall.\n\n<strong>Biggest Upset</strong>\n\nThis section will feature the most unlikely winners. When the preseason ratings are involved, the unlikely winners have a chance to be the better team, but we use the ratings at the time of the game to determine who goes here.\n\nChisholm 72, Bigfork 58 (0.01% chance of upset)\n\nBigfork is two years removed from being Mountain Iron-Buhl’s biggest challenger is section 7A and Chisholm has won a combined eight regular season games the past two years. The Bluestreaks have already won three games this year.\n\nHonorable Mention: North Lakes 36, Trinity School 33 (0.05%), Mounds Park 55, St. Croix Prep 50 (0.18%)\n\n<strong>Biggest Gainers</strong>\n\nThis section will be reserved for the teams that move up the rankings the most.\n\nA – Ely (preseason Class A #105, currently #66)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wins – at Nashwauk-Keewatin (58-24), at Greenway (60-51), International Falls (65-44)</li>\n 	<li>Losses – Two Harbors (52-47 OT)</li>\n</ul>\nAA – Mesabi East (preseason Class AA #53, currently #12)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wins – at Pequot Lakes (71-51), at Mountain Iron-Buhl (70-66), at Moose Lake-Willow River (83-68), Eveleth-Gilbert (57-27)</li>\n 	<li>Losses - none</li>\n</ul>\n[caption id=\"attachment_122553\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-122553 size-medium\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/KaylaBohr-NateWahl-300x197.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Kayla Bohr has helped lead Blaine to a 5-1 start. Photo courtesy of Nate Wahl, Prep Girls Hoops.[/caption]\n\nAAA – Red Wing (preseason Class AAA #29, currently #7)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wins – Plainview-Elgin-Millville (67-35), Goodhue (53-40), at Mankato West (66-57), Northfield (56-55)</li>\n 	<li>Losses – none</li>\n</ul>\nAAAA – Blaine (preseason Class AAAA #53, currently #32)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wins – Duluth East (82-50), at St. Francis (68-29), at Buffalo (53-48), Totino-Grace (51-41), Apple Valley (77-38)</li>\n 	<li>Losses – Providence Academy (72-69 OT)</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Biggest Fallers</strong>\n\nThis section will include the teams that fell down the rankings the most.\n\nA – Bigfork (preseason Class A #33, currently #78)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wins – none</li>\n 	<li>Losses – at Chisholm (72-56), Littlefork-Big Falls (42-30), at North Woods (54-43), at Cherry (61-24), Floodwood (50-28)</li>\n</ul>\nAA – Thief River Falls (preseason Class AA #38, currently #89)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wins – none</li>\n 	<li>Losses – at Bemidji (69-30), at Roseau (68-35), at Ada-Borup (46-32), N Barnesville (44-26)</li>\n</ul>\nAAA – Hibbing (preseason Class AAA #7, currently #31)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wins – at Greenway (64-40), Princeton (62-50)</li>\n 	<li>Losses – at Grand Rapids (59-53), Bemidji (74-63), North Branch (55-38)</li>\n</ul>\nAAAA – White Bear Lake (last week Class AAAA #26, currently #47)\n<ul>\n 	<li>Wins – Robbinsdale Armstrong (48-35), Irondale (66-36)</li>\n 	<li>Losses – Elk River (69-50), N Lakeville South (60-38), N Rosemount (55-33), at Park of Cottage Grove (47-36)</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Highest Scoring Games</strong>\n\nThe offense appears to be ahead of the defense early in th<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">e season as the average point total per game through the first 2+ weeks of the season was 107.1 points per game.</span>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Minnehaha Academy 89, Sauk Centre 86 (3 OT)</li>\n 	<li>Farmington 92, St. Michael-Albertville 79</li>\n 	<li>Robbinsdale Cooper 85, Holy Angels 82</li>\n 	<li>Stillwater 97, Woodbury 69</li>\n 	<li>Jackson County Central 91, Martin County West 75</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Predictions</strong>\n\nEach week I will list the computer predictions for some of the more interesting games around the state.\n\nMonday\n<ul>\n 	<li>Minneapolis South @ Anoka (Minneapolis South 67-63)</li>\n</ul>\nTuesday\n<ul>\n 	<li>Jordan @ Hutchinson (Hutchinson 66-65)</li>\n 	<li>Chaska @ Minnetonka (Chaska 70-69)</li>\n 	<li>St. Michael-Albertville @ Waconia (St. Michael-Albertville 84-78)</li>\n 	<li>Lake City @ Winona Cotter (Lake City 60-58)</li>\n</ul>\nThursday\n<ul>\n 	<li>East Grand Forks @ Pelican Rapids (Eas<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">t Grand Forks 56-50)</span></li>\n</ul>\nFriday\n<ul>\n 	<li>Rochester Lourdes @ Lake City (Rochester Lourdes 78-67)</li>\n</ul>\nSaturday\n<ul>\n 	<li>Holy Family @ Providence Academy (Providence Academy 64-61)</li>\n 	<li>Hermantown @ Proctor (Proctor 61-52)</li>\n</ul>\n<em><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">Top photo: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mara-braun/\">Mara Braun</a> and Wayzata hold the top spot in Strength of Record with wins over Eastview, Chaska, Lakeville North, Fergus Falls, Maple Grove, and Prior Lake. Photo courtesy of the Star Tribune.</span></em>','By the Numbers: What is Strength of Record?','','publish','open','open','','by-the-numbers-what-is-strength-of-record','','','2019-12-08 17:32:24','2019-12-08 23:32:24','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122486',0,'post','',0),
	(122504,1,'2019-12-09 15:34:41','2019-12-09 21:34:41','Mt. Zion held on for an Overtime victory at home on Saturday against Pana, 62-56. It was a back and forth affair with good energy and effort from both teams. In this article we examine 5 key takeaways from the game.\n<ol>\n 	<li><strong>Jillian Hamilton </strong>is a 5\'10 2022 from Pana. Jillian has a huge upside. She is strong and very athletic. When you see a girl that can consistently hit jumpers off the dribble and can shoot while fading one way or the other, you know you are seeing something different. Jillian has good control of her body and jumps well. She has the chance to be great if she can improve her ball handling and her shooting. Both are acceptable, but neither are elite. Both play well for a small college forward but she can be a D1 guard if she improves. She has that body and athletic ability.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Emma Ewing and Lainee Wolter </strong>form a very nice guard tandem for Mt. Zion. Both girls are smaller (5\'5-5\'6) guards that can do it all. The Lady Braves go as these two go. Lainee had 19 points and Emma had 12 points and 12 boards. Emma was really hot early and Lainee took over late. Lainee clinched the game in OT with some clutch free throw shooting. These girls both play very good defense and can handle the ball. Emma tends to play off the ball a little more and Lainee tends to play the point, but both seem confident in either role.These two are the kind of players that small colleges should looking at. They have extensive experience in school and AAU ball and can contribute in many ways.</li>\n 	<li>Pana has had a good start to their season. At 6-2 they are showing the ability to make some noise in the SCC this season. Seniors <strong>Sway Denton, Rylee Beck and Rhylee Freeman </strong>are starters that provide leadership and experience to lead Pana. Sway has the potential to be a double figure scorer each night for Coach Storm. In the Mt. Zion game Rhylee Freeman had a nice game hitting from the 3-point line. If they are going to go far, these 3 will have to be the leaders for the underclassmen.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Addison Rhoades and Taylor Fox</strong> are two seniors that add to the experienced lineup that Mt. Zion puts on the floor. Both girls are long and can score. Addison is 5\'10 and chipped in with 12 points and Taylor is 5\'9 and had 8. Both girls can score inside the 3 point line in a variety of ways with mid range jumpers and drives to the basket. <strong>Abby Scharf </strong>is a 5\'10 2022 that showed a nice shooting stroke with range out behind the arc. She hit a 3-point shot and had a nice release. Her shooting can really be a weapon as other teams concentrate of Wolter and Ewing.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Rachel Holthaus </strong>is a 5\'5 2022 point guard from Pana. Rachel had a nice game with 12 points and one huge game tying 3 point shot late in regulation. She handled pressure well and showed some nice moves getting to the basket. Rachel used a nice hesitation move a couple of times where she had the defender believing she was going to change direction and then went right back at them into the lane. She had a couple of nice finishes in the lane and nice assists when defenders came to help. She has excellent point guard instincts and can score. With continued or work on tightening up her ball handling Rachel has a bright future.</li>\n</ol>\nThis was an excellent early season matchup. Pana had just won a huge conference game over Greenville and Mt Zion is 6-2. So, both teams are  out to a good start and looking to continue to make some noise.\n\n&nbsp;','Pana vs Mt. Zion: 5 Takeaways','','publish','open','open','','pana-vs-mt-zion-5-takeaways','','','2019-12-09 15:34:41','2019-12-09 21:34:41','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122504',0,'post','',0),
	(122508,1,'2019-12-08 16:00:21','2019-12-08 22:00:21','Each Sunday we will be previewing the best games in the upcoming week. It is the first full week of games and there are going to be some very good matchups. Below you can find the top ten games around the state for Week #3.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong>Monday</strong>: Clear Lake (3-0) @ Mason City (4-0) @ 6:15PM\nThis might very well be one of the top games of the entire week. Clear Lake looks like a legitimate team early on but so does Mason City. However, Mason City has racked up some impressive wins while Clear Lake still hasn\'t been tested. They will be tested here in what could be a season-defining rivalry game for both teams.\n\n<strong>Monday</strong>: Southeast Polk (3-0) @ Dowling Catholic (3-0) @ 6:15PM\nBoth teams have gotten out to identical 3-0 starts and will meet on Monday night. This is a big conference matchup for both teams as they look to gain an upper hand early on. Dowling Catholic\'s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/caitlin-clark/\">Caitlin Clark</a> and Southeast Polk\'s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/grace-larkins/\">Grace Larkins</a> are both ranked as the top player in their class so this one should be entertaining at the least.\n\n<strong>Tuesday</strong>: Marquette Catholic (4-0) @ Maquoketa Valley (4-0) @ 6:00PM\nTuesday night we get a matchup between two teams who on the surface look really solid with 4-0 records, but haven\'t played anyone of note. Both teams are very similar statistically, but Marquette Catholic has a much better inside game as they average over 21 rebounds more than Maquoketa Valley. This will be an interesting game to track.\n\n<strong>Tuesday</strong>: Johnston (3-1) @ Waukee (3-0) @ 6:15PM\nJohnston has three big wins and a one-point loss to Cedar Falls while Waukee has three blowout wins. Johnston has won the last three matchups between the two schools but look to have their deepest team in years. This one is going to come down to which set of guards play a better game and which take takes care of the ball.\n\n<strong>Tuesday</strong>: Prairie (2-0) @ Waterloo West (3-0) @ 7:30PM\nBoth of these teams have run through their opponents to a perfect record thus far. Prairie has had the tougher slate so far but Waterloo West is just dismantling their opponents. This game will come down to how well Waterloo West can slow down the guards for Prairie. I think we\'ll see a high scoring battle in this one.\n\n<strong>Thursday</strong>: Clear Creek-Amana (2-1) @ Grinnell (3-1) @ 6:15\nBoth of these teams have looked solid in the early going as each of their losses have been to very solid groups in close games. Clear Creek-Amana will likely be 3-1 coming into the game and will look to slow down a Grinnell team that will put up as many 3-pointers as possible. You\'re not going to beat Grinnell unless you have a good defensive plan.\n\n<strong>Friday</strong>: Carroll (3-1) @ Bondurant-Farrar (3-0) @ 6:00PM\nBoth of these teams have looked very good early in the year and Carroll\'s lone loss came to Glenwood, one of the top teams in 3A this year. Bondurant-Farrar has been very balanced so far this season so this should be a very good test for both teams in a conference battle.\n\n<strong>Friday</strong>: AGWSR (3-1) @ West Marshall (3-0) @ 6:15PM\nAGWSR started the year with two huge wins but then fell to Hampton-Dumont-CAL before taking a two-point win over BCLUW. West Marshall has taken care of business so far this season and has gotten three big wins. The winner of this game will prove they are legit, while the loser will have some work to do.\n\n<strong>Saturday</strong>: ADM (3-1) @ Gilbert (3-2) @ 2:30PM\nMuch like the AGSWR and West Marshall game, this is one where we will be able to find out if both teams are legit. ADM is 3-1 with a loss to Ballard and Gilbert sits at 3-2 with a loss to Iowa City West and North Polk. If ADM wants to prove themselves, they need to win this game while Gilbert will need to win this to likely complete a 3-0 week.\n\n<strong>Saturday</strong>: Algona (2-1) @ Bishop Garrigan (3-0)\nBishop Garrigan is going to contend for the 1A state title this year, but the three teams they\'ve played so far aren\'t very good, to put it lightly. With a game against Algona this week we will really be able to see what Bishop Garrigan is made of. This would be a huge win for Algona as well.','Games of the Week: Week 3','','publish','open','open','','games-of-the-week-week-3','','','2019-12-08 16:00:21','2019-12-08 22:00:21','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122508',0,'post','',0),
	(122523,1,'2019-12-08 16:40:14','2019-12-08 22:40:14','<strong>THE WEEK THAT WAS:</strong>  We got to see alot of high-profile match-ups this past weekend, especially in Class A.  A few teams surprised, including Omaha Northwest going 2-0 to start out the season.  In our lower classes, Omaha Mercy starts out 2-0 for the first time in recent memory, along with Bennington and Platteview also off to a nice start.  Again, you don\'t want to say too much about the opening weekend, but these teams got off to a nice start for the 2019-20 season.\n\n<strong>THREE THINGS I LIKE:</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li>Boy, can Millard South score the basketball!  It is obviously early, but anyone that tops 100 points in a regulation game and is averaging 94 points a game is quite impressive.  As the competition level picks up for the Patriots, that number is sure to become smaller, but our preseason pick to win Class A is off to a great start.</li>\n 	<li>Equally as impressive is Lincoln Pius X, with two impressive victories over Omaha Marian and Lincoln Southwest.  After losing an excruciating semi-final last season to Millard North, Pius looks like they might be the second best team in Class A.</li>\n 	<li>Chadron makes a nice run in the Western Trails Tournament, defeating Class B contender Scottsbluff and then Class A North Platte in the championship game.  A nice start for one of the traditional powers of Nebraska\'s Panhandle region.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong>PLAYER OF THE WEEK: </strong>As stated before, Lincoln Pius X opened with two impressive wins, and they were lead by their catalyst, 6\'3\" South Dakota State commit Alexis Markowski, Markowski had 15 points in their opening victory against Omaha Marian (a game where the Thunderbolts lead 52-14 at one point), then followed that up with 33 points in a convincing victory over Lincoln Southwest.  Markowski and the Thunderbolts have hit the ground running to start the new campaign.\n\n<strong>GAME OF THE WEEK –&gt; LINCOLN-OMAHA CORRIDOR:</strong> In Class A, the best, most intriguing match-up of the week is this coming Saturday when Lincoln East travels to Omaha to visit the surprising 2-0 Omaha Northwest Huskies.  Lincoln East, which returns all five starters from their state sem-final team last year, will be looking to get a nice wild-card points victory early in the season, while Omaha Northwest will be looking for an early signature victory to show that they are here to stay in the ranks of the Class A elite.\n\n<strong>GAME OF THE WEEK –&gt; STATE-WIDE:</strong> Perhaps the best game of the week will take place in Nebraska City, where 2-0 Nebraska City Lourdes will take on one of the top ranked clubs in Class D2, Falls City Sacred Heart.  Both teams figure to be heavily involved in what happens in their class during late February and early March, so this will be a good measuring stick for both squads and allow both of them to see where they stand.\n\n<b>Honorable Mention: </b>Guardian Angels Central Catholic at Wynot (12/12), North Central at CWC (Thursday, 12/12), Beatrice at Crete (Thursday, 12/12), Norris at Elkhorn (Friday, 12/13), Crete at Grand Island Northwest (Friday, 12/13), Millard North at Lincoln Southwest (Saturday, 12/14), BDS at Lawrence-Nelson (12/14)\n\nCLASS A ELITE EIGHT: Millard South, Lincoln East, Westside, Papillion LaVista, Lincoln Northeast, Fremont, Lincoln Pius X, Elkhorn\n\nCLASS B ELITE EIGHT: Grand Island Northwest, Crete, Norris, Beatrice, Sidney, Bennington, Scottsbluff, York\n\nCLASS C1 ELITE EIGHT: Broken Bow, North Bend-Central, Lincoln Chrisitan, Milford, Ogallala, Wahoo, O’Neill, Chadron\n\nCLASS C2 ELITE EIGHT: Hastings St. Cecilia, Crofton, Fillmore Central, Grand Island Central Catholic, Nebraska City Lourdes, Oakland-Craig, Centennial (Utica), Superior\n\nCLASS D1 ELITE EIGHT: CWC, Weeping Water, Pleasanton, Dundy County-Stratton, Humphery/ Lindsay Holy Family, Johnson-Brock, Overton, Pender\n\nCLASS D2 ELITE EIGHT: Falls City Sacred Heart, Ewing, Humphery St. Francis, Wynot, BDS, Loomis, Lawrence-Nelson, Cody-Kilgore','This Week in Nebraska Girl\'s Basketball-December 8th, 2019','','publish','open','open','','this-week-in-nebraska-girls-basketball-december-8th-2019','','','2019-12-08 16:40:14','2019-12-08 22:40:14','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122523',0,'post','',0),
	(122543,1,'2019-12-08 17:30:22','2019-12-08 23:30:22','<strong>BLAINE-- </strong>Prep Girls Hoops Minnesota took in the battle between the Blaine Bengals (5-1)and the Apple Valley Eagles (0-5)  on Saturday afternoon in Blaine. Here are Nate\'s standouts from Blaine\'s 77-38 rout of the Apple Valley Eagles.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kalena-myers/\">Kalena Myers</a>, Guard, Apple Valley (2020)</strong>\n\nMyers was a player that although started with limited long-range shot production, ended as one of the top two scorers from the Eagles. Meyers battled hard and deserves to be one of the key contributors that kept Apple Valley present in this game.\n\n<strong>Madison Hoehne, Guard, Blaine (2021)</strong>\n\nHoehne played extremely well in this one as a key player off the ball for the Bengals. She did have her fair share of points, but was one of Blaine\'s key contributors as far as rebounds and dishing the ball to the right player at the right time type of player. She gets my team player of the game in this one.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/chyna-young/\">Chyna Young</a>, Guard, Apple Valley (2021)</strong>\n\nYoung was not only the leading scorer for the Eagles, but she was also the hardest worker I saw on Saturday afternoon for this struggling Apple Valley squad. Finishing with 9 points, Young was a player, in my opinion, should have played more minutes in the 1st half, which would have given Apple Valley a loss by a better margin. Chyna was a physical player on Saturday and not only wasn\'t afraid to dribble drive on the Bengals defense but did everything she could to cash in on key rebounds and took the ball to the rim regardless of the size of the player that was in front of her from the Bengals.\n\n<strong>Anna Garfield, Guard, Blaine (2020)</strong><span style=\"font-size: 1.125rem; letter-spacing: 0px;\">Garfield was another key player against the Apple Valley Eagles. Finishing with 16 points, Garfield continued her stellar senior campaign with the Bengals by using her quick shot and dribble and shoot technique with ease against the weaker Apple Valley defense. Garfield has been a diamond in the rough player for Prep Girls Hoops this season, as she has made a significant difference for the Bengals offense this season.</span>\n\n<strong>Game MVP: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kayla-bohr/\">Kayla Bohr</a>, Forward, Blaine ( #133 in our Class of 2020 rankings)</strong>\n\nThe second chance opportunities for Bohr is what made her overpower the Eagles defense with ease. Finishing with 29 points on the night, Bohr raised her stock a fair amount by her rebounding ability plus her ability to score at will against the smaller post of Apple Valley. Bohr is was a grinder in this one, and never was afraid to muscle up against the Eagles to bring her team over a dominating victory against struggling Apple Valley (0-5).\n\nBlaine (5-1) will start their conference play against Anoka (2-2) on Tuesday night at home.\n\nApple Valley (0-5) will also go home on Tuesday night and play a tough Lakeville North (2-2) team that features <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-jensen/\">Lauren Jensen</a></strong>, who is averaging 23.5 ppg thus far this season for the Panthers and was PGH Minnesota\'s AAU player of the year in 2018','Bohr and the Bengals Routed Apple Valley 77-38','','publish','open','open','','bohr-and-the-bengals-routed-apple-valley-77-38','','','2019-12-08 17:30:22','2019-12-08 23:30:22','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122543',0,'post','',0),
	(122545,1,'2019-12-08 18:35:46','2019-12-09 00:35:46','I try to watch as many different brands of girls high school basketball as I can, both throughout the course of the season and during any given week. That was certainly the case during week 3 of the 2019-20 campaign, which offered a veritable buffet of basketball. It began Monday with a small-town encounter featuring Lake Crystal-Welcome Memorial at Medford and ended with a seven-game showcase event in the far Southwestern corner of the state. In between there was a 4A upset by East Ridge on Tuesday, an all-Minneapolis contest on Wednesday, some religious warfare on Thursday, and the ginormous Farmington vs Hopkins show on Friday.\n\nHere is a brief recap of the Week That Was #3 with one proviso: everything Hopkins vs Farmington was covered in my Saturday recap of the game and you can <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/12/hopkins-tops-farmington-in-the-game-of-the-week/\">read it here</a>.\n\n<strong>PLAYER OF THE WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Winner – <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sadie-voss/\">Sadie Voss</a></strong>, sophomore guard, Jackson County Central. The uber-athletic Voss dominated my final game of the week, JCC’s 86-71 victory over New Ulm in the last  game of the Big South Showcase in Jackson. Voss is a volleyball-first athlete with limited AAU exposure but huge basketball upside. We’ll have lots more on Sadie on our Big South recaps in the next couple of days.</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>NEWCOMER OF THE WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Co-winners – <strong>Grace Knupp</strong> and <strong>Emily Christenson</strong>, freshmen, East Ridge. ‘How the heck did East Ridge beat Roseville by 13?’ is a question I heard from several people during the week. The answer is simple: the Grace and Emily Show, with an ample assist from 6’4 sophomore post <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/britt-carlson/\">Britt Carlson</a> </strong>and 6’2 senior forward<strong> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kate-burns/\">Kate Burns</a> </strong>(St. Thomas). The 5’8 Knupp was cool under pressure, ran the offense well and distributed the ball from the point like a seasoned veteran. The 5’10 Christenson is long, lanky and skilled, and she scored 18 points to lead the Raptors to their first-ever win at Roseville. The trio went on to spark the Raptors to a 74-61 defeate of  Cretin-Derham Hall later in the week. We’ll have more on East Ridge when we take a look at the Suburban East conference this week.</li>\n 	<li>Runner-up – <strong>Ella Pritchard</strong>, freshman forward, Cristo Rey Jesuit. Wednesday at Minneapolis Southwest was our first look at the 5’11 9th grader. She’s definitely green, but with terrific length, nice athleticism and tremendous leaping ability, Ella has the raw material to work with. She reminds me a lot what former Minneapolis Edison forward <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sierra-morrow/\">Sierra Morrow</a></strong> looked like as a 9th grader, and Morrow has turned out to be an outstanding collegiate player. Pritchard is leading the Pumas in scoring at 14.5 points per game. She’ll play AAU next summer for Derek Turner’s Minnesota Stars team.</li>\n</ul>\nWe’ll have more newcomers to talk about in our coverage of the Big South Showcase.\n\n<strong>COACH OF THE WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Winner – Rafe York &amp; Janet Haren, co-head coaches, Jackson County Central. York and Haren took over a mediocre program at JCC this fall and immediately instituted David Arsenault’s Grinnell System, which is a variation of the famed run-and-gun approach utilized by Paul Westhead at Loyola-Marymount University in the early 1980s. The system relies on applying constant defensive pressure with a full-court press while substituting platoons of five players every couple of minutes. In Saturday’s win over New Ulm, 14 or 15 Huskies saw action and New Ulm was under constant siege from start to finish. The system is working. JCC is 3-0, averaging 88 points per game, and the athletes are clearly having a blast flying all over the court in chaotic fashion. Kudos to coaches York and Haren for daring to be different.</li>\n 	<li>Runner-up – Greg Wilson, New Life Academy. I watched Wilson direct his 2020 MN/WI Force AAU team over the past few summers and have always been impressed with his passion, preparation and positive approach. It was certainly on display at New Life on Thursday night in Woodbury as the Eagles came from 10 down in the final couple of minutes to beat Southwest Christian 73-72 in overtime. Scrappy senior guard <strong>Carly Hager</strong> scored 30 points for New Life, which is led by junior guard <strong>Bethany Brocker</strong>. I liked what I saw from 5’10 senior forward <strong>McKayla Montgomery</strong> and 5’8 sophomore guard <strong>Mallory Moseman</strong>. Sophomore <strong>Kaitlyn Groeneweg</strong> is a terrific shooter who isn’t afraid to get in the trenches and be physical. Southwest Christian senior guard <strong>Lily Schwen</strong>, who is weighing D3 opportunities, scored 19 and was very good. SWC’s best prospect is 5’10 <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/chloe-brunsberg/\">Chloe Brunsberg</a></strong>, who is in the Prep Girls Hoops Freshmen 50.</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>TEAM OF THE WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Winner – East Ridge. The Raptors didn’t win a game during the 2017-18 season. Last year East Ridge was better, but nothing prepared us for what we saw this week. With wins over Roseville and Cretin, the Raptors appear to have taken flight.</li>\n 	<li>Runner-up – Medford. Monday night’s game against Lake Crystal-Wellcome Memorial was Medford’s first contest of the season. With a roster full of accomplished volleyball players still trying to find their basketball legs, the Tigers got off to a slow start. It didn’t last long, though, thanks largely to talented wing <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/emma-kniefel/\">Emma Kniefel</a></strong>, the #54-ranked senior in the state. Emma came to life in the second half, finishing with 18 points to give Medford a 64-55 win. In doing so the home team beat a very good LCWM team that includes three nice prospects – freshman <strong>Olivia Harazin</strong>, junior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lakesha-carter/\">Lakesha Carter</a></strong> and senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexi-cloyd/\">Lexi Cloyd</a></strong>. Harazin is in her third season as the Knights point guard and her maturation is going very nicely. Cloyd is one of the best three-point shooters in the state. Carter is an aggressive but undersized 5’8 forward with a big motor and a scorer’s touch. We’ll also be keeping an eye on 2024 prospect <strong>Katelin Flack</strong>, a strong, stocky guard who shows promise.</li>\n</ul>\n<strong><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-122558\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Lakers-trio-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"400\" height=\"263\" /></strong>\n\n<strong>A trio of talented Lakers</strong>\n\nWednesday’s night’s Minneapolis Southwest vs Cristo Rey encounter was a strange one. The Lakers jumped out to a 22-0 lead thanks to the melodic basketball stylings of the above trio –  <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jhanae-green/\">Jhanae Green</a></strong> (left), <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/virginia-johnson/\">Virginia Johnson</a> </strong>(center) and<strong> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/josie-igherighe/\">Josie Igherighe</a> </strong>(right). When the subs were inserted, however, things went south in a hurry and the Pumas scored a dozen straight points. In the end Southwest’s talented youngsters regained control of the proceedings and cruised to a 69-32 victory. Johnson scored 16 points in the win while Green and Igherighe had 15 apiece.\n\n<strong><img class=\"alignright wp-image-122559\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Ruzek-300x291.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"230\" height=\"223\" />MILESTONES</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Senior guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/carla-meyer/\">Carla Meyer</a></strong> of Totino-Grace became the 6th Eagle in school history to top 1,000 career points.</li>\n 	<li>Senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/myia-ruzek/\">Myia Ruzek</a></strong> (center of photo) is now the all-time leading scorer for Lewiston-Altura, having eclipsed the 1,468 mark.</li>\n 	<li>Mesabi East senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ava-hill/\">Ava Hill</a></strong> surpassed the 2,000-point milestone. In the same game sophomore guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/natalie-mikrot/\">Natalie Mikrot</a></strong> of Moose Lake-Willow River topped 1,000.</li>\n 	<li>Holy Angels junior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/frankie-vascellaro/\">Frankie Vascellaro</a></strong>, who is ranked #19 in the 2021 class, also surpassed 1,000 by scoring 16 points. 11 rebounds and 7 assists in a win over Minnehaha Academy.</li>\n 	<li>Plainview-Elgin-Millville point guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/macy-holtz/\">Macy Holtz</a></strong> also reached 1,000.</li>\n 	<li>At Lakeville North senior guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-jensen/\">Lauren Jensen</a></strong> set the all-time school three-point shooting mark with 199 for her career. In doing so she passed the great <strong>Rachel Banham</strong>, who plays for Connecticut of the WNBA and is an assistant coach at Roseville.</li>\n 	<li>Senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mallory-brake/\">Mallory Brake</a></strong> on Friday became the second Hastings Raider to reach 2,000 career points.  <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/krystal-carlson/\">Krystal Carlson</a></strong> (University of Sioux Falls) finished with 2,251.</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>5 GAMES TO SEE THIS WEEK</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Monday – 6 p.m., Alexandria at Big Lake</li>\n 	<li>Tuesday – 7 p.m., DeLaSalle at Hopkins</li>\n 	<li>Thursday – 7:30 p.m., Austin at Mankato West</li>\n 	<li>Friday – 7 p.m., Eden Prairie at Chaska</li>\n 	<li>Saturday – HVL-TRC Showdown in Rochester all day</li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><em>Top photo: Frankie Vascellaro of Holy Angels topped 1,000 points this week. (Photo courtesy of StarTribune)</em></span>','The Week That Was #3: A buffet of basketball','','publish','open','open','','the-week-that-was-3-a-buffet-of-basketball','','','2019-12-08 18:35:46','2019-12-09 00:35:46','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122545',0,'post','',0);
