	(122659,1,'2019-12-09 12:00:19','2019-12-09 18:00:19','This past Saturday was the season’s first installment of the Chicagoland Invitational Showcase, hosted by Fremd High School. The event displayed eleven games featuring several of Illinois’ top teams, in addition to top teams from Wisconsin (Beaver Dam) and Indiana (Crown Point). With these great teams, came dozens of high-level and intriguing players. Here are a few of my biggest takeaways from the day:\n\nEveryone knows about Marist’s standout Guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sydney-affolter/\">Sydney Affolter</a></strong>, and for good reason. She’s a dynamic Guard who can do a lot of things at a high level and is a top player in her class. What people will soon know, though, is how good the Point Guard duo of <strong>Jenna Ryan</strong> and <strong>Kira Chivers</strong> is for this Marist team. Ryan is a 5’6” Senior that handles the ball well with speed and makes plays happen in the lane, both passing and scoring. Chivers, a 5’2” Sophomore, is also quick with the ball and excels in transition. She finishes well at the hoop and can step outside and knock down shots at a consistent rate.\n\nWhen Nazareth Academy lost All-Stater <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/annie-stritzel/\">Annie Stritzel</a> to graduation last year, I was curious to know who would step up and help out Loyola commit <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kaylen-evans/\">Kaylen Evans</a></strong>. It appears that a couple of underclassmen are already filling that void nicely. Sophomore <strong>Janeth Resendez</strong> is a 5’6” Combo Guard that shoots the ball well from deep. She plays defense well and takes care of the ball on the offensive end. In addition, 5’9” Freshman <strong>Grace Carstensen</strong> provides great length and the ability to cause havoc in a stingy zone defense. She, too, displayed a consistent ability to knock down shots from outside with a good-looking form.\n\nA team that many consider to be the best in state at 4A, it’s not a surprise that Benet Academy’s depth is the real deal. Everyone knows the stars and high major college commits, but there is very little drop-off when you look to the bench. 5’8” Junior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/molly-sheehan/\">Molly Sheehan</a></strong> led the Redwings in scoring with 19 points, hitting on 5 three-pointers. 5’11” Senior <strong>Allison Forney</strong> provides good length and athleticism and gives solid minutes on defense. And Senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexi-moriarty/\">Lexi Moriarty</a></strong> does much of the same, while also contributing as a consistent shooter and is active in the transition game.\n\nAfter a deep run in the postseason last year, many saw Evanston as one of the teams to beat in 2019-2020, and they have done nothing but prove that so far this season. Seniors <strong>Ambrea Gentle</strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jayla-turchin/\">Jayla Turchin</a></strong> are elite in the post, making it difficult for teams to match up with the two of them. Turchin has such a well-rounded skillset, being able to score from any level, that matching up with her alone is a nightmare. 5’8” Senior PG <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kayla-henning/\">Kayla Henning</a></strong> runs the offense well and can give you scoring when needed. There’s so many options on this Evanston team, opposing coaches will have fits trying to game plan against them.\n\nI’ve watched Kenwood twice this year now and, boy, are they going to cause problems this season. Led by Sophomore <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brianna-mcdaniel/\">Brianna McDaniel</a></strong> (PGH IL #1 Ranked Player in 2022), this team is relentless. <strong>Zoe Belcher</strong>, a 5’11” Junior Guard, is as athletic of a post player as you will find. Her strength and quickness are tough for opposing post players to defend, in addition to her ability to knock down mid-range jumpers. 5’8’’ Sophomore <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/whitney-dunn/\">Whitney Dunn</a></strong> has turned into a high-level shooter, which gives McDaniel and Belcher someone to stretch the floor, to go along with Senior <strong>Breeyona Burrell</strong>.\n\nMontini’s season ended last year in the Sectional Championship to a red-hot Benet squad, but the Lady Broncos bring nearly everyone back this year. Sophomore <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophie-sullivan/\">Sophie Sullivan</a></strong> is a terrific lead guard that can knock down shots from deep, the trio of <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/taylor-charles/\">Taylor Charles</a></strong>, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tatiana-thomas/\">Tatiana Thomas</a></strong>, and <strong>Taris Thornton</strong> are each 6’+ athletes that can play inside and out, giving teams fits on how to guard them, and two Freshmen in <strong>Maddie Saracco</strong> and <strong>Lexi Salazar</strong> are already giving solid minutes.\n\nMother McAuley may have lost an All-State player in <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/grace-hynes/\">Grace Hynes</a> and key floor general in Nikki Murphy, but they are still the same competitive group that will be in every game they play. Lewis commit <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jenna-badali/\">Jenna Badali</a></strong> is a star All-State player, and players such as Sophomore <strong>Isabella Finnegan</strong> and Senior Point Guard <strong>Alexis Mayer</strong> are already proving to be outstanding contributors.','Chicagoland Invitational Showcase: Key Takeaways','','publish','open','open','','chicagoland-invitational-showcase-key-takeaways','','','2019-12-09 12:00:19','2019-12-09 18:00:19','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122659',0,'post','',0),
	(122683,1,'2019-12-09 10:05:06','2019-12-09 16:05:06','<strong>The <em>Top Prospect Classic</em> included:</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Henry Clay vs Bishop Brossart</li>\n 	<li>Campbell County vs Johnson Central</li>\n 	<li>Menifee County vs Washington County</li>\n 	<li>Notre Dame vs Dunbar</li>\n 	<li>Holy Cross (Covington) vs Jenkins</li>\n 	<li>Conner vs Butler</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Top Junior Performances: </strong></p>\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/marie-kiefer/\">Marie Kiefer</a> (Bishop Brossart)</strong>\n\nStanding at about 6 foot 3, Marie was excellent for Bishop Brossart in their victory over Henry Clay. She won Player of the Game with 20 points, 13 rebounds, and 1 block. She is an offensive threat down-low because of her amazing length. She is also a defensive threat inside the paint because of her ability to contest shots and grab defensive boards. She took over in 3Q as she made her presence felt with 5 points &amp; 6 rebounds. She has excellent post skills and her ability to finish under the basket is one of the best. Top 10 Player in the 2021 Class, according to PrepGirlsHoops (KY).\n\n<strong>Dynastee White (Butler)</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-122788\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/dynwhite-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nThe Junior point guard was absolutely incredible in this game. She missed two go-ahead FTs towards the end-of-regulation but she kept her composure and had all of Butler\'s points in OT. In fact, she scored the game winning And-1 and won the Player of the Game Award with 17 points and 7 rebounds. She has great size for her position and she is excellent at making decisions when taking care of the ball. She can finish at the rim and she isn\'t afraid to shoot the deep ball either. Great game from Dynastee and the Butler Bearettes in the OT win over Conner, 43-40.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kelsie-woodard/\">Kelsie Woodard</a> (Menifee Co.)</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-122790\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/woodard-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nWoodard knows how to draw contact as she went to the line 8 times and made 5 of them. She is a glass cleaner as she recorded 12 rebounds. Kelsie ended the game with a double-double with 17 points and 12 rebounds and the victory over Washington County. She likes to attack the paint and finish under the basket as all over points were in the paint. Junior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kelsie-woodard/\">Kelsie Woodard</a> and Senior Kelsie Evans were a dynamic duo and will have to carry this team throughout the season. They combined for 42 points of their 67.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sammi-sites/\">Sammi Sites</a> (Johnson Central)</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-122791\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/sites-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nThe Top-35 Junior in KY loves to attack inside the paint and draws a lot of contact. She made 14 of her 16 free throw attempts. She ended the game with 20 points and 8 rebounds. She is aggressive on both ends of the floor as she\'s causing contact offensively and going up for rebounds on the defensive end. She is very shifty with the ball and she can easily maneuver through multiple defenders. 14 of her 20 points came at the free throw line and the remaining points were two 3-pointers. She has an excellent jump shot.\n\n<strong>Grace Bezold (Holy Cross - Covington) </strong>\n\nBezold can really shoot the ball. She made three 3-pointers in their victory over Jenkins High School. She is long and can rebound really well. She ended the game with 19 points and 6 rebounds. She\'s not just a shooter though, she loves to attack the rim and get her baskets that way too. Bezold went on to win Player of the Game as she led Holy Cross in the big win, 55-25.\n\n<strong>Jerrica Thacker (Jenkins)</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-122792\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/thacker-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nJenkins really struggled the entire game against Holy Cross but Jerrica Thacker did not. She had 21 of Jenkins\' 25 points. She can really shoot the ball. I think she had to be the best shooter in this Classic as she made six 3s. She even hit a half-court buzzer beater at the end of the 1st Quarter. Even though they lost by 30, Thacker showed heart and she had the green light every single time she touched the ball. Great shooter.\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Recap &amp; What\'s Next</strong></p>\nThis <em>Classic</em> was loaded with Juniors. Some of the best talent here were Juniors.\n\nTomorrow I will release the Top Sophomores from the<em> Top Prospect Classic.</em>','Top Prospect Classic: Top Junior Performances','','publish','open','open','','top-prospect-classic-top-junior-performances','','','2019-12-09 10:05:06','2019-12-09 16:05:06','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122683',0,'post','',0),
	(122694,1,'2019-12-09 11:58:38','2019-12-09 17:58:38','With the first week of the season in the books, we had a lot of very qualified nominees for our Player of the Week poll. We whittled the list down to the top 10 nominees. Polls are open until noon on Friday!\n\n<strong>CAL\'s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/shelby-calhoun/\">Shelby Calhoun</a> - </strong>The Cal Senior had 19 points, 10 rebounds and 10 assists against Moore. Followed up with 10 points, 10 rebounds, 5 steals and 4 blocks against Butler. 8 points, 16 rebounds and 3 assists against Whitehaven (TN) and 19 points, 20 rebounds, 7 assists and 3 blocks in a win over Arlington (TN).\n\n<strong>Henderson County\'s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/emilee-hope/\">Emilee Hope</a> - </strong>On Monday, Hope had 30 points, 11 rebounds and 7 assists against Apollo. Friday she went for 22 points and 6 rebounds against McCracken County then finished the week with 21 points and 6 rebounds against Vincennes Lincoln.\n\n<strong>North Laurel\'s Halle Collins - </strong>Collins is only a 7th grader but she put up 11 points and 8 rebounds against Southwestern and 27 points, 16 rebounds and 2 assists against Marion County.\n\n<strong>Owensboro Catholic\'s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/hannah-mckay/\">Hannah McKay</a> - </strong>The Murray State commit scored 21 points and grabbed 7 boards against Castle (IN) then had 26 points and 20 rebounds against Bowling Green before finishing with 15 points and 9 rebounds against Pope John Paul II (TN).\n\n<strong>Owen County\'s Carly Smith - </strong>The 8th grade point guard scored 41 points, dished 7 assists, pulled down 6 rebounds and pilfered 4 steals in 2 games for the Owls.\n\n<strong>Madison Southern\'s Sam Cornelison - </strong>The Junior from Richmond had 20 points, 7 rebounds and 6 steals against Powell County. 12 points, 12 rebounds and 2 steals against Scott County. and finished the week with 22 points, 5 rebounds and 3 steals against Somerset.\n\n<strong>Greenwood\'s Leah Trinh - </strong>Another 8th grader, Leah scored 17 points and dished 6 assists against Glasgow then had a 17 point, 7 assist game against Allen County-Scottsville.\n\n<strong>Southern\'s Kaela Ballard - </strong>The freshman from Louisville scored 31 points and grabbed 8 rebounds against Fairdale then added 17 points against Brown and 20 points against Western in a busy week.\n\n<strong>Russell\'s Shaelyn Steele - </strong>Another 8th grader, Steele hails from Russell where she put up games of 16 points and 8 rebounds against South Charleston, 13 points and 10 rebounds against Johnson Central and 25 points and 11 rebounds against West Carter.\n\n<strong>Beth Haven\'s Delanie White - </strong>The Senior had 15 points and 11 rebounds against Highlands Latin then followed that by leading Beth Haven to their first district win since 2010 when her 21 points and 18 rebounds helped Beth Haven beat Valley.\n\nhttps://poll.fm/10474595','POLL: PGH Kentucky Player of the Week (Week 1)','','publish','open','open','','poll-pgh-kentucky-player-of-the-week-week-1','','','2019-12-09 11:58:38','2019-12-09 17:58:38','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122694',0,'post','',0),
	(122705,1,'2019-12-08 23:58:22','2019-12-09 05:58:22','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After a strong offseason on the summer circuit, Columbia Hickman point guard  </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/maci-kuchta/\">Maci Kuchta</a> i</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">s gearing up for a big season with the Lady Kewpies.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A 5’3 point guard, Kuchta likes to play a fast paced style of play. She runs the floor well, enjoys the drive and kick game and can pull up from 3-point range. Kuchta has terrific court vision and the ability to distribute the ball. She is coming off a season in which she averaged 12.6 points, including several games of more than 20 points.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I definitely filled a bigger role last year both in scoring and leadership wise and I look forward to seeing what this year brings,” she says.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Kuchta spent the offseason running with</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">  17U Missouri Phenom Columbia and says the experience has helped prepare her for the upcoming season. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“We traveled to many different states and large tournaments in preparation for this year,” she says. “We had college level practices and many elite players coming back to help us train. After playing with my team this summer I can confidently say that I’m the most ready I have ever been for my senior year and beyond.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After going 7-19 a year ago, Kuchta says she hopes Hickman can continue to grow and improve this upcoming season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">I am hoping to really surprise people,” </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Kuchta said. “</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">We lost Emma Chapman last year and she was a huge help on both ends of the floor. However, I think we have a great group of girls this year that we can build of off and hopefully be a 500 team this season. A match up I’m definitely looking forward to is playing against <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/hannah-nilges/\">Hannah Nilges</a> from Jeff City. She also plays for Phenom and we get very competitive.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Kuchta says </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Greg Logsdon and Devin Griffin have had the biggest impact on her basketball career to date.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Greg has been my summer Coach for 4 years now and had a huge impact in my recruiting and has made me a better person and player just by being around him,” </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Kuchta says. “</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Devin has been my trainer since day 1. He has been a huge support system to have and has helped improve my game tremendously since I first started working with him. Both of these guys have been my biggest fans and believed in me and my ability from the beginning.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A fan of Carsen Edwards, Kyrie Irving, Grayson Allen and Maya Moore, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Kuchta says she enjoys watching guards play to see how she can improve her own game.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“They all are great at their own things but Edwards specifically stuck out to me because of his career at Purdue, he has incredible hesitations and change of speed moves I would love to add to my game,” </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Kuchta says. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A William Penn commit who plans to sign officially soon, Kuchta held offers for both basketball and track, including William Woods and Culver-Stockton.</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Maci Kuchta (2020)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-maci-kuchta-2020','','','2019-12-08 23:58:22','2019-12-09 05:58:22','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122705',0,'post','',0),
	(122708,1,'2019-12-10 14:04:34','2019-12-10 20:04:34','<b>#1 Shadow Mountain 8-0</b>\n\nShadow Mountain comes in the first regular season power rankings as the #1 team in 4A. This squad has been on an absolute mission! Shadow Mountain currently sits at 8-0 with some big time blowouts.\n\nSierra Linda 65-30 W\n\nCactus Shadows 61-40 W\n\nSunrise Mountain 59-42 W\n\nNorth 59-47 W\n\nCoconino 66-19 W\n\nParadise Valley 61-26 W\n\nEstrella Foothills 59-15 W\n\nTempe 62-13 W\n\n<b>#2 Seton Catholic 3-0</b>\n\nSeton was my #1 team in the preseason. They haven’t done anything wrong to drop, as they are still undefeated and playing well. I just couldn’t put them over Shadow Mountain’s dominance. These two play each other this week so the power rankings could shift drastically!\n\nSt. Mary’s 74-22 W\n\nCactus 67-47 W\n\nFlagstaff 59-22 W\n\n<b>#3 Sahuaro 7-0</b>\n\nAnother team that has been on a mission is Tucson’s Sahuaro. Sahuaro is led by the outstanding play of 6’1 Junior Forward, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alyssa-brown/\">Alyssa Brown</a>. Brown has taken her game to the next level and therefore has taken her team to a whole new level.\n\nPalo Verde 54-18 W\n\nEmpire 64-32 W\n\nSunnyside 70-54 W\n\nCatalina Foothills 54-30 W\n\nSalpointe Catholic 59-52 W\n\nDouglas 65-26 W\n\nTanque Verde 85-49 W\n\n<b>#4 Salpointe Catholic 7-1</b>\n\nSC is also having a great year. They are currently 7-1 and they are the #4 team after losing to Sahuaro in the Salpointe Tournament late last month.\n\nNogales 60-31 W\n\nVista Grande 86-24 W\n\nPusch Ridge 88-15 W\n\nNogales 53-35 W\n\nRio Rico 46-33 W\n\nSahuaro 59-52 L\n\nRio Rico 53-45 W\n\nAmphi 50-12 W\n\n<b>#5 Cactus 4-1</b>\n\nWrapping up the top 5 is Cactus High School. Cactus has had a really good start to their season and could drastically see a big change, for better or worse, once all of their game scores are recorded. As of right now, they are 4-1, but are missing 4 games on their schedule/have not reported scores.\n\nBradshaw Mountain 47-35 W\n\nIronwood 52-33 W\n\nSeton Catholic 67-47 L\n\nSnowflake 31-28 W\n\nKellis 39-29 W','Power Rankings: 4A','','publish','open','open','','power-rankings-4a','','','2019-12-10 14:04:34','2019-12-10 20:04:34','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122708',0,'post','',0),
	(122743,1,'2019-12-09 11:32:41','2019-12-09 17:32:41','I was only able to attend the Friday session for the Lakewood Shootout, but I got to see a lot of talent in the 3 games I witnessed (one game was cancelled between Ft. Myers and Carrollwood Day). The first game was a 63-43 win for Braden River over Lakewood. The second game was a 60-49 win for Sandalwood over Booker. The last game was a tight 56-51 win for Bishop Kenny over Atlantic. Here are my top ten players during Friday\'s action (no specific order):\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>O\'Mariah Gordon, Braden River (Jr.)  - </strong>Braden River started out slow in their game as they were down after one quarter, but they picked it up behind the leadership of O\'Mariah and Julia. There isn\'t much else you can say about O\'Mariah that hasn\'t already been said. She didn\'t miss a free throw on Friday and finished with 22 points with three 3\'s that all came in the early part of the game. O\'Mariah can take over against solid opponents like Lakewood with her ability to score, steal the ball, and make her teammates looks better. A superstar that hustles on every play and after every mistake is hard to find.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/julia-rodriguez/\">Julia Rodriguez</a>, Braden River (Sr.) -</strong> She doesn\'t draw as much attention as O, but she is one of the best players in the state who is a D1 commit. Julia scored 25 against Lakewood with 12 of those coming from long range. There aren\'t many teams in the state that can compete with these two and the other pieces that the Pirates have. Julia is a very athletic kid who hustles all over the court on both ends and really can do it all. She will be a good addition to Kennesaw State next year.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jada-jones/\">Jada Jones</a><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jada-jones/\">, Sandalwood</a> (Fr.) - </strong>I am convinced that Jada is the best post player in the 2023 class in Florida. You can tell she is young in the face, but her game says otherwise. Jada scored 27 points, rebounded well, and had some monster blocks against Booker on Friday. She showed some strong post moves and looked refined for only being a Freshman. They biggest thing she can work on is her free throw shooting that was lacking in this one.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amari-wright/\">Amari Wright</a>, Sandalwood (Sr.) - </strong>Easily one of the best passers in the state, Amari brought this Saints squad back from being down after each of the first 3 quarters. Sandalwood came alive in the final quarter behind the facilitation of Amari which created a lot of opportunities for Jada and company. Amari scored 23 in the win as she has had to step up her scoring with two of their best players out. Once this team is at full health, they will undoubtedly be one of the best teams in the state behind the passing of this Seton Hall commit.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jasmyne-roberts/\">Jasmyne Roberts</a>, Bishop Kenny (Jr.) - </strong>Atlantic face-guarded Jasmyne in the second half after she torched them for 14 points in the first half. She finished with 19 on the night, and the only way they could stop her was by making sure she didn\'t get the ball. Jasmyne is as smooth as they come with her shooting touch and ability to get to the hole. She\'ll have her pick at a number of big time programs.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/maddie-millar/\">Maddie Millar</a><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/maddie-millar/\">, Bishop Kenny</a> (So.) - </strong>She was the best pure shooter on Friday. Maddie made six 3\'s to help her team get a gutsy victory. She\'s only a Sophomore, so it will be interesting to see her elevate her game in areas other than shooting. Maddie is strong all-around, but if she really works on those other aspects then she will be VERY tough to stop.\n\n<strong>D\'asia Small, Atlantic (Sr.) - </strong>She is an undersized post on this team, but she did a little bit of everything for this scrappy Atlantic team to stay in the game. D\'asia put up 21 points and did everything from rebounding, passing, and playing tough D with some steals and blocks in this one. I think she is someone who could contribute at the next level if she improves her shot and fine tunes some of those crafty moves.\n\n<strong>Cashanti Bradley, Booker (Sr.) - </strong>The tornadoes are playing a very tough schedule, but Cashanti has played the best in the games that I have seen. She hit five 3\'s in this one (20 total points), but it wasn\'t enough for the dominant 4th quarter that Sandalwood had. Cashanti can obviously shoot, but she does other things well too like passing, rebounding, and knowing where to be on the floor.\n\n<strong>Omari Davis, Booker (Sr.) - </strong>Booker has a trio of guards that have given them a chance against their tough schedule, and Omari played a nice game by scoring 16 points all over the court on Friday. Her shot looks nice, and she can get to the hoop with ease. If Omari added a little speed and strength, she could be one of the best in the area.\n\n<strong>Ta\'Nauviyon Williams, Lakewood (Jr.) - </strong>She is one of the most athletic players I\'ve seen, and Braden River didn\'t really have an answer for her. Nauvi posted 12 points by rising above everyone for her buckets. She is going to have a strong junior year as a scorer and rebounder on a team that should start seeing more success. Lakewood just didn\'t look very comfortable in this game after the first quarter.','Insider Exposure Lakewood Shootout: Top 10 Players on Friday','','publish','open','open','','insider-exposure-lakewood-shootout-top-10-players-on-friday','','','2019-12-09 11:32:41','2019-12-09 17:32:41','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122743',0,'post','',0),
	(122744,1,'2019-12-09 10:40:43','2019-12-09 16:40:43','<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Prep Hoops Girls Team Preview</strong></span>\n\nAs we enter the 2019/2020 high school basketball season in Kansas.  Prep Hoops will preview some of the Kansas City Area high schools.  These preview articles will give you details on key players, season expectations and more.\n\nIn this article we preview the defending Class 5A State Champion, St. Thomas Aquinas Lady Saints.  Posting a 20-4 record in 2019-20, they\'ll be looking to defend their title this year.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Players To Watch </span></strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Molly Harnett, Guard, Senior, (2020)  <img class=\"alignright wp-image-122779 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/Molly-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></span>\n\nHarnett the 5\'9 Northwest Missouri State University commit is a returner from a year ago and will look to help lead a younger group for the Saints. Molly is an experienced and fundamentally sound player with all the leadership qualities you\'d want in a senior. A selfless athlete that does everything she can to help her team. Look for her to help lead Aquinas in her final year.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif;color: #000000\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madison-skelton/\">Madison Skelton</a>, Guard, Junior, (2021)</span>\n\n<img class=\"wp-image-91954 size-thumbnail\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Madison-Skelton-1-150x150.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />\n\nThe 5\'8 guard returns from her junior season a bit more polished and experienced after a long summer of club ball with Next Level Eclipse. Skelton is a fundamentally sound player with great vision and court awareness. Has the ability to knock down the open jump shot with consistency as well as get to the basket. Madison has a very high basketball IQ which allows her to facilitate and be a key player for the Saints.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/beatrice-culliton/\">Beatrice Culliton</a>, Center, Sophomore, (2022)   </span>\n\nA returner and key contributor from last year\'s state championship team, Beatrice will look to continue to be a dominating force on the interior for Aquinas. The 6\'3 post player is strong and agile around the basket. Uses size and strength to get good position to score and rebound. A physical defender that makes opposing players work for every bucket.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAquinas looks to reload by adding some key additions and also some other returners this year. Syndey Watts is a dynamic freshman with all the tools to become an impact player in her first year. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sameera-elmasri/\">Sameera Elmasri</a> is a very talented junior transfer from Mill Valley high school, where she started every game before suffering a season-ending knee injury. Charlotte O\'Keffe played minutes her freshman year for the Saints looks to help on the interior again this year.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Upcoming Games</span>\n\nFriday December 20th, 2019.  Road game at St. James Academy\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Team Preview: St. Thomas Aquinas Saints','','publish','open','open','','team-preview-st-thomas-aquinas-saints','','','2019-12-09 10:40:43','2019-12-09 16:40:43','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122744',0,'post','',0),
	(122745,1,'2019-12-09 08:52:47','2019-12-09 14:52:47','Michigan high school basketball has a lot of top notch talent on the perimeter. This allows us to see many great combinations of players team up in the backcourt. Let\'s take a look at a couple must see backcourts.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-122759\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/f1cf028e6b137d3eb835ccae3c9866eb-300x157.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"157\" />\n<h4>Michigan Center</h4>\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/teagan-haynes/\">Teagan Haynes</a> (2020, PG)</strong>\n\nHaynes will be playing next season at Aquinas. Mark my words, she could be a STAR there. She\'s a bona fide playmaker with the pass, but also has versatility in her game. Last season she was greatly improved in her ability to be a score first lead guard. Haynes takes pride in her pesky defense and likes to create havoc for the offense.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alize-tripp/\">Alize Tripp</a> (2020, CG)</strong>\n\nTripp recently committed to Concordia College. She\'s a prototypical team first type player that puts wins over statistics. Tripp has 3 point range on her jumper. Just like her backcourt mate, she is a big factor on the defensive end. Her on ball and team defense will help win games this season for Michigan Center.\n<h4>Wayne Memorial</h4>\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lachelle-austin/\">LaChelle Austin</a> (2021, SG)</strong>\n\nAustin had a huge spring and summer with Hype Lady Hoopers, and solidified herself as a Division 1 prospect. The D1 offers prove as much.  She\'s a smooth scorer that can carry a team offensively. She has a nice mid range jumper that she can hit off the dribble and in traffic. Austin is dangerous with the ball when coming off a screen.\n\n<strong>Jordan Wright (2022, G)</strong>\n\nWayne Memorial Head Coach Jarvis Mitchell seems to have a pedigree when it comes to developing perimeter talent. Next up:  Jordan Wright. She attacks off the dribble and goes like a landslide from the moment she touches the ball. Wright has a solid mid range game where she can pull up for a jumper or dish to an open teammate.','2 Must See Backcourts','','publish','open','open','','2-must-see-backcourts','','','2019-12-09 08:52:47','2019-12-09 14:52:47','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122745',0,'post','',0),
	(122799,1,'2019-12-09 10:42:04','2019-12-09 16:42:04','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oklahoma City-OK</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Deer Creek began its regular season with a match against the reigning state champions, Norman High. With odds stacked against them, Deer Creek put it all on the line, and came out with the dominant 77-71 win on December 3rd.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With leading frontman Skyler Vann, the Antlers took down the #1 Norman High Tigers.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Vann not only caused three turnovers alone, she racked up steals and blocks throughout the entire game.</span>\n\nVann was the top scorer, shooting an impressive 10-17, racking up 27 points for the Antlers.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Alongside Vann, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/angel-scott-2/\">Angel Scott</a> had 11 points to rally against the Tigers.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With Vann and Scott, Brenna Burk went 6-8 on the night her 14 points also added to the fight.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Burk and Vann were an unstoppable duo on Tuesday night, combining for 13 rebounds, respectively.</span>\n\nNorman High Sophomore Myka Perry had a whopping 24 points in the shocking loss for the Tigers.\n\nJuniors <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kelbie-washington-2/\">Kelbie Washington</a> and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/chantae-embry/\">Chantae Embry</a> combined for a staggering 23 points against Deer Creek.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Despite being ranked 12th in the state, Vann, Burk, and Scott, and the rest of the Antlers fought to the end and came out with a win against not only the reigning state champs, but also the number one team in the state, Norman High.</span>','Deer Creek Defeats Reigning State Champs in Thriller','','publish','open','open','','deer-creek-defeats-reigning-state-champs-in-thriller','','','2019-12-09 10:42:04','2019-12-09 16:42:04','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122799',0,'post','',0),
	(122824,1,'2019-12-09 12:37:52','2019-12-09 18:37:52','Wow! What a Saturday to be in the gym watching a lot of great talent in South Florida. I was able to see three of the top teams in the state in Miami Country Day School, Montverde Academy and St. Thomas Aquinas. The 2 p.m. match up between Miami County Day and Montverde was one that many spectators wanted to see. The game definitely was worth it as you were able to see two top teams, which both are well coached and both feature some of the top players in our state go at it. Montverde won the game by a score of 50-45.\n\nHere are some takeaways that I saw from all the action this weekend:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt;\"><strong>Montverde Academy Eagles </strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Mariana Valenzuela - Forward Junior </strong></span>\n\nHer hands and rebounding was awesome, made great catches and had a few strong finishes at the basket. Forced some of Miami Country Day\'s players to change their shot on the interior just from her presence.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Carolina Fernandez-Nion - Guard Junior</strong></span>\n\nThe floor general on the court for the Eagles. She showed an understanding of game pace by knowing when to push the ball up the court and when to settle her team down to get them into their offense.\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Maria Myklebust - Guard/Forward Junior</span></strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"> </span>\n\nShe can do it all. Maria was able to show you everything her game consists of. With her size she was able to play inside out. She can knock down the three ball, hit the mid range shot, go down in the post area and be physical, plus she defended while on defense. I can definitely seeing her winning the teams MVP award at the end of the season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt;\"><strong>Miami Country Day School</strong></span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sydney-shaw/\">Sydney Shaw</a></span> - Guard Sophomore</strong>\n\nDo it all player for Miami Country Day. Can score, create her own shot, create opportunities for her teammates to score, rebound and defend. Shaw has stepped up and takes on the leadership role for her team. Last year she had the luxury of playing with Koi Love and Maria Alvarez. Shaw kept MCD in the game by doing all that she can. Looking forward to see her growth as a leader and continued competitiveness,\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/andrea-daley/\">Andrea Daley</a> - Forward Junior </span></strong>\n\nAthletic, explosive and solid finisher around the basket. Daley\'s athleticism is off the charts. She\'s truly a catalyst for MCD on the defensive end as she can cover ground and get to spots fast when they are pressing. She can block shots and goes after just about every rebound. Runs the floor well and finishes.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt;\"><strong>Miami Christian </strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Samantha Vales - Guard 8th Grader </strong></span>\n\nCrafty skilled guard that can knock down the open shot. Gets to the basket and understands the game. Plays hard on both ends of the court. Only an 8th grader and is holding her own against high school players.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Ambar Ramirez - Guard Junior </strong></span>\n\nGuard that plays the game hard and plays to win every possession. She really get her team going with her energy and aggressive play. She\'s able to make her teammates feed off of her energy and force them to play at a different gear. Getting in the lane and hitting her shots was something i saw her excel at over this weekend.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Enjulina Gonzalez - Guard Sophomore</strong></span>\n\nLooking at Gonzalez you wouldn\'t think she can do what she does out there on the court. Deception is the word to describe her rebounding skills, she has great timing and can really get up. She\'s a quiet athletic player that gets out there and just does her job.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt;\"><strong>Nova Titans </strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Jamie Levy - Guard Senior</strong></span>\n\nLevy showed her ability to hit the open three and her teammates were not shy about finding her to knock down those shots. She moved well on the defensive end and made some great decisions on offense. I was really impressed with how she took care of the basketball this weekend.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/trinity-delancy/\">Trinity Delancy</a></span> - Guard Senior</strong></span>\n\nTrinity played hard on both sides of the floor. Being vocal and leading her team by example are the things that stood out to me the most. Trinity always gives 110% when she playing and this past weekend showed just that. Her senior leadership helped her team come out victorious.\n\n&nbsp;','Top Performers Cardinal Gibbons Chiefs Basketball Classic (Part 1)','','publish','open','open','','top-performers-cardinal-gibbons-chiefs-basketball-classic-part-1','','','2019-12-09 12:37:52','2019-12-09 18:37:52','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122824',0,'post','',0),
	(122853,1,'2019-12-11 12:17:31','2019-12-11 18:17:31','A tournament hosted by Thunderridge High School with some good competition to kick off the season.  Cherokee Trail and Mullen competed in the championship game.  It was a heated battle between the two teams until the Lady mustangs went off in the 2nd half with the final score being 51-29.\n\nMullen had no problem getting it going against Cherokee Trail.  The lady Mustangs worked the ball inside-out with their dominant post present, and players that can be ready to knock down a open shot.  <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/megan-pohs/\">Megan Pohs</a></strong> scored 10 points, 2-5 behind the arc, 2 steals.  <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/elaina-martinez/\">Elaina Martinez</a></strong> with 6 points, all coming from behind the arc.  These two guards are great floor generals, and loves to get their teammates involved.  Pohs and Martinez did not have a big scoring night but does not mean that can\'t score whenever they want.  It was just time for the post-wing players to get it going on the offensive end.\n\n<strong>Gracie Gallego</strong>s was the standout player of the game scoring at will.  She led the team in scoring with 15 points, 6-12 from the field, 2-4 from behind the arc, 7 rebounds.<strong>  Gallegos</strong> did extremely well attacking the rim and finishing with ease.  She also was ready to shoot the ball when she needed knocking down two open shots behind the arc. <strong> Gallegos</strong> stands at 6\'0\" making it difficult for teams to score the ball because of her length and size.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/imani-perez/\">Imani Perez</a></strong> being a handful inside of the paint with her dominant present.  Scoring only 8 points but extremely efficient around the rim.  She shot at 80 percent with 4-5 from two point field goal, <strong>Perez</strong> snatched 10 rebounds putting her team in a great position to win.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kilah-freelon/\">Kilah Freelon</a></strong> a sophomore who swings up varsity came into the game and did her job.  Standing at 5\'11\" she is extremely athletic, long, and shows great foot speed.  With limited minutes due to a stack roster, she came in and scored 4 points for the lady Mustangs.  The ceiling is high for <strong>Freelon</strong>, it will be great to see how she do this season.\n\nDespite everyone not scoring as much for Mullen, It was a night for <strong>Gallegos</strong> as she dominated the entire game.  Any one of the Mustangs player can get going.  Saturday championship game it was <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/gracie-gallegos/\">Gracie Gallegos</a></strong>, who is next for the lady Mustang?\n\n<strong>Dominique Rodriquez</strong> only player on Cherokee Trail to score in the double figure against Mullen on Saturday.  She did a great job getting to the rim and drawing some fouls.  <strong>Rodriquez</strong> tried to put the team on her back with her scoring and her competitive edge.  <strong>Rodriquez</strong> is a crafty player that can shoot, and slash to the hoop with variety of moves around the rim.  This will be her break out year as she is still yet to sign, and could play at the next level.','Five Takeaways: Cherokee Trail vs Mullen','','publish','open','open','','five-takeaways-cherokee-trail-vs-mullen','','','2019-12-11 12:17:31','2019-12-11 18:17:31','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122853',0,'post','',0),
	(122876,1,'2019-12-09 19:37:12','2019-12-10 01:37:12','As the afternoon started to come to a close, the competition in the Cardinal Gibbons Chiefs Classic picked up as expected. Featuring match ups with Broward County teams facing Dade County teams, like St Thomas versus Mater Lakes and also Nova versus Miami Christian. All the teams played hard and we were in for a treat of good quality basketball. We also were able to see the home team, Cardinal Gibbons as they faced Cypress Bay and one of the top players in the 2020 class. Check out the players that performed well:\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Cardinal Gibbons </strong></span>\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>Emily Jimenez - Guard Junior </strong></span>\n\nWas impressed of the sacrifice that she made for her team on the defensive end. Coach went to a box and one on the other teams best player and she stepped up to that challenge. She made the player work for every shot that she was able to get. Even with exerting all of her energy to defend the other teams best player the entire game, she still ran the floor on offense and was able to be one of the key players for her team.\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Mariah McKenzie - Guard Freshman</span></strong>\n\nThis kid\'s body passes the eye test right now at her young age. She\'s athletic, strong and a physical player. Played with absolutely no fear. She was a rebounding machine, which to me shows her effort and determination to get the job done. She created opportunities on both sides of the ball for her team. The potential that she has is off the charts.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>Ashley Battle - Guard Freshman</strong></span>\n\nBattle is small, but fast. Her speed on the court is truly something to see. The young point guard has a nice handle of the ball and of her team. She\'s very vocal and understands the game. She makes sure that her teammates are in the right places and I saw her be the floor general for her squad. Very impressed with what she can do with her size at 4\'11.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>Cypress Bay</strong></span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophia-jones/\">Sophia Jones</a> - Guard Senior (Signed to San Jose State University)</span></strong>\n\nOne of the better players in Broward County had to do it all for her team. Each point she scored was not easy as she faced a box and one the entire game. Kept her composure and still lead her team as best she could. Showed her ability to knock down shots even while she was tired and facing two defenders at one time. She also displayed nice ball handling skills as she didn\'t have many turnovers in the game. From what I see she will be facing defenses like this the entire season.\n\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000\"><strong>Aicha Keita - Forward Freshman</strong></span>\n\nKeita has a lot of upside. She\'s long, athletic, slender and can run the floor. She stands at 6\'0 tall and is already causing opponents to change their shot when she\'s inside of the paint. She was a key contributor for her team throughout the game, whether she was rebounding or defending she got the job done.\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Mater Lakes Academy </span></strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Brianna Alexander - Guard Senior </span></strong>\n\nThe lefty showed how well she can stroke the ball from three and mid range. I saw her make some great decisions with the basketball, get her teammates involved and was very vocal on the court on the defensive end. Her leadership will definitely help her team down the road as the time gets closer to district play.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\"><strong>St Thomas Aquinas</strong></span>\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000\">Jada Green - Forward Sophomore</span></strong>\n\nWatching her this past weekend has shown me that she has grown in the past few weeks from the last time I saw her play. She\'s consistently knocking down the free throw jump shot, she\'s agile and can move for her size of about 5\'11. She was very aggressive rebounding the basketball. Displayed some great finishing moves at the basket. I can see her easily averaging a double-double throughout this season.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;color: #ff0000\"><strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/karina-gordon/\">Karina Gordon</a> - Guard Freshman</strong></span>\n\nShe came out this weekend on fire. She went 2/2 from the three point line to open the game up. Gordon is able to get to the basket, kick it out to open teammates and just make the right basketball play. Transferring from Miami Country Day, I\'m very impressed with how shes fitting in with a new system, coaches and teammates. She\'s truly excelling and thriving with how she\'s playing. Excited about her growth and continued development.\n\n&nbsp;','Top Performers at Cardinal Gibbons Chiefs Basketball Classic (Part 2)','','publish','open','open','','top-performers-at-cardinal-gibbons-chiefs-basketball-classic-part-2','','','2019-12-09 19:37:12','2019-12-10 01:37:12','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122876',0,'post','',0),
	(122888,1,'2019-12-09 13:44:19','2019-12-09 19:44:19','I can go on and on about the star-studded lineups from Cibolo Steele and Cedar Park on opening day and there are a number of individuals that stood out on each squad, <strong>Bria McClure</strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/aja-holmes/\">Aja Holmes</a> (TCU)</strong> were putting on long ball shooting exhibitions on both days of pool play for Cibolo Steele while<strong> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/hannah-wheeler/\">Hannah Wheeler</a> (Incarnate Word)</strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/nicole-leff/\">Nicole Leff</a> (Texas State)</strong> brought heat from a variety of ways with Cedar Park, ironically these two teams wound up playing each other for 3rd place in the GOLD D1 Division, Cedar Park won but here are some that caught my eyes on the first day\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_122897\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-122897\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0274-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/shelby-hayes/\">Shelby Hayes</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/shelby-hayes/\">Shelby Hayes</a>-6\'0 F (Cedar Park)</strong> the talented sophomore fills in many of the blanks as well as baskets in the paint on this talented squad. She can score with power as well as with a soft touch but her work ethic is second to none as she just battles for everything in the paint. Her upside is untapped, she\'s definitely a throwback player\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/zaya-price/\">Zaya Price</a>-5\'10 G (Cibolo Steele)</strong> you have to wonder how she\'s an unsigned senior, she a PGH Texas Top 100 player, I added her after heading to a fall league earlier and she made my Tip Sheet last season but the portal will stay full when too many people are giving to many erroneous evaluations for numerous reasons. She\'s powerful attacking the basket and defending, she can shoot it, mid to long and she defends, I\'m never wrong\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_122898\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-122898\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0359-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amira-mabry/\">Amira Mabry</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong>Da\'Necia Trusty-6\'2 F (Hastings)</strong> the long and athletic junior continues to show me a variety of new things that she\'s added to her game after impressing me a couple of years ago as a defensive standout. Yeah she blocks shots, rebounds and can defend inside and out but she\'s scoring consistently around the basket over and over\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amira-mabry/\">Amira Mabry</a>-5\'11 F (Converse Judson)</strong> with <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kierra-sanderlin/\">Kierra Sanderlin</a></strong> out, a lot more of the offense had to come from somewhere and she added more in a variety of ways. She plays over \"the magic number\" much of that to her length, wingspan, and athleticism but that desire is something you can\'t teach\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_122899\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-122899\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0336-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Alaina Payne[/caption]\n\n<strong>Chiresha King-5\'3 G (Converse Judson)</strong> special S/O to this young lady just because I enjoy watching her not only want to take the big shots but comes up big after taking them. She\'s a gamer, loves the  pressure and it definitely helps when you can deliver\n\n<strong>Alaina Payne-5\'8 G (North Crowley)</strong> didn\'t take me long after watching her explode to the basket and elevate over defenders but the talented junior does some of everything including creating her shot under pressure and shooting it from a variety of spots on the court. On top of that, she brings the heat on defense, baseline to baseline\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_122900\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"169\"]<img class=\" wp-image-122900\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0103-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"169\" height=\"111\" /> Chrishelle Washington[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/crishelle-washington/\">Crishelle Washington</a>-5\'5 G (North Shore)</strong> you can\'t teach heart and I guess that Energizer commercial about \"keeps going and going\" sort of fits because the sophomore keeps going and going no matter what the score is, she plays the same. She\'s attacking strongly and finishing plus scoring from outside and her defense has taken a jump\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/maliyah-johnson/\">Maliyah Johnson</a>-6\'3 P (Summer Creek)</strong> the Texas A&amp;M signee was on red alert as she just went completely off. Her athletic ability and strength can wear defenders down on the inside but her range, from bta, gives her numerous options because if you try and defender her tightly, she can take defenders off of the dribble\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_122901\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"195\"]<img class=\" wp-image-122901\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0214-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"195\" height=\"128\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/victoria-rivera/\">Victoria Rivera</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/victoria-rivera/\">Victoria Rivera</a>-6\'0 G (Dobie)</strong> does things so effortlessly and scores in the flow but she\'s also one of those rare \"can\'t miss\" that doesn\'t realize how good she is. Her range is when she walks onto the court, she is smooth as silk on offense that she has that \"takeover\" capability but she plays the game as it should be and her unselfishness stands out as well\n\n&nbsp;','Texas Invitational D1 Top Performers day 1','','publish','open','open','','texas-invitational-d1-top-performers-day-1','','','2019-12-09 13:44:19','2019-12-09 19:44:19','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122888',0,'post','',0),
	(122910,1,'2019-12-09 14:19:43','2019-12-09 20:19:43','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Basketball season is underway. With most of Class A getting started last week, teams will be jumping right into league play. There will be no shortage of intriguing matchups on a weekly basis. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Here are some of the games to watch this week:</span>\n\n<em><strong>West Fargo at Fargo Shanley, 5:45 p.m., Tuesday, December 10</strong></em>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Fargo Shanley is coming off a dominant win over Bismarck St. Mary’s to start the year and the Deacons are likely the favorite to win the EDC. West Fargo is in that mix of teams that figures to contend for a top-four seed in the league and has no shortage of talent. McKenna Becher and Chloe Pfau form a really solid 1-2 punch for the Packers while Reile Payne is arguably the best player in the EDC.</span>\n\n<em><strong>Watford City at Bismarck Legacy, 6 p.m., Friday, December 13</strong></em>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Watford City beat Williston to kick off the season while Bismarck Legacy handled Fargo South, so both teams are coming into this one with a win and a week to prepare. The Wolves held Williston to 50 points while forcing 20 turnovers, while the Sabers held Fargo South to just 44 points. Both teams figure to be elite on the defensive end of the floor this year, so this one could be a rock fight. </span>\n\n<em><strong>Jamestown at Bismarck, 6 p.m., Friday, December 13</strong></em>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Two teams that figure to compete for top-four spots in the WDA, Jamestown and Bismarck both started the year with wins. The Demons put up 75 points with eight players tallying at least four, so the balance could be a strength again this year. Mandie Picard had 12 points and 10 rebounds while Jilee Golus scored 14 points. Jamestown has a terrific group returning led by Kameron Selvig, Grace Hegerle and Ella Falk. Selvig had eight points and seven assists while Hegerle had 16 points and six rebounds in the Bluejays’ win over Valley City. </span>','North Dakota Class A Games to Watch, December 9-14','','publish','open','open','','north-dakota-class-a-games-to-watch-december-9-14','','','2019-12-09 14:19:43','2019-12-09 20:19:43','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122910',0,'post','',0),
	(122930,1,'2019-12-09 17:26:04','2019-12-09 23:26:04','Girls basketball is officially in full swing in Arizona and with that, it\'s time to discuss some of the key match-ups to keep an eye on this week. While some have gotten more games under their belts than others, there\'s a number of players and teams showing a ton of improvement from last season. Here are some of the top match-ups across the state taking place between Monday, December 9th and Friday, December13th.\n<h3>Monday:</h3>\n<h4>Saguaro (4A) vs. St. Mary\'s (4A)</h4>\nThe Saguaro Sabercats look to show they are the real deal this year as the team travels to face the St. Mary\'s Knights. Saguaro comes into the match with only one loss so far this season to New Mexico\'s Kirtland Central High School and  It\'s been a bit of a rough start for the Knights, who opened up its season on the road against one of the top ranked 4A teams, the Coconino Panthers, dropping a close one. They then went on to face the most dominant 4A program in the last two decades, the Seton Catholic Sentinels, where they lost another one, before following up with a win over Combs.\n<h3>Tuesday:</h3>\n<h4>Chaparral (5A) vs. Basha (6A)</h4>\nChaparral is continuing to challenge itself with the 2019 schedule, and the game against Basha is no different. Facing a team in a conference above yours is always a challenge, but the Firebirds aren\'t one to shy away. Despite a 3-3 record, the Firebirds will show you what all the hype is about surrounding the team. Meanwhile, Basha will come into the game with a pair of losses, one to Desert Vista and one to Mountain Pointe, but a handful of other wins.\n<h4>Salpointe Catholic (4A) vs. Buena (5A)</h4>\nSalpointe Catholic is another school that never shies away from a challenge. This week, the Lancers are looking to continue showing why they\'re among the elite places for athletes in the Tucson area when they host the Buena Colts, who are a conference above them. Both Salpointe Catholic and Buena only have one loss on the season going into this game, but Salpointe Catholic has played in more games so far this season.\n<h4>Williams Field (5A) vs. Raymond S. Kellis (5A)</h4>\nThe Williams Field Black Hawks are looking to show how much they\'ve improved from last season as the season continues to progress. Last year, the Black Hawks went 15-12, but they\'re already off to a much better start this year with only one loss so far this year to Willow Canyon that was decided by three points. Prior to the Black Hawks\' game against Kellis, they\'ll first have to face Agua Fria on Monday. Raymond S. Kellis will be coming in to the game off its first loss against Cactus last Friday, and if anything, it should motivate them to play harder. At 7-1, they\'ve managed to shut down their opponents\' offense almost entirely in nearly every game. The biggest statement was holding Tucson\'s Desert View to just two points in the entire game.\n<h4>Seton Catholic (4A) vs. Shadow Mountain (4A)</h4>\nA repeat of this year\'s 4A State Championship, this will be a game you won\'t want to miss. Both teams come into this game undefeated and will bring a lot of skill to the court. Seton Catholic has only played in three games so far this season, but all three of them have been dominant wins. The team is lead by a group of sophomores and juniors, but despite having no seniors on the roster, there\'s a high level of basketball IQ among them. With eight games, Shadow Mountain has faced a tougher test against schools that are also in bigger conferences. The closest game for the Matadors was against the 6A North High School Mustangs, where they still won by 12. Both teams like to play up close, in-your-face defense the entire game and have the cardio to do so. Expect this to be the most exciting game of the week by far.\n<h3>Thursday:</h3>\n<h4>Highland (6A) vs. Sandra Day O\'Connor (6A)</h4>\nHighland\'s final game before playing in the Nike Tournament of Champions will be on Thursday against Sandra Day O\'Connor. Highland showed some areas where improvements were needed when the season first got underway at the Minor Webster tournament, but have had some time to work on things since then. Meanwhile for O\'Connor, it will be among their first big tests so far this season. The only other team O\'Connor has faced that\'s done decent this year is Xavier, but it is not anywhere close to the same Xavier team that played in the 6A State Championship game last year. Expect this game to be a close one.\n<h4>Mesquite (4A) vs. Moon Valley (4A)</h4>\nBoth Mesquite and Moon Valley have faced tougher challenges earlier in the year, playing schools in the 5A and 6A conferences, but when it comes to playing other schools in the 4A conference, they\'ve looked pretty good so far. This will likely be the first true test for both the Wildcats and the Rockets to see how they\'ll likely do as the rest of the season starts to take shape.\n<h3>Friday:</h3>\n<h4>Chandler (6A) vs. Tucson (6A)</h4>\nChandler will be making the trip down I-10 to play the Tucson Badgers on Friday. Tucson has four losses to schools from California and Colorado, but despite those losses, the team can still say they learned and continued to grow overall. For Chandler, they\'re looking to capitalize on the dominant start to the season. The wolves will be looking to show why they are a dark horse contender to win the 6A Premier region this year.','Previewing AZ\'s top games of the week','','publish','open','open','','previewing-azs-top-games-of-the-week','','','2019-12-09 17:26:04','2019-12-09 23:26:04','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122930',0,'post','',0),
