	(122988,1,'2019-12-09 19:52:09','2019-12-10 01:52:09','The <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/11/texas-invitational-takeaways-from-cy-ranch-vs-cibolo-steele/\">Cy Ranch vs Cibolo Steele</a> game had a few takeaways including down around 20, never give up as The Mustangs came back against the Lady Knights to take the lead however they lost in overtime. <strong>Rianne Burton (Cincinnati)</strong> carried the offensive load early with <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/shadiya-thomas/\">Shadiya Thomas</a> (Air Force)</strong> adding bits and pieces thought the game and what can I say about <strong>Bria McClure</strong> and<strong> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/aja-holmes/\">Aja Holmes</a> (TCU)</strong> combining for 13 three pointers, is that a record.<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/2019/12/cy-creek-wins-texas-invitational-d1-gold/\"> I didn\'t see D1 Gold champion Cy Creek</a>, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kyndall-hunter/\">Kyndall Hunter</a></strong> was named MVP and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rori-harmon/\">Rori Harmon</a></strong> made All-Tournament, check the Texas Invitational website for updates. I didn\'t see <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/deyona-gaston/\">Deyona Gaston</a> (Mississippi State)</strong> but I\'m sure she was her dominating self. The tournament was a hit, as usual, heavy hitters were spread out and this kept some of the national guys away but I\'ll make a suggestion for next season because just about everyone wants \"national exposure\" warranted or not\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123008\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"134\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123008\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0001-1-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"134\" height=\"88\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/shira-patton/\">Shira Patton</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/shira-patton/\">Shira Patton</a>-5\'9 G  (Cy Ranch)</strong> one of many overly used phrases of \"jumps out of the gym\" applies to this young lady who defies gravity with her acrobatic layup, pull-ups, and fadeaways but down the stretch, she was virtually unstoppable in the overtime game against Cibolo Steele. She has amazed me for years and will continue to do so at Northern Arizona\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123012\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"136\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123012\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0093-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"136\" height=\"89\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alisa-knight/\">Alisa Knight</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alisa-knight/\">Alisa Knight</a>-5\'9 G (Cedar Park)</strong> blends in well on a solid team and gets hers in the flow. One of the most athletic players at the event that could actually play and her first step is somewhat devastating as she elevates over defenders and finishes with contact but what I really like is the way she plays the passing lane and with her speed, that\'s usually a lay-up going the other way\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123038\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"158\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123038\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0097-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"158\" height=\"104\" /> Da\'Nae Johnson[/caption]\n\n<strong>D\'Nae Johnson-5\'6 G (Clear Springs)</strong> explosive on both ends, she puts in work and her energy trickles down to her teammates as she adds fuel to a talented guard-heavy team. She anticipates and defends well, throw in \"plays the passing lane\" and can attack the basket from anywhere on the floor. The senior also falls into that \"Under The Radar\" category\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123040\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"155\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123040\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0075-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"155\" height=\"102\" /> Sidney Love[/caption]\n\n<strong>Sidney Love-5\'9 G (Cibolo Steele)</strong> she\'s one of the best coming off of the bench and I don\'t know if they have a 6th man award, maybe people can vote, no scratch that, she would start on many squads and the more I see the talented sophomore, the more she shows. I\'m partial to her first name, no matter how it\'s spelled and watching her glide to the basket or just elevate over defenders is something to see\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123044\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"160\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123044\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0115-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"160\" height=\"105\" /> Jade Goynes[/caption]\n\n<strong>Jade Goynes-5\'10 PF (North Crowley)</strong> she can overpower defenders inside and face the basket and hit the shot. Good rebounder on both ends of the floor, she also dives on the floor for, loose balls as well as goes after them in the stands. She brings the heat on defense, inside or baseline to baseline but she won\'t let you outwork her and falls into that never takes a play-off type of player and she\'s a junior\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123045\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"163\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123045\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0134-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"163\" height=\"107\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ashlyn-jones/\">Ashlyn Jones</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ashlyn-jones/\">Ashlyn Jones</a>-6\'0 F (Klein Oak)</strong> one of the top juniors in the state, she is just one of those players that fills up the stat sheet, effortlessly and when you look.... Her jumper is fluid and she gets it off against anyone, mid to long, and it\'s consistent yet if you guard her tightly, she can attack, hang in the air and change hands while waiting, you can\'t teach some of the things she does','Texas Invitational D1 Top Performers day 2','','publish','open','open','','texas-invitational-d1-top-performers-day-2','','','2019-12-09 19:52:09','2019-12-10 01:52:09','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122988',0,'post','',0),
	(122995,1,'2019-12-09 18:06:43','2019-12-10 00:06:43','It’s early yet, but three weeks into the high school basketball season is not too soon to start seeing some preliminary trends develop. While there are plenty of familiar names lighting up the scoreboards around the state, we have seen other players begin emerging from the shadows and doing more. Although it is only one aspect of performance – and I am by no means a numbers-only kind of guy – point production is something we can easily measure, and it’s about the only aspect of individual performance that is widely available. With that in mind, here are some players who have jumped quickly from the starting gates this winter.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kayla-bohr/\">Kayla Bohr</a></strong>, <strong>Anna Garfield</strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madge-hoehne/\">Madison Hoehne</a></strong> of Blaine have been on fire through their first six games of the season as the Bengals have leapt out to a 5-1 start after winning just seven games all last year. Bohr, a 5’10 junior, scored 29 points on Saturday against Apple Valley, raising her season average to 16.7 points per game. Garfield, a senior guard, is also averaging 16 as is Hoehne, a 6’0 junior whose stock has been on the rise for the past six months. Hoehne had a 26-point game against Providence Academy.\n\nLake City sophomores <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/natalie-bremer/\">Natalie Bremer</a></strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lilly-meincke/\">Lilly Meincke</a></strong> have also been lighting it up. Bremer, a 5’10 guard ranked #60 in the class of 2022, topped the 30-point mark in consecutive games last week. She’s averaging 22 points and 8 rebounds per game. Meincke, a 5’10 guard ranked #52 in the class, is averaging 18 points, 8 rebounds, 3 assists and 3 steals per game. Not surprisingly, the Tigers are undefeated at 5-0.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jenna-johnson/\">Jenna Johnson</a></strong>, the second-rated player in the class of 2021, has been sizzling for Wayzata. The 6’2 forward, who is also racking up Division 1 scholarship offers, has been more assertive offensively following the graduation of <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kallie-theisen/\">Kallie Theisen</a></strong> (South Dakota State). Jenna scored 32 in the Trojans’ season-opener against Fergus Falls and had 33 against Lakeville North. Point production is not unexpected from Johnson, but she’s now at 25 ppg, up from 15.7 last season and 11.2 as a freshman.\n\n<strong>Going north of 30</strong>\n\nThere have been multiple players top 30 point in a game so far, including <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-bueckers/\">Paige Bueckers</a></strong> of Hopkins, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tori-peschel/\">Tori Peschel</a></strong> of Sauk Centre, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-meyer/\">Paige Meyer</a></strong> of Albany, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brielle-bartelt/\">Brielle Bartelt</a></strong> of Waterville-Elysian-Morristown, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/katie-borowicz/\">Katie Borowicz</a></strong> of Roseau and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/frankie-vascellaro/\">Frankie Vascellaro</a></strong> of Holy Angels, who scored 36 against Robbinsdale Cooper last week. Junior <strong>Logan Anderson </strong>is emerging as an offensive threat for Forest Lake following mass graduations last spring. Anderson had 31 points in the Rangers’ win over Woodbury, a game in which she went 15-for-15 at the free throw line to establish a new school record. She’s leading the Rangers in scoring at 20 ppg. <strong>Haley Hawkinson</strong> of Hibbing had a 31-point performance last week against Princeton and is averaging 18.\n\n<strong>Minnesota’s top 10 scorers</strong>\n\nThe list of top 10 scorers in the state is chock-full of familiar names, including the leading point producer overall – <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/gianna-kneepkens/\">Gianna Kneepkens</a></strong> of Duluth Marshall. The junior guard led the state in scoring last year, as well, and is currently at 35 ppg. She’s followed by Borowicz at 30 and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/adalia-mackenzie/\">Adalia McKenzie</a></strong> of Park Center at 28.2. Other familiar faces in the top 10 include <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jade-hill/\">Jade Hill</a></strong> of Minneapolis South (26.3), MSU-Moorhead commit <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/karley-motschenbacher/\">Karley Motschenbacher</a></strong> of Park Christian (26.3) and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mia-curtis/\">Mia Curtis</a></strong> of Minnehaha Academy (25.7), who had a 41-point performance in a four-overtime win against Sauk Centre. <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mallory-brake/\">Mallory Brake</a></strong> of Hastings (24.8) and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lilly-meister/\">Lilly Meister</a></strong> of Rochester John Marshall (24.7) are among the top 10, too.\n\nThere is one less-familiar name in that group: <strong>Abbie Theusch</strong> from Alden-Conger/Glenville-Emmons, who is in fourth place at 27 points per game. The 5’9 junior had a 30-point performance against Grand Meadow, a game in which she went 13-of-23 from the field, 5-of-7 at the line, and had 7 rebounds, 3 assists and 10 steals! Although she finished second on her team in scoring last year to <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/erika-bute/\">Erika Bute</a></strong>, who now plays volleyball at Augustana, Theusch averaged over 20 points per game. FYI, since I had to look it up, Alden is located in Freeborn County about 20 minutes west of Albert Lea.\n\n<strong>New kids on the block </strong>\n\nAlthough she’s not a complete unknown, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-peaslee/\">Paige Peaslee</a></strong> is definitely drawing more attention so far this season. The 5’11 sophomore forward from North Branch has bettered the 20-point mark in three of the Vikings’ four games to date and is averaging 19.2, up 8 from last season. North Branch won just five games in 2018-19. They are currently 4-0. One player who has definitely been a surprise is 7th grader <strong>Ella Kuhlman</strong>, who sits fourth in scoring on the team at 9 points per game.\n\nIn Osseo, 8th grader <strong>Ava Holman</strong> led the team in points in two of their first three games. The North Tartan athlete leads the squad at 13.3 points per game. At Blake, 7th grader <strong>Addison Mack</strong> launched her high school career with 23 against Mayer Lutheran and followed that up with 21 versus South St. Paul. Mack is averaging 16.2 ppg, but it is her distribution and court savvy that is most worthy of note.\n\n<strong>Leading from three</strong>\n\nNo matter how much we beg and plead it is still a chore getting high school coaches to post anything beyond point totals with their game scores. Even that is an issue in many places. As a result, kids don’t always get recognized for their accomplishments. I wouldn’t have known, for example, that MSU-commit <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-thompson/\">Paige Thompson</a></strong> of Hawley went 29 and 12 against Frazee if someone hadn’t given me a heads up. Some diligent coaches do a good job, however, including posting three-point makes. Among those who have posted, these are the leaders.\n\n18 – <strong>Larisa O’Neil</strong>, senior guard, Rosemount\n\n17 – <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/taryn-hamling/\">Taryn Hamling</a></strong>, freshman guard, Grand Rapids\n\n17 – <strong>Emily Christenson</strong>, freshman guard, East Ridge\n\n16 – <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tanna-gallo/\">Tanna Gallo</a></strong>, senior guard Minnehaha Academy (Waldorf)\n\n15 – <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexi-cloyd/\">Lexi Cloyd</a></strong>, junior guard, Lake Crystal-Wellcome Memorial\n\n14 – <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/natalie-mikrot/\">Natalie Mikrot</a></strong>, sophomore guard, Moose Lake-Willow River\n\n14 – <strong>Laura Hauge</strong>, 8th grade guard, St. Croix Lutheran\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><em>Top photo: Abbie Theusch of Alden-Conger/Glenville-Emmons (in black) is soaring towards the top of the state in scoring so far this season. (Photo courtesy of Albert Lea Tribune)</em></span>','Which Minnesota players are off to a fast start?','','publish','open','open','','which-minnesota-players-are-off-to-a-fast-start','','','2019-12-09 18:06:43','2019-12-10 00:06:43','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=122995',0,'post','',0),
	(123043,1,'2019-12-09 20:49:28','2019-12-10 02:49:28','Over the first month of the season, I spent a great deal of time evaluating teams and prospects along I-69 Northeast of Indianapolis. Below is a look at 11 members of the 2020 class who I thought stood out in the action I was able to take in.  There will be follow-up articles with members of the 2021, 2022, and 2023 classes.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/breann-barger/\">Breann Barger</a>, 2020, 5-11 F, Norwell H.S.</strong>\n\nI have watched Breann play since she was younger, and her progression has been really fun to see. She has an athletic frame with length, she moves well in most directions, and she plays with a good motor. When she was younger, she was much more limited to the interior, but now she is comfortable around the perimeter, she can attack the basket a little off the bounce, but she\'s best attacking or hitting shots from the mid-post. Without a big history of playing travel ball, her exposure has been limited, but I think she could be a nice, versatile, small college \"sleeper\".\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kassidy-dishman/\">Kassidy Dishman</a>, 2020, 5-7 G, Delta H.S.</strong>\n\nI have seen Kassidy since her Sophomore year, and she is by far and away playing much better and more completely than she ever has. She is a strong, physical, and skilled combo guard. For Delta, Kassidy is the primary ball-handler, she operates their offense efficiently, but she is also hitting shots from the perimeter more consistently and doing a nice job of getting to the basket and drawing free throw opportunities. If she could do anything better, it would be to defend the ball a bit better, as she needs to be more explosive. But she is a really nice prospect many small colleges have likely never even heard of.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rashaya-kyle/\">RaShaya Kyle</a>, 2020, 6-6 C, Marion H.S.</strong>\n\nWhen motivated, RaShaya is not only one of the best prospects in the state, but also in the country. So far this season, she has been very motivated and posted 30-point games, triple-doubles, etc. She has the skill to handle the ball in transition, she has the skill to knock down outside jumpers, but this season I see her playing more in the mid-post, aggressively attacking the basket off the bounce, and going straight to the low-block and dominating. She is using her physical traits to overwhelm opponents much more than in past seasons. RaShaya has signed to attend and play at Purdue University next season.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Erin Lehner, 2020, 5-7 W, Southwood H.S.</strong>\n\nErin has been a integral part of Southwood\'s team the past two seasons, and she\'s one of their best players again this season. She has good length, some athleticism, and she plays with versatility. At times she acts as a point forward and primary ball-handler, plus she can slash to the basket to get easy scores. Her perimeter shot has been more consistent this year, but that part of her game can continue to improve to make her a dual-threat offensively. I also like her potential to become a tough defensive matchup.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Izabella Mitchell, 2020, 5-9 W, Wes-Del H.S.</strong>\n\nIzzy is a solidly built wing who has been a Varsity regular for most of her career. Towards the end of the 2018-2019 season, Izzy suffered an ACL injury, but she is back playing already. She still isn\'t quite as explosive as she was a year ago, but she should get there in time. She has a solid handle and plays a point forward position for Wes-Del, she can shoot it a little from outside, and she\'s a physical rebounder from the perimeter. I really like a lot of what she does for the small college level, and I think she could eventually be a versatile, impactful wing at the next level.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Makenna Pace, 2020, 5-5 G, Southwood H.S.</strong>\n\nMakenna is another Southwood perimeter player who has been vital to their lineup since she got to high school. She has a solid frame, she\'s a decent athlete, though she could stand to be a bit more explosive, but she has been their best threat to shoot/score the ball. She moves very well without the basketball and does a nice job of finding space. She has become a real threat who can knock down rhythm jumpers with consistency, and she\'s doing more off the dribble this season. At her size, if she could ever show the ability to be more of a traditional point guard full-time, I think it would help her recruiting.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Gracie Phillips, 2020, 5-3 G, Tipton H.S.</strong>\n\nGracie is one of the few Varsity regulars who returns from the Blue Devils strong 2018-2019 team. Despite her size, she is better off the ball. She can handle it and play point, but her ability to move without the basketball, coupled with her consistency knocking down outside jumpers, make her a real threat alongside the athletic younger wings Tipton possesses. Size will be an issue with her recruitment, but she is tough-nosed, somewhat feisty, and really understands her role and how to play. I think she could be an asset at the small college level as a \"glue\" kid.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Marissa Quiroz, 2020, 5-11 F/C, Muncie Central H.S.</strong>\n\nMarissa is back, following a 2018-2019 knee injury that kept her out all season. She is a solidly built, strong front-liner, but she also possesses good skill around the perimeter. She handles it reasonably well for her size, she has good instincts and is a nice passer, plus she can knock down the occasional perimeter jumper, though her shot selection could definitely improve. I think by the end of the season, once she fully returns to herself, she could be a very recruitable, small college, face-up \'5\' for the next level.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Abby Shaw, 2020, 5-6 W, Oak Hill H.S.</strong>\n\nOak Hill was the 2019 Class 2A State Champion, but they also graduated a number of statistical performers who are now playing at the next level. Minus those losses, Abby has seen her role increase a great deal, and she has become their #2 option. She has a solid, wiry strong frame, she\'s a decent athlete with a great motor, but she\'s also an accurate shooter who I think can help provide a 3-point presence to a small college one year from now. She could stand to be a bit more versatile, but her ability to make shots could be coveted by the right coach.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ellie-vermillion/\">Ellie Vermillion</a>, 2020, 5-5 PG, Marion H.S.</strong>\n\nA year ago when I saw Ellie, I was intrigued by her overall game. This season, I am very impressed with how far she has come in such a short time. She is strong, physical, and tough-nosed as a point guard. She shows good quickness, solid speed, but she also understands how to change speeds at the right time. Her perimeter stroke is more accurate than ever, and you must respect her from the moment she crosses into her team\'s side of half-court. She has also worked on speeding up her release and shooting an athletic, true jump-shot. She has signed with Indiana Wesleyan University, and I think they might have found themselves a real \"sleeper\".\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/taylor-westgate/\">Taylor Westgate</a>, 2020, 6-1 F/C, Oak Hill H.S.</strong>\n\nTaylor is a player in the 2020 class who I thought was under-recruited throughout the entire recruiting process. I think she has found a great location/fit for herself after signing with Taylor University, and they have likely gotten a steal in her. She has good size, strength, and she plays with physicality. There aren\'t many front-liners in Indiana who rim-run end to end like she does. In the past for Oak Hill, she has fulfilled a vital role as a rebounder, defender, and post player. This season, minus several 2019 graduations, she has taken on a much bigger role and is showing her all-around skill with regards to handling the ball away from the basket, knocking down jump-shots, and allowing to offense to flow through her.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<i>Feature image is of <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rashaya-kyle/\">RaShaya Kyle</a> of Marion High School.</i>','November Review: Class of 2020','','publish','open','open','','november-review-class-of-2020','','','2019-12-09 20:49:28','2019-12-10 02:49:28','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123043',0,'post','',0),
	(123077,1,'2019-12-10 12:00:23','2019-12-10 18:00:23','This past Saturday was the season’s first installment of the Chicagoland Invitational Showcase, hosted by Fremd High School. The event displayed eleven games featuring several of Illinois’ top teams, in addition to top teams from Wisconsin (Beaver Dam) and Indiana (Crown Point). With these great teams, came dozens of high-level and intriguing players. Here are a few of the top performances from the day:\n\nLake Forest star and Wisconsin commit <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/halle-douglass/\">Halle Douglass</a></strong> was, once again, outstanding in the days first game against Marist. Offensively, the 6’2” Point Guard was excellent all around. She is a tough matchup inside with her length and athleticism and knocked down a couple outside jumpers, both off the dribble and from spotting up, <img class=\"size-medium wp-image-111387 alignright\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Halle-Douglass-e1573572506154-300x248.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"248\" />netting 23 points in the game. Douglass is a tremendous passer with great court vision and makes those around her better. Defensively, I’m not sure there’s a better post defender and shot blocker in the area.\n\nWhen watching Benet Academy play, you quickly realize that there are eight or nine players that could go off in any given game. On Saturday against Lincoln-Way West, it was 5’8” Junior Point Guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/molly-sheehan/\">Molly Sheehan</a></strong>. Sheehan consistently displays great ball handling and passing abilities, and the scoring is starting to come. She knocked down five three’s and added a couple transition layups to lead Benet with 19 points.\n\nRivaling Sheehan for Lincoln-Way West was standout Senior Point Guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/taylor-gugliuzza/\">Taylor Gugliuzza</a></strong>. The 5’7” Lewis commit is a knock-down shooter from deep, but also displayed her crafty inside scoring in this game. LWW thrives at turning steals into transition buckets, and Gugliuzza is among the best at it. She finished with a game-high 24 points.\n\nThe lone underclassman on this list, nobody had a bigger day than Hersey’s <strong>Katy Eidle</strong>. The dynamic 5’11” Freshman Point Guard did it all, dropping 32 points and bringing 10 rebounds in a win over Bartlett. Eidle is a playmaker with the ball in her hands with the ability to finish at a high level at the rim or step outside and knock down threes at a high rate.\n\nAfter eclipsing the 1,000 career points mark earlier in the week, 5’8” Bartlett Point Guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexie-sinclair/\">Lexie Sinclair</a></strong> added 25 more against Hersey. She can hit jumpers from time to time, but Sinclair thrives at getting in the lane and either finishing strong at the hoop or drawing fouls and knocking down Free Throws. She’s a defender that will wear opposing guards down throughout the game and takes advantage with steals and transition buckets.\n\nIn what was the best game of the day, <strong>Ambrea Gentle</strong> was unstoppable in Evanston’s win over Beaver Dam (WI). The 6’3” Senior Center put up 29 points over one of the top teams in Wisconsin. Gentle uses her body well to get position in the post and sets herself up nicely for easy buckets. Her footwork and post moves are very impressive, and with Evanston’s stellar guard play, she should be able to avoid a large number of double teams.','Chicagoland Invitational Showcase: Top Performances','','publish','open','open','','chicagoland-invitational-showcase-top-performances','','','2019-12-10 12:00:23','2019-12-10 18:00:23','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123077',0,'post','',0),
	(123078,1,'2019-12-09 21:55:00','2019-12-10 03:55:00','The 9th annual Dan Fitzgerald Memorial Basketball Showcase was another successful display of high level girl\'s basketball talent from around the region. Past performers have included UConn\'s Evina Westbrook, Stanford\'s Haley Jones, Oregon\'s Otiona Gildon and many more players that have gone on to play at the highest levels on down. This year\'s group included nine players headed to a variety Division 1 conferences and they all had their different shining moments.\n\n2020 5\'11 PG <strong>Mary Kay Naro</strong> (Beaverton HS) - Mary Kay did what has become the norm for her and that is run the offense, facilitate to teammates and score when the opportunity presents itself. She had 15 points versus Central Valley, but most importantly, she is a winner and she helped her team to a 2-0 record at this year\'s event. *Boise State signee\n\n2020 6\'1 F <strong>Sydney Erikstrup</strong> (Beaverton HS) - Sydney was a load to handle in both games, putting up 15 and 16 points versus two really solid GSL teams. She can score inside and out and crashed the boards time after time. *Arizona State signee\n\n2020 6\'2 F <strong>Laura Erikstrup</strong> (Beaverton HS) - She scored nine points in game one, but picked it up in game two pouring in 18 and dominating University inside. Laura has a strong frame, but she has more than enough skill at the same time. She definitely had dominant stretches. *San Diego signee\n\n2020 5\'9 PG <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/peyton-howard/\">Peyton Howard</a></strong> (Central Valley HS) - Peyton was impressive on both days all around. She commanded the ball, knew time and possession and made winning plays. She was a difficult matchup for Beaverton, scoring 18 points on day one. *Seattle U signee\n\n2021 5\'10 SG <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mj-bruno/\">MJ Bruno</a></strong> (Central Valley HS) - MJ gave her usual energy this past weekend and did a lot of little things to keep her team competitive. She had some drives against Beaverton, finishing with 9 points and she led CV in scoring with 13 in their win over St. Ignatius. *Portland verbal / Feature image\n\n2020 5\'8 PG <strong>Rachel Harvey</strong> (St. Ignatius HS) - Despite being in early foul trouble and sitting nearly half the game, Rachel put up 14 points in the double OT loss to University. She had some really nice drives to the basket, displaying quickness and craftiness around the hoop. *CSUN signee\n\n2020 5\'9 PG <span style=\"color: #00ccff;\"><a style=\"color: #00ccff;\" href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/elizabeth-boni/\"><strong>Ellie Boni</strong></a> </span>(University HS) - Completely dominant on day one! She put up 35 points and double digit rebounds versus St. Ignatius. Ellie scored nine in a big loss to Beaverton, but the Titans just looked completely gassed from their game the night before. Still, a good all around showing for Ellie Boni. *Colorado State signee\n\n2020 5\'10 SG <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tyler-mccliment-call/\">Tyler McCliment-Call</a></strong> (University HS) - Tyler was very aggressive looking for her own shot on both days and she definitely put the ball in the hoop. With 31 on day one and 24 on day two, Tyler led the event in scoring for 2019, but her team will look to regroup after a 47-70 loss to Beaverton. *Portland signee\n\n2020 5\'9 SG <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jacksen-mccliment-call/\">Jacksen McCliment-Call</a></strong> (University HS) - Jacksen\'s three point stroke looked good this event and she found herself with some really good looks from long range with so much of the defense focused on Tyler and Ellie. She made seven threes between the two games and showed why she is one of the better shooters in the state. *Portland signee','Division 1 Committed Players Shine at Fitz Tourney!','','publish','open','open','','division-1-committed-players-shine-at-fitz-tourney','','','2019-12-09 21:55:00','2019-12-10 03:55:00','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123078',0,'post','',0),
	(123086,1,'2019-12-10 08:00:09','2019-12-10 14:00:09','The Lady Pioneers of Simon Kenton defeated the George Rogers Clark Lady Cardinals Tuesday night by a score of 78 to 58.  Simon Kenton lit up the scoreboard in the first half for 51 points, and although the Lady Cardinals clamped down defensively in the second half they did not quite have the offensive firepower to make a comeback.  There were standout players on each side, so here are some awards for the best individual performances.\n\n<strong>Low-Post Presence: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/morgan-stamper/\">Morgan Stamper</a>, Simon Kenton- </strong>While Simon Kenton generated much of their offense with strong outside shooting, they may not have gotten as many open shots without the physical inside play of Stamper.  The senior forward was obviously comfortable down low, scoring herself as well as passing the ball out to generate open shots for her teammates.  She ended up with 17 points, 6 rebounds, and 3 assists, as well as 4 steals, showing that her low-post play was excellent on both ends.\n\n<strong>Best at Drawing Contact: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tyra-flowers/\">Tyra Flowers</a>, George Rogers Clark- </strong>In a game where they struggled to get into a rhythm offensively, the Lady Cardinals were at their best when they were able to get inside and draw contact.  Nobody was better at this than Flowers, who spent much of her night at the line.  The sophomore forward earned 5 of her 11 points at the line before fouling out due to her overall physical play.  Had she not gotten into foul trouble Flowers may have been able to create even more problems for the Lady Pioneers.\n\n<strong>Stat-Sheet Stuffer: Brianna Bryars, George Rogers Clark- </strong>Bryars did a little bit of everything to try to keep the Lady Cardinals in the game.  She played well in all phases and ended up with 14 points, 6 rebounds, and 2 assists.  Even as a freshman she looked poised throughout, making more plays than anyone else on her team and ending up with a stat sheet to reflect that.\n\n<strong>Best Hustle: Chelsea Little, Simon Kenton- </strong>Little was all over the place, disrupting passing lanes, grabbing boards, and diving on the floor for loose balls.  The senior also displayed a nice stroke, knocking down some jump shots and all of her free throw opportunities.  She ended up with 9 points, 3 rebounds, 2 assists, and a block and steal, but those stats don\'t truly capture the impact she had on the game.\n\n<strong>MVP: Maggi Jones, Simon Kenton- </strong>While Simon Kenton as a team was strong offensively, nobody lit up the scoreboard like Jones.  The senior guard made her first five threes before finally missing one in the fourth quarter, and ended up with 21 points overall on very efficient shooting.  Aside from her scoring contributions, Jones also controlled the pace of the game and made good passes throughout, setting up much of the offense for her teammates.  There is no doubt that she was the standout of the evening and the biggest piece of the Lady Pioneers\' win.','Simon Kenton vs George Rogers Clark Individual Awards','','publish','open','open','','simon-kenton-vs-george-rogers-clark-individual-awards','','','2019-12-10 08:00:09','2019-12-10 14:00:09','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123086',0,'post','',0),
	(123107,1,'2019-12-09 23:30:51','2019-12-10 05:30:51','Strawberry Crest High School is located in Dover, Florida. The Lady Chargers are coached by Coach Latosha Lewis. This is Coach Lewis’ eleventh (11th) season at Strawberry Crest High School. Coach Lewis has an impressive coaching resume, coaching Division 1 College basketball for ten (10) years (5 years at Stephen F. Austin/5 years at The University of Central Florida), four (4) years at the Semi-Pro level, five (5) years AAU, and now eleven (11) years at the high school level. With the background of Coach Lewis it’s no surprise that she has created a winning culture at Strawberry Crest. In her tenure, she has assisted eight (8) student-athletes play basketball at the collegiate level. With the talent on her roster this season, I see this number definitely increasing.\n\nThe Lady Chargers finished the 2018-2019 season at 22-7. Coach Lewis has the expectations this season to win another district title. Her goal for her team is to compete at the highest level every time they step on the court and to be better then they were the year prior. Coach Lewis is excited about this year due to the talent on her roster. She has many talented players with on the court experience. The Lady Chargers have three (3) seniors (<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/megan-watson/\">Megan Watson</a>, Aset Franklin, and Taylor Butler) on the floor that are  leading the way for the underclassmen.  Taylor Butler is a veteran point guard that makes everyone around her better. Butler is a natural leader with excellent court vision. Up and coming Freshman Ki’Ajane Gordon is going to be a force to be reckon with. Gordon had a breakout game vs Seffner Christian where she had 16 points, 8 rebounds, 2 steals, and 1 assist. “Gordon has the potential to be one of the top players in Florida,” stated Coach Lewis.\n\nCoach Lewis and the Lady Chargers have started the 2019-2020 season at 3-1. With the combination of elite coaching and a talented roster the sky is the limit this season for Strawberry Crest High School.','Season Preview: Strawberry Crest High School Lady Chargers','','publish','open','open','','team-spotlight-strawberry-crest-high-school','','','2019-12-09 23:30:51','2019-12-10 05:30:51','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123107',0,'post','',0),
	(123118,1,'2019-12-09 22:40:46','2019-12-10 04:40:46','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">One of Missouri’s top small school players, Green City 2020 <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brooke-littrell/\">Brooke Littrell</a> is poised for a big senior season after a strong offseason with the Missouri Phenom.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">At 6’1, Littrell has terrific size and athleticism who has scored 2,230 points and 944 career rebounds entering her senior season. Growing up a farm in rural Missouri, Littrell says she brings a strong work ethic to the court.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I’m a farm kid and have been carrying feed buckets and wrestling hogs around since I was little,” she says. “If a 700-pound boar doesn\'t intimidate me, nothing else will.  I pride myself on being very difficult to Coach against. I play guard or in the post. If they put a guard on me, I’ll move to post her up, if its a post type player, I\'ll make her come out and guard me. It\'s hard to find just one girl to guard me, and I work extremely hard to make sure of that.  </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I shoot a really high percentage from beyond the three to try and stretch the floor but prefer to make my threes the old fashioned way with the “and one!”  It\'s honestly just more fun to get in there and beat around.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Littrell averaged 30.9 points and 10.8 rebounds last season for a Class 1 team that went 19-4 and advanced to the state quarterfinals.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Although it wasn\'t enough to get our team where we wanted to be.  Im looking forward to this year and hoping we can accomplish our goals of a final four appearance,” Littrell said. “The girls I play with are my best friends, we win it all or go down together.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“This season is really exciting for me.  We only lost one senior, and although she was a great player, we have someone stepping into her spot who is great as well.  We are playing fast and in great shape. In June we started running three miles several times a week as a team then working out afterward.  At this point for us as a team, anything less than a final four will be a disappointment.” </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">After a strong summer running with the Missouri Phenom and played for coaches Dennis Baggett, Devin Griffin, Nikki Kuchta and Greg Logsdon and says the experience helped prepare her for the upcoming season and beyond.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Coach Possail has also really helped me along the way,” Littrell says. “I have had some amazing Coaches who have pushed me and my game to new levels all the time.  Summer ball really helps me adjust and play better during the season. During High School ball I almost always see a box and one or even a triangle and two. Most coaches don\'t do that during the summer it really helps me work on my game.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Littrell says Devin Fields, coach Green City Cody Moore, trainer Matt Ayers, coach Logsdon from the Phenom, and others have all had the biggest impact on her basketball career to date.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Throughout my basketball career I\'ve had so many people believe in me and help me,” she says. “My friend Devin Fields, who plays for Truman State, has pushed me since I was a little kid. His Father is one of my Coaches and has always inspired me and held me to a very high standard.  Last year he never stopped helping me even though he was battling cancer. He never missed a game or a practice. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I have also been blessed to have Cody Moore every year as my high school coach. Not very many players are able for that to happen and I think that has been a huge part in our success as a team. He has helped in a lot of ways and we were able to have a great connection on and off the court. Matt Ayers has trained me for several years now.  He lives on a farm down the road from us. He was a Coach at the collegiate level and transformed my game dramatically. Coach Logsdon from the Phenom has been one of my biggest fans and just fills me with confidence and teaches me all the little things. He has been a huge, huge part of any of my success. And finally, my parents. All the travel, driving countless hours, the time sitting in a gym.  It\'s more than I can ever be thankful enough for.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A fan of former NBA players Larry Bird, Michael Jordan, Dirk Nowitzki and Akeem Olajuwon.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I have been trying to copy Birds swagger and confidence for years, and Jordans “you will never beat me” stare, along with his approach to the game,” she says. “Dirks fadeaway is a work in progress for me but Im getting it down enough to start using it in a game, and my Dream Shake isn\'t too bad.  Ive been using it in practice quite a bit so I can try and use it more often in a game.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Littrell recently committed to the University of Central Missouri.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“ I know the coaches there can lead me through the experience of the next level and help me adjust and be successful,” she said. “UCM is already a very good team.  I just hope that I can contribute to that in some way as much as I possibly can. I know it will be a whole new world and I\'m ready for the challenge.”</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Brooke Littrell (2020)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-brooke-littrell-2020','','','2019-12-09 22:40:46','2019-12-10 04:40:46','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123118',0,'post','',0),
	(123128,1,'2019-12-09 23:02:14','2019-12-10 05:02:14','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A rising player in Kansas 2020 class, Andover small forward <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/emma-cunningham/\">Emma Cunningham</a> is gearing up for a big senior season after running with Next Level Eclipse this summer.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A versatile, well-rounded player, Cunninghham is a strong defensive player who can play an inside-out brand of basketball.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A year ago, she was new to Andover but says she quickly fit in and enjoyed the experience. With several key players returning in 2019-20, Cunningham says the expectations are high at the school for the upcoming season.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400\">My high school season last year was definitely one to remember, I was new to the school and team but they were very welcoming,” Cunningham said. “Our season didn’t end the way we wanted it to. We had many close games. We were a solid team, but it just didn’t go our way. I felt like I did pretty good, considering I moved from a 4A school to a 5A school. I loved playing with them. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I am very excited for my upcoming season. we have a new coach who I think is a great fit for our team. I think it might be a difficult season, but I think we will be able to hold our own. I don’t really have any expectations yet. Of course I want us to have a winning season, but I think it will be exciting to see where Coach Anderson can take us. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I am really looking forward to playing Goddard Eisenhower. The first time we played them, we lost, but the second time we played them, we went into 2 overtime’s and I made the winning shot, so i think they might be looking for some revenge.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Cunningham says playing for Next Level Eclipse 2020 McCorry helped her prepare for the upcoming season</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“We had so much fun on and off the court,” she said. “We had such a good connection to each other which made it even better. I had great coaches that pushed me to be the very best I could possible be. Being with them taught me how to be the best teammate and friend that I could be.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Cunningham says her dad has had the biggest influence on her basketball career.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“He has always been there to help me improve my game. He is my biggest fan,” she says.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">A fan of former UConn standout Katie Lou Samuelson, Cunningham says she appreciated her all-around style of play. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“Her style of ball reminds me of me and I loved watching her move on the court,” Cunningham said. “I felt I wanted to mirror her. She was such an aggressive player, with a great shot.”</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Cunningham recently committed to Baker University and chose the school after visiting the campus and meeting the team.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I was able to meet and practice with the team this summer, and later went on visit,” she says. “I met with Coach Rees and toured the campus and just knew it was the right fit academically and athletically. They have a great exercise science program which I am wanting to peruse to become a chiropractor. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">“I am an aggressive player that has what Coach Rees is looking for. I am able to play many positions on the court which makes me a very versatile player. I am looking forward to working with Coach Rees and having the opportunity to better my game.”</span>','Prospect Spotlight: Emma  Cunningham (2020)','','publish','open','open','','prospect-spotlight-emma-cunningham-2020','','','2019-12-09 23:02:14','2019-12-10 05:02:14','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123128',0,'post','',0),
	(123145,1,'2019-12-10 01:15:35','2019-12-10 07:15:35','<b>#1 Sabino 7-0</b>\n\nSabino remains at the #1 spot through the Pre-Season and throughout the first update of the power rankings. Sabino has a ton of firepower and I would guess that they’ll stay up here at the number one spot for a while. Around thanksgiving, Sabino had a great showing, beating 3 top 6A schools.\n\n<b>#2 Page 4-0</b>\n\nPage has looked very impressive thus far, going 4-0 and beating Winslow. Only time will tell how could this team could be. I think if any squad in 3A could overtake the number one spot, it’ll be Page.\n\n<b>#3 Chinle 2-1</b>\n\nChinle comes in at number 3 and I think this group could do something special. Behind the efforts of Tea Murray, they defeated Holbrook and I think Murray and her teammates will keep the ball rolling throughout the season. They could be a sleeper team!\n\n<b>#4 Winslow 1-1</b>\n\nWinslow has a couple prospects that I am inter interested in that could potentially go under the radar. I’ll have to check them out further to see if they are legit or not. My guess would be on the former.\n\n<b>#5 ALA-QC 6-3</b>\n\nAmerican Leadership Academy-Queen Creek may  be a shock to a lot of people. However, what I have seen so far is some good stuff! They’re team is very well balanced and they have really good team chemistry. I know their record doesn’t show how good they are or could be, but if they get clicking, they could be dangerous. Look for ALA-QC to be a dark horse team in 3A this season.','Power Rankings: 3A','','publish','open','open','','power-rankings-3a','','','2019-12-10 01:15:35','2019-12-10 07:15:35','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123145',0,'post','',0),
	(123160,1,'2019-12-08 17:00:14','2019-12-08 23:00:14','Each Sunday we will be posting the previous week\'s player evaluations. This past week we headed out to four games and saw eight different teams and four really solid games. We were able to see Aplington-Parkersburg vs. BCLUW, Roland-Story vs. East Marshall, Center Point-Urbana vs. Waverly-Shell Rock, and Indianola vs. Norwalk. Below you can find 25 evaluations on players that stood out the most.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophia-jungling/\">Sophia Jungling</a> - 5\'5 PG - 2020 - Aplington-Parkersburg</strong>\nJungling was all over the floor in her game as she was able to attack the defense with her driving ability but also had her court vision on full display. She has a great motor and the ability to decide the outcome of the game herself with her defense. <em>Committed to Northern Iowa for Track.</em>\n\n<strong>Megan Johnson - 5\'9 SG - 2020 - Aplington-Parkersburg</strong>\nJohnson looks much more confident in her jumper than she did last year. Johnson is an active player on both ends of the floor and holds the ability to get the ball up the court quickly. She has active hands on the defensive end of the floor and with her length she is able to create a lot of turnovers.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madison-ubben/\">Madison Ubben</a> - 5\'11 PF - 2020 - BCLUW</strong>\nUbben was impressive in the post with her ability to score with both hands. She is a very good rebounder who has the ability to go and grab the ball, not just wait for it to drop off the rim to her. Ubben is an under-the-radar talent in the class in the post.\n\n<strong>Allison Engle - 5\'10 F - 2021 - BCLUW</strong>\nEngle plays a bit out of position for BCLUW as she is likely going to be a wing or a stretch-four at the next level. She can handle the ball well for her size and can initiate the offense. She had a solid game for BCLUW and as she develops could be a steal for a small school at the next level that utilizes her well.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/reagan-barkema/\">Reagan Barkema</a> - 5\'11 SF - 2022 - Roland-Story</strong>\nBarkema has improved so much over the past year that it is almost uncanny. She can knock down shots at a much more consistent rate now. If anything, I would like her to be even more aggressive with the ball in her hands as she was sometimes thinking too much about driving or shooting it.\n\n<strong>Reece Johnson - 5\'6 G - 2022 - Roland-Story</strong>\nJohnson is a nice piece for Roland-Story as she does a little bit of everything on the floor. Defensively she was very solid as she’s gotten a little quicker over the past year and is much more aggressive on that end. Johnson also scored the ball well against East Marshall while shooting the ball solidly from deep.\n\n<strong>Juliann Clark - 5\'5 PG - 2020 - Roland-Story</strong>\nClark is a very solid lead guard who you can trust with the ball in her hands. She can score the ball but tends to take on more of a distributing role. She has good awareness on the floor and finds the open man leading to easy baskets. Really quick hands on the defensive end.\n\n<strong>Olivia Terrones - 5\'7 SF - 2020 - East Marshall</strong>\nTerrones is an intriguing guard because I think she can be good with some additional scorers around her and at Eas Marshall that’s just not the case. She would fit well as the two or three in a motion offense as she can hit off the catch well. She’ll post big numbers this year because she has to.\n\n<strong>Clare Veren - 5\'9 SF - 2021 - East Marshall</strong>\nI liked Veren as she was super active on both ends of the floor. She was at the top of the press and showed a very good ability to get her hands on the ball. She showed the ability to shoot the ball from the perimeter but also get into the lane and score. She’s someone to keep an eye on.\n\n<strong>Ellie Hull - 5\'7 G - 2022 - East Marshall</strong>\nHull struggled a bit shooting the ball but was an overall very solid player for East Marshall. She has a high basketball IQ and a very solid court vision allowing her to pass teammates open. Her quickness also allows her to generate steals and put pressure on the offense.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/adrianna-katcher/\">Adrianna Katcher</a> - 5\'11 SF - 2020 - Center Point-Urbana</strong>\nKatcher struggled early on in the game against Waverly-Shell Rock but settled in after a while. I thought that she played at a good pace throughout the game and got others involved. She has the ability to get going on the offensive end but I thought her defense was what won them the game. <em>Southern Illinois commit.</em>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ryley-goebel/\">Ryley Goebel</a> - 5\'11 SF - 2022 - Center Point-Urbana</strong>\nGoebel was as good as advertised once again. Her defense is one of the best in the state with her ability to force steals at the top of their press. She showed the willingness to shoot the jumper and as that becomes a more consistent piece to her game, her overall ability is going to take off even more.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/bryn-hadsall/\">Bryn Hadsall</a> - 5\'6 PG - 2020 - Center Point-Urbana</strong>\nHadsall is the next point guard in line for her team. Even though she didn’t score the ball, she showed the ability to create her own shot and get teammates in good positions to score. Hadsall plays tough and looks to hit the boards hard despite her size.\n\n<strong>Emma DeSmet - 5\'11 SF - 2021 - Center Point-Urbana</strong>\nDeSmet didn’t play much in the game but she is a very intriguing piece for Center Point-Urbana. She is a mobile wing who has a lot of length. She moves well without the ball and can rebound it at a high level when in the game.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/laine-hadsall/\">Laine Hadsall</a> - 5\'3 PG - 2023 - Center Point-Urbana</strong>\nHadsall came off the bench and was someone who caught my eye with the ability to shoot the ball. She was 1-of-3 on the night but was able to knock one down off-the-catch. She’ll continue to improve as she gets older.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/abbie-draper/\">Abbie Draper</a> - 6\'1 PF - 2021 - Waverly-Shell Rock</strong>\nDraper was a stalwart on the inside for Waverly-Shell Rock. She was able to score the ball on pretty much every touch and she rebounded the ball at a high level. I would like to see her be a little more aggressive on the inside with her skill because she’s going to have to be the bulk of the scoring this year. <em>Bradley commit.</em>\n\n<strong>Britney Young - 5\'8 G - 2020 - Waverly-Shell Rock</strong>\nYoung had tremendous success shooting the ball against Center Point-Urbana. She showed confidence in her jumper and also showed the ability to connect from well beyond the arc. She dished off five assists in the game showcasing her overall offensive ability. She’s a player who I think can be good at the next level.\n\n<strong>Camryn Grawe - 5\'7 G - 2020 - Waverly-Shell Rock</strong>\nGrawe didn’t score as much as she can but she still had a good game as she was able to dish off a few assists and had a couple steals as well. She has a good frame that can hold strength allows her to defend at a high level but also finish through contact. I’ve always been impressed with her game.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/trinidee-moore/\">Trinidee Moore</a> - 5\'6 PG - 2022 - Waverly-Shell Rock</strong>\nMoore came off the bench in this game but was effective on both ends. She is a smart player who controls the ball well and plays very solid defense. She might not enter the stat sheet a ton, but she is such a solid all-around player. Great ability to create for others.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-blake/\">Lauren Blake</a> - 5\'10 SF - 2022 - Indianola</strong>\nI was very impressed with Blake against Norwalk. She showed the ability to score both in transition and in the half-court at all three levels. Early in the spring Blake was a little raw but very athletic and now she’s improved her skill quite a bit and shows flashes of being able to take over a game. Really impressed with her performance.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\"> </span>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kendall-clatt/\">Kendall Clatt</a> - 5\'10 SG - 2021 - Indianola</strong>\nClatt was able to shoot the ball at a high level against Norwalk as she was 3-for-6 from behind the arc and ended up scoring 18 points in the game. She can be a really solid scorer from the two-guard spot in college and I think her summer and now her junior year is showing just that.\n\n<strong>Alley May - 5\'10 PF - 2021 - Indianola</strong>\nI hadn’t seen May prior to this week and I was really impressed with what I saw from her. She an athletic rebounder who high points the ball really well off the rim. May has the ability to score the ball but didn’t really do that much around the rim scoring-wise. She is someone who could jump on the radar quickly.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mara-bishop/\">Mara Bishop</a> - 5\'7 G - 2022 - Indianola</strong>\nBishop was all over the floor playing at a high level. She has the ability to score the ball at a really high level and is automatic from the line as she went 8-for-8 from the floor. She fits into the team at Indianola really well and can consistently be a third scorer for a team that will score a lot this year.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jocelyn-bice/\">Jocelyn Bice</a> - 5\'7 G - 2022 - Norwalk</strong>\nBice struggled a little bit in the early going of the game as she was being facegaurded for the entire game. She showed the ability to move well without the ball and get open on her own for most of the game. Bice is a quick guard who once she gets going is tough to stop. She’ll have to learn to play with pressure a bit better, however.\n\n<strong>Bren Moritz - 6\' PF - 2021 - Norwalk</strong>\nMoritz was solid on the inside for Norwalk as she was able to score the ball consistently and rebounded the ball really well. Moritz walked away with a double-double and was able to send several shots ball. She has the ability to dominate on both ends of the floor.','Weekly Evaluations: Week 2','','publish','open','open','','weekly-evaluations-week-2','','','2019-12-08 17:00:14','2019-12-08 23:00:14','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123160',0,'post','',0),
	(123179,1,'2019-12-10 08:35:58','2019-12-10 14:35:58','Yesterday we looked at 2 must see backcourts (Wayne Memorial and Michigan Center). With so much talent on the perimeter, why stop at just 2? I\'ll give you a look at 2 more loaded backcourts in Michigan that everyone needs to pay attention to.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-123199\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/961cacb8cc60eeafb632cc17e10b0ad2-300x157.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"157\" />\n<h4>Arbor Prep</h4>\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kaiden-glenn/\">Kaiden Glenn</a> (2021, G)</strong>\n\nGlenn transferred from Ann Arbor Huron and will be a huge addition for Arbor Prep. She\'s a strong player that not only plays through contact, but can initiate it and play off of it. Glenn has a nice looking jumper and is a solid secondary ball handler in the backcourt. She makes excellent decisions with the basketball off a jump stop.\n\n<strong>Mya Petticord (2022, G)</strong>\n\nI\'ll start by saying this:  Petticord is an elite basketball player on a national scale. Honestly, there shouldn\'t be a next level school in the country that wouldn\'t want her there. Petticord has always had a very mature game and it keeps growing in that aspect. She has an incredible basketball IQ. Her game is diverse, flashing the ability to dribble drive, hit from behind the arc, handle the ball, and play solid defense.\n<h4>Midland</h4>\n<strong>Jordan Phillips (2020, G)</strong>\n\nPhillips has been perpetually underrated. I admit, I\'ve been guilty. She really looks like she\'s on the verge of a huge senior season and should put the doubters in their place. Phillips is an electric scoring guard. She has another gear offensively and when she hits it, she\'s a game changer.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/anna-tuck/\">Anna Tuck</a> (2021, G)</strong>\n\nTuck is full of potential and could have a big time future in basketball ahead of her. As a 6\'0\" floor general, she can play above most opponents. It also makes her a matchup nightmare for almost every defense. Tuck is coming off an injury and isn\'t quite 100% yet. Even at less than full strength, her and Phillips are a show to see.\n\n&nbsp;','More Must See Backcourts','','publish','open','open','','more-must-see-backcourts','','','2019-12-10 08:35:58','2019-12-10 14:35:58','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123179',0,'post','',0),
	(123180,1,'2019-12-10 09:11:52','2019-12-10 15:11:52','<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sadie-voss/\">Sadie Voss</a></strong> is one of the most athletic players we have seen this year. Period. Full stop. End of story. OK, it’s not the end of the story, because I have plenty of say about Voss, her Jackson County Central team and the Big South Showcase that took place Saturday in Jackson. It was 12 hours of interesting basketball that concluded with an entertaining display of JCC’s new fun-and-gun approach to the game that has the conference buzzing.\n\nJCC finished 3-9 in the Big South last season, 9-16 overall. Following a coaching change and subsequent implementation of the new system, the Huskies were 3-0 after Saturday’s 86-71 home court victory over New Ulm. The team is averaging a whopping 88 points per game, and the kids are clearly having a ton of fun.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123186\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"193\"]<img class=\"wp-image-123186\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/sadie-and-rudy-169x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"193\" height=\"344\" /> Sadie Voss and her brother Rudy.[/caption]\n\nJackson’s approach to the game is constructed around the Grinnell System that relies on constant defensive pressure via the full-court press with hockey-style personnel swaps every couple of minutes. It’s a bit jarring to watch at first – ‘chaotic’ is the first adjective that springs to mind – but it’s a way of playing that is totally suited to Voss and her nearly-as-athletic cousin <strong>Alaina Wolff</strong>, a 5’6 dynamo who has committed to play volleyball next year at Wayne State in Nebraska.\n\nVoss was flying around the court on Saturday, and was seemingly everywhere at once. You want smothering one-on-one defense? Someone who can force turnovers and fluster opponents? A player who knows what to do with the ball once it’s back in her possession? That’s Voss. The 5’8 sophomore is a great shooter, finishes through contact, has very quick feet and hands, and plays the game with intense passion. There are very few players who can run at maximum RPMs like that, which is why Voss stands out so much.\n\nOn Saturday that approach paid off as Voss scored 30 points in the win. According to stats guru Kevin Anderson, who charted the game against New Ulm, Sadie’s production was at a rate of 88 points per 36 minutes! Last season Voss averaged 13.6 points per game to go along with 3.2 rebounds, 4.3 assists and 1.2 steals. One can only imagine what those numbers might look like this year. If the scorekeeper can keep up.\n\nWe first saw Voss last year at this event and we wrote about the then-freshman’s potential. Plans to watch her later in the season went awry because Voss was injured during the only window in the schedule when it would have been possible to make the six-hour round trip to Jackson. She doesn’t play much summer basketball, either – club volleyball is the priority – so based on that single viewing we dropped Voss into the Prep Girls Hoops class of 2022 rankings mid-pack. She’s currently ranked in the 80s. That’s way too low. Voss belongs at least 40 spots higher, maybe more.\n\nSadie is not the only great athlete in the family. Brother Rudy arrived late for his sister’s game on Saturday because he was playing quarterback in the Minnesota Football Showcase all star game at U.S. Bank Stadium in Minneapolis. Rudy holds football offers from North Dakota and South Dakota State, and is a standout basketball player, as well. He’s got options. So does Sadie. Our sister publication Prep Dig has Voss rated as the #22 volleyball player in the state.\n\n<strong>The rest of Saturday’s Top 10</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/gus-boyer/\">Gus Boyer</a> </strong>– senior guard, Waseca (UM-Duluth). At #27 in the class of 2020, Boyer was the highest-ranked player in the Big South Showcase and it showed. The 5’10 guard does it all, with a huge motor, superior skill set and one of the finest shooting motions we’ve seen. She fills the stat sheet on a regular basis with averages last season of 11.7 points, 4.6 rebounds, 3.9 assists and 2.5 steals. Boyer was cold from beyond the arc Saturday but she made up for it from two-point territory as Waseca dispatched Redwood Valley by a score of 52-25.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/zoe-velde/\">Zoe Velde</a> </strong>– senior guard, Pipestone (Mary). Velde is a bulldog, a scrappy player who works hard every single minute and epitomizes the term ‘gym rat.’ She’s also quite skilled, which is why Division 2 Mary out of Bismarck, N.D., was willing to accept her signature on the dotted line to play point guard for the Marauders. Zoe was everywhere on Saturday in Pipestone’s 37-20 win over St. James, clearly demonstrating her athleticism, strength and versatility.\n\n<strong>Olivia Hayenga</strong> – sophomore forward, Worthington. We have been excited about the 5’9 Hayenga’s potential for the past year, and it’s all starting to come together now for this lean and lengthy athlete who has big strides, nice elevation and a quick first step. Hayenga also has ball-handling skills, finishes at the rim in traffic and can run the floor. Olivia has a ways to go but may be a scholarship player in the making.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brooklyn-scheitel-taylor/\">Brooklyn Scheitel-Taylor</a></strong> – sophomore guard, Worthingon. Brooklyn is an athlete who stood out at the Prep Girls Hoops Top 250 Expo in October and showed us more of the same on Saturday. She runs track, plays volleyball and has excellent potential to play high-level basketball at the next level. Scheitel-Taylor has fast feet, nice elevation and a natural flair for the game. Brooklyn is putting in extra work on her skill development and the effort is paying off.\n\n<strong>A few more standouts</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jordyn-hilgemann/\">Jordyn Hilgemann</a></strong> – junior forward, Marshall. Opponents regularly game plan around the 5’10 Hilgemann, who has strength and length, can shoot the basketball, and cashes in at the rim. Those game plans seldom work, however, as Hilgemann is a top-30 prospect who scored 25 points per game last winter for the Tigers.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rachel-breck/\">Rachel Breck</a></strong> – senior forward, Waseca (Iowa Lakes). The 6’0 senior is a top 100 prospect who has put in a ton of extra work to grow her game. The effort has resulted in a versatile, experienced player who owns the paint, finishes at the rim and rebounds hard. Breck will compete in both basketball and volleyball at Iowa Lakes.\n\n<strong>Nora Windschill</strong>, senior forward, New Ulm. The 5’10 Windschill might be better known as a volleyball player but she showed at the Big South Showcase that she knows her way around the basketball court, too. With the graduation of <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/joey-batt/\">Joey Batt</a>, the Eagles are in transition and players like Windschill have to step up. Nora certainly did, collecting a double-double with 22 points and 17 rebounds.\n\n<strong>Jazlynn Prins</strong> – senior guard, Southwest Minnesota Christian. Prins has been a skilled, productive point guard at the varsity level seemingly forever. The 5’10 senior averaged 19 points per game last season for the Edgerton-based team that went 23-5. She’s smart, versatile, shoots the three and loves to drive to the hoop. Jazzlyn was very good on Saturday as per usual.\n\n<strong>Maya Scheitel-Taylor</strong> – senior forward, Worthington. Maya doesn’t draw quite the attention that younger sister Brooklyn does but her contributions for the Trojans are no less important. She rebounds aggressively, defends hard and is a solid all-around contributor. Maya can also shoot the three and has some length. She showed us at the Top 250 Expo and again on Saturday that knows how to use it.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/haley-garman/\">Haley Garman</a></strong> – junior forward, Redwood Valley. Haley is one of the biggest bodies in Minnesota girls basketball. At 6’2, with an enormous frame, Garman is a handful as she showed clearly in a stunning performance against Roseau at the state tournament last spring. Garman averaged 19 and 10 during the 2018-19 season. She’s currently carrying the load for Redwood Valley, which lost standout guard <strong>Sydney Sommers</strong> to a torn ACL and had six injured players on the bench in street clothes Saturday.','Big South Showcase: Jackson\'s Sadie Voss tops the Top 10','','publish','open','open','','big-south-showcase-sadie-voss-of-jackson-leads-the-top-10','','','2019-12-10 09:11:52','2019-12-10 15:11:52','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123180',0,'post','',0),
	(123207,1,'2019-12-10 13:17:33','2019-12-10 19:17:33','Finally, the starting gate is full, sleek fillies poised to jump out, friendly bets placed, and PGH anticipates great entertainment. Let the games begin.\n\n<em><strong>(Bold font with italics indicate game is carried on NFHSnetwork.com (at $10/month) or for free on livetv.com)</strong></em>\n\nPGH\'s pick for Class \'AA\'  2020 supremacy slams into 2019 champion Brandon Valley on Friday at 6:00 pm, then rumbles onto Yankton Saturday afternoon.  Two outstanding games will mark early leaders among probable state tournament combatants. Kyah Watson, Jayda McNabb, and Bailee Sobczak, an all-state trio of complementary talents, should stress BV\'s inexperience and interior for an initial win. BV \'s Sidney Thue and Hilary Behrens cannot rebound well enough to succeed against the trio\'s athleticism. Resorting to perimeter tries, BV\'s accuracy will suffer from active guards, who harrass in a deep rotation.  <strong><em>Saturday\'s 1:00pm foe, the Yankton Gazelles,</em></strong> does feature excellent outside scorers and  pull-up poppers. All-State Madison Wuebben, Payton Wolfgram,  Saddie Fedders and  Kelsey Oswald return as a strong nucleus; however, Stevens\' agility &amp; strength inside rules the day.\n\nAnother Friday memory-maker has<strong><em> Mt Vernon/Plankington in Gregory at 4:00 pm CT. </em></strong> Emilee Fox, Dacie Rehanek, and Katlyn Briggs should overwhelm two sister combos: Brooklyn &amp; Jessy VanDerWerff  and Gracie &amp;  Brooklyn Kenzy.  Both teams are state tournament contenders, starring young guards.\n\n<em><strong>SF Christian visits Lennox at 6:30 Friday</strong></em> for an early Dak-12 showdown. Lennox\'s smooth assault team should handle the challenge, with Rianna Filippe, Isabelle Ihnen, and Madysen Vlastuin in front.  Caitlyn Pruis &amp; Kylah Van Donkersgoed starred on SFC\'s VB championship run. Add in all state Lexi Unruh, Lauren Tims, &amp; Maddie DeJong to make an upset plausible. A Lennox win means not much; SFC will be substantially better in March.\n\n(Other games with the projected winner in<strong> BOLD</strong> font.)\n\n<strong>SF Lincoln</strong> over Watertown, 7:00 pm Friday - Morgan Hansen &amp; Emma Osmundson versus Megan Fannin - two all-staters versus one - hmm-m-m\n\n<strong>Elk Point/Jefferson</strong> over Canton, 7:30 pm Friday  EPJ  brings pressure defense for turnovers &amp; easy buckets with Cali Davis, Lily Kempf, and Reily Connelly. Canton is young and learning How-To from their special,  new coach; a work in progress.\n\n<strong>Miller at </strong>Cheyenne/Eagle Butte Saturday 2:00 pm MT  Doubling down on VB success, Miler\'s height dominates Kayde Fernholz, Vonna Schlecter, Rachel Joy, &amp; Storm Johnson. Meanwhile, defensive stars Macie Werdel and Abby Ketelhut frustrate foes outside.CEB\'s Freshman flash is Daci LendsHisHorse small but often brilliant like a gamma-ray burst. Markee Shaving, Mia Paris, Sunni Dupris, Miranda Vines, and JayEllen Red Fox round out a small energetic team that annually upsets a higher-ranked squad.\n\nElk Point/Jefferson at <strong>Madison</strong> Saturday 3:45 pm - Bulldogs have a new coach, plus Zoey Gerry, Kendra Leighton, and Abby Brooks to repel this Dak-12 invader. (Streaming video on www.amazingmadison.com)\n\nHanson at <strong>Ethan</strong> in Alexandria Saturday 3:00 pm - Matchup of  Mitchell-area \'B\' powers, and Ethan gets the nod here. Camryn Logan, Jessica Bartscher, and Maddie Miller overcome the younger Beaverettes, featuring Morgan Huber, Grace Weber, Vanessa Doyle, Elizabeth Arend, and Mekiah Campbell. This contest could go either way.\n\nClark/Willow Lake at <strong>Sioux Valley</strong> in Volga Saturday 5:30 pm CT  Too much Miakken Vincent,  Abbie Schneider, and Reagan Johnson, as SV starts their march to March Madness in Rapid City. Clark relies on Saylor Burke, Olivia Sass &amp; Charity Wabwe in the paint. 2023 Jada Burke has size, hops, and aggression; LH handles are audacious.\n\n<strong>Faith</strong> at Kodoka Saturday at 3:00 pm MT Kadoka, led by all stater Lavin Bendt take on the confident Longhorns, starring Sydnie Schauer &amp; Kaycee Groves. Pace, turn-overs, and proper spacing will decide.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','First Weekend\'s Top Games','','publish','open','open','','first-weekends-top-games','','','2019-12-10 13:17:33','2019-12-10 19:17:33','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123207',0,'post','',0),
	(123266,1,'2019-12-11 10:53:18','2019-12-11 16:53:18','As the season has been underway for the last two weeks, I have had the opportunity to see a lot of teams play. From the Manchester Tip Off Classic to the TVC Turn It Gold event, here are my 5 takeaways.\n\n- Circleville and Vinton County D2 Top teams\n- Wheelersburg and Ironton D3 Top Teams\n- Peebles is D4 Top Team\n- Fairfield Lady Lions the Surprise start\n- Few players that I feel have had impact for their teams\n\n1. <strong>Circleville</strong> 5-0 and <strong>Vinton County</strong> 5-0 are the top 2 D2’s this year. Both teams are coming off nice runs in the last years tourney, that didn’t end where they wanted, and that has made them both hungry this season.\n\n- <strong>Circleville</strong> 5-0 has size with 2020 6’3” <strong>Meghan Davis</strong> and 2021 6’ <strong>McKenzie McConne</strong>l in the post, both can score the ball in the lane and dominate on the glass. The biggest addition is guard 2021 <strong>Jaylah Captain</strong> who will give them another outside threat and who can take players off the dribble. Circleville has size and length to make that run to the Regionals this year.\n\n- Vinton County 5-0 is a even more uptempo and high energy this year. The development of 2022 <strong>Cam Zinn</strong>, a high motor player who just does everything, gives them a four headed monster to worry about. 2021 <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/morgan-bentley/\">Morgan Bentley</a> </strong>looks in great shape and is picking when she takes over games, 2021 <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/myriah-davis/\">Myriah Davis</a></strong> is getting her legs back under her after a knee injury last season, 2022 T<strong>eagan Bartoe</strong> has developed a nice ability to take players off the dribble and get to the rim. Defensively they are quick in the passing lanes and harass the ball handler. By the end of the year they will have it down and could be the Regional Representative for the area.\n\n- Contenders <strong>Unioto 2-0</strong>\n\n2.<strong> Wheelersburg</strong> 4-0 and <strong>Ironton</strong> 4-0 are the two best D3 Teams in the area.\n\n- <strong>Wheelersburg 4-0</strong> may be better than last years team that finished Regional Runner Up to Berlin Hiland. Their ability score offensively has improved as not only do they have three double figure scores in 21’s <b><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kaylee-darnell/\">Kaylee Darnell</a>, Ellie Kallner</b> and 2022 <strong>Alaina Keeney</strong>, who can get 20 any give night, they have some help from the bench this year. Defensively they are turning up the tempo and turning teams over and turning that into offense.\n\n- <strong>Ironton 4-0</strong>, has always been a team that is in the mix, however this year could be the year they return to the Regionals, with 2021 <strong>Samantha Lafon</strong> in the post, a strong physical player who can finish around the rim, and the return of a healthy 2020<strong> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexi-arden/\">Lexi Arden</a></strong>, the top 2020 in the area, a player that not only can score the ball from 3 levels with range but sees the floor and gets teammates involved. They also have a strong young group around them that by Tournament time will be tested and ready.\n\n- Contenders <strong>Eastern Brown 4-0, Fairfield 6-1, Coal Grove 4-0, Northwest 4-0, Alexander 4-2</strong>\n\n3. D4 teams this year is <b>Peebles 4-0</b>, <b>Waterford 2-0</b>, <b>Portsmouth Notre Dame 4-0</b>. Peebles made it all the way to the Elite 8 last year and looked to have used that as fuel to turn it up this season. Waterford is in the hunt every year, even after graduation.  Portsmouth Notre Dame, even with loss of 6’4” <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/katie-dettwiller/\">Katie Dettwiller</a>, is the “business as usual” team. This year however they are quicker and getting out a little more in transition.\n\n- <strong>Peebles 4-0</strong> is led by 2021 <b>Jaycey Justice,</b> who is a scoring machine, dropped 40 in a win already this year. Peebles is long, athletic and fast. The continued emergence of 2020 <strong>Tatum Arey</strong> as scorer this year will help even more They can pressure the ball full court and cut the passing lanes, their defense this year will be the key in their run back to the Regionals.\n\n- Contenders <strong>Waterford 2-0, Portsmouth Notre Dame 4-0, Manchester 3-2, Green 4-0</strong>\n\n4.<strong> Fairfield Lady Lions</strong> (Highland County) has started the season 6-1, with the lone loss at Washington Court House by 4. The 2019-20 Lady Lions are very young, with a total of 8 players on varsity 5 sophomores and 3 freshmen, not the type of team you would expect to start like they have. Fairfield currently has two players averaging double figures, 2022’s <strong>Emma Fouch</strong> 15.4,<strong> Madison Bronner</strong> 13, three others right around 10pts <strong>Ella Newkirk, Peyton Magee</strong> and <strong>Braylin Haines</strong>. Madison Bronner has had a 20 rebound game also. This years team is doing with intensity on defense, sharing the ball on offense  and an attitude of a team that expects to win each night.\n\n5. Impact players at the start of 2019-20 season\n<strong>Vinton County’s</strong> 2022 <strong>Cameron Zinn,</strong> 5’9”, W is a high motor player who just does a lot for this team, and guards the other teams best player. Just an athlete.\n<strong>Fairfield’s</strong> 2022 Duo <strong>Emma Fouch</strong>, 5’7” SG and <strong>Madison Bronner</strong> 5’10” F, in their second year the young ladies have picked up and leading their young team by their work ethic. Fouch is a knock down shooter on the wing and will attack the lane, Bronner is just a player who outworks the other teams post\n<strong>Fairland’s</strong> 2023 <b><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tomi-hinkle/\">Tomi Hinkle</a></b>, 5’7” G, Hinkle is a stat stuffer player. All over the floor and not only scores the ball but facilitates as well. One to watch over the next four years\n<strong>Eastern Browns </strong>2023 <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rylee-leonard/\">Rylee Leonard</a></strong><strong>,</strong> 5’7” PG, is one of the top PG’s in the 2023 class in South Central/Eastern Ohio. She runs the show for Eastern Brown, which allows one of the better shooters in the area 2020 Camryon Pickerill to play SG. Quick with the ball and can score at three levels. Defensively gets after it.\n<strong>Peebles</strong> 2020 <b>Tatum Arey</b>, 5’8” G, has stepped up her scoring this year and is giving Peebles that viable second scoring option. Also defensively has picked it up.','5 Takeaways To The Start Of The 2019-20 Season In South Central/Eastern Ohio','','publish','open','open','','5-takeaways-to-the-start-of-the-2019-20-season-in-south-central-eastern-ohio','','','2019-12-11 10:53:18','2019-12-11 16:53:18','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123266',0,'post','',0),
	(123289,1,'2019-12-11 09:57:47','2019-12-11 15:57:47','As we enter the 2019/2020 high school basketball season in Kansas.  Prep Hoops will preview some of the Kansas City Area high schools.  These preview articles will give you details on key players, season expectations and more.\n\nIn this article we preview the Blue Valley Southwest Lady Wolves.  Coming off of a 18-7 record and class 5A state final appearance a year ago. Southwest looks to reload on 2019-20.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Players To Watch</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\">Maddie Garreston, Forward, Senior, (2020)</span>\n\nGarretson, a 5\'11 versatile player who can post, put it on the floor, as well as shoot it from distance. A good rebounder and finisher in close. One of a few returning seniors from a year ago and a leader on this younger Wolves team, look for her to help as they try to contend in the EKL.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/abby-augustine/\">Abby Augustine</a>, Guard, Sophomore, (2022)</span>\n\nThe 5\'8 lefty is returning back for her sophomore season looking to highlight leadership skills by playing the point guard position for Southwest. Abby has great court vision and displays good ball skills which allows her to create for herself and others. A superior shooter with limitless range look for Augustine to help lead the charge for the Lady Wolves.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-family: impact, sans-serif\"><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amiah-simmons/\">Amiah Simmons</a>, Guard, Junior, (2021)</span>\n\nAn athletic slasher, Simmons is a returning starter from last years group.  Exhibits <span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">speed and willingness to get to the basket </span><span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">the as well as knock down the mid-range.  Shoots passing lanes on defense for easy layups and a pest on the ball for opposing teams. </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOther key returners that should help the Wolves are <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sydney-beck/\">Sydney Beck</a>, Jaylie Hicklin and Jasarra Gantt.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 18pt\">Upcoming Games</span></strong>\n\nWednesday December 11th, 2019 at a neutral tournament site TBD.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\"> </span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Team Preview: Blue Valley Southwest Lady Wolves','','publish','open','open','','team-preview-blue-valley-southwest-lady-wolves','','','2019-12-11 09:57:47','2019-12-11 15:57:47','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123289',0,'post','',0),
	(123334,1,'2019-12-10 13:04:02','2019-12-10 19:04:02','<em><span style=\"font-size: 10pt\">USA Basketball press release:</span></em>\n\nFollowing her participation in four USA Basketball events in 2019, including being named tournament MVP while helping to lead the USA to a gold medal at the 2019 FIBA U19 World Cup, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/paige-bueckers/\">Paige Bueckers</a> (Hopkins H.S./St. Louis Park, Minn.) today was named the 2019 USA Basketball Female Athlete of the Year.\n\nBueckers also suited up for the USA 3x3 team that finished 3-1 in the inaugural World Beach Games from Oct. 13-16 in Doha, Qatar; she led her team to a second place finish at the 2019 USA Basketball 3x3 U18 National Championship; and she took part in the USA Basketball Women’s Junior National Team training camp that included the 2019 NCAA Next Generation Event at the NCAA Final Four in Tampa, Florida.\n\n“It means a lot,” Bueckers said. “When Carol (Callan) called me and told me, I was kind of amazed, seeing all of the people who have won it before. Me being one of the youngest to get it, it just means a lot to me. To be able to represent my country, alone, and then to get this award, it meant even more.”\n\nUSA Basketball has presented its Female Athlete of the Year award annually since 1980.\n\n“In 2019, Paige represented the best of USA Basketball in winning gold medals and in her dedication to representing her country at multiple events ,” said Jim Tooley, USA Basketball chief executive officer. “She not only helped USA Basketball win the FIBA U19 World Cup, she was recognized as the most valuable player at that tournament, which is further testament to the tremendous performances she turned in this past year.”\n\nBueckers started in all seven games at the FIBA U19 World Cup, and on her way to being named MVP, averaged a tournament best 5.4 assists per game to go along with 11.6 points and 4.1 rebounds per game.\n\n“I really appreciated her competitiveness, how hard she competes,” said Jeff Walz, the head coach of the 2019 USA U19 team and a 2019 USA Basketball Co-National Coach of the Year. “She’s definitely a special talent. She is able to score in all three phases of the game. She hits 3s, has a pull-up jump shot and can get to the rim. But, I just appreciate how she competes. She definitely has that competitive fire within her.”\n\nBueckers finished in double-digit scoring in five of the USA’s seven games, including: 11 points and six assists against Australia on July 20; seven assists against South Korea on July 21; 13 points and six assists against Hungary on July 23; 15 points, five assists and five steals versus Germany on July 24; 13 points and seven assists against Belgium in the semifinals on July 27; and a team-high 17 points and five assists in the overtime gold medal win over Australia.\n\nAt the 2019 USA Basketball 3x3 U18 National Championship, she helped her team, Quest, to a 6-2 record and runner-up finish.\n\nThe 2018 and 2019 Gatorade State Player of the Year and Naismith and MaxPreps All-America first team member, Bueckers averaged 24.4 points and 5.5 assists per game to lead her high school team to the 2019 Minnesota 4A state title and a 32-0 record.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 10pt\"><em>Photo and content courtesy of USA Basketball</em></span>','Bueckers named USA Basketball Female Athlete of the Year','','publish','open','open','','bueckers-named-usa-basketball-female-athlete-of-the-year','','','2019-12-10 13:04:02','2019-12-10 19:04:02','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123334',0,'post','',0),
	(123345,1,'2019-12-10 14:10:45','2019-12-10 20:10:45','Talk about clicking on all cylinders, Cy Springs came out and was scoring from everywhere against Elkins at the Girls Texas Jamboree and the squad showed me yet another side of them as I\'ve seen the Panthers play in multiple settings. <strong>Leyla Boutte</strong> stepped in nicely for<strong> Anaiah Wade</strong> and made her presence felt.<strong> Alexis Howard</strong> also came in and hit some big shots. After processing much of what I saw from both teams, I came away with a few thoughts about both squads\n\n<strong>Takeaways</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123362\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"189\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123362\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0154-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"189\" height=\"125\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/emari-sidney/\">Emari Sidney</a>[/caption]\n\n<strong>Panthers <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/emari-sidney/\">Emari Sidney</a> MVP</strong>\n\nThe talented junior does so many things, she rebounds on both ends, can attack the basket from various angles and score mid to long-range. The thing I really like about her game is that she plays within herself and gets hers in the flow\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123363\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"226\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123363\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0145-1-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"226\" height=\"148\" /> Amber Williams[/caption]\n\n<strong>Firepower from the Panthers backcourt</strong>\n\n<strong>Amber Williams</strong> has been putting up numbers all season, just had a 30 plus a few games ago but her growth since I caught her in the 7th grade, not to mention her poise definitely stands out alongside her range is giving her a breakout junior season. Senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sydney-rollins/\">Sydney Rollins</a></strong> can score outside or off the dribble but she also understands the game starts at the one and she does a good job distributing the ball\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123364\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"216\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123364\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0099-1-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"216\" height=\"142\" /> Sian Phillips[/caption]\n\n<strong>Panthers inside game</strong>\n\n<strong>Sian Phillips</strong> played one of the best games I\'ve seen her play, on both ends, as she simply controlled the paint and was somewhat overpowering with a nice drop step as well as putbacks but her rebounding, running the floor and defense have all taken jumps. Another bright spot was freshman Aiyana Johnson who came in and did a good job of using her body on the inside\n\n<strong>Elkins Big Three</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123367\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"168\"]<img class=\" wp-image-123367\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0153-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"168\" height=\"110\" /> Tatiana Gater[/caption]\n\n<strong>Anika Damera</strong> was named MVP as she attacked the basket strongly but the same can be said<strong> Tatiana Gater</strong> as both found ways to go hard from various angles. Damera is one of four seniors on the squad but the bulk of their scoring will be back. Gater and a very athletic <strong>Ndidi Ilochonwu</strong> are juniors that will provide a lot for the Knights next season\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123372\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"140\"]<img class=\"wp-image-123372\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/DSC_0069-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"140\" height=\"210\" /> Tatiana Gater[/caption]\n\n<strong>Knights youth</strong>\n\n<strong>Mikayla Tarver</strong> and <strong>Aliyah Payne</strong> are only freshmen while <strong>Daisha Siler</strong>,<strong> Joneisha Terry</strong>, <strong>Rachel Sweeny,</strong> and <strong>Va Jay Finley</strong> are sophomores and all are getting valuable varsity experience that hopefully will help down the road. I\'m not going to use that old saying of \"the great things about freshmen is that they become sophomores\" because it makes no sense. The more you do something, no matter what age at this level, you should get better and they will\n\n<strong>Game #4 Final Cy Springs 70 Fort Bend Elkins 18 (Cy) Sian Phipps 14, Emari Sydney 13, Amber Williams 12, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sydney-rollins/\">Sydney Rollins</a> 12 (E) Anika Damera 9</strong>','Takeaways from Cy Springs vs Elkins #GirlsTXJamboree','','publish','open','open','','takeaways-from-cy-springs-vs-elkins-girlstxjamboree','','','2019-12-10 14:10:45','2019-12-10 20:10:45','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123345',0,'post','',0),
	(123365,1,'2019-12-10 14:02:18','2019-12-10 20:02:18','Today is a great day for basketball! It is a hoop fans dream! In 4A, we have one of the best match ups you\'ll see all year as Shadow Mountain (#1 in 4A Power Rankings) takes on Seton Catholic (#2 in 4A Power Rankings). This match up gives us a quick glimpse of what the future potential 4A State Championship could be! Throughout the pre-season, I have expressed my interest in both of these teams and said that I believe either Shadow or Seton will take home the 4A State Championship.\n\nI predict a close game, as both teams have a ton of fire power on their roster. I think this game could get pretty high scoring and will eventually lead in a Shadow Mountain 10 point victory.\n\nI\'d be really interested to see the match up in the backcourt with <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexi-mcnabb/\">Lexi McNabb</a> and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/senya-rabouin/\">Senya Rabouin</a>. Both are about the same size and speed. However, Senya is a senior while McNabb is a sophomore. That could be a really interesting battle of experience versus youth.\n\nAnother match up that could be interesting is <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dyamond-butler-worley/\">Dyamond Butler-Worley</a> versus <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amanda-barcello/\">Amanda Barcello</a>. I would assume Barcello would take on the task of guarding DBW, as I believe that Barcello is SC\'s best defender. DBW is hard to stop or contain, so I would be really interested to see how that match up plays out.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\">Players to Watch: </span>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/senya-rabouin/\">Senya Rabouin</a> 5\'5 2020 G Shadow Mountain </strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dyamond-butler-worley/\">Dyamond Butler-Worley</a> 6\'0 2020 F Shadow Mountain</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/isabella-digiovanni/\">Isabella DiGiovanni</a> 6\'0 2021 G/F Seton Catholic</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amanda-barcello/\">Amanda Barcello</a> 5\'11 2021 G/F Seton Catholic</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexi-mcnabb/\">Lexi McNabb</a> 5\'6 2022 G Seton Catholic</strong>\n\nOn the other side of town and in the 3A conference, we have a terrific match up of talent. Valley Christian takes on ALA-Queen Creek at home. Both of these squads could be sleepers in the 3A Conference and have some amazing 2020 prospects. I predict a very neck and neck game with ALA-Queen Creek winning by 5 points.\n\nI do have some questions going into the game, the big one is: who is going to guard <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jada-pourier/\">Jada Pourier</a>? Likely, ALA-QC will come out in a 2-3 zone, as I don\'t think they have a defender with the size or speed to contain Pourier. I will say that Pourier is very good at picking apart a zone so ALA-QC may have to switch it up and go man. We\'ll see tonight! It should be interesting!\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline\">Players to Watch:</span>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jada-pourier/\">Jada Pourier</a> 6\'0 2020 F Valley Christian</strong>\n\n<strong>Jess Winquist 6\'1 2020 F ALA-QC</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kaycee-kimball/\">Kaycee Kimball</a> 5\'5 2020 G ALA-QC</strong>','Two Big Time Games Tonight!','','publish','open','open','','two-big-time-games-tonight','','','2019-12-10 14:02:18','2019-12-10 20:02:18','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123365',0,'post','',0),
	(123366,1,'2019-12-10 14:20:48','2019-12-10 20:20:48','<strong>The <em>Top Prospect Classic</em> included:</strong>\n<ul>\n 	<li>Henry Clay vs Bishop Brossart</li>\n 	<li>Campbell County vs Johnson Central</li>\n 	<li>Menifee County vs Washington County</li>\n 	<li>Notre Dame vs Dunbar</li>\n 	<li>Holy Cross (Covington) vs Jenkins</li>\n 	<li>Conner vs Butler</li>\n</ul>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Top Sophomore Performances</strong></p>\n<strong>Kylie Koeninger (Campbell County)</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-123380\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/kk-300x197.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nKylie is a smooth finisher when attacking the inside. She loves to penetrate the defense and use her body to draw contact and get to the line. She made 7 out of her 9 attempts at the free throw line. She also has a really nice mid-range jumper. Campbell County defeated Johnson Central and Koeninger went on to win the Player of the Game with 22 points and 5 rebounds. Koeninger is really solid overall player. She displayed a little bit of everything.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lacey-bradshaw/\">Lacey Bradshaw</a> (Notre Dame)</strong>\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-123383\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/lacey-bradshaw-1-300x197.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" />\n\nBradshaw is super shifty when driving with the ball. Her dribbling skills had to be one of the best in this Classic. She knew exactly what to do and where to go when handling the ball. Amazing basketball IQ for only her 2nd year in high school. She ended the game with 12 points and 5 rebounds. I could tell that Bradshaw was one of the most talented players on this Notre Dame team. She has great potential and will have an amazing career at Notre Dame and so on.\n\n<strong>Jillian MacKnight (Notre Dame)</strong>\n\nMacKnight can absolutely stroke the ball. All of her points came in the 1st half with 14 points. Of those 14 points, 12 of them came from behind the arc. Those four 3s all came in the 2Q. She has a pretty shot and even though she did not score in the 2nd half, she went on to be the Player of the Game. Notre Dame defeated Dunbar, 46-26.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-thomas/\">Lauren Thomas</a> (Henry Clay)</strong>\n\nThomas finished with only 8 points but she snatched 8 rebounds as well. As this Henry Clay team really struggled to find the basket, Lauren\'s 8 points all came in an impressive fashion. She can handle the ball really well at her size and even pulled out an euro-step in transition. She can finish on the offensive end and she can grab defensive rebounds. With more time and development, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lauren-thomas/\">Lauren Thomas</a> might arise as Henry Clay\'s 1st or 2nd option offensively.\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Recap</strong></p>\nI was very impressed with these Sophomores as they did not look like Sophomores at all when they hit the hardwood. They all looked confident in their game and at times looked like the best players on the court. Bright futures for these players and I look forward to seeing what they can do this season.','Top Prospect Classic: Top Sophomore Performances','','publish','open','open','','top-prospect-classic-top-sophomore-performances','','','2019-12-10 14:20:48','2019-12-10 20:20:48','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123366',0,'post','',0),
	(123432,1,'2019-12-10 15:16:29','2019-12-10 21:16:29','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Basketball is here. With a good chunk of Class B teams getting started last week, there will be some fun matchups to watch on practically a nightly basis from here on out. </span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Here are some games to watch:</span>\n\n<em><strong>Oakes at Richland, 7:30 p.m., Thursday, December 12</strong></em>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Richland is off to a very good start with two blowout wins. The Colts schedule gets tougher Thursday as they face off against a solid Oakes team that could contend in Region 3. Megan Roob leads a Colts team that figures to contend in Region 1. Oakes is 2-0 win wins over South Border and Enderlin, and returns two of the best players in Class B in Nicole Schmitz and Sadie Hanson.</span>\n\n<em><strong>Four Winds/Minnewaukan at Shiloh Christian, 7:30 p.m., Friday, December 13</strong></em>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Four Winds/Minnewaukan is, in the eyes of many, a top-10 team in Class B this year. The Indians have a terrific core of returning pieces and have just one loss to Devils Lake’s JV team early in the year. The Indians will get a good test Friday when they head to Bismarck to take on Shiloh Christian, a team that was in the state tournament a year ago and returns a handful of key players.</span>\n\n<em><strong>Thompson at Langdon/Edmore/Munich, 3 p.m., Saturday, December 14 </strong></em>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">This one should be a dandy as Thompson and LEM are both top-five teams in Class B going into the season. Both teams are undefeated early in the year, and winning with a combination of excellent offense and lockdown defense. Thompson already has an impressive win over Velva to start the year while LEM beat Shiloh Christian handily to start the season. Both these teams have a ton of returning talent from state tournament teams a year ago and have the potential to win a state title.</span>','Class B North Dakota Games of the Week, December 9-14','','publish','open','open','','class-b-north-dakota-games-of-the-week-december-9-14','','','2019-12-10 15:16:29','2019-12-10 21:16:29','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123432',0,'post','',0),
	(123437,1,'2019-12-10 16:17:37','2019-12-10 22:17:37','The Monday night matchup between Southeast Polk and Dowling Catholic was tremendous on paper, but it might have been an even better game to watch in person. Dowling Catholic controlled the entire first half and led by the upper single digits throughout before a mini-run at the half by Southeast Polk cut the lead to 39-35. In the second half, it was all Southeast Polk as every player on their roster stepped up for the team and made winning plays. Southeast Polk led by four at the end of the third and had a tremendous scoring outburst in the fourth to take the win, 80-71. You can view the 10 Best below.\n\n<hr />\n\n<strong>MVP: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/grace-larkins/\">Grace Larkins</a> (Southeast Polk)</strong>\nThere are about four different players I could name Most Valuable Player, but I am going to go with the South Dakota commit <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/grace-larkins/\">Grace Larkins</a>. Grace was all over the floor and despite scoring just six points in the first half, exploded for 21 points in the second half. She was instrumental on both ends of the floor as she nabbed eight rebounds and dished off nine assists to her teammates. It was an all-around spectacular performance from Larkins leading her team to the win.\n\n<strong>Best Offensive Player: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/caitlin-clark/\">Caitlin Clark</a> (Dowling Catholic)</strong>\nClark scored an efficient 41 points while only taking 25 shots from the floor and shooting 60 percent from the floor. She was able to get to the rim at will and once she\'s there she is going to end up either getting to the line or making a shot. She was the player who kept Dowling Catholic in the game until the end as her teammates combined to go 12-for-27 from the floor. The only downside to Clark\'s game was her 3-point shooting as she went 3-for-11 from behind the arc. But she was 12-of-14 from inside the arc, so it cancels out.\n\n<strong>Best Defensive Player: Jessica Stuart (Southeast Polk)</strong>\nStuart was all over the floor all night long and played a big role on the defensive end of the floor. She ended the night with four steals and all of them came at huge moments. Stuart wasn\'t phased by the moment at all on Monday night and she brought her A-game all night long. She played good defense and helped her team set the tone by not letting anything past her. Her length was evident in this one.\n\n<strong>Best Under-The-Radar Player: Jessica Stuart (Southeast Polk)</strong>\nTo echo the above, Stuart was unbelievably good at everything she did. She scored 14 points, grabbed four rebounds, dished out four assists, and had four steals. I don\'t think I can think of another player who played their role so perfectly in the last few years. Stuart knows what to do to help her team win games and that was very noticeable in the game.\n\n<strong>Best Shooter: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rylie-kruse/\">Rylie Kruse</a> (Southeast Polk)</strong>\nKruse is a known shooter on the wing for Southeast Polk but that didn\'t stop her from hitting all of her attempts from behind the line. She was 2-of-2 on the night for her team and was able to knock both in under pressure. She has a very unorthodox release but she can really let it fly. Kruse once again showed that she is among the best shooters in the state.\n\n<strong>Best Rebounder: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/nyajuok-toang/\">Nyajuok Toang</a> (Dowling Catholic)</strong>\nToang was a force on the boards as the Saint Louis commit grabbed 11 rebounds which include five on the offensive glass. Toang was paramount in getting her team some second looks at the rim. She played with a really good motor and was flying around the floor under the rim to get the ball. She has really improved her mobility over the past few months and her rebounding is seeing a jump because of it.\n\n<strong>Best Underclassman: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brooklin-dailey/\">Brooklin Dailey</a> (Southeast Polk)</strong>\nDailey was unreal in the early going of the game scoring eight quick points for Southeast Polk and performing well all night long. She was 6-of-10 from the floor and finished the game with 20 points. She had two huge offensive rebounds and always seemed to be in the right spot to get the big rebound. Dailey was on her A-game all night long and as a freshman on this stage, that is very hard to do.\n\n<strong>Best Intangibles: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ella-mcvey/\">Ella McVey</a> (Dowling Catholic)</strong>\nMcVey is one of my favorite players to watch because she plays the game so hard. She was all over the floor tonight chasing rebounds and getting into the offensive player when they had the ball. I was impressed with her aggressiveness all night. While she won\'t score a ton of points, she is going to be a paramount player for the success that Dowling Catholic has this year.\n\n<strong>Best Hustle Play: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexi-boles/\">Lexi Boles</a> (Dowling Catholic)</strong>\nBoles didn\'t play a ton in the game but made the most of it when she was in. In one sequence after a missed 3-pointer, Boles sprinted to the corner to corral an offensive board that flew long off the rim. Tiptoeing the sideline she turned and threw the ball right to a waiting <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/caitlin-clark/\">Caitlin Clark</a> who, of course, nailed a 3-pointer off the pass from Boles. It was a tremendous hustle play that cannot be overlooked.\n\n<strong>Best JV Player: Olivia Spracklin (Dowling Catholic)</strong>\nI was able to catch a bit of the JV game and Spracklin caught my eye with her length and basketball IQ. She\'s a lengthy point guard who seems to know the game well and has the ability to distribute the ball to her teammates well. She finished at the rim a couple of times through traffic and I thought that she was able to play at a much higher level than everyone else.\n\n&nbsp;','10 Best: Southeast Polk vs. Dowling Catholic','','publish','open','open','','10-best-southeast-polk-vs-dowling-catholic','','','2019-12-10 16:17:37','2019-12-10 22:17:37','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123437',0,'post','',0),
	(123491,1,'2019-12-11 11:22:48','2019-12-11 17:22:48','The defending IAAM champs, St. Frances Academy Panthers, traveled to Laurel to take on the St. Vincent Pallotti Panthers on a rainy Tuesday night. The stands were filled with supporters from schools naturally, but many players from other schools also came out for this marquee match up. The game was competitive with St. Frances jumping out to a 7-0 lead before Pallotti settled in and gave their crowd something to cheer about. This turned out to be a game of runs with St. Frances leading the entire game, except for a second quarter surge led by <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/eniya-russell/\">Eniya Russell</a></strong> that tied the game at 27. St. Frances senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/angel-reese/\">Angel Reese</a></strong> had a dominant first half with 20 points and 9 rebounds. St. Frances ended up wearing Pallotti down 70-59 in a somewhat ugly game. Here are my takeaways from the game.\n\n<em><strong>The Game Was Hard to Watch at Times</strong></em>.\n\n<a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/angel-reese/\">Angel Reese</a> (Maryland) and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/eniya-russell/\">Eniya Russell</a> (South Carolina) are two of the best players in the country and both shined at different times in the game. I think it\'s awesome that we get to watch that right here in the DMV.  Both players showed why they are special at different points in the game. Reese was dominant inside on the boards and caused match up problems with her ball handling on the perimeter. Russell electrified the crowd with her ball handling, passing and highlight moves. They have earned the right to talk a little trash if they want so I can deal with it. What\'s hard to deal with is players that do not really contribute talking just as much or more. Please stop. Just play your role, support your teammates and work on your game and your pregame handshake routine.\n\nGirls basketball seems to be over officiated in this area. This game was marred by constant foul calls and a bunch of turnovers. At some points in the game there were fouls or turnovers in five to six possessions in a row. That was frustrating as this had the potential to be a classic. The teams will meet again at St. Frances so maybe some things will get cleaned up by then.\n\n<em><strong>Khalia Turner Was Impressive For St. Frances</strong></em>\n\nThis was a game of runs and every time Pallotti made one of their runs it seemed like senior guard Khalia Turner (Bowie State) was there for St. Frances. She only scored 11 points but she made three 3 pointers and they all came when St. Frances had gone cold. She kept her composure during the game and was pretty solid all around. She\'ll have a nice career at Bowie State.\n\n<em><strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/larrin-sydnor/\">Larrin Sydnor</a> Should Play More for Pallotti</strong></em>\n\nThe athletic junior guard got the start in this game and I thought she played well. She is tenacious and disruptive on defense and does not back down. She makes hustle and heart plays on both ends of the court and I thought she was perfect for this game. I would have liked to see her matched up more with <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/angel-reese/\">Angel Reese</a> because she\'s always up for any challenge. Her minutes were scattered and it did not help that she picked up a technical foul for mixing it after the whistle. I still think Pallotti needs more of her as she usually makes good things happen.\n\n<strong><em>Kameryn Dorsey Is The Real Deal</em></strong>\n\nI really like this kid\'s game and demeanor. The tough freshman point guard has leapfrogged some of the sophomore guards on the roster and it\'s easy to see why. She is all business on the court and will be the point guard of the future at St. Frances. She is small, but strong and explosive with a tight handle. She only scored 2 points, but I thought she acquitted herself quite well for a freshman in a game like this.\n\n&nbsp;','4 Takeways From The Panther Battle: St. Frances at Pallotti','','publish','open','open','','4-takeways-from-the-panther-battle-st-frances-at-pallotti','','','2019-12-11 11:22:48','2019-12-11 17:22:48','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123491',0,'post','',0),
	(123623,1,'2019-12-10 18:18:39','2019-12-11 00:18:39','<strong>BIG LAKE -- </strong>Last night Prep Girls Hoops Minnesota stayed close to home to watch Big Lake take on Alexandria. See who stood out to us in Alexandria\'s big 65-46 win over the Big Lake Hornets.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/reagan-sternquist/\">Reagan Sternquist</a>, Forward, Big Lake (2020, 82nd in our 2020 player rankings)</strong>\n\nIn my opinion, Sternquist was one of the few bright spots for the Hornets. She played pretty well in the 2nd half even though Big Lake was down by a large margin. She was impressive with her dribble-drive to the bucket and her will to keep grinding and wasn\'t worried about the score, just played her game. A seen leader for the Hornets last night.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lilly-horn/\">Lilly Horn</a>, Forward, Alexandria (2021)</strong>\n\nWhat I loved about watching Alexandria was their awareness on the court. In the 2nd half, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lilly-horn/\">Lilly Horn</a> threw a football pass to a wide-open <strong>Mia McGrane </strong>for an easy lay-in to muscle the Cardinals to an even stronger margin over a Big Lake team that I expected a better outcome out of.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/caela-tighe/\">Caela Tighe</a>, Forward, Big Lake (2021, 23rd in our 2021 player rankings)</strong>\n\nTighe was the force in the post for the Hornets. It\'s easy to see why Tighe is a captain on this Hornet\'s team as she used her strong rebounding ability with force to go up against the Cardinals the best she could. I look to see Tighe blossom into an even nicer post player in the Granite Ridge this season.\n\n<strong>Mia McGrane, Guard, Alexandria (2020)</strong>\n\nMcGrane\'s court awareness is what took me in the second half. I mentioned the football pass that she received earlier and found the fast-break bucket but she also threw a beautiful full-court pass to <strong>Myah Kremer </strong>who caught it for another Alexandria score that silenced the Big Lake crowd. I look forward to seeing Mia\'s high basketball IQ improve even more in her senior season for the Cardinals.\n\n<strong>Game MVP: <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ella-grove/\">Ella Grove</a>, Alexandria (2020, 48th in our 2020 player rankings)</strong>\n\nGrove made a strong case for a jump in our 2020 rankings last night against Big Lake. The University of Mary commit was on her a-game all night and not only dominated offensively but caused some defensive problems for the Big Lake frontcourt. Kudos to Ella for winning Game MVP!\n\nAlexandria (3-2) will travel to Little Falls on Thursday night at 7:15 to play the Flyers who Nate from Prep Girls Hoops Minnesota will watch tonight in St. Cloud.\n\nBig Lake (1-3) will travel to Zimmerman on Thursday who is another team with only 1 win on the season coming against Chisago Lakes 59-44 and is lead by <strong>Lydia Hagstrom</strong>, who was on our Preseason All-Sherburne County Team.','Big Lake-Alexandria Standouts','','publish','open','open','','big-lake-alexandria-standouts','','','2019-12-10 18:18:39','2019-12-11 00:18:39','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123623',0,'post','',0),
	(123633,1,'2019-12-11 10:34:08','2019-12-11 16:34:08','In a couple weeks, the 2019 Raymond James HOF classic will be taking place. It is a mini tournament that has been set for Friday, December 27 and Saturday, December 28. This illustrious event will highlight the best in Indiana high school basketball.\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">2019 Girls’ Raymond James Hall of Fame Classic Schedule</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">New Castle Fieldhouse - Friday, December 27, 2019</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">11:00 a.m. (ET)           Brownsburg vs. Penn</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">to follow                     Salem vs. Crown Point</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">6:00 p.m.                     Consolation Game</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left\">to follow                     Championship Game</p>\n&nbsp;\n\nBrownsburg H.S. (Brownsburg, Indiana)\n\nThe Bulldogs are coming off at 20-4 season. Senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/allison-bosse/\">Allison Bosse</a></strong> (Marian University) averaged 15.7 points per game, junior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ally-becki/\">Ally Becki</a></strong> averaged 13.4 points, 5.5 rebounds, 4.4 assists and 3.5 steals, and senior <strong>Mackenzie Stein</strong> scored 8.5 points last season. Brownsburg makes their 2nd appearance in the Girls Classic.  They won the 2010 event, defeating eventual 4A champion Jeffersonville and eventual 3A champion Evansville Memorial, led by sophomore <strong>Stephanie Mavunga</strong>, who was named 2010 Classic MVP and 2013 Indiana Miss Basketball.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_11775\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-11775\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Ally-Becki-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /> Photo Credit: Prep Girls Hoops[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nPenn (H.S.) (Mishawaka, Indiana)\n\nThe Kingsmen return their top three scorers from a 25-1 team that made it to the 4A regional finals in 2018-19. Junior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/trinity-clinton/\">Trinity Clinton</a></strong> averaged 14.6 points, 6.4 rebounds and 3.8 steals, senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/reganne-pate/\">Reganne Pate</a></strong> averaged 12.4 points and junior <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jordyn-smith/\">Jordyn Smith</a> scored 10.3 per game.Penn makes their 2nd appearance in the Girls Classic.  They won 2011 event, defeating Mt. Vernon (Fortville) and Norwell, with <strong>Caroline Buhr</strong> earning that year’s Classic MVP honors.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_11984\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"210\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-11984\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Trinity-Clinton-e1536778609285-210x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"210\" height=\"300\" /> Photo Credit: Prep Girl Hoops[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSalem (H.S.) (Salem, Indiana)\n\nThe Lady Lions return four starters from their 24-4 3A semi-state finalist team. Senior point guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/leah-miller/\">Leah Miller</a></strong> averaged 14.4 points per game, senior guard <strong>Hope Tomlinson</strong> scored 10.1, sophomore <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/karly-sweeney/\">Karly Sweeney</a></strong> averaged 9.1 points and 5.2 rebounds and 6’2” senior <strong>Letti Nice</strong> averaged 7.2 points and 8.6 rebounds this past season. This will be Salem’s very first appearance in the Classic.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_14962\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"201\"]<img class=\"wp-image-14962 size-medium\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Leah-Miller-e1539098690433-201x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"201\" height=\"300\" /> Photo Credit: Prep Girls Hoops[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nCrown Point (H.S.) (Crown Point, Indiana)\n\nA youthful and budding Bulldogs squad returns key contributors fresh off a 28-1 4A semi-state team. Sophomore point guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jessica-carrothers/\">Jessica Carrothers</a></strong> averaged 21.6 points, 5.5 rebounds and 4.7 steals, 6’1” senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/abby-stoddard/\">Abby Stoddard</a></strong> scored 9.3 points per contest, junior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alyna-santiago/\">Alyna Santiago</a></strong> averaged 6.7 points and 4.2 steals and 6’3” sophomore <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lilly-stoddard/\">Lilly Stoddard</a></strong> held averages of 5.4 points and 6.1 rebounds. Crown Point will be making their 2<sup>nd</sup> appearance in the Girls Classic.  The Bulldogs lost to Rushville and Austin in the 1984 event, but finished the season as 1985 IHSAA girls basketball state champions\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_64597\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-64597\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Jessica-Carrothers-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> Photo Credit: Prep Girls Hoops[/caption]','2019 Raymond James HOF Classic Preview','','publish','open','open','','2019-raymond-james-hof-classic-preview','','','2019-12-11 10:34:08','2019-12-11 16:34:08','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123633',0,'post','',0),
	(123642,1,'2019-12-11 13:24:05','2019-12-11 19:24:05','Prairie came out quickly getting out to an 18-9 lead before Waterloo West started using their press in the second quarter. It worked well as Waterloo West went on an 11-2 run before Prairie\'s <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mallory-mcdermott/\">Mallory McDermott</a> and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sidney-mccrea/\">Sidney McCrea</a> were each able to knock down two 3-pointers to give Prairie a 32-22 halftime advantage. Prairie was able to run away with the game in the second half stretching the lead to 16 after three quarters and ending with a 68-48 victory. I take a look at five takeaways from the game below.\n\n<hr />\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\"><strong>The McDermott and McCrea duo can\'t be stopped</strong></span></p>\nThe senior duo of guards <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mallory-mcdermott/\">Mallory McDermott</a> and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sidney-mccrea/\">Sidney McCrea</a> can\'t be stopped and you can only hope to slow them down. McDermott, a Western Illinois commit, and McCrea, a Northern Illinois commit, combined to score 50 points in the game. They were the driving forces behind the Prairie win. They might not combine to score 45 points a game each night as they have thus far this season, but they both will be efficient with their scoring. If they aren\'t scoring the ball they are able to both pass the ball very well finding teammates that are open for easy baskets. In this game, they had a combined 11 assists and were tremendous all night long. There might not be a better guard duo in the state than these two.\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">A duo of freshmen led Waterloo West</span></strong></p>\nWaterloo West has a trio of very talented freshmen on their roster this year and they are certainly going to be a group to watch over the next four years. However, one didn\'t play tonight due to injury and the other two stepped up big. <strong>Halli Poock</strong> is a high-level freshman guard who scores the ball at a very high rate. She came into the game scoring 20 points a contest and finished this one with 16 points. Poock has really good body control at the rim and showcased the ability to score through contact but she also was able to hit from the perimeter as well. Another freshman, <strong>Sahara Williams</strong>, had a nice game as she was stellar on the defensive end and was able to make her way to the basket fairly easily. She finished with six points but had five steals in the game. She has a lot of potential with her length on the wing and as she continues to settle in should be able to make noise throughout the state.\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Waterloo West\'s press can do some damage</span></strong></p>\nWaterloo West didn\'t use their press in the first quarter, but early in and throughout the second quarter, they were really able to do some damage with it. Heading into the second quarter they were down by nine points and used the press to claw back into the game and tie it at 20 points. Prairie turned the ball over a few times which led to easy baskets for Waterloo West as they made their run. Waterloo West is a tough and scrappy team with the ability to pressure the ball with their length. They ended up forcing 20+ turnovers in the game and two players had five or more steals in the game. Once Prairie showed the ability to break it, they were off to the races with their shooting ability. The press will really hamper teams that struggle to handle the ball which is going to allow them to win some lopsided bouts.\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Prairie has players who can step up</span></strong></p>\nOf course McDermott and McCrea are going to do the bulk of the scoring but Prairie does have players who can step up and score the ball. Sophomore <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kamryn-grissel/\">Kamryn Grissel</a> is one of those players even though she wasn\'t able to connect much in this game. She is a high basketball IQ wing who has the ability to score at all three levels and has proven that already this year. She was just 1-for-8 in this one but she is definitely a player who can relieve some pressure. <strong>Jenna Leggat</strong> is a senior and she too has the ability to cash in a few baskets a night. She scored six points and shot 50 percent from the floor. She isn\'t going to go off for 20 points in any game but she can provide a spark with some consistent scoring. With the passing ability of McDermott and McCrea, there will be a lot of easy baskets this year for Prairie.\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 14pt\">Both teams can make a splash this year</span></strong></p>\nPrairie has the talent to make a deep run this year with all the talent they have. They might struggle against teams with size but so far they have shown that they can handle it. With two of the best scorers in the state that will always have a chance to win every game. It\'s going to take both of McDermott and McCrea to be cold from the field for opposing teams to win. This year they are shooting over 50 percent from behind the arc which for three games in is pretty impressive. Waterloo West isn\'t at the same level that Prairie is but they are going to soon be there. They are a very young team with the ability to score the ball, defend, and play team-oriented. They do have a few players who have the capability of taking over a game but right now when they play as a team they will be hard to stop. Waterloo West has the ability to really shake up the conference if they can nail a few upsets.','Five Takeaways from Prairie vs. Waterloo West','','publish','open','open','','five-takeaways-from-prairie-vs-waterloo-west','','','2019-12-11 13:24:05','2019-12-11 19:24:05','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123642',0,'post','',0),
	(123663,1,'2019-12-10 21:29:51','2019-12-11 03:29:51','<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Art Turner Memorial - Top Performers - Day 1</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">The early part of the High School Basketball season allows for some out of state or region games, to see how your team is going to matchup versus teams you don’t usually play against.  Paul VI High School (VA) Head Coach: Scott Allen - hosts the Art Turner Memorial ( In honor of his Grandfather who is a WW II veteran &amp; Sports enthusiast) that brings some of the top teams from up &amp; down the east coast to kick off their seasons. 20 schools that traveled from GA, VA, MD, PA, DC, NY &amp; NJ came to play, I am highlighting the standouts from the 1st day of action.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">Schedule</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">5:00 PM Edison (VA) vs National Christian (MD)</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">6:30 PM Westlake (GA) vs St. John’s (DC)</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">8:00 PM Paul VI (VA) vs Christ the King (NY)</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">1. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/aurea-gingras/\">Aurea Gingras</a> - 2020 - 5’9” -  Guard - Edison HS - Scored 12 Pts including 9 in the 2nd half &amp; overtime, hit 2, 4th Quarter 3 -Ptrs that helped bring her team back and helped pushed the game to overtime. The George Washington Signee let the game come to herself &amp; was a key part of her teams 57 - 53 Victory over National Christian.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">2. Raven Johnson - 2021 - 5’8” -  Guard - Westlake HS - 1 of the top players in the country, she lead her team from the tip to the buzzer…. Finished the game with 10 Pts - 7 Assists - 5 Rebounds - 5 Steals in leading her team to a strong Victory over St. John’s - Her ability to control the tempo of play is a quality that has all of the top colleges in the country offering her a scholarship.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">3. Delaney Thomas - 2023 - 6’2” -  Forward - St. John’s HS - Outstanding performance by this freshman in keeping her team in the game, she was able to control the paint on both sides of the floor.  Scored 13 Points &amp; 8 Rebounds but her court awareness and effort were way beyond her age, she was able to space the floor with her shooting ability &amp; cleaned the glass for putbacks. Game MVP.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">4. Saniyah Glenn - 2022 - 6’1” - Guard - Christ the King - Long athletic player that can get up and down the court in a heartbeat, was able to keep her team in it early with some highly skilled plays.  Can score it all all 3 levels of play, exciting highlight reel player.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">5. Brianna Turnage - 2021 - 6’2” - Guard - Westlake HS - Highly skilled player that can affect the game in so many ways, was able to score 12 Pts, add 10 Rebounds &amp; 4 Steals throughout the game.  Her size + skill + motor are a tough combination to matchup with especially at the High School level, a very highly recruited player Nationally - Game MVP.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">6. Jaelyn Talley - 2022 - 6’0” - Forward - Paul VI HS - High energy player that fit the offensive flow perfectly, was able to score the basket below the free throw line consistently all night. Ran the floor with a purpose and moved with out the ball to create easy catch &amp; finish plays around the basket. Finished the night with 15 Pts &amp; 8 Rebounds off the bench to earn the game MVP.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">7. Ciara Harris - 2020 - 5’9” - Guard - National Christian HS - Skilled perimeter player that can shoot the ball with consistency from the mid-range or beyond the arc. Was able to give her team balance &amp; timely scoring throughout the night, leading her team with 15 Pts &amp; received the Game MVP.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">8. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/celeste-castma/\">Celeste Castma</a> - 2021 - 6’1” - Forward - Edison HS - Versatile player that was able to lead her team back from a 10 Pt deficit in the 3rd Qtr to an Overtime Victory. Started the game on fire scoring 7 in the 1st period &amp; was up to 11 Pts at halftime, Finished with a game high 18 Points including a huge 3-Ptr in Overtime to secure the lead. Game MVP.</span>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400\">9. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/faith-alston/\">Faith Alston</a> - 2020 - 5’9” - Guard - Paul VI HS - Floor leader is the best way to describe the Senior leader of this team, she set the tone early on against Christ the King by being locked in on defense.  The App State Signee was all over the court during the game, finished with 4 Points - 5 Rebounds - 4 Steals - 5 Assists.</span>','Art Turner Memorial - Top Performers - Day 1','','publish','open','open','','art-turner-memorial-top-performers-day-1','','','2019-12-10 21:29:51','2019-12-11 03:29:51','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123663',0,'post','',0),
	(123712,1,'2019-12-11 00:30:52','2019-12-11 06:30:52','Seton Catholic remains undefeated on the season, defeating Shadow Mountain 61-56 in a battle. It’s the first loss of the season for Shadow Mountain, but the Matadors battled the entire night and never once gave up. The game had a buzz surrounding it that normally is felt during the playoffs, so getting to play in an atmosphere like that so early in the season is huge.\n\nSeton Catholic was able to jump out to an early 24-7 lead at the end of the first quarter, thanks to an explosive start from sophomore <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/lexi-mcnabb/\">Lexi McNabb</a> </strong>and junior <strong>Bella DiGiovanni.</strong>\n\nhttps://twitter.com/bbowyer07/status/1204586953280114688?s=20\n\nThat huge lead didn’t hang around for long, though, as Shadow Mountain finally was able to find its stride in the second quarter, largely lead by seniors <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dyamond-butler-worley/\">Dyamond Butler-Worley</a> </strong>and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/senya-rabouin/\">Senya Rabouin</a></strong>.\n\nhttps://twitter.com/bbowyer07/status/1204592942762999808?s=20\n\nThe Matadors were able to cut the Sentinels’ lead to only eight points, which was both because of an offensive surge and a huge improvement by the defense. Defensively, the Matadors allowed the Sentinels to score only 12 points in the second quarter, while the offense was able to put up 21.\n\nComing back out for the second half, Shadow Mountain continued to chop away at Seton Catholic’s lead from earlier in the game and was able to bring the game within two. It was like a game of cat and mouse, though, because every time Shadow Mountain would score, so would Seton Catholic.\n\nIn the third quarter, Seton Catholic saw large contributions from freshman <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amelie-cartagena/\">Amelie Cartagena</a> </strong>and juniors <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/annemarie-trojanovich/\">Annemarie Trojanovich</a> </strong>and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amanda-barcello/\">Amanda Barcello</a>.</strong> Cartagena hit two clutch three-pointers in the third to help contribute for the team, while Trojanovich had a three of her own in the third. Meanwhile, Barcello was able to create plays by forcing turnovers and getting the steal. Barcello also had eight points on the night, two of them in each quarter.\n\nhttps://twitter.com/bbowyer07/status/1204596852563136512?s=20\n\nIt all came down to about the final five minutes of the game, though, where both teams turned up the intensity. Shadow Mountain was able to take the lead at one point, but that lead didn’t last for long. Seton Catholic rallied, with a critical moment coming with just over a minute remaining. After Barcello got the steal, she passed the ball to Sophomore <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sasha-daniel/\">Sasha Daniel</a>, </strong>who then passed it to Sophomore <strong>Lee Lee Willis</strong>. Willis took the ball to the hoop and not only got the bucket, but also drew the foul and hit the free throw, giving her team a four-point lead.\n\nhttps://twitter.com/bbowyer07/status/1204604010885341184?s=20\n\nThere was no lack of excitement in this game at all. The two teams will likely meet again in the playoffs, but I wouldn’t be surprised if it’s in the state championship game. Keep an eye on both of these teams as the season progresses. Both are stacked with talent and are sure to continue growing and improving as the season unfolds.','Seton Catholic edges past Shadow Mountain to remain undefeated','','publish','open','open','','seton-catholic-edges-past-shadow-mountain-to-remain-undefeated','','','2019-12-11 00:30:52','2019-12-11 06:30:52','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123712',0,'post','',0),
	(123722,1,'2019-12-11 00:39:16','2019-12-11 06:39:16','Senior <strong>Senya Rabouin </strong>had an outstanding game for Shadow Mountain on Tuesday night despite the team’s upsetting 61-56 loss to Seton Catholic. Despite a strong defensive effort from Seton Catholic, Rabouin was still able to put up 25 points in the game and looked nearly unstoppable.\n\nCoach Erica Farnsworth says that Seton Catholic knew about Rabouin’s ability to shoot from anywhere on the court and they tried their best to shut her down, but her ability to put up 25 points shows how talented of a player she still is.\n\n“They know that, and she still can put it up in their face, which is a true testament to what she’s capable of doing,” Coach Farnsworth said.\n\nRabouin really started to get hot in the second quarter of the game. As the game progressed, she was able to hit five threes on the night, a pair in both the second and third quarters and one in the fourth. She also was two-for-two from the free throw line tonight.\n\nhttps://twitter.com/bbowyer07/status/1204592097740738560?s=20\n\nIt was a big game for the team tonight, but Rabouin handled it with ease and carried herself with a high leve of confidence.\n\n“I think I took the pressure well,” Rabouin said. “It’s all just mental. It’s having confidence throughout the whole game. I just know in my head my ability and I’m confident,” Rabouin said.\n\nShe highlighted how strong Seton Catholic’s defense was, which was something the Matadors hadn’t seen yet this early in the season. Despite having 25 points on the night, Rabouin still acknowledges there was more she could have done.\n\n“I wish I could have gotten more shots off, like I said, the defense was tough, but my team fought through the end,” Rabouin said.','Senya Rabouin shines despite Shadow Mountain\'s loss to Seton Catholic','','publish','open','open','','senya-rabouin-shines-despite-shadow-mountains-loss-to-seton-catholic','','','2019-12-11 00:39:16','2019-12-11 06:39:16','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123722',0,'post','',0),
	(123723,1,'2019-12-11 11:37:58','2019-12-11 17:37:58','It is no secret that Mead\'s girls basketball program has struggled the last couple years. They\'ve been young, inexperienced and inconsistent. So far this season, there has been hints of that youthfulness and inconsistency, but a lot more good things to build off of game by game. In their first GSL matchup with Shadle Park, Mead kept their early season momentum rolling and improved to 5-0 on the season after a 72-41 victory. After reviewing my notes, I have some takeaways and key questions that will be answered here very soon.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Takeaways:</strong></span>\n\n<strong>1) 2020 5\'8 PG <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/joelnell-momberg/\">Joelnell Momberg</a> is a heck of a passer. </strong><em>*Feature image</em>\n\nThe Montana signee had some eye opening passes at different points during the game that made people look around in amazement. She sees the floor so well and it appears to come so naturally. She is a dual threat, because she can also score the ball, posting 18 points on the night. One thing that I like about her passing is her ability to throw it with either hand. This really allows her to make passes through tight seems and awkward angles. An impressive performance all around for the future Montana player.\n\n<strong>2) 2021 5\'8 PG Izzy Boring is really SOLID. </strong>\n\nShadle Park picked up a transfer this season in Izzy Boring and she has been posting good number across the board this season, despite Shadle Park\'s struggles as a team. She finished with 16 points and a half dozen assists tonight, breaking Mead\'s press with the pass many times throughout the game. Izzy does a little bit of everything on the floor and is the clear leader for Shadle Park. A player to keep an eye on.\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;font-size: 14pt\"><strong>Questions that need to be answered:</strong></span>\n\n<strong>1) Can Mead stay mentally focused versus top teams?</strong>\n\nAs mentioned before, Mead has a lot of youth in the program. 2022\'s <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/olivia-moore-2/\">Olivia Moore</a></strong>, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alicia-suggs/\">Alicia Suggs</a></strong>, <strong>Haley Burns</strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kyla-momberg/\">Kyla Momberg</a></strong> are all playing major minutes. At times, the sloppy or late passes and missed assignments hurt, but then there are some moments when they are clicking and locked in mentally to where it looks like they can compete with anyone. Which team will show up in their next game and can they maintain focus throughout? This will be answered on Saturday when they play Mt. Spokane in a home rivalry game.\n\n<strong>2) Who will really step up versus Mt. Spokane?</strong>\n\nIt will take a team effort versus Mt. Spokane and it cannot just be the Joelnell Momberg show. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/alicia-suggs/\">Alicia Suggs</a>, <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/olivia-moore-2/\">Olivia Moore</a> and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kyla-momberg/\">Kyla Momberg</a> will have to be solid at the least. Contributions from quickly improving 6\'0 Haley Burns would be huge inside. Someone is going to have to get big stops at key moments and make big shots during Mt. Spokane\'s runs.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>Next game: </em>\n\n5:30pm at Mead HS vs. Mt. Spokane','Mead Keeps Momentum Rolling Behind D1 Signee','','publish','open','open','','mead-keeps-momentum-rolling-behind-d1-signee','','','2019-12-11 11:37:58','2019-12-11 17:37:58','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123723',0,'post','',0),
	(123733,1,'2019-12-11 00:46:56','2019-12-11 06:46:56','Seton Catholic Prep sophomore <strong>Lexi McNabb</strong> had a stellar performance in the Sentinels’ 61-56 win over the Shadow Mountain Matadors on Tuesday night. With 16 points on the night, a number of both offensive and defensive rebounds and a handful of assists and steals, McNabb earned my baller of the night honor.\n\n“One of the things Lexi did much better tonight was rebound the ball, especially down the stretch in the fourth quarter,” Coach Karen Self said. “She had an all-around great game, and I don’t think that I could have asked for more out of her. She did everything we asked.”\n\nMcNabb came out hot from the very beginning, hitting two consecutive threes in the first as the Sentinels jumped out to an early 24-7 lead over Shadow Mountain. McNabb also had a clutch play in the third quarter to close it out, putting two more points on the board for the Sentinels as it was a back and forth battle for the lead.\n\nhttps://twitter.com/bbowyer07/status/1204590261222797313?s=20\n\nShots seemed to be falling for McNabb all night, as she was a key factor to the team’s win. But while she looked outstanding offensively, she also stepped it up defensively, which is something Coach Self really highlighted about McNabb’s performance.\n\n“She took multiple roles. She had to guard Senya (Rabouin), she had to guard Zhane (Jordan), she had to guard some pretty talented kids and she had some moments where she was kind of our designated helper and she was collecting some rebounds. She did a great job cleaning up the boards in the last two possessions, and that’s not normally a role that she takes,” Coach Self Said.\n\nFor McNabb, her performance on the court is partially dependent on how she carries herself. While she is only a Sophomore, she plays with the poise and composure of someone who has been playing for a lot longer in high pressure situations.\n\n“We wanted to win this game, so you just do what you’ve got to do. You can’t think about it too much, you’ve got to just be calm and play your game,” McNabb said.\n\nhttps://twitter.com/bbowyer07/status/1204617261719285760?s=20\n\nMcNabb didn’t want to take too much credit for her performance though, and said that it was really a team effort to get the win tonight.\n\n“We came together as a team in this game in a way that we’ve never seen before and it helped us in the end,” McNabb said.','Lexi McNabb has outstanding performance against Shadow Mountain','','publish','open','open','','lexi-mcnabb-has-outstanding-performance-against-shadow-mountain','','','2019-12-11 00:46:56','2019-12-11 06:46:56','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123733',0,'post','',0),
	(123751,1,'2019-12-11 03:26:34','2019-12-11 09:26:34','Hello Readers!\n\nApologizes for this monthly overview post coming a little late. I wanted to take some time and go over all of the things you can expect from our site this month!\n\nFirst off, we are fully underway on the season so expect a ton of game coverage. The team will be heading out to games all month long and sharing what happened throughout and giving our analysis.\n\nAdditional coverage could include, player of the week/month, top players so far, etc.\n\nAnother thing to look out for is rankings, both player and team rankings.\n\nEach week, I will go over the top 5 teams in each conference, articles will be titled: “6A Power Rankings”. This list will change week to week as teams play more and more games, so be on the lookout for that.\n\nPlayer rankings are always a hot topic for our readers and in the basketball community. Since we are fully underway, this is a great month for our team to evaluate more players and create a more in depth ranking pool from 2020-2023.\n\nOf course, we are only a 2 person team so although we will try our best to accurately rank everyone, we will likely miss a few players just due to the amount of girls in the state. You are always welcome to contact us and give recommendations on players we should check out. We will try our best to accommodate the request.\n\nSince we are going to be working on updating rankings this month, expect to see them posted early January. Thank you for your continuous support and we hope everyone has a great holiday season!','What to Expect this Month','','publish','open','open','','what-to-expect-this-month-2','','','2019-12-11 03:26:34','2019-12-11 09:26:34','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123751',0,'post','',0),
	(123753,1,'2019-12-11 12:05:13','2019-12-11 18:05:13','I come from watching an era where several high school teams refused to put freshmen on varsity, let alone start them because of several reasons including \"parental pressure\" of the new kid had to wait their turn which was stupid to me back then and it shows you some parents and players have always not seen things as they were, it\'s just been amended and modernized by social media but let me start off with an old saying I actually like \"the cream always rises to the top\" and usually that cream has been poured by me when I see players at a young age who show me they have \"it\" way before some national media person or \"handler\" comes into the picture so it\'s no surprise to me at the success of some of these players early but here\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Freshmen I haven\'t seen this season</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_123756\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-123756 size-medium\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/ELNt3d5W4As3OA5-1-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/gisella-maul/\">Gisella Maul</a> &amp; Sammy Wagner[/caption]\n\n<strong>Sammy Wagner (SA Reagan)</strong> has been lighting it up this season and based on Twitter, is coming off an All-Tournament performance recently.  <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/maddie-cox/\">Maddie Cox</a></strong> is on varsity at Flower Mound, she\'s the younger sister of <strong>Lauren Cox  (Baylor)</strong> who I also said would be in the running for #1 player in her class, I was right as usual and this was her 8th-grade year. <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/loghan-johnson/\">Loghan Johnson</a> (Tompkins)</strong> and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kameryn-phillips/\">Kameryn Phillips</a> (Humble)</strong> are in the Houston area yet due to numerous conflicts, I haven\'t seen either yet based  on \"good social media\" they\'re on fire and let me add<strong> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/jacei-denley/\">Jacei Denley</a> (Bea<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\">umont Westbrook)</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 1rem\"><strong> </strong> to another who I\'m reading is sizzling</span>\n\n<strong>Freshmen I have seen this season</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_118507\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-118507\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/RyLee-Grays-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rylee-grays/\">RyLee Grays</a> LBC[/caption]\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/gisella-maul/\">Gisella Maul</a> (Cedar Park)</strong> is making her presence felt coming off the bench in a big way as she provides \"instant offense\" and speaking of coming off the bench and making presence felt, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/rylee-grays/\">RyLee Grays</a> (Village School)</strong> has been somewhat unstoppable at times and with her frame and power, the sky is the limit. <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dalanna-carter/\">Dalanna Carter</a> (Barbers Hill)</strong> actually went against Grays squad last night and based on the score, without being there, I know she went completely off, I\'m not clairvoyant, well not totally but I just know that she is one of the top guards in the country. <strong>D\'Asia Thomas (Waller)</strong> is already showing BEASTLIKE moments and the ability to take over games while <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brandy-jones/\">Brandy Jones</a> (North Crowley)</strong> showed at the Texas Invitational that she has already made the adjustment easily. Also from the TI, no Tiny feat for<strong> Ja\'Shelle Johnson and <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/angel-tumbarello/\">Angel Tumberello</a> (San Antonio Johnson)</strong> as they showed that if you didn\'t know they were freshmen, their savviness and ability to handle pressure would lead you to believe they were seasoned veterans. Special S/O to <strong>Janae Tucker (Dobie)</strong> who I omitted from the 2023 Watch List but I hadn\'t seen her in a few years and didn\'t realize she was still in the state, that error will be rectified\n\n<strong>Players I will see very soon</strong>\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_82776\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-82776\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Amarachi-Kimpson-PTN-300x197.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" /> <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amarachi-kimpson/\">Amarachi Kimpson</a>[/caption]\n\nI saw <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/zeryah-lee-aokusa/\">Zeryhia Lee-Aokuso</a> (Amarillo</strong>) a couple of seasons ago at Prime Time Nationals, and I said just like almost all of these other players named, she was a D1 Lock before entering high school. It doesn\'t take a genius, well actually it does and she\'s adding a lot to one of the top teams in the state, I\'ll catch her at the upcoming Mansfield Spring Creek BBQ Tournament. That tournament is one of four I\'ll catch December 26-28, three are on the outskirts of Dallas, one is in Waco. I\'ll start opening day off with the Lady Bulldogs Classic and <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/amarachi-kimpson/\">Amarachi Kimpson</a> (Little Elm)</strong> will be remembered in my GPR archives as one of the most poised under pressure elementary school players I\'ve seen. She\'s also one of the most \"clutch\" players I\'ve seen as well, I have stuff floating around on The Gram and I\'ll catch these two and hopefully many others in a couple of weeks\n\n&nbsp;','2023 group sending early messages','','publish','open','open','','2023-group-sending-early-messages','','','2019-12-11 12:05:13','2019-12-11 18:05:13','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123753',0,'post','',0),
	(123785,1,'2019-12-11 10:46:14','2019-12-11 16:46:14','It\'s early in the season, but the talent is showing itself early. There were a lot of prime time performances last night so it\'s impossible to cover them all. The following are some from Tuesday night that stood out.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-108572\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Prep-Girls-Hoops-1-1024x646-300x189.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"189\" />\n\n<strong>Ellie Toney (2022, G/F, Corunna)</strong>\n\nToney is young, versatile and full of talent. She had a double-double with 20 points and 15 rebounds.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sarah-soraghan/\">Sarah Soraghan</a> (2021, G, Royal Oak)</strong>\n\nHer 18 points in a win over Plymouth aren\'t necessarily \"eye popping\", but her overall play to start the season is.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/whitney-sollom/\">Whitney Sollom</a> (2020, PF, Hartland)</strong>\n\nIt\'s just <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/whitney-sollom/\">Whitney Sollom</a> being <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/whitney-sollom/\">Whitney Sollom</a>. 11 points and 21 rebounds in a 37-26 victory over Saginaw Heritage.\n\n<strong>Alecsis Smith (2022, PF, Bay City Central)</strong>\n\nHer stats last night, and last week, are staggering. She had 23 points and 21 rebounds in a win over Saginaw. Smith absolutely controls the paint.\n\n<strong>Athena Samson (2020, PF, Troy)</strong>\n\nThis young lady needs to be on a college basketball team next season. She had 12 points and 12 rebounds in a 49-38 loss to Berkley.\n\n<strong>Rachel Sample (2021, G, Birmingham Groves)</strong>\n\nSample felt it from 3 point range, hitting 6 on the game. She finished with 20 points and a win over Oxford.\n\n<strong>Quinn Robak (2022, G, Waterford Our Lady of the Lakes)</strong>\n\nYes, another Robak for opposing coaches to deal with. She had 35 points in a 56-49 loss to Flint Hamady.\n\n<strong>Mya Petticord (2022, G, Arbor Prep)</strong>\n\nApparently I could just write a book about Petticord. She\'s been lights out, leading her team to a 3-0 start. She was at it again last night, dropping 21 points, 9 rebounds, 4 steals, and 2 blocks in a 61-53 win over Airport.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/reeya-patel/\">Reeya Patel</a> (2020, CG, Ann Arbor Huron)</strong>\n\nShe was dominant last night, controlling the pace and feel of the game from the perimeter. Patel led her team to a tough win over Wayne Memorial with 25 points.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/aaliyah-nye/\">Aaliyah Nye</a> (2020, Wing, East Lansing)</strong>\n\nNye eclipsed the 1000 career point mark last night. She ended the night with 22 points and a win over Williamston.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/carly-mccrum/\">Carly McCrum</a> (2021, G, Bay City John Glenn)</strong>\n\nI\'m telling you, watch out for McCrum this season. In a 56-22 win over Gladwin, she totaled 25 points and 7 rebounds.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/mya-hiram/\">Mya Hiram</a> (2021, F, Onsted)</strong>\n\nHiram might average a ddouble-double this season. She notched 15 points and 13 rebounds in a victory over Manchester.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/taylor-heaton/\">Taylor Heaton</a> (2020, G, Clarkston)</strong>\n\nSchools looking for a well rounded guard, don\'t look past Heaton. She had 20 points, 6 rebounds, and 4 steals.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ciara-hardy/\">Ciara Hardy</a> (2021, PG, Romulus)</strong>\n\nHardy is on the verge of a big junior season. She had 31 points 31 points and 6 assists in a 59-35 win over Thurston.\n\n<strong>Brooke Daniels (G, L\'Anse Creuse North)</strong>\n\nDaniels led her squad to a 74-41 win against Marine City. She dropped 24 points and had 6 assists.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kenzie-bowers/\">Kenzie Bowers</a> (2021, G, Kent City)</strong>\n\nBowers is a top notch talent in Michigan. She had 23 points in a 66-27 victory against Grant.\n\n<strong>Alison Bishop (2020, F, Allegan)</strong>\n\nBishop was outstanding in a 49-20 win over Parchment. She finished with 22 points, 8 rebounds, and 3 assists.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Terrific Tuesday','','publish','open','open','','terrific-tuesday','','','2019-12-11 10:46:14','2019-12-11 16:46:14','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123785',0,'post','',0),
	(123866,1,'2019-12-11 10:51:54','2019-12-11 16:51:54','Each week on PGH Ohio we will provide our opinion on the top 5 teams for each division in Northeast Ohio.\n\nThe power rankings for this week are determined by games completed prior to December 11th and all teams listed belong to the Northeast District board and subsequent sectional and district tournaments.\n\nDivision 1\n\n1. Medina\n\n2. GlenOak\n\n3. Stow\n\n4. Hoban\n\n5. Nordonia\n\nNordonia moves in to the top 5 after a huge Suburban League conference victory over Wadsworth. They followed that up with an ugly win – but a win nonetheless – against Hudson. The Knights have quite the early-season resume. In addition to their wins against Wadsworth and Hudson, they have already defeated North Canton Hoover, Akron Buchtel, South Range and Warren Howland.\n\n<strong>Nordonia\'s Madison Cluse is pictured above. Photo Credit: MyTownNEO</strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nDivision 2\n\n1. Laurel\n\n2. Akron St. Vincent St. Mary’s\n\n3. Gilmour Academy\n\n4. West Geauga\n\n5. Akron Buchtel\n\nLegendary coach Bob Beutel is back to his winning ways at West Geauga. <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/athena-hocevar/\">Athena Hocevar</a> had to sit for the 2nd half and tournament last season, after a transfer from Gilmour Academy. The good news for the Wolverines is that she can play the entirety of her junior year – joining a very talented/athletic group that has started the season 4-0 with wins over Hudson, Riverside, Hawken and Geneva.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nDivision 3\n\n1. Chippewa\n\n2. Elyria Catholic\n\n3. Loudonville\n\n4. Massillon Tuslaw\n\n5. Apple Creek Waynedale\n\nTuslaw enters the top 5 with a 4-1 record, after impressive wins over Proctorville Fairland, Fairless and Northwest. They opened the season with a win over Garfield Heights Trinity – before losing a close one to Louisville. Waynedale defeated Smithville, knocking them out of the top 5. Both teams have tough games coming up with Tuslaw facing CVCA and Waynedale taking on Ashland Crestview.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nDivision 4\n\n1. Cornerstone Christian Academy\n\n2. Dalton\n\n3. Western Reserve (Berlin Center)\n\n4. McDonald\n\n5. Newton Falls\n\nMcDonald has impressed. Their win over Champion caught our attention, propelling them into this week’s top 5 for DIV. Dalton has a huge match-up on Thursday with Chippewa – the winner will be on top of the WCAL – a place that both teams would certainly like to be.','Northeast Ohio Power Poll - 12/11/2019','','publish','open','open','','northeast-ohio-power-poll-12-11-2019','','','2019-12-11 10:51:54','2019-12-11 16:51:54','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123866',0,'post','',0),
	(123879,1,'2019-12-11 12:09:29','2019-12-11 18:09:29','Each week on PGH Ohio we will provide our opinion on the top 5 teams for each division in Northwest Ohio.\n\nThe power rankings for this week are determined by games completed prior to December 11th and all teams listed belong to the Northwest District board and subsequent sectional and district tournaments.\n\n<strong>Division 1</strong>\n\n1. Notre Dame Academy\n\n2. Southview\n\n3. Perrysburg\n\n4. Northview\n\n5. Findlay\n\nNDA continued their outstanding start to the season with a convincing win over Magnificat. Perrysburg has a loss to Southview on the season, but did defeat Northview. Southview and Northview play each other on Thursday - provided us with even more clarity on the area\'s D1 pecking order.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 2</strong>\n\n1. Bellevue\n\n2. Napoleon\n\n3. Shelby\n\n4. Willard\n\n5. Toledo Central Catholic\n\nBellevue\'s win over Southview was as impressive as any for D2 schools in Northwest Ohio through the first few weeks of the season. Although Toledo Central Catholic lost to Margaretta this week - their effort in that loss caught our attention. TCC\'s tough schedule is preparing them for a potential post-season run.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 3</strong>\n\n1. Hopewell Loudon\n\n2. Margaretta\n\n3. Ottawa Glandorf\n\n4. Liberty Benton\n\n5. Ashland Crestview\n\nHopewell Loudon is steam-rolling opponents - scoring a lot of points and playing a lot of kids. Margaretta faces Bellevue next week - a huge SBC game and one that will surely draw attention from basketball fans all over the state of Ohio. Ashland Crestview joins the top 5 for the first time after a couple of big Firelands Conference victories.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Division 4</strong>\n\n1. Ottoville\n\n2. Minster\n\n3. Lucas\n\n4. Toledo Christian\n\n5. Fort Recovery\n\nToledo Christian has started fast - in large part due to the addition of one of the state\'s top players, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/madison-royal-davis/\">Madison Royal-Davis</a> (pictured above - Photo Credit; Toledo Blade)</strong> from Toledo Rogers. Lucas is still undefeated - they have a big Mid-Buckeye Conference match-up on Saturday against perennial league favorite Loudonville.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Northwest Ohio Power Poll - 12/11/2019','','publish','open','open','','northwest-ohio-power-poll-12-11-2019','','','2019-12-11 12:09:29','2019-12-11 18:09:29','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123879',0,'post','',0),
	(123895,1,'2019-12-11 11:43:12','2019-12-11 17:43:12','December 6th clash of Texas 6A titans ended in a hard-fought double digit win for <strong>South Grand Prairie</strong>. Their opponent, <strong>Plano East</strong> field a strong roster but shooting struggles wouldn’t allow them to string enough runs <img class=\"alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-91266\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/IMG_67171-e1568256109315-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />together to win. Nearly halfway through both of their seasons, their prospects are coming into their own.\n<div>For Plano East <strong>Donavia Hall</strong> flexed her vocal leadership muscle way before the tip. I could hear the sophomore checking in on teammates in shoot around making sure they were working to their full potential. Hall didn’t have the best scoring performance, but she knocked down two threes at a high clip and made a strong move to the basket for two points. She’s really improved as a passer making all the right plays to get teammates in <span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-182B91457E567B70C585143C78283E91\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"DET_CG_2\" data-pwa-category=\"grammar\" data-pwa-hint=\"Possible missing determiner\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"a position~the position\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"position\">position</span> to make plays.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-123924 alignleft\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1291-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Kendall <span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-81B3140D742D37F8A18278A61BE01A82\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"SIMPLE_SPELLING\" data-pwa-category=\"spelling\" data-pwa-hint=\"Unknown word: McGruder\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"McGrody\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"McGruder\">McGruder</span></strong> looked so fluid as a lead guard. The 5-9 South Grand Prairie junior shot the ball well from three while showing off her passing IQ. She moved well off the ball always looking for a scoring angle she could take when the ball swung her way. <span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-AB7B581D4B0DF3C4416A4BEF021E3E4D\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"SIMPLE_SPELLING\" data-pwa-category=\"spelling\" data-pwa-hint=\"Unknown word: McGruder\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"McGrody\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"McGruder\">McGruder</span> sent defenders flying using jab steps and shot fakes out of the triple threat. She played a complete game using her length to contain drives and skate around picks.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><img class=\"alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-123925\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1294-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/camryn-hill/\">Camryn Hill</a></strong> is <span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-90B17CFC01F97F08A378F0B8314F9067\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"READABILITY_2264\" data-pwa-category=\"style\" data-pwa-hint=\"Readability may be enhanced by removing this\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"(omit)\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"incredibly \">incredibly </span>versatile on the offensive end of the floor for South Grand Prairie. Hill shot 3 for 5 from three with a quick, effortless release. Thanks to a few sets she flashed the ability to finish over her right shoulder and through contact. She truly looks to be a reliable three level scorer knocking down all of her free throws as added evidence.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><img class=\"alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-123926\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1296-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/taylor-haggan/\">Taylor Haggan</a></strong> dominated everything within 5 feet of the basket. She rebounds, scores through defenders, and runs the floor. Haggan’s physical stature and soft hands are a lethal combination at this stage in the game. The freshman panther has a bright future ahead of her.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-123928 alignright\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1292-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Kiara Jackson</strong> is exactly South Grand Prairie needs at combo guard. The 5-7 guard is a long ball handler that creates her shot with efficient moves. When Jackson operated pick and rolls she read the floor leaking into scoring opportunities for everyone around <span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-FB613D2C63F048FE927DD85EC44ADF81\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"CRFSR_HER_9\" data-pwa-category=\"grammar\" data-pwa-hint=\"Possible confused word\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"here\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"her\">her</span>.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><img class=\"alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-123929\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1295-1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Ebonee Kyle</strong> plays with a slick handle that allows her to slip through defenses. Once she puts the ball on the floor, she’ll be in the lane going for two or dishing out to one of her panther teammates.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-1A75F27BAF71588D3BDE2BE8CB08862A\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"SIMPLE_SPELLING\" data-pwa-category=\"spelling\" data-pwa-hint=\"Unknown word: Adabugwu\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"Debug~Daubigny~DBW~Dargwa~Debugs\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"Adabugwu\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-123930 alignright\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1299-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Adabugwu</span> <span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-92EB6DAF79BAEB44E020180322055917\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"SIMPLE_SPELLING\" data-pwa-category=\"spelling\" data-pwa-hint=\"Unknown word: Anamekwe\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"Yingkow~Unmake~Unmaker~Nameko~Unmakes\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"Anamekwe\">Anamekwe</span></strong> looks the part of a high-level wing. She’s fluid, agile with size to match up with guards and forwards. Only a sophomore for Plano East she still needs molding but all of those physical attributes highlight a ton of potential.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><img class=\"alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-123931\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1298-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Idara Udo </strong>of Plano East plays a stellar game for a freshman. Standing six feet tall, she has a strong frame and uses it to create space when rebounding. She’s extremely coordinated for her age and flashes major ball skills. If she continues to develop that, she’ll be a mismatch combo forward ready to dominate the local high school scene.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-123934 alignright\" src=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/IMG_1289-1-1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />Shooters shoot and that’s exactly what <strong><span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-F4143FC79788CC8DDD9900C5A5C87EA0\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"SIMPLE_SPELLING\" data-pwa-category=\"spelling\" data-pwa-hint=\"Unknown word: Vasana\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"Vääna~Vatana~Västanå~Asana~Lasana\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"Vasana\">Vasana</span> Kearney</strong> does. She shot 40% from three of five attempts and her South Grand Prairie teammates didn’t bat an eye. The effortless jump shot must be automatic for the 5-8 sophomore.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong><span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-7DFD8749CA63698D82E02D39235734BA\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"SIMPLE_SPELLING\" data-pwa-category=\"spelling\" data-pwa-hint=\"Unknown word: Nxerro\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"Interior~Anterior~Navarre~Inferior~Navarro\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"Nxerro\">Nxerro</span> <span class=\"pwa-mark pwa-mark-done pwa-mark-ignored\" data-pwa-id=\"pwa-F0BD9B2C5F34635178AC71DB8E24E5B6\" data-pwa-rule-id=\"SIMPLE_SPELLING\" data-pwa-category=\"spelling\" data-pwa-hint=\"Unknown word: Maluw\" data-pwa-suggestions=\"Malua~Malur~Malú~Malu~Malew\" data-pwa-heavy=\"false\" data-pwa-dictionary-word=\"Maluw\">Maluw</span></strong> is a walking ball of potential. The six-footer is long and mobile but not coordinated enough to put it all together. As the game comes to her, she could be this South Grand Prairie\'s diamond in the rough.</div>','Plano East VS South Grand Prairie Standouts','','publish','open','open','','plano-east-vs-south-grand-prairie-standouts','','','2019-12-11 11:43:12','2019-12-11 17:43:12','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123895',0,'post','',0),
	(123973,1,'2019-12-11 13:23:15','2019-12-11 19:23:15','This past Saturday was the season’s first installment of the Chicagoland Invitational Showcase, hosted by Fremd High School. The event displayed eleven games featuring several of Illinois’ top teams, in addition to top teams from Wisconsin (Beaver Dam) and Indiana (Crown Point). With these great teams, came dozens of high-level and intriguing players. Here are a few of the top guards from the day:\n\nA 6’0” Junior from Lake Forest, <strong>Finola Summerville</strong> was making plays all over the court on Saturday. She’s strong and lengthy which gives her the ability play at different spots on the floor and guard multiple positions on defense. She can shoot well from deep and rebound well. When there was a scramble for a loose ball or several hands fighting for a rebound, it was typically Summerville making the play.\n\nSophomore <strong>Alayna Soukup</strong> from Lake Zurich showed great leadership and poise in a tough game against Nazareth. The 5’9” Combo Guard handled the ball well and ran the offense terrifically against the zone. Her ability to shoot the ball consistently from deep makes her a very well-rounded player on the offensive end.\n\nNazareth standout Junior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/justina-hernandez/\">Justina Hernandez</a></strong> fills the void nicely left by the graduation of <a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/annie-stritzel/\">Annie Stritzel</a>. The 5’10” SG displayed great athleticism on both ends of the floor, turning a handful of steals into transition buckets with her active hands and constant pressure in the zone. Hernandez also shot the ball well from deep and mid-range with a good-looking form.\n\nSenior Point Guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/ashley-berry/\">Ashley Berry</a></strong> from Benet continues to be a steady piece for an extremely talented team. She’s a lock down defender on defense and brings the ball up with quickness and confidence against pressure. Berry has also turned into a reliable three-point shooter, knocking down a pair of threes in a Benet win.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/sophie-sullivan/\">Sophie Sullivan</a></strong> from Montini showed why she is one of the better Point Guards in the area in a big win over Maine West. The 5’8” Sophomore is a crafty ball handler who deals well with pressure and can make plays in the lane. Her three-point shooting continues to impress, but her scoring inside is making her an even more dynamic player.\n\nMaine West Senior <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/dylan-van-fleet/\">Dylan Van Fleet</a></strong> is such a fun player to watch. A 5’8” Point Guard, Van Fleet runs the offense well and does a tremendous job of getting her teammates involved. She pressures opposing ball handlers consistently and thrives in the transition game, finishing at a high rate at the hoop.\n\nStockton Point Guard <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/tiana-timpe/\">Tiana Timpe</a></strong> is one that we will continue to hear more about as her career goes on. The 5’11” Senior is a natural scorer from everywhere, showing the ability to create her own shot off the dribble. Timpe is an outstanding shooter from three and, with her quickness and length, can get past defenders to get easy looks at the hoop.\n\n<strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/kayla-henning/\">Kayla Henning</a></strong> from Evanston does a nice job making sure this talented team flows well on offense. The 5’8” Senior is a strong ball handler who knows the game and sees the court well. She has a nice shot from outside, but her ability to make plays inside and in the transition games makes her dangerous.\n\nThe top player in the class of 2022 in Illinois, <strong><a href=\"https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/player/brianna-mcdaniel/\">Brianna McDaniel</a></strong> just keeps getting better. The 5’11” Combo Guard attacks the lane quickly with strength and is extremely tough to stay in front of. Her decision making with the ball is Elite, and her jump shot and mid-range game only add to her dominant offensive skillset.','Chicagoland Invitational Showcase: Standout Guards','','publish','open','open','','chicagoland-invitational-showcase-standout-guards','','','2019-12-11 13:23:15','2019-12-11 19:23:15','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=123973',0,'post','',0),
	(124122,1,'2019-12-11 18:00:41','2019-12-12 00:00:41','Omaha Westside has been one of the most consistent programs in the state the last decade.  A member of the state tournament field more often than not, including two state championships in the last five years, has made the Warriors one of the most admired programs in the state.  Both of those titles were a big part of the legacy of current Wyoming Cowboy Quinn Weidemann, but she had a tremendous supporting cast, which includes seniors Ella Wedergrean and Jasmine McGinnis-Taylor, two senior leaders of this year\'s squad that would like to have some hardware of their own.\n\n\"I am so excited to get back on the court in a game setting,\" said Wedergran, a Rockhurst (MO) signee. \"I feel like it has been forever since we played an actual game, and for it to be my last season is bitter sweet. I’m interested to see what this team is capable of. I think we have a lot more talent than people think.\"\n\nWedergren and McGinnis-Taylor, an Illinois State commit, were part of the team that won the Class A state championship in 2018, but they have played together for much longer.\n\n\"Ella and I have played together since 5th grade.  We started on the Westside feeder team together and played on that team through 8th grade, Ella and I played in the Boys and girls club all-star game as 8th graders. We also played AAU together, starting in 7th grade and through our freshman year at Retro Hoops here in Omaha,\" Jasmine explained.\n\nThis wasn\'t an accident.\n\n\"Our parents wanted all of the Westside girls playing together so we could build the bond and have the chemistry once we got to high school,\" continued McGinnis-Taylor. \"Abby Hellman, Brooklyn James, Ella and I have all always played together.  We love each other and support each other through everything.\"\n\nWedergren, a wing player, and McGinnis-Taylor, a strong, athletic post player, have skill sets that compliment each other very well.  In Westside\'s motion system that emphasizes ball movement, spacing and back door cuts, both of these players have found their niche for both themselves and the good of the team.\n\n\"Our system is set up to work for every player - our skills hopefully make it work a little better,\" said McGinnis-Taylor.  \"We both play good defense and there to help if the other needs back up. We may have a couple of plays to take advantage of height differentials or jumping abilities.\"\n\n\"Jasmine and I usually pick and roll well together so we try to incorporate that but majority of the time he (Coach Steve Clark) just lets us play our game,\" added Wedergren. \"I like that I can always throw it up and know she will get it. Not a lot of players are able to post up and release well, but Jas does. I think I pass very well to her so that would be what compliments her. She runs the floor hard and I’ll hit her with a pass and she converts it for a score.\"\n\nBeing teammates for eight years will breed familiarity, and these two players know each other well.\n\n\"I love playing with Ellla because she is always positive and uplifting; she is a true floor general. She sees the floor well, is an excellent passer and playmaker. Because we have played together for so long, we know what the other is going to do and I am alway ready for that next great pass Ella is going to make,\" said McGinnis-Taylor.\n\nWestside has started the season off well, playing in a competitive tournament with state contenders Fremont and Lincoln Northeast.  After convincingly taking care of the Rockets, Westside lost a tough game to Fremont, 50-43.  However, there is a long ways to go, and both of these seniors feel good about their odds to add a trophy to their legacy for their senior year.\n\n\"I am excited about the season. We have nothing to fear or lose. Our team is strong and we love each other, and it has been so much fun playing with Ella, Abby and Brooklyn since fifth grade. Our goals are to play as a team, to love each other and to win another state championship,\" said McGinnis-Taylor.\n\n\"Millard South, Fremont, and Millard North will be some of the harder teams that we will have to play this season,\" said Wedergren. \"Our team goals are to make it back to state and win it again.\"','Dynamic Duos: Wedergren and McGinnis-Taylor Want a Title of Their Own','','publish','open','open','','dynamic-duos-wedergren-and-mcginnis-taylor-want-a-title-of-their-own','','','2019-12-11 18:00:41','2019-12-12 00:00:41','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=124122',0,'post','',0),
	(124150,1,'2019-12-11 18:18:19','2019-12-12 00:18:19','<b>#1 Sabino 7-0</b>\n\nSabino remains the number 1 team in the 3A Power Rankings. The squad has moved to 7-0 and has been flat out demolishing teams. Sabino is not only #1 in 3A but they may be #1 in the state. Stay tuned for our All-State Power Rankings coming out soon.\n\n<b>#2 Page 4-0</b>\n\nPage comes in at #2. The Sand Devils are now 4-0 and have been some solid teams such as Winslow and Tuba City. They have a big game coming up on their schedule against Snowflake. I am very interested to see how that game goes as Snowflake was just on the cusp of making this list. Things could shake up very soon!\n\n<b>#3 Florence 4-0</b>\n\nThe Florence Gophers are in the #3 spot, as they are apart of the few undefeated teams left in the conference. They’ve played decent competition so far, against Blue Ridge and Safford. Their next two games will tell a lot about this team as they take on Snowflake and Valley Christian. Like I said before, things are about to get interesting!\n\n<b>#4 Chinle 3-1</b>\n\nChinle is the number 4 team in the 3A Power Rankings. Interestingly, they beat Holbrook by double digits and then lost to Holbrook by 1 point a few games later. Both teams are very good so I thought that was interesting. Other than those two games, Chinle hasn’t played the most competitive schedule. However, that is soon to change! Chinle goes through a gauntlet of Tuba City, Page, Paradise Honors, and Winslow. These upcoming games will surely test the Chinle squad!\n\n<b>#5 ALA-QC 6-2</b>\n\nAmerican Leadership Academy-Queen Creek rounds out the list at the number 5 spot. Since the last Power Rankings update, ALA-QC has beaten Valley Christian. VC is a solid squad who I think could potentially be a sleeper so that’s a solid win. Looking at their upcoming schedule, I think ALA-QC could string some wins together and potentially move up the rankings.','3A Power Rankings','','publish','open','open','','3a-power-rankings','','','2019-12-11 18:18:19','2019-12-12 00:18:19','',0,'https://www.prepgirlshoops.com/?p=124150',0,'post','',0);
